<hr noshade><p><li><a name="CTP"><b>Trade Policy in the Computer Industry</b></p><ul>	<p>	by Robert W. McGee and Yoemin Yoon	</p>	<p>	This article reviews some recent antidumping and countervailing	duty investigations that involved various segments of the computer	industry.  Part I provides an overview of	the antidumping laws.  Part II discusses administration of the	antidumping laws.  Part III reviews recent antidumping investigations	involving segments of the computer industry.  Part IV points out some	of the harmful effect of the antidumping laws.  Part V presents	some philosophical issues.  Part VI offers conclusions and	recommendations. The authors conclude that the antidumping laws	violate property and contract rights, are harmful to the computer	industry in particular and to trade in general, and should be	repealed, the sooner the better.	</p><p>	<b>Trade Policy in the Computer Industry</b>	</p>		<p>	<li><a href="Computer-Trade-Policy.html">HTML</a> Format, 132 Kb		file, 37 pages of text plus 15 pages of footnotes.	</p>		<p>	<li>Adobe <a href="Computer-Trade-Policy.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	 228 Kb file, 37 pages of text plus 15 pages of footnotes.	 </p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="KJP"><b>A Discussion of Protectionist Trade Policies in	the USA, Japan, and Korea</b></p><ul>	<p>	by Robert W. McGee and Yoemin Yoon	</p>		<p>		Hardly a day goes by that the national press does not have at	least one article about trade relations with Japan.  The articles	generally take a somber tone, and discuss things like trade	imbalances, protectionism, Japanese unwillingness to compromise, and	the possibility that the United States (or Japan) might retaliate for	something the Japanese (or United States) either did or failed	to do. Japan has accused the United States of reneging on its	pledge to lower tariffs on electronics and other goods, and has	threatened to retaliate by narrowly targeting U.S. exports of	computer components  A U.S. trade official said that the U.S.	was targeting items that are made almost exclusively in Japan so that	other countries would not be adversely affected by the U.S.	policy.	</p>		<p>	<b>A Discussion of Protectionist Trade Policies in the USA, Japan,		and Korea</b>	</p>		<p>	<li><a href="Korea-Japan-Protectionism.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>		<p>	<li>Adobe <a href="Korea-Japan-Protectionism.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,	 81 Kb File (27 pages, including footnotes).	 </p></ul><hr><p><a name="WRB"><li><b>Who Really Benefits from Liability Litigation?</b></p><ul>	<p>	by Robert W. McGee	</p>		<p>	From the mounds of evidence that have accumulated over the past	few decades, it is clear that the plaintiff bar is the major	beneficiary of the present tort system -- as well as its creator. 	They benefit at the expense of the rest of us -- consumers as well as	producers.  The plaintiff bar has been able to accumulate the	best legislators that money can buy to hold back the floodgates	of reform. And they have the audacity to say that they are doing it	to protect the little guy.  In fact, they are feathering their	own nests, and it is time that they stopped.  A fair system	would compensate victims for their wrongs without treating them	like lottery winners, and would not punish producers of goods	and services when they have done no wrong. It's time to restore	justice and fairness to the tort system in America.	</p>		<p>	<b>Who Really Benefits from Liability Litigation?</b>	</p>		<p>	<li><a href="Liability-Litigation.html">HTML</a> Format	</p>		<p>	<li>Adobe <a href="Liability-Litigation.pdf">Acrobat</a> Format,		33 K File (10 pages, including footnotes).	</p></ul><hr><p><li><a name="EC"><b>A Solution to the Education Crisis</b></a></p><ul>	<p>	by Robert W. McGee	</p>		<p>	Robert W. McGee is a professor at the W. Paul Stillman School of	Business, Seton Hall University in South Orange, New Jersey. 	He has authored or edited more than 40 books and monographs and	has written more than 300 articles and reviews for a variety of	professional and scholarly journals.	</p>	<p>	One of the largest expenditures of state and local governments	in the USA, and of various governments at all levels in other	countries, is for the provision of education.  In the USA,	states provide a free public school education to students for	the first twelve years, and subsidize tuition at state universities	thereafter.  As a result, public education has become a near monopoly	because privately provided education finds it difficult to compete on	price.  Where private education exists, it can compete only because	of nonprice advantages.	</p>		<p>	Dr. McGee's essay points toward a solution for the crisis in	education in America.	</p>		<P>	<B>A Solution to the Education Crisis</B> 	in <A HREF="Education-Crisis.html"> HTML</A> Format	</P></ul><hr><p><LI> <A NAME="DUMP"><B>Antidumping Laws in the 21st Century</B></A></p><UL><P>This paper reviews the evolution of antidumping laws, the negative effects theyhave had on trade, and the recent changes in these laws that resulted from theUruguay Round.  The author then focuses on the human rights abuses that areinherent in any antidumping law regime and concludes that the only way to stopsuch abuses is to abolish the antidumping laws, the sooner the better.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>Antidumping Laws in the 21st Century</B> 	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="Antidumping-Laws.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 28 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Antidumping-Laws.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><hr><p><LI> <A NAME="GATT"><B>GATT as a Protectionist Club</B></A></p><UL><p>The Uruguay Round of GATT was touted as a major advance for freetrade and a death blow for protectionists.  But a close analysis of theactual agreement reveals something far different.  Indeed, any tradeagreement that is more than 22,000 pages in length might lead one toquestion why an agreement that demolishes trade barriers has to be solong.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>GATT as a Protectionist Club</B> 	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="GATT-Protectionist-Club.pdf">Adobe		Acrobat</A> Format, 11 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="GATT-Protectionist-Club.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><hr><p><LI> <A NAME="CASE"><B>The Case for an Absolute Right of Negative		Association</B></A></p><UL><p>The freedom of association consists of two separate but relatedfreedoms--the right to associate with whomever you want and the right tonot associate with whomever you do not want.  In its broadest sense,the freedom of association also includes the right to transact or nottransact.  Basically stated, the freedom of association means that acts(including transactions) between consenting adults should be legal andunrestricted. But it means more than that, because such a right alsoincludes the possibility of not acting with adults who do not consent.</P><p>This essay explores the myth and the reality of this concept as implementedunder U. S. political law.</p><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>The Case for an Absolute Right of Negative Association</B> 	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="Right-of-Non-Association.pdf">Adobe 		Acrobat</A> Format, 91 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Right-of-Non-Association.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><hr><p><LI> <A NAME="POLL"><B>Pollution Trading Permits as a Half-Way	Solution</B></A></p><UL><p>The concept of marketable pollution permits (MPP) has becomean increasingly popular topic of discussion for environmentalists inrecent years, although the idea has been around since at least 1968,when J.H. Dales published a book on the issue.  This approach was givenadded credibility when the Congress passed the Clean Air Act of 1990,which made the concept an official part of environmental regulatorypolicy.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee and Walter E. Block</P>	<P>		<B>Pollution Trading Permits as a Half-Way	Solution</B> 	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="Pollution-Trading.pdf">Adobe 		Acrobat</A> Format, 102 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Pollution-Trading.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="THMO"><B>The Moral Case for Free Trade</B></A></p><UL><P>The vast majority of the books and articles that have been writtenover the past few centuries about trade policy in general andprotectionism in particular have been written from a utilitarianperspective.  This article takes a distinctly different approach.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>The Moral Case for Free Trade</B> 	</p>		<p>	<A HREF="Free-Trade-is-Moral.txt">Text</A> Format, 32 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Free-Trade-is-Moral.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 35 Kb file.	</P></UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="ABCD"><B>The Fatal Flaw in NAFTA, GATT and All Other	Trade Agreements</B></A></p><UL><P>The vast majority of articles and books that have been written about trade andtrade policy— nearly all—look at trade from a utilitarian perspective. Utilitarians take the position that if free trade is a good policy, it is goodbecause the vast majority benefits.  Free trade gives consumers more choices. It gives them lower prices.  It creates more jobs than it destroys.  It is apositive-sum game.  An underlying assumption of most utilitarian-based tradearguments is that governments have some inherent right to regulate trade.</P>	<P>This article looks at trade policy from a different perspective.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>The Fatal Flaw in NAFTA, GATT and All Other Trade		Agreements</B> 	</p>	<P>	<A HREF="Fatal-Flaw-in-NAFTA.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 53 Kb file.	</P>		<p>	<A HREF="Fatal-Flaw-in-NAFTA.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="ISTA"><B> Is Tax Evasion Unethical?</B></A></p><UL><P>The Roman Catholic Church recently issued a revised catechism thatcategorizes tax evasion as a sin.  Part I of this article explores thearguments that could be used to support the view that tax evasion is asin, or is unethical.   Part II presents arguments to support the positionthat there is nothing sinful or ethically wrong with tax evasion.  Thearticle concludes that the arguments offered to support the view thattax evasion is sinful or unethical do not hold up under analysis, andsuggests that it is the tax collectors who might be guilty of sin, sincethey participate in the taking of property without the owner's consent.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>Is Tax Evasion Unethical?</B> 	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Tax-Evasion-Ethical.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 74 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Tax-Evasion-Ethical.html">HTML</A> Format	</P>	</UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="MCAS"><B>The Moral Case to Abolish Social Security	Now</B></A></p><UL><P>This essay a short enough and concise enough so it requires noabstract--read it.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<p>	<b>The Moral Case to Abolish Social Security Now</b>	</p>		<P>		Not available in Text Format  at this time.	</p>		</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Social-Security-Immorality.pdf">Adobe 		Acrobat</A> Format, 11 Kb file.	</P></UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="MCAE"><B>The Moral Case to Abolish Estate, Gift, and	Inheritance Taxes</B></A></p><UL><P>This essay a short enough and concise enough so it requires noabstract--read it.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B> The Moral Case to Abolish Estate, Gift, and		Inheritance Taxes</B> 	</P>		<p>	Not available in Text Format at this time.	</p>		<P>	<A HREF="Estate-Gift-Taxes.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 11 Kb file.	</P></UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="PTPW"><B>Principles of Taxation for People Who Have	Principles</B></A></p><UL><P>This essay is quite long, yet very clear and concise.  Everything in it isfully supported to extensive citations.  The title says it all....</P><P>An essential essay for all those interested in the subject.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B> Principles of Taxation for People Who Have Principles</B>	</p>		<p>	Not available in Text Format at this time.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Unprincipled-Taxes.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 245 Kb file, 56 pages.	</P></UL><HR><p><LI> <A NAME="DTBV"><B>Dwarf Tossing Bans Violate Human Rights</B></A></p><UL><P>In their attempt to legislate and regulate everything in life, including"dwarf tossing," they vividly illustrate the fact that they are in fact"dwarfs"--intellectual dwarfs.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B>Dwarf Tossing Bans Violate Human Rights</B>	</p>		<p>	Not available in Text Format at this time.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Dwarf-Tossing-Rights.pdf">Adobe 	Acrobat</A> Format, 91 Kb file.	</P></UL><HR NOSHADE><p><LI> <A NAME="MWCC"><B>The Minimum Wage and the Contract 		Clause</B></A></p><UL><P>The debate about minimum wage laws refuses to die.  Although numerousstudies have concluded that raising the minimum wage destroys jobs,politicians hesitate to speak out against an increase for fear of beinglabeled insensitive or “against the working man.”  The matter isfurther complicated by the fact that many polls reveal that a majorityof people are in favor of raising the minimum wage at any given time,so politicians who come out against an increase in the minimum wage areseen as going against the will of the majority.</P><P>by Robert W. McGee</P>	<P>		<B> The Minimum Wage and the Contract Clause</B> 	</p>		<p>	<A HREF="Minimum-Wage.txt">Text</A> Format, 14 Kb file.	</P>		<P>	<A HREF="Minimum-Wage.pdf">Adobe Acrobat</A> Format, 14 Kb file.	</P></UL><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>&copy: 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation<P><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></P></CENTER><HR>