<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Productivity FAQ</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#96f9f5"></HEAD><BODY><HR NOSHADE><H1><CENTER>The Freedom Server&copy;</CENTER></H1><HR NOSHADE><H2><CENTER>Productivity FAQ&copy;</CENTER></H2><HR NOSHADE><P><CENTER>This page has been visited <BR><BR><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Productivity.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <BR><BR>since 1996, March 28. </CENTER><P><HR NOSHADE><H4><CENTER>| <A HREF="Contents.html">Table of Contents</A> |</CENTER></H4><HR NOSHADE><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>What is productivity?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Productivity is the measure of error-free tasks produced per unitof time. </DL><HR noshade><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>What is the major stumbling block to productivity?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The primitive production compensation concept based on <I>Being There</I>--payingpeople based on their presence in the workplace rather than on the marketvalue of error-free production. </DL><HR noshade><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>How did the &quot;Being There&quot; concept evolve?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>From laziness associated with technological inability to evaluatethe market value of tasks and record their associated production. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Why has this concept of production compensation based on <I>BeingThere</I> continued?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The problem is a concept elucidated by Thomas Paine, when he said:  <DD><BR>  <DD><CITE>&quot;A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong, gives it asuperficial appearance of being right, and raises at first a formidableoutcry in defense of custom. But the tumult soon subsides. Time makes moreconverts than reason.&quot; </CITE>  <DD><BR>  <DD>Unfortunately, sufficient time has still not passed to make the problemobvious enough to implement the solution. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>What is the solution?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The solution is for production compensation to be based solely onthe market value of error-free production. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>What are the advantages to the individual?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>It restores to the individual control over their life and destinyby allowing them to have an income based solely on their ability, imagination,education, experience and drive. Not based on any external and nonrelevantfactors such as ethnic origin, mental or physical handicaps, race, religion,etc. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Are there other reasons this should be done, other than economic reasons?  <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Yes. It is the only moral and rational way to compensate people forproduction, whether it is for the creation of tangible products or intangibleproducts, (ideas or innovation).   <DD><BR>  <DD>Conversely, it is immoral in any time scale-and certainly irrationalin the long term if not the short term-to do otherwise. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>You seem to indicate that mental or physical handicaps are not relevant.How do you justify this?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Of course they are relevant to getting the job done in less time thansomeone without such handicaps, yet they may not be relevant to completionof an error-free task. Also, virtually any individual--and especially handicappedpeople-can learn and do many things that may not be apparent to the nonhandicappedperson.   <DD><BR>  <DL>    <DD>Further, innovation and true productivity depends on thinking,     <DD>and sometimes the simple thought is better. A clever way around    <DD>a physical handicap may in itself be a valuable product.   </DL>  <DD><BR>  <DD><BR>  <DD>Lastly, and perhaps more importantly, the self-esteem generated bybeing able to do something productive and to earn some money is the mostvaluable of all. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>But what of the individual who has no experience, such as someonejust leaving school?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The concept provides a place for every individual to start based ontheir experience, and to have a job and to learn, and at least some income.It is a characteristic of human beings that when they have unrestrictedopportunities to learn and to do things, they will learn very rapidly.   <DD><BR>  <DD>When a person sees that their income is limited only by their educationand experience, it provides a powerful incentive to learn.   <DD><BR>  <DD>Further, it is in the interest of the company that each individuallearn as rapidly as possible and become as productive as possible, as thisis a prescription for the success of the company as well as the individual.In this system, the fate of individual and company are based on the sameconcept, something not realized in the old system of <I>Being There</I></DL>. <HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>It is obvious that with this concept the individual can earn moreper unit of time, but how does the company then benefit from the increasein productivity?   <DD><BR>  ,hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The company benefits because the agreement with each individual providesfor the sharing between individual and company of the benefits of productivityincreases on a mutually profitable and agreed basis. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>But in reality, isn't it difficult to make big increases in productivityjust by working harder or faster?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Yes, this is very true. And this is where the concept of innovationbecomes the operative factor for both company and individual.   <DD><BR>  <DD>Without innovation there is nothing. There is no initial product,no process for creating the product or the service, and no product or processimprovements. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>What about differences in productivity for the same or similar tasks?Doesn't this represent a production scheduling and control problem?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>This problem already exists but is generally masked by productioncontrol and scheduling systems that cater to the slowest worker in the class.This makes the entire process less efficient.   <DD><BR>  <DD>What happens when individuals set their own pace is that it is intheir individual self-interest to coordinate their activities with peoplein their production &quot;chain.&quot; By doing this, they maximize theirown production and income. Further, each time they do this &quot;maximization&quot;they may create a process innovation with market value, either for themselvesor as part of a collaborative effort in which others share in the resultinginnovation royalty. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>You mentioned &quot;innovation royalty.&quot; How does this work?  <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>An innovation is in itself a product, and has a value in the marketplace. It is logical, rational and moral to pay the innovator based on thevalue of their innovation in the market place. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>How would this be handled?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The innovator or innovators are paid a percentage of the amount savedor earned by the innovation. As an example, the royalty might be 5% of themarket value. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>But that could be a very large amount of money. Suppose the innovationsaved or earned &#163;2 million in a year. The innovator would then be paid&#163;100,000. Isn't that too much?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>A better suggestion might be that it is too little. It must be enoughto recover any costs to an innovator and leave them with enough left overto make them want to do it again.   <DD><BR>  <DD>For those who think it might be too much, if the payment was &#163;100,000and the company was left with &#163;1.9 million, that is a rather good returnon their investment. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Who determines the amount or percentage of an innovation royalty?  <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>It must be mutually agreed between the innovator(s) and the entitythat will use the innovation and earn money from it in the market place.  <DD><BR>  <DD>However, it must be remembered that the innovation is the propertyof the innovator(s). Just as it is immoral to use someone's car or othertangible property without their permission, so it is immoral to use theirintangible property without their permission.   <DD><BR>  <DD>It might appear to be rational in the short term to use innovationswithout the property of the owner, but in the long term it is both irrationaland immoral. Irrational because it either prevents people from innovating,or from disclosing their innovations. When this happens, both parties arelosers. With a proper system of innovation royalties, both parties are winners.</DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>You say that an innovation is the property of the individual who thoughtof it. What about the company for which the individual works?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>If there were a truly voluntary preservice agreement saying that innovationswere to be shared by individual and company this would be moral, but notvery rational for either party. It puts up a stumbling block to innovation,and it is better to leave it that the individual will disclose it firstto the company.   <DD><BR>  <DD>Common sense says that it would be better if individual and companyreached a mutually profitable agreement for the use of the innovation. Moralitysays that if they do not reach such an agreement, then the innovation remainsthe property of the innovator to do with as they wish, and that no one mayuse it without the express and explicit permission of the innovator.   <DD><BR>  <DD>Put yourself in either position and you will see that in the longterm this is the only situation that makes any sense. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>You used innovators in the plural sense. How do you handle the caseof multiple innovators for a single product?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The innovators must agree among themselves as to the percentage dueto each. This is easily done by simply and arbitrarily setting a value forone part of the innovation. Such as 100. Then look at another part and sayits value is half, or 50. Another part might be 250. Add up the numbersand divide the total by the value for each innovator to arrive at theirpercentage figure.   <DD><BR>  <DD>This same concept can be used when there is a modification to theoriginal product and a new innovator or innovators must be compensated.</DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]<HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>For how long must royalties be paid?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>This is up the innovator, but in principle they should be paid foras long as the innovation creates income in the market place.   <DD><BR>  <DD>It makes sense for both parties--innovator and company--that royaltiesshould continue for as long as the innovation earns money. From the standpointof the company, besides being moral, this insures the continued interestof the innovator in the earning power of the innovation.   <DD><BR>  <DD>It also provides the innovator with income which may allow the innovatorthe financial freedom to do what they apparently do best: Innovate.   <DD><BR>  <DD>If the company has treated the innovator well, then they have everyreason to expect the innovator will disclose new innovations to the company,offering them the right of first acceptance on new ideas. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>How long does the innovator own the innovation?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>In perpetuity. A thought, and the resulting idea and innovation alwaysbelongs to the thinker and innovator. The use of it may be &quot;licensed&quot;or allowed by the innovator, but ownership itself is perpetual and can neverbe transferred. The is inherent the universal and absolute definition ofprimary property. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>In this system people appear more like independent contractors ratherthan employees. Do you mean they don't receive a regular salary?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>No, they do not. They are paid according to what they produce, whichmeans their income would normally vary from period to period. By workingfaster and better (innovating) they can earn more and more money in thesame or less time. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>But what about job security?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>The present system of compensation based on Being There obscures thefact that--in reality and in the long term--the ability of each individualis the best job security.   <DD><BR>  <DD>However, strangely almost, this system offers a form a security thatthe old system does not offer. Let's suppose the individual has a problem,either short or long term. They do not produce as fast as &quot;average,&quot;or they are actually very slow. Yet when they finish the job it is finishedand there are no errors.   <DD><BR>  <DD>In principle, and certainly when the company is aware of this &quot;problem,&quot;they do not care how long it takes to do a job. Why? Because they pay onlyfor the market value of the job, which means their profit is assured atall times.   <DD><BR>  <DD>This factor explains why such a system is of great benefit to handicappedpeople, school leavers, and anyone without experience or above average abilities.</DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Before I ask you about handicapped people and school leavers, whatabout the problem of production control or production scheduling. Doesn'tthe disparity in working speeds create such a problem?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>We have already covered that above. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Okay, what about handicapped people, school leavers, and others withoutexperience? How does this system help them?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>As long as the company knows the production rate for various tasksand their associated products, individual rates become non-critical in theoverall picture. Each individual can work and learn at their own rate. Asthey do so, their productivity will generally increase. There is also thepossibility of doing other things, perhaps things--different tasks or jobs--forwhich they are better suited.   <DD><BR>  <DD>A company operating on this basis would lose nothing and have muchto gain by having people do whatever they are best at. There is no reasonwhy a person should not try new things. If it takes them many times theaverage time to do something the first time, the company does not lose,nor should the individual. Tackling a new job, a person might see a betterway to do it, then both are winners. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Can't companies exploit inexperienced or handicapped workers?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Companies do that now. However, in this system there would be lesschance of that. It is never exploitation to pay the person the market valueof a job. Any job that is worth doing, is worth determining the market valueof that job. And to pay someone less than value does no good for eitherparty, besides the fact it is immoral for the company to do such a thing.  <DD><BR>  <DD>As the usage of a system such as this proliferates, companies thatindulged in such behavior would receive a low &quot;credit rating&quot;in the market place, and customers and the &quot;super stars&quot; of productionor innovation would not want to deal with them. This is the moral marketin action.   <DD><BR>  <DD>On the other side, companies which treated inexperienced and handicappedpeople well would tend to attract the top producers and innovators who wouldfeel they have less hassle and greater chance of being treated well at sucha company. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Will such companies offer the usual health, education, pension andother benefits that old style companies offer?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>That would be up to the individual company, although as individualsregain control of their lives and destiny, they might want to expand thatto include handling such matters for themselves.   <DD><BR>  <DD>In reality, a person can devise and operate their own pension planand end up with considerably more money than companies normally offer inpension plans. This would be further augmented by the increased earningpower of individuals.   <DD><BR>  <DD>As an example, with an average performing investment even in today'schaotic market conditions, a person can end up with more than &#163;500,000in assets by investing as little as &#163;10 a week during a normal workinglife.   <DD><BR>  <DD>To attract top performers companies might create conditions favorableto the formation of investment clubs and insurance groups so that individualscould secure the best possible results in the market. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>What about holidays and vacations?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>This would be an individual thing between producer and company. Beingpaid based solely on error-free task completion, with advance notice andagreement there is no reason why an individual can not take off any timethey wish. Whether it is a matter of a few hours or months.   <DD><BR>  <DD>As individuals became more and more innovative--as would naturallyhappen--they would spend less and less time doing tangible, routine tasksand gain more control of their time. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Wouldn't such a compensation system mean that a person would not dosomething unless it was a defined task with a value attached to it?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Not really. Just as many people today do things today on speculationor risk, doing it as an investment in the future. Perhaps expecting theywill learn something from it, or by doing it they will be formally askedto do things for which they will be compensated. In fact, in this systemthere would probably be more of that because there would be more freedomto do such things, and more chance that by doing so the individual wouldderive benefit. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>How do you start such a compensation system?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>It is really no different than now, and would probably start basedon current compensation. This would be a natural starting, as there is infact some connection, however tenuous, between current compensation andits market value. Further, this relieves some of the trauma associated withgoing to compensation based on task completion. A person should receiveessentially the same compensation as before at a minimum, with the opportunityfor much more.   <DD><BR>  <DD>You can determine how long it would take a person with a certain amountof experience to do a task and how much such a person would normally earn.Then do the logical and pay them for errorfree completion of the task.   <DD><BR>  <DD>At the same time, also make an agreement as to how the results ofproductivity increases (other than by direct and obvious innovation) willbe shared. And, much more importantly, how innovation will be handled. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>You keep saying &quot;error-free&quot; task completion. What doesthis mean?   <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Just that. If an error is made the choice is either for the creatorto fix the error themselves, or to pay to have it done. Of course they mayalso do the task over again without the error. In this case, any wastedmaterials (unless the materials were provided by the producer) must be reimbursedalong with the cost of wasted services such as electricity, gas, use ofmachine tools, etc. which were for the account of the company. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Why this emphasis on errorfree task completion and the need for errorrectification and reimbursement of wasted materials and other resources?  <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>First, it is the only moral thing to do. Why should someone otherthan the errormaker pay for an error? Why should the company or fellow workerspay for it? Why should the consumer or customer pay for it?   <DD><BR>  <DD>Secondly, it gives individuals a proprietary interest in their workand their ability to do it correctly. It puts a premium on experience andability and--more importantly--is a basic method of learning. Volitionalbeings learn by making mistakes. As my teacher once said, &quot;Show mea person who has never made a mistake, and I will show you a person whohas never done anything.&quot;   <DD><BR>  <DD>The ideal thing of course is to do some advance thinking and not makea mistake, but this is often much easier to say than to do. However, themore a person does, the more mistakes they make, the more they learn, andthe more competent they become. </DL><HR><DL>  <DT><B>Question</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Would people then be responsible for their own training and education?  <DD><BR>  <hr>  <DT><B>Answer</B>   <DT><BR>  <DD>Yes. Who else should be? Who should have more of an interest in thesuccess of an individual than that individual?   <DD><BR>  <DD>This is not to say that companies should not or would not provideeducation and training. They could offer it is an incentive to associatewith that company, or offer it on a profit-making basis.   <DD><BR>  <DD>But when an individual's earning ability is directly related to anddependent only on their education, experience, imagination, ability, anddrive it is only natural that the individual would have a strong desirefor education. Self education. </DL><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE>&copy;1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation <BR><BR><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I> </CENTER><P><HR NOSHADE><B>Contact Information:</B><BR>E-Mail: administrator@Freedom-Server.co.uk<BR><HR>The URL of this page is: <BR><P><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Productivity.html&gt; <HRNOSHADE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
