<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>The Freedom Server - Press Articles</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><P><CENTER></HEAD><BODY><HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H1><CENTER>The Freedom Server&copy;</CENTER></H1><H4><CENTER>Second Edition</CENTER></H4><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE><A NAME="Press"></A></CENTER><H2><CENTER>Comments on Press Articles</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><HR NOSHADE><BR><BR>This page has been visited <BR><BR><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Press-Articles.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><BR><BR>since 1996, March 28. <BR></CENTER><P><HR NOSHADE>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, June 1<BR>Version: 002i <HR><H4><CENTER>| <A HREF="index.html">Home</A> | <A HREF="Contents.html">Tableof Contents</A>|</CENTER></H4><HR NOSHADE><BR><BR>The vast majority of articles published in so-called &quot;newspapers&quot;concern political events, or events having to do with property interference,and are thus almost totally insignificant in long term history. I had toinsert the &quot;almost&quot; because they are actually very detrimentalin the sense that readers believe the articles express normality and morality.The articles make the fact that societies based on coercion and its attendantproperty interference seem &quot;normal&quot; and acceptable. It has alwaysbeen that way, so it must be right. <BR><BR>By reviewing and discussing a very small cross-section of articles, withthe discussion based on semantic precision and absolute and unchanging definitions,it is my intent to induce readers into thinking about (with credit to FredericBastiat) &quot;that which is seen and that which is not seen.&quot; <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER>Events and Articles</CENTER></H3><LI><A HREF="#COABS">Creation of a &quot;Best Seller.&quot;</A> <BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#ABCD">Clinton to brand tobacco a &quot;drug.&quot;</A> <BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#EFGH">Is it too early to tell if Chirac is a &quot;statesman&quot;?</A><BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#FGHI">Judge strikes down Oregon's &quot;Assisted Suicide Law&quot;</A><BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#LUT">Boredom rules among Luton's rebel youth.</A> <BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#BRIBE">U. S. Federal Prosecutors bribe Oklahoma bombing suspect.</A><BR><BR><LI><A HREF="#MPD">Mad Cow Disease &amp; Mad PoliticianDisease</A> <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><H4><A NAME="COABS"></A>Creation of a &quot;Best Seller.&quot;</H4>A &quot;Best Seller&quot; has apparently been created by trickery ratherthan the usual marketing means. Of the approximately 230,000 copies soldto date by the publisher, at least 30,000 to 40,000 copies of <I>The Disciplineof the Market Leaders</I>, published by Addison-Wesley Publishing Company,have been purchased by an organization or agents for whom the authors haveconsulting agreements. There is <B>no</B> indication that the publisherwas involved in any of these shenanigans. I personally hold them in highregard. <BR><BR>The situation might not be so unusual except for the extent of the purchasesin this case. However, what interested me more was a comment in a storyon the event, saying that &quot;...it isn't clear whether such practiceswould be illegal, but publishers and booksellers say they are highly unethical.&quot;<BR><BR>I was wondering how unethical something must be in order to be &quot;highly&quot;unethical. More importantly, I was wondering if there are degrees of unethicalbehavior. Could it be said that something was 37% unethical? And, is this&quot;too unethical,&quot; or would it be okay if something were 49% unethical?That is still less than half, although I am not sure what it less than halfof. If you burned down 49% of your neighbor's house would you be considered&quot;49% unethical&quot;? Would Hitler be considered to be &quot;only,&quot;say, &quot;37.637% unethical&quot; because he was only responsible for thedeath of 50 million people, and his armies came into contact with some 60%more people than that? <BR><BR>According to the definitions I use, there are two cases only: 0% and 100%.Something is 100% ethical, or it is unethical. If is 0.0003% unethical,it is unethical. Such as if I destroy only one small tile on my neighbor'sroof. <BR><BR>Then there is the problem of which branch of ethics we are discussing. Ihave noticed that there seem to many different branches. I assume, althoughthe author did not clarify the matter, he was talking about &quot;publishingethics.&quot; Although he could have been talking about &quot;marketingethics, sales ethics, distribution ethics,&quot; etc. If you have read manyof my essays, you will know that there is only <B>one</B> definition ofethics, and that it applies to all volitional endeavors. <BR><BR>Finally, there as the mention of &quot;legality.&quot; Which means, didit conform all of the myriad of immoral decrees issued by one or more politicalstates based on coercion. As I have stated elsewhere, &quot;legality&quot;and morality are mutually exclusive concepts. <BR><BR>If you disagree with any of my statements, read some more essays and think.<BR><BR><HR><H4><A NAME="ABCD"></A>Clinton to brand tobacco a &quot;drug.&quot;</H4>According to a recent press article, someone named &quot;Clinton&quot; isproposing to &quot;brand&quot; tobacco as a &quot;drug.&quot; <BR><BR>Clinton, as an individual, can of course &quot;brand&quot; tobacco as anythinghe wishes, but since he is not--to my knowledge--a qualified physiologist,his opinion on this subject should be viewed with suspicion. As long ashe does not try to impose his ideas on anyone else, he has done nothingimmorgal. <BR><BR>However, in his function as the Ruler of the political entity known as &quot;UnitedStates of America,&quot; if he tries to impose his ideas on anyone elseusing his control of the police monopoly, then of course the action is immoral,resulting in property interference. I leave it to the reader to decide forthemselves how to name this act. <BR><BR>The use of tobacco has been demonstrated to be harmful to the human body,and thus irrational. It is not however immoral unless the act of using itis imposed by one individual on another. Then it is both irrational andimmoral, yet the decision of whether or not to use it must be a personal,freely-made decision by each individual. <BR><BR>In this case there appears to be another factor. For, as the article indicated,a major reason for this action and the proposed associated use of the policepowers of the political state to impose his personal decision on other individuals,is because he has been told--and apparently believes--that this will &quot;...sendhis popularity soaring.&quot; What this seems to mean is that it will buyvotes for him to continue as head of his local political r&eacute;gime.If this is true, then there is another factor which should be examined besideshis qualifications as a physiologist. <BR><BR>That is the nature of the transaction. What is being offered, and what isbeing purchased. The reason for this is that all interactions between volitionalbeings are property transaction. Some involve the exchange of intangibleproperty, others of tangible property. <BR><BR>Even helping a little old lady across the street is a property transaction.The person doing it provides--sells--the act of helping the lady safelyacross the street. In this case the seller voluntarily offers to providethe service, with the implication that the amount and type of payment--ifany--is a decision of the &quot;buyer.&quot; Most rational sellers wouldexpect no more payment than a verbal statement of &quot;thanks,&quot; andperhaps a smile. But this <B>is</B> in fact a payment, just as surely asif the lady had handed the person a $5 note. The former is an intangiblepayment, the latter a tangible one. It is the failure to recognize thisand understand what is happening--and why--that is a major part of the causeof our societal problems. <BR><BR>Now it becomes clear that there is a property transaction in The Ruler'saction. He &quot;offers&quot; an action--an offer that can not be refused--toclassify tobacco as a drug, with his payment to be votes to allow him tocontinue as head his local political r&eacute;gime. So that he does notjoin the ranks of the unemployed, and can continue to enjoy the &quot;perqs&quot;of his position of employment. When his subjects or victims perform suchan act &quot;privately,&quot; it has various descriptions that attract theattention of those operating the various police monopolies, often with undesirableeffects on such individuals. <BR><BR>However, Mr. Clinton should be congratulated on acknowledging that he, personally,is taking this action rather than ascribing it anonymously to &quot;Washington,&quot;&quot;the administration,&quot; &quot;the US,&quot; or other normal subterfugesused in politics to protect the guilty. He thus continues to ensure hisplace in history as a VIP--a <B>V</B>ery <B>I</B>nsignificant <B>P</B>erson.<BR><BR><HR><H4><A NAME="EFGH"></A>Is it too early to tell if Chirac is a &quot;statesman&quot;?</H4>According to a recent press article, Chirac, the Ruler of France, is nowthe envy of less competent people at ruling such as Mr. William Clintonwho--to endear himself to his subjects and appear to be a &quot;nice guy&quot;(a requirement for being a ruler in a &quot;democratic&quot; r&eacute;gime)--prefers to associate himself with the &quot;common people&quot; by havingeveryone call him just plain &quot;Bill.&quot; I somehow doubt that evenMr. Chirac's close associates call him &quot;Jack.,&quot; let alone lesserindividuals. I don't remember anyone referring to G&eacute;n&eacute;ralde Gaulle as &quot;Charlie.&quot; The fact that this is true already arguesfor his descension to the rank of &quot;statesman.&quot; <BR><BR>There should be no doubt that Chirac is certainly in a position to havethe supreme dishonor of having the negative accolade of &quot;statesman&quot;applied to him. He, like Louis XV, clearly believes that &quot;the state--that'sme.&quot; He does not appear to need--or even to want--the approval of TheRuling Family Council. Of &quot;advisors&quot; who might only confuse himwith their own ideas of how to interfere in the property of others. Notonly his own direct subjects, but even those of his fellow Rulers. He appearsto want to make it absolutely clear that he and he alone is clearly responsiblefor any and all immoral acts of the French politcal state thus staking animmediate claim to descension to the top negative importance levels in history.<BR><BR><HR><H4><A NAME="FGHI"></A>Judge strikes down Oregon's &quot;Assisted SuicideLaw&quot;</H4>A recent report says the Federal Judge Michael Hogan has struck down the&quot;Assisted Suicide Law&quot; of the political entity known as &quot;Oregon.&quot;An action such as this would not normally be remarkable. What distinguishesthis action is the associated comment that &quot;Certain fundamental rightsmay not be dispensed with by a majority vote.&quot; Such as statement, inassociation with the action is mind-numbing. There are so many thoughtscreated that it is hard to sort them out. <BR><BR>One idea is that I thought I distinctly remembered that the United Stateswas based on the concept that the &quot;majority&quot; of the &quot;people&quot;made the political laws. That one reason why the United States was establishedwas to avoid the situation of one individual making an arbitrary decisionthat effection the lives of all subjects of the particular r&eacute;gime.The fact that Judge Hogan said it violated a part of the U. S. Constitutionis of no significance, since the &quot;people,&quot; the majority he dismissedwith a whim, are the ultimate law of the land. <BR><BR>Another thought is the Judge's ignorance of the concept of funamental rights.One of which is the sanctity of property and the sovereign right of eachvolitional being to make their own decisions regarding the conduct of theirlife as long as it does not involve interference in the property of another.I realize that the U. S. Constitution itself does this, but following theconstitution rather than what is moral is no different than a Goreing orHimmler following Hitler. <BR><BR>Yet it is still the tragi-comedy of Judge Hogan dispensing with the willor the majority--a concept that established the mechanism within which heworks--that is the most outrageous. It bears out the statement of GeorgeOrwell, when he said &quot;Doublethink means the power of holding two contradictorybeliefs in one's mind simultaneously, and accepting both of them.&quot;<BR><BR>What Judge Hogan has said is that &quot;...now that you have set up thesystem, I will run at as I please. You have now lost total control of themechanism and it is <B>me</B> who is the supreme one around here, not you.&quot;This is no different than Louis XIV saying, &quot;The state--that's me.&quot;Many people worry about a future in which we build computers who will thenturn around and become out master, and have no more need for human beings.With a system that permits--and even encourages--actions such as that ofJudge Hogan. <BR><BR>This again illustrates why political judges rate a -10 on a scale of ten,being even more dangerous and insignificant in history than are Chief'sof State. KIng George III would be green with envy, as he would not haveimagined such political power. Even Ghengis Khan, for different reasons,would also be green with envy. With the stroke of a pen the lives of millionsof people are decided. What would he do with his unemployed &quot;hordes&quot;?<BR><BR><HR><H4><A NAME="LUT"></A>Boredom rules among Luton's rebel youth</H4>During July Luton experienced nights of rioting, with youths battling police.Their complaints apparently having to do with the fact they have no jobs,and the political state is not listening to them, aware of their needs,and doing nothing about it. <BR><BR>Children spoke of their frustration, say &quot;There's nothing for us todo here.&quot; A 40 year old father of five said, &quot;This is one of theworst places you would want to live.&quot; <BR><BR>Sadly, and as most people who read the newspapers know, this situation isnot restricted to any one country, but is a pervasive factor in many societies.The fact that the cause should be obvious, and the solution simple has notbeen recognized. Anyone who looks rationally at history and understandshuman nature should be able to come up with the cause and solution. Yet,at the same time, I know that once this information is presented, almosteveryone will say &quot;No, that's too simple. That can't be it.&quot; Nevertheless,it is worth a try... <BR><BR>The problem is attributable to: <OL>  <LI>In coercion-based societies, it is inevitable that people increasinglylose control of individual life and destiny;   <LI>As this happens, they take irrational action to correct this situation;  <LI>Our system of production compensation (payment for work) is basedon an irrational concept, making jobs unavailable for a large segment ofthe population. </OL>Let's take these in order. The first is a natural consequence of a societalstructure in which people are increasingly deprived of their right and <B>need</B>to make decisions regarding the conduct of their own individual lives. Avolitional being needs this for two reasons: <BR><OL>  <LI>It is the dominant way of learning. To try things, make the occasionalmistake, and to learn what works and what does not work;   <LI>It is necessary for the building of competence and self-esteem. </OL>As individuals increasingly loss control of their individual life, and thereforethe ability to build an increasingly better life for themselves and otherindividuals who may rely on them for these factors, they become depressed,irritated, and frustrated. With the increasing sense of loss of controlin being able to sustain and increase a quality life, an individual eventuallyreaches the point at which they become willing to take any actions necessaryto try to alleviate this feeling and vent their frustrations, and to tryto &quot;right the wrongs&quot; in their life. Eventually, concepts of rationalityand morality fall by the wayside, with the person feeling they no longerhave anything to lose. <BR><BR>On the other hand, people who feel that they have control over their individuallives, and that the quality of life tomorrow will be at least as good astoday, and perhaps better, such people are unlikely to take any &quot;anti-social&quot;acts that will have a negative impact on this situation. <BR><BR>The fact that the youths (and many other people) find themselves unemployed,and with little prospect of improving their lives, can also be attributedto the current, defective concept of production compensation. A system Icall <I>Being There</I>, in which people are compensated almost solely onthe basis of their presence in the workplace. Under this system, peoplewho take longer than a certain &quot;average,&quot; prescribed time to dothings, can not find work. Even while there is no shortage of things tobe done. Of course the existence of the so-called &quot;minimum wage&quot;laws only exacerbates this situation. When I was a child I had no problemin finding a job, since employers could pay me a wage that reflected myvalue in the marketplace. Which is the answer to the problem of findingjobs. Along the way, it vastly increases productivity, innovation, and quality.<BR><BR>The basic reason a person is not acceptable for a certain job is that itis believed they will not create value in the marketplace with an acceptablerelationship to their cost. A human worker is no different in principlethan an inanimate material or commodity. Something which must be &quot;purchased&quot;at a price such that it can be &quot;sold&quot; at a profit. <BR><BR>Therefore, the principle is: <UL><CITE>Production compensation must be based <B>solely</B> on the marketvalue of error-free production. <BR></CITE></UL>A further discussion of why this is so, how to implement such a system,and the results thereof, appear in the <I>Productivity Galore</I>&copy;essays available in the near future. They have existed for years, but willnot be published here for a few weeks at least. You can gain an overviewof the concept by readin the <A HREF="Productivity.html">Productivity FAQ</A>Document. <BR><BR><HR><H4><A NAME="BRIBE"></A>U. S. Federal Prosecutors bribe Oklahoma bombingsuspect.</H4>Press reports say that a former army buddy of the prime suspect in the bombingof the Federal Building in Oklahoma has agreed to cooperate with federalprosecutors to avoid being charged as a principle participant. Mr. MichaelFortier has agreed to testify against Mr. Timothy McVeigh in exchanged forthe prospect of a much lighter sentence. <BR><BR>This is referred to as &quot;plea bargaining&quot; in criminal circles.Yet a close examination of the event reveals it is what would be calleda &quot;bribe&quot; if it were done by someone other than an agent of apolitical r&eacute;gime. The transaction is a &quot;payment for servicesrendered,&quot; which is the operative definition of &quot;bribe.&quot;It only acquires it's sinister image when it is an action the politicalr&eacute;gime does not like. Or, when a non-member of such a r&eacute;gimepays a member of the r&eacute;gime for a &quot;service rendered,&quot; thenit becomes a bribe, and the non-r&eacute;gime person becomes a &quot;criminal.&quot;But, since political r&eacute;gimes make the rules, when <B>they</B> bribesomeone, then--voil&agrave;!--it is no longer illegal and not a crime. <BR><BR>Why must the rules change? In the absence of fraud or coercion, and in amutually agreed transaction, payment for a service is always moral. However,once political states and their associated agents get involved in a transaction,rules always changed. People who were criminals become victims, and peoplewho were victims become criminals. Such inconsistencies make the world difficultto understand... <BR><BR><HR><H4><A NAME="MPD"></A>Mad Cow Disease &amp; Mad Poliician Disease</H4>Who should be disposed of--the cows or the politicians--the ruling familycouncil. Who is the most dangerous to mankind? <BR><BR>People in the UK tribal areas are now concerned with something which ispopularly called &quot;Mad Cow Disease,&quot; medically known as &quot;bovinespongiform encephalopathy&quot; (BSE). They are concerned because of a possibleconnection with a human disease known as &quot;Creutsfeldt-Jakob Disease(CJD). In humans it is currently incurable. <BR><BR>The problem is that there is a possibility--as yet not verified--that BSEmay be communicated to humans and appear as CJD as a result of eating cow'smeat. There have been about 6-8 cases of CJD in the UK which alarmists aretrumpeting as being caused by eating cow's meat that <I>could</I> have beeninfected with BSE. <BR><BR>How many people have died in this century as a result of the acts of politicians?In the two World Wars there were probably 70-80 million who died. Who knowshow many died in China during the rule of &quot;Chairman&quot; Mao? Certainlyten's of millions when you consider those who died of famine as a resultof being sent to the countryside for &quot;re-education&quot; and thosewho &quot;routinely&quot; died of famine and other politically-induced diseases.<BR><BR>People in the UK are worrying about the <B>possibility</B> that 6-8 peoplewho have died of CJD <B>may</B> have been infected by eating cow's meat,while we know that several hundred did die as a result of the war in theFalklands. Perhaps the politicians in the UK were not the direct cause ofthe war, but if not, the one's in the Argentine tribal areas surely were.<BR><BR>As always in the political environment--as opposed to rational and durablesocietal mechanism--there must be winners and losers. And, as always, oneof the losers are the victims of tax theft, who must compensate farmersfor the cattle who will be butchered. An action which the National FarmersUnion sanctions. <BR><BR>The National Farmers Union sanctions this because the beef industry in theUK has been in decline in recent years, and there are already excess cattle.When the farmers are compensated for the butchering of their cattle, thiswill then allow them to go out of business without declaring bankruptcy.The result will be a shortage of beef, since the market WILL recover somewhat,and beef prices will then be higher than before. Thus we create anotherset of losers, those who wish to continue eating beef. <BR><BR>The winners? Well, there are only <I>apparent</I> winners in the short term,the politicians. They will be seen to have again saved mankind. What isnot seen is that they are the ones who created the problem in the beginning.And of course in the long term it is all of mankind which loses, includingthe politicians, as the specie heads inexorably into demise. Caused by &quot;MadPolitician Disease.&quot; Aided by their victims, who don't even seem torealize there is something wrong, let alone the cause of the problem. <BR><BR>It is time for people to realize the true source of all of man's miserieson this planet. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>] <HR NOSHADE><BR>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation <BR><BR><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I> <BR></CENTER><P><HR><B>Contact Information:</B><BR>E-Mail: administrator@Freedom-Server.co.uk<BR><HR>The URL of this page is: <BR><P><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Press-Articles.html&gt; <BR><HR NOSHADE></CENTER></BODY></HTML>
