table></center><p>Thoughts produced by the motion picture <i>Land of the Pharaohs</i>, starringJack Hawkins and Joan Collins, answer the cause of many of the societalproblems of man.  And point to the solution.</p><p>The film is a fictionalized account of the life of the Pharaoh Khufu. Virtually from the moment of becoming Pharaoh he begins to plan for histomb.  To provide him with security for his body, and the food andother items necessary for his journey into and through the afterlife. And to ensure that the memory of his existence is preserved for alltime.</p><p>Most human  beings, at least in the latter part of their lives, beginto think of what they have accomplished in life, the purpose andmeaning of their life, and wonder if and how they will be remembered. Some make a conscious effort to ensure they will be remembered.</p></p>Yet--and this is a major thought of this essay--those who are trulyimportant in history need take no steps to ensure they will beremembered.  The corollary to this is that if a person is not trulyimportant, they can do nothing to ensure they will be remembered in thelong term.  For the purpose of this discussion I will define "longterm" as being 2,000 years or more.  The reason for this concerns thelives of Cicero and Marcellus, which I will discuss later.</p><p>	When we think of important people in history, what type of persongenerally comes to mind?  Most people would probably think first ofgenerals and politicians.  And perhaps religious figures.  This isreinforced by history books, encyclopedias, and the statues andmonuments found all over the planet.  Including of course the pyramidsof Egypt, probably the most spectacular of physical monuments.<p>	The reason for emphasizing the word "physical" also involves a centralthought of this essay, for I maintain that the truly spectacularmonuments are those which are largely intangible.  Not physical in thesense of being a statue or monument.<p>	Since we are talking about the concept of importance, perhaps I shouldoffer a definition.  Definitions are necessary to ensure effective,precise communication.  If I mean one thing by a word, and you assume adifferent meaning, then we can not communicate effectively.<h4>Importance</h4><p><a name="1r"></p><ul>"A measure of the amount of property<a href="#1">[1]</a> created or effected."</ul><p>	As a matter of interest, and for possible use in this essay,I would like to also provide a definition of urgency, which is closelyrelated to the concept of importance.<h4>Urgency</h4><ul>"A measure of the amount of property created or effected relative to thetime involved."</ul><p>	It should be noted from the definition of importance there isthe possibility of negative importance, which would be associated withthe destruction of property.  I shouldn't need to mention that thedestruction of property is something not to be desired and should notbe considered to be a "noble" act or purpose of life of an individualvolitional being.  If you think about it, such an objective or purposeis not consistent with volitional life.  No progress could be made ifthe objective--or even a major function--was to create and then destroyproperty.  Which of course is one of the reasons why our currentsocietal structures are in decay.  We seem to enjoy creating andbuilding things, and then destroying them.  Much as a two year oldchild does.  Including cities and even entire countries and groups ofpeople, as in World War Two.	<p>	Yet when we read history books and encyclopedia, who are the featuredheroes?  The ones who get the most pages?  I think it would bereasonably accurate to say that, as a rule of thumb, the more propertydestroyed--including human lives--the longer the encyclopedia entry andthe more books and articles written about the person.	<p>	Conversely, it almost seems the greater the property creation,especially when it is intangible property such a knowledge, the smallerthe entry in the encyclopedia.  Although in fairness, such people oftenhave a large number of book written about them.  But I would argue thatas a relative thing, they have far fewer books written about them.	<p>	For example, contrast the work of Heinrich Hertz, James ClarkMaxwell, and Nikola Tesla vs. Alexander of Macedon and Napoleon. Hertz, Maxwell, and others are responsible for creation of theknowledge which has provided us with radio and modern communications,and television.  While the work of Tesla--as the inventor of alternatingcurrent technology--lights and powers the world.	<p>	I have not looked recently and don't really remember the numberof pages in, for example, the Encyclopedia Britannica, devoted to eachof the above people.  But, since I am talking principles and the exactnumber is not important, I think it is safe to say that many more pagesare devoted to the politicians--civil, military and religious--than totruly important people.  Those who create property.	<p>	What was the basic characteristic of the work of the two groups? Alexander and Napoleon destroyed property and lives--with life being aform of property)--and generally reduced the quality of life. Especially for those who died and whose property was destroyed.  But itwent beyond that, as Napoleon impoverished France and Europe for acentury.  That was his legacy for mankind.<p>	The work of the other group--the so-called "scientists"--createdknowledge which could add to the quality of life.  I said "could" onlybecause when it does not it is usually also due to the other group--thepoliticians.  They often use it to destroy property and lives andrestrict its ability to be used for the betterment of mankind.<p>	There is another characteristic of people such as Alexander, GenghisKhan, Napoleon and Hitler.  There are all serial killers.  And serialproperty destroyers.  The phrase and elucidation of the concept is ofmodern derivation, usually meant for a private killer.  Someone who isnot empowered to kill people through the political process.  Since Ihave used the word and concept of politics and wish to elaborate onthat in the context of the discussion, I will provide a definition ofthat word and concept:	<h4>Politics</h4><ul><p>	"A system in which one group of people called politicians controlthe lives and property of other people."</ul><p><a name="2r"></p><p>	This is the basic characteristic of a political group or entity. How this control is achieved or who and how many people are controlledis immaterial.  Whether it is one person who has effective control or asmall group, and whether the person or group assume the control throughforce or are appointed by members of the group is also immaterial and amatter of style not effecting the principle.  The concepts of socialismand communism and whether the state merely controls the property oftheir victims or professes to own<a href="#2">[2]</a> it are also amatter of style in that it represents a degree of control, and notwhether there is or is not control over the lives and property ofothers.  Whether there is freedom or slavery. 	<p>	Now that I have used the words freedom and slavery, perhaps Ishould provide a definition of those:	<h4>Freedom</h4><ul>"The societal condition that exists when every individual has 100% controlover their own property."</ul><H4>Slavery</h4><ul>"Seizure or control of the property of an individual without their consent."</ul><p>	I should not have needed to emphasize the word <i>own</i> inthe definition of freedom, but it is so common for people to controlthe property of others without their permission that I felt itnecessary.  And, I think I must again comment on the permission ofconsent in controlling the property of others.  With slavery, the mostobvious property controlled is that of the person enslaved--theirphysical body.  Although by doing so you are effectively controllingthe remainder of any tangible property they may own.<p>	There is a great difference in allowing a friend to use yourproperty, and in empowering the political state to control yourproperty through the process of voting.  This could be moral, althoughperhaps irrational, but what is immoral is that at the same time youalso appoint and allow the state to control the property of otherpeople.  The fact that they have done the same for your property andthat of others does not make the act moral.  There is also the matterof what item or property is controlled, how much of it is controlled,the extent of control, and when.  These questions are left open when weonce say it is okay for one person or group to control the property ofothers.  Rather than carry on with a detailed discussion of thisconcept, I will leave it for the reader to think more about it if theywish.<p>	Since time immemorial it has been considered almost necessaryand "normal" for man the specie to engage in war, to kill others of thespecie and destroy their property.  Although this was and is onlyconsidered acceptable when the political entity of the individualsinvolved declared war on another such entity.  To kill as a privatematter was not considered acceptable.  As Voltaire said,</p><p><a name="3r"></p><ul>	"It is forbidden to kill...unless to trumpets."<a href="#3">[3]</a></ul><p>	It is the acceptance of the concept of politics that empowerspeople to kill other people and to destroy their property.  And to takecontrol of it, perhaps for days or centuries.  And it empowersindividuals such as an Alexander or Napoleon to be serial killers.  Andto then be venerated and honored in history for their deeds.<p>	Not everyone who goes into politics has aspirations of becominga serial killer, although there should be--but is not--thought they areembarking on an immoral enterprise.  Many who enter politics think onlyof "doing good" for others, yet the mechanism they select is defectiveand both immoral and irrational.  Further, politics is a great seducer. As answering the siren call of Lorelei, the trappings of power--theability to control things and people--eventually seduces and corruptsalmost all.<p>	There is only the occasional great man who can, because of thenecessity of protecting their own lives and property, and that of theirfriends and group, acquire great power and--when the emergency isover--relinquish it.  And even refuse the insistence of others to carryon controlling their lives and property.  An individual such as PubliusCornelius Scipio--the great and important <i>Scipio Africanus</i>.<p>	When Carthage attacked Rome starting the Second Punic War, killingScipio's father and threatened Rome itself, the young Scipio--barely outof school--offered to take command of the shattered Roman armies inSpain when no one else would take the apparently hopeless job.<p>	Within four years Carthage had been routed from Spain and Hannibal'sbrother killed.  Scipio then turned his attention to Hannibal's owncity, even though Hannibal was still virtually at the gates of Rome. By so doing, and then defeating at the Battle of Zama the man manyconsider to be the greatest general in history, ended the war.  Scipiothen refused to sack Carthage and had his defeated enemy appointedmilitary governor of his own country.<p>	For his great victory, Scipio was of course accorded a Triumph. He was also offered the position as sole ruler of the Roman Empire forlife. Which at that time was ruled by a trio of consuls, one of whombecame nominal ruler on a rotating one year basis.  At the age of onlythirty-five, Scipio refused, saying...</p><p><a name="4r"></p><ul>"No man should rule other men, and certainly not for alifetime."<a href="#4">[4]</a></ul><p>	Yet we live in such a miasma of falsehoods that we believe theonly way to solve the problems of mankind and to regulate individualsocietal behavior is through coercion.  Through societal structuresbased on coercion, whether their style is democratic or dictatorial,socialist or communist.  The latter two are more economic concepts thanpolitical, although all depend on controlling the lives and property ofothers.  Dictatorial and democratic involve the style of choosing theleader and/or ruling group, not whether there will be coercion.<p>	The concept of fraud enters the picture when a ruler or r&eacute;gimeuse mind control--often euphemistically called education--to convincetheir victims that something is other than what it is.  Thus we equatedemocracy and freedom, when they mutually exclusive concepts.  Weconvince people they are free when in fact almost all decisionsregarding their lives are not under their control.  Even when they seemto be.  We tell people their "education" is "free."  We tell them thatby going to war they will ensure freedom.  We refer to killing peoplein war--and even without war--as "wasting" them.  This avoids theunpleasantness of having to think we have murdered them.<p>	We mesmerize people into  believing that giving away freedom ofaction will preserve individual freedom.  Or provide safety from crime. Yet as we give away ever more freedom, crime increases.  We believethere is a difference between a tax collector confiscating money andthe actions of a burglar or thief.  That the one who tries to stop andapprehend a burglar is a hero, while the one to tries to stop a taxcollector is a criminal.<p>	Our entire social structure is based on such fallacies and fantasies. A truly fabulous system--a system based on fables and superstitions. And, like the thousands building pyramids for Pharaoh, we sing as welabor under the whip, toiling to support the state.<p>	Who then is important?  And what are their monuments?  This brings tomind the beautiful statement of the son of Christopher Wren, who said:</p><p><a name="5r"></p><ul>	"...Lector, Si monumentum requiris, circumspice..."<a href="#5">[5]</a></ul><p>	This monument--St. Paul's Cathedral--is an intellectual idea whichhas been transformed into something tangible.  And, in a sense, this isno different than a Sony Walkman, which is also a monument, although toand created by many different people.  The technology required to buildit comes from thousands of people over as many years, each of whomcreated knowledge which led to the creation of new and additionalknowledge.<p>	Almost as a first thing, it required some way to catalogue andpreserve knowledge as it was created.  Thus those involved in thecreation of language, writing, and "printing"--even including chiselingsomething into stone or writing on a papyrus scroll--were involved atthe very beginning of the knowledge and technology that would lead to aWalkman.<p>	Of course there are more obvious and well known people involvedalso, such as Galileo, Newton, Faraday, Hertz, Maxwell and the peopleinvolved in materials technology.  With credit to one of the two mostimportant people who ever lived, Andrew J. Galambos, I would call thisgroup of people and the knowledge they created, the ideologicalflowstream of history.  These are the people who comprise themainstream of history, and not those who destroy and control theproperty of others.<p>	It also required knowledge in business.  How to bring people togetherin a cooperative business effort to create and manufacture a product. Knowledge of production engineering and product assembly, ofcontrolling product quality.  Of finance and advertising.<p>	To see their monuments you need only look around you.  In tangibleform it is the products of our modern technological world.  Thematerial things and the knowledge represented by them which have thepotential to add to the quality of life of each individual human being. I said potential because some times, and for various reason, they donot.  Or at least the full potential is not realized when it could andshould be.  Such as when the political state interferes, for example inhealthcare, although I do not wish to pursue this branch of thoughthere.<p>	Sadly, many people, while accepting the degradation of individuallife caused by the concept of politics, then clamor and rail againsttechnology.  Even while accepting it, perhaps surreptitiously.  Theylike the fact they can flick a switch and have light, to watchtelevision, to travel to a far corner of the world on jet aircraft, butthen complain about other aspects of technology.	<p>	Conveniently forgetting that with the products of technology andbusiness you have a choice.  You can buy a toaster or not buy one.  Orany one of a variety of toasters.  You can travel to the other side ofthe world on a jet or walk or not go at all.  But with the "product" ofthose to whom we raise statues and monuments--the politicians--you haveno choice.  You must accept their "product" or "service" under penaltyof punishment for not doing so.  You must either do as they say, or notdo something which is prohibited.  Until recent decades it wasgenerally assumed that if something was not prohibited you could do it. Now the prevailing concept is that unless something is specificallypermitted, you may not do it.<p><a name="6r"></p><p>	I mentioned Archimedes and Marcellus.  About 2200 years agothe name of Marcellus was known throughout the world, at least theRoman world, which comprised most of the "known world."<ahref="#6">[6]</a>  The name of Archimedes was virtually unknown outsideof Sicily.  This was the situation at the time a soldier of Marcellus,albeit against the instructions of Marcellus, murdered the old manArchimedes--the <i>Sand Reckoner</i>--as he sketched an idea in the sand.<p>	Now, 2200 years later, the situations are reversed.  Archimedesis more well known and respected (and for the right reasons) than isMarcellus.  And, ironically, we originally learned of the existence ofArchimedes through Plutarch's Life of Marcellus.  Now Marcellus islargely remembered because of Archimedes and the fact his troopsmurdered him.<p>	Who is important in history?  Why?  Who should  be our heroes,and who should we emulate?  Which are the acceptable monuments for athinking specie?  Those who create property and give us a choicewhether to use it or accept it?  Or those who destroy property? Property which may have taken millennia of slow, painfully-acquiredknowledge to create.  From where do we receive value in life?  Thosewhose main ambition and ability in life is to control the lives andproperty of others?  Those who destroy property?  Or those who createit?<p>	I leave the decision--and the fate of our civilization and specie--inyour mind and hands.</p>	<hr noshade><h4>Version History</h4><p>Version 01: 1997, January 19</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>	For this discussion, please understand that I	mean both tangible and intangible property, such as knowledge	and ideas.		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>	Ownership is a moral concept which can not	be achieved through theft and confiscation, although control	can be acquired in this manner.  If we truly allowed theft to	confer ownership it would make a shamble of the concept of	"civilization."		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>	Voltaire  [Francois Marie Arouet]  {1694 -1778}	<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>	Although eventually, to honor the men who	died defeating the aggressor, he did accept for a year.  During	which he did precious little ruling.  After which he retired to	his villa at Liternum.		<a href="#4r">Return</a><p><a name="5"><li>	[...Reader, if you seek his monument, look	around...].	Inscription in St. Paul's Cathedral, London (Written by his son.	 It should therefore be properly ascribed to his son, but I do	not know the son's name at the moment, however the gratitude for this	beautiful tribute goes to him.)		<a href="#5r">Return</a><p><a name="6"><li>	I do not mean to slight the Chinese, the Eastern	World, and others.  Although if we look at the sumtotal of positive	human knowledge, the vast majority of it came from the socalled	Western World, of which Rome and the Roman world was the center	at that time.		<a href="#6r">Return</a></ol>	<HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Land-of-Pharaohs.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
