<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Origin & Purpose of Religions</TITLE>	<META Name="AU" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META HTTP-EQUIV Name="Keywords"		CONTENT="Galambos, government, coercion, capitalism, 			history, Bedeman, keyword, keyword, keyword, keyword">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corporation Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, September 23<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Origin-Purpose-Religions.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, September 18, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><h3>The Origin, Purpose and Use of Religions</h3><h4>and</h4><h3>The Decline of Civilization</h3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4><hr noshade><h4>Synopsis</h4><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="80%"><tr>	<td>All volitional species will develope the concept of a god	during their primitive stage of development.  However, the concept	presents an opportunity for mischief and must be quickly discarded	else the specie will not make the transition to a rational and	durable societal structure.  Using the universal  laws of volitional	behavior it is possible to prove that god is not volitional and, in	fact, that god can exist only as a figment of human	imagination.	</td></tr></table><h4>Definitions</h4></center><ul><li><b>Absolute</b><p>That which is independent of arbitrary standards of measurement.</p><li><b>Confidence</b><p>Belief that something will happen based on rational reasons and validthought processes...</p><li><b>Equality</b> (in a societal sense)<p>Born and existing under the laws of nature, and havimg unrestricted accessto nature.</p><li><b>Faith</b><p>Belief that something will happen based on irrational reasons and invalidthought processes...</p><li><b>Intellectual Honesty</b><p>The ability to accept a theory which, by definition is right on an absolutebasis, when it conflicts with existing hypotheses on the subject.</p><li><b>True</b><p>That which is observable.</p><li><b>Valid</b><p>Having a conclusion derived from true premises.</p></ul><center><h4>Background</h4></center><p>As Voltaire said,</p><p><a name="1r"></p><center><p>"Si Dieu n'esistait pas, il faudrait l'inventer"<a href="#1">[1]</a></p></center><p>	The obvious truth is that man did invent the concept of a godand gods.  In fact, I would say it is a universal law of nature thatprimitive volitional beings everywhere would and must invent theconcept of a god.  This is consistent with the basic, natural need of avolitional being--a being capable of thought, reasoning, anddiscrimination--to have a feeling of "security" about its world beforeit can venture into that world to learn more about it.<p>	It seems that I have given you the answer to the origin and purposeof religions before we hardly got started.  Yet there are still thingsto discuss, such as the use of the concept of religion and theassociated implications for the survival of the specie<p>	I have long thought that it was fruitless to try to prove theexistence or non-existence of God.  Also that it was possible to provethat God was not volitional, which I can now do.  The concept that Godmight be anthropomorphic seemed so ridiculous as to not be worthy ofdiscussion.  First I will discuss:<p><ul><li>The origin of religion<p>This mostly answers its purpose, although I may spend a few minutes on that.</p><li>The use of religion.<p>This is the most depressing part of religion: How it has been used for thebetterment of its users, and the to the detriment of the lives of itsvictims.  Ultimately, as used by the political state, both as a concept ofreligion and of the technique of fraud which accompanies it, and then as amajor factor in the demise of civilization itself.</p><li>The Consequences of Religious Beliefs<p>Faith and confidence, and what believing in religion does to a person.</p><li>Then I will promulgate the proof that God is not volitional, and therefore	can not exercise any form of control over human beings or any other	component of any universe or world.<li>Lastly, religion, mysticism, and the decline of civilization</ul><center><h4>Origin and Purpose of the Concept of Religion</h4></center><p><a name="2r"></p><p>	Imagine yourself suddenly transported to a new and differentworld.  A world where nothing made sense to you.  Strange andinexplicable things were happening. Things you did not and could notunderstand.  A truly "alien" world in which there was no obviousconnection between cause and effect.  And you could not communicatewith any of the few other volitional beings you encountered.  Imaginethe planet Aristarchus<a href="#2">[2]</a> at the dawn of volitionallife.<p>	You would be very wary of venturing forth into this world.  Sometimesit was dark and you could see almost nothing.  Other times there was somuch light it hurt your eyes.  It was hot and then cold, wet and thendry.  Animals appeared from nowhere, some of them bigger than you.  Andwith an obvious interest in knowing more about you.  Perhaps even howyou tasted.<p>	There was lightning and thunder.  The appearance of the skyfilled you with foreboding, although you weren't sure why. Sometimeseverything was green, and gathering food was simple.  Other times itwas dry, a veritable wasteland, and survival relatively much moredifficult.  Occasionally there were fearsome fires, over which you hadno control.  When it had dwindled to almost nothing you found it verynice and not so fearsome, yet didn't know how to create it if it was nolonger there.<p>	So many things you did not understand that it almost seemedpreferable to not venture forth and try to learn something about themyriad of seemingly incomprehensible things.  Even moreincomprehensible and filling a person with trepidation than unboxingand contemplating your first computer when they were truly primitivethings.  Or someone with no automotive experience contemplating astalled car miles from any possible help.  A very helpless "... where tobegin" feeling.<p>	In order to function in an alien, seemingly incomprehensibleenvironment, a volitional being must feel that they understandsomething, else they are unlikely to make an attempt at acquiringknowledge and learning.  Even when it involves everything of theirworld.  This was the situation of the earliest thinking beings on thisplanet<p>	Another, and in a sense more significant problem, was the lackof knowledge on how to acquire knowledge.  Coupled with a mechanism forpreserving knowledge once it was created.  An ever-increasing body ofknowledge upon which to build.  When the only method for "storing"knowledge was in the minds of living people, this is a tremendousproblem and handicap.  Imagine a situation in which each new generationwould be required to listen to people recite what was known and to tryto build on that.  And when something was not remembered, or notremembered correctly, to be required to learn or discover thatknowledge  all over again.  A great impediment to  knowledge creationand accumulation.<p>	This was the story of our specie for the first 4-5 million years. Only in the last one hundred years have we really acquired the abilityto create and store knowledge in a form which is available to nearlyeveryone so they can use it as the basis for creating additional newknowlege.  This time period represents 0.002% of the period of ourevolution.  If we equated 5 million years to the number of minutes in ayear, this would say that we only truly acquired the ability--on a massscale, available to almost everyone--to store knowledge and make itavailable on a mass scale in the past 10 minutes.<p>	From the requirement that living people be the respositories ofknowledge, the concept of the "hearing" came into our language.  In theMiddle Ages and before, when there was some sort of disagreement,people went to a "hearing" to hear what was known, as there was nothingpreserved in writing.  Now that we have printing and various means ofpreserving things visually we could refer to them as "readings" or"seeings" because that technology is available.  But it is still "Hearye, hear ye ..."	<center><h4>The Tribal Chief and the Witch Doctor</h4></center><p>	For as far back as we have written records there were tribes andtribal chiefs, and also the witch doctor.  We can only make asupposition as to which came first, but I would venture that it is thetribal chief who came first, although followed very closely by thewitch doctor.	<h4>The Tribal Chief</h4><p>	I believe that the concept of the tribal chief came first because ourevolutionary ancestors developed brawn before brain capacity.  Becauseall human beings and their ancestors were created equally (but notequal) under the laws of nature, this means that some were strongerthan others.  It would be natural that one among a group would rise toassume a position of dominance.  Whether it was one of benevolence andcare for the others, or simply that control of others meant an easierlife for the leader.  This is consistent with the First Law ofVolitional Behavior which says that:</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="80%"><tr><td align=center>	Individual volitional beings seek to acquire the most amount of	property for the least amount of effort.</td></tr></table></center><p>	Were this not so, life as we know it could not exist.  It isboth a necessity for successful volitional life, and something which isthe cause of a great deal of mischief.  This is the cause of peoplewishing to rule others, whether through force or fraud (mysticism).This basic law of nature will be familiar to readers of my essays.<p>	Such readers will also know that--fortunately--there is a balancingSecond Law of Volitional Behavior which says:</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="50%"><tr>	<td align=center>	All individuals seek happiness	</td></tr></table></center><p><a name="3r"></p><p>	This doesn't seem like a very strong counter-balance to what appearsto be motivation toward naked greed and unrestrained ambition. However, if you have read my essay "Need and Morality in Society" youwill know that this can be a very effective deterrant to attempts togain control of property through force or fraud.  In fact, it is thebasis for the mechansim which replaces the current, primitive,regulatory mechanism of society: Political laws and a political policeto enforce them.<a href="#3">[3]</a><p><a name="4r"></p><p>	Please note that the Second Law does not say an individualwill find happiness in an action.  More appropriate to politicalsocieties, what it does say is that an individual will select analternative which results in the least unhappiness.<a href="#4">[4]</a> That, given a choice, a person will not deliberately chose an unhappyoutcome.  It also means the decision and percieved outcome is relative. It is relative to each individual and their description of happiness(or least unhappiness) to them. Another individual with a differentoutlook on what makes them happy might chose a different action.  Italso says that any definition of happiness is valid (but notnecessarily moral or rational, and thus not necessarily right on anabsolute basis) for any one individual, and that no other person maymorally or rationally say that the definition of another individual isinvalid.<p>	Please note that by property I mean not just tangible property,but also intangible or "intellectual" property.  And, when the two lawsof volitional behavior are merged it also explains why someone canenjoy a sunset, stroking a cat, or being stroked by another humanbeing.  The "property" known as tranquility--and perhaps otherproperties--may be acquired by these actions.<p>	As stated above, The Second Law does not say that the resultsof the quest will be happiness.  What it does says is that a volitionalbeing will not willingly (in the absence of coercion or falsealternatives) seek or accept unhappiness.  In political societies theseeker is often presented with false alternatives:</p><ul>	<li>Would you rather have a 50% tax or a 45% tax?<li>would you rather have an abortion and go to jail, or have the child?<li>would you rather pay an annual road tax for your car of $1,000 or not	be able to drive you car?  And without competition from another road	company offering you an alternative.<li>would you rather send your child to a bad neighborhood school, or to a	less bad school some distance away?<li>etc.</ul><p>	Regardless of the reason, it is an undisputed fact of historythat tribes had chiefs, just as our modern version of a tribe--known asa "country"--also has a chief.  Modern tribes are larger, and with moremegalomaniacal chiefs.  The basic concept has not changed, which ispart of the problem.  It is something which we should and must outgrowif we are to survive as a viable volitional specie.<p>	A truly clever chief will try to rule through a combination offorce and "persuasion," which might also be called "fraud."  After all,the happier your subjects are, the easier it is to rule them. Satisfying both lawsof human behavior for the Chief, but none for thevictims.</p><h4>The Witch Doctor</h4><p>	As intimated above, the witch doctor will inevitably appear in aprimitive society of volitional beings to satisfy the basic need for"intellectual" or mental security.  Mental tranquility to minimizeapprehension--to develope sufficient confidence to venture forth into analien, unknown, and seemingly incomphrensible environment.<p>	Also, being living, biological beings, humans are susceptibleto biological diseases.  Besides the need for mysticism to banishuncertainty about their world, a specie would need people to care forthe sick.  Many lower-order animals show empathy for other members oftheir specie.  We know that at least 100,000 years ago our specieshowed empathy and understanding for the sick and injured members oftheir specie, as indicated by findings in a cave called Shanidar inIraq.<p><a name="5r"></p><p>	The bone evidence found in the cave indicated that Neanderthal mansuffered from arthritis and the inevitable injuries of the difficultlife.  As Rick Gore stated, "All the injuries show signs of healing,evidence that crippled members of the group were fed, protected, andhelped to move by others--the dawn of empathy."<a href="#5">[5]</a>[Emphasis by this author]  I would not be surprised if we find evidencethat empathy existed even much earlier.  I think I see it in lowlandgorillas, and perhaps in dolphins. 	<h4>The Struggle for Supremacy</h4><p>	The witch doctor occupied a position of great power, in a senseperhaps even greater than that of the chief. For millennia it is almostcertain that they contested for the position of supreme influence in atribal group.  Whether it was a very small group, or something as largeas the Egyptian or Roman Empires.<p>	The struggle for supremacy between the traditional priests andAkhenaten--the first prominent and recognized monotheist--are welldocumented.  In the end, the old order won, and Akhenaten and Nefretitiwere murdered, and the pantheon of gods was restored.  They had astrong union.<p>	The functions of chief and witch doctor continued largely separatelyuntil the council of Nicae in 325 AD, when they joined forces for theirmutual benefit and to the detriment of mankind.  It was also here thatby majority vote of mortal human beings the concept of the "trinity"was voted into being.  The concept of the "father, son, and the holyghost."<p><a name="6r"></p><p>	The loser was Ariaus, who believed that Jesus was of a similarsubstance as God (homoiousios) but not of one substance (homoousios).  Only an "i" separated them.  In a truly democratic fashion, by majorityvote of mortal men, he lost.  His losing group then became known as theArian Heresey.  Constantin and the church merged the concepts of forceand fraud to better solidify their control over their subjects.  Aconcept which has been much expanded and "improved" upon over theyears.  Now fraud is an institutionalized part of any chief's tool kitas part of the method of ruling people.  So much so that the Church caneven be dispensed with.  The witch doctor now appears under manyaliases, such as propaganda minister, spin doctor, etc., but they playonly a supporting role to the leader or fühurer.<a href="#6">[6]</a>	<p>Joseph G&ouml;bbels said something to the effect that,</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="70%"><tr>	<td align=center>	"The more outrageous the lie, the more often it is repeated,<br>	the more likely it is to be believed."	</td></tr></table></center><p>When you couple this with the concept elucidated by Thomas Paine:</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="70%"><tr>	<td align=center>	"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong,<br>	gives it a superficial appearance of being right...	</td></tr></table></center><p>you end up with people believing all sorts of outrageous and absurd things,such as:<p><ul><li>	democracy means freedom;<li>	inflation is caused by price increases;<li>	a minimum wage boosts prosperity;<li>	a certain level of inflation is necessary, and even good;<li>	monopolies are bad--except for those of the political state;<li>	increasing the number and enforcement of laws will reduce crime.<li>	etc.</ul><p>And, again, as G&ouml;bbels said,</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="50%"><tr>	<td align=center>	Propaganda made the Third Reich	</td></tr></table></center><p>	It also made the American one, the Russian, and all of the othermodern Reichs or political states.<p>	It creates a situation in which people believe they are freewhen they are not.  A situation in which people actually yearn to beruled, and feel they can not discharge the functions andresponsibilities of individual life.  That only the state can tell themhow to function in the world.  And, as the state increasingly performsfunctions that should be the responsibility of the individual, theindividual loses the ability to make informed and responsible decisionsconcerning their life.  The mind is similar to muscles, in that atrophysets in if it is not used.<p>	An individual with high self-esteem, an inquisitive mind, andintellectual honesty--someone who is or wishes to be in control of theirlife and destiny--should not and will not accept the fact that someoneelse can rule their life.  Even if their name is God.<p>	The only concept or rule a person must observe to live a morallife is that they should not interfere in the property of anotherperson.  That is the only "regulation" needed in a societal group. Rationality is another matter, but also very simple, for as long as allactions are moral, mistakes--which are virtually inevitable in life--willbe handled in a satisfactory manner.	The most pathetic volitional be<p>ing is the one that does noteven recognize that they are a slave and do not have control of theirown lives.  And even extol the beauty of their serfdom, recommending itto others.  Such as people who live under the so-called "democracies."<p>	The Roman galley slave was, in a sense, better off. Chained tohis oar and bench, he knew he was a slave.  There could be little doubtthat he was, for all practical purposes, a 100% slave.  But the personwho believes they are free when the state takes more than 50% of theirproduction and effectively controls all of their property, is living adangerous and pathetic illusion.  The witch doctor--or spin doctor, touse the modern name--has done an outstanding job.	<center><h4>God is Not Volitional</h4></center><h4>Introductory Discussion</h4><p>	It is interesting how you can be certain that something is true,feel confident that you can prove it, but for some reason not reallysearch for the proof.  Yet the idea keeps running around in your head,as if it is being processed in the subconsious.<p>	A number of times starting to write about it, but not getting far andjust leaving it.   Then one day, when you are in a somewhatinappropriate place, having your mind "fetch" the problem and presentyou with the solution.  And for me, the most amazing thing, notforgetting it before I could make a couple of notes about it. So oftenI think of something that seems so perfectly obvious that I could notpossibly forget it, and then promptly doing just that.  Another aspectof the human mind...<p>	One problem in presenting the solution is that it is very simple andobvious from the laws of human behavior.  Yet, while the answer came tome "in a flash," it took decades of thinking before the flash appeared. And, it required inputs from history, biology, pscyhology,thermodynamics and a number of other disciplines.  Thus, while it isnow "obvious" to me, it was not always so. And will certainly not seemobvious to you.  This brings to mind a thought:</p><p><a name="7r"></p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="80%"><tr>	<td>	"The originator of a new concept....finds, as a rule, that it is	much more  difficult to find out  why other people do not understand	him, than it was to discover the new truth."<a href="#7">[7]</a>	</td></tr></table></center><p>	I also remember the story of the great Arthur Stanley Eddingtonwho, upon hearing of the conclusions of Eintein's Special Theory ofRelatively, sat down and wrote out the proof.  Eddington--who may in ahundred years appear to have been even more significant thanEinstein--did not think of the conclusion himself before Einstein did,but had the knowledge and intellectual capacity to realize in aninstant how Einstein had derived it.<p>	Also the story of &Oslash;&Oslash;rsted and his discovery ofa connection between electricity and magnetism.  It is almost certainthat a number of other people had passed a compass or a magnet near anelectrical field and noticed an interaction.  But also that they eitherdid not stop to think about it, or just said "Hmm, that's odd," and itpassed from their mind.  But &Oslash;rsted knew it was a verysignificant phenomena that required an explanation.<p>	People who don't understand epistemology, which is most people,say his discovery of the connection between electricity and magnetismwas an "accident."  Yes, the occurrence of &Oslash;rsted passing the compassin the area of flowing electrical current was an accident, but hisunderstanding of the resulting phenomena was most certainly not anaccident. It required much background knowledge and an inquisitivemind.<p>	The last example I will impose on you is the one of the motoristwhose car was not running properly.  He was in an isolated area andstopped at the only available place to have it attended to.  Themechanic looked at it and in less than a minute it was runningperfectly.  When the motorist asked him how much the service cost, themechanic said "$10."  "Ten dollars!  That's ourageous!  You worked onit for only two minutes!  I want an itemized bill."</p>	<p>	The mechanic sauntered back to this office and in a few minutesreturned with the bill, which said:</p><dl>	<dt>Adjusting Screw		<dd>$00.02	<dt>Knowing which screw to adjust		<dd>9.98	<dt>Total		<dd>$10.00</dl><p>	Yes, perhaps for two minutes of work it seems "outrageous," yetknowing which screw to adjust and how much--and whether it was that orsome other problem--might have taken years of study and work. And somemechanics, taking advantage of the obviously ignorant motorist, mighthave rebuilt the engine for $1,000.<p>	Why have I pestered you with these quotations and stories?  Becausethat which is "obvious" (and correct), is not always obvious.  And thatwhich is obvious and simple to one person may seem like gibberish orgarbage to another.  There may be another reason, for which  I willrepeat an earlier quotation:<p><a name="8r"></p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="70%"><tr>	<td align=center>	"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong,<br>	gives it a superficial appearance of being right...<a href="#8">[8]</a>	</td></tr></table></center><p>	We often believe things to be true when they are not, just because wehave not thought about them, or because no one has pointed out thatthey are wrong.  The knowledge in what is commonly and incorrectlycalled "social science" is composed almost entirely of this type ofuseless, non-knowledge.  This represents a very great handicap, sincemost societal ideas which are right will contravene "conventionalwisdom."	<p>	You may have already found it quite difficult to understand andaccept the definitions I presented and my statements involving the lawsof volitional behavior.  And now I will stretch your knowledge andintellectual capacity further.	<h4>Why God Can Not Be Volitional</h4><p>	If God were volitional, it would represent a irreconcilablecontradiction with laws of volitional behavior.  Let's repeat the FirstLaw of Volitional Behavior again...</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="80%"><tr>	<td align=center>	Individual volitional beings seek to acquire the most amount of	property for the least amount of effort.	</td></tr></table></center><p>	This is inconsistent with wars and other acts of property destruction. If there were a volitional god, it would not allow such things tohappen.  History as generally written is virtually a never-endingdiscussion of acts of property destruction.  And the old saying that "...god works in mysterious ways ..." is not an acceptable answer.<p>	This oft-repeated statement that "God acts in mysterious ways"is also not consistent with the fact that the universe iscomprehensible.  Our modern technological world is evidence of itscomprehensibility.<p>	God would also seem to be incapable of learning from experience, orat least a very slow learner.  After fifteen billion years he could notconstruct a planetary system that doesn't suffer from all sorts ofnatural or God-induced disasters.<p>	And very slow in his work.  Fifteen billion years to create life?  Atleast in this part of the Universe.<p>	Perhaps incompetent also.  Since, if he is truly omnipotent, hewould also be in charge of making insurance policies.  And not requirethe people he has created to labor under the uncertainties of "acts ofGod."<p>Then there is the Second Law of Volitional Behavior:</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=4 width="40%"><tr>	<td align=center>	All individuals seek happiness	</td></tr></table></center><p>	Any god who seeks happiness by creating the miseries of this planet isa pervert.  How could someone find happiness in famine, poverty, wars,inflation, depressions, crime, decaying education standards, and allthe other miseries of this planet?<p>	Also, such acts are not consistent with evolution.  In the sense thatnature, apparently--and horror of horrors, acting almostvolitionally--"seeks" improvements and perhaps even "perfection" in whatit does.  What makes me think of that is the wonder, glory, and beautyof nature.  Its wonderful diversity.  And the human body, with itsequisite arrangement of functions and attributes.<p>	Yet having done the wonderful work of constructing the humanbody, would a volitional god have, with malice of forethought, createdcancer, heart disease, malaria, Alzheimer's disease, leprosy, and allof the other hideous maladies than can befall the human body?<p>	Lastly, by allowing and even promoting activities which destroyhuman life, God would be violating the purpose of life.  I don't careto discuss this in detail for several reason. One is that it will giveyou a chance to learn something if you wish to think about the little Isay on this subject.<p>	A major characteristic of life is order, as opposed to disorder. Disorder in nature, as studied specifically in thermodynamics, is knownas entropy.  Life represents order, but when a human being dies youcould say they have been consumed by entropy--that entropy has takenover.<p>	Entropy and disorder is what makes the universe "hostile" toward orfor life.  Live and entropy is almost like good and evil.  It isextraordinarily difficult for life to occur in the Universe, andperhaps even more difficult to sustain itself and flourish.<p>	This is the great sadness for one who understand the lessons ofhistory.  Who sees the perhaps 3.5 billion year evolution of life onthis planet.  From the most primitive single cell life forms to theeventual appearance of hominids "only" five million years ago.  And toknow that this wonderful experiment with life will end if we don'tsolve our societal problems within perhaps 50 years at most.  And tosee politicians posturing around the world as if they were solving theproblems, while they are only accelerating the decline.  With the basicreasons being those I have mentioned in this and other essays.	<center><h4>The Consequences of Religious Beliefs</h4></center><p>	If you have thought about and understood what I have said, youwill realize that virtually everything that passes for religiousknowledge is false, immoral, irrational, or violates natural law. Often all of these.  About the only thing of any value is statementswhich are obviously moral and/or rational, such as the Ten Commandmentsof Christianity.<p><a name="9r"></p><p>	It is immoral to steal, and irrational in the long term ifnot short term.  It is not immoral to covet your neighbor's wife aslong as you do not take any actions on that thought which would violatethe property of the wife or her husband.  Or anyone else.  In the longterm it is almost certainly irrational.  However, it could be moral(but may not be) for the covetor if the covetee<a href="#9">[9]</a>wished to be coveted.  However if she wished to be coveted, then it isprobably immoral relative to her contract with her husband.  Unless shehappens to have an agreement with her husband which allows for suchcoveting and associated actions. No reason why serious thinking can notalso be fun and funny, and provide an increase in happiness.  Even ifmomentary.<p>	Yet, having stated these nice moral things, and emulating the immoralpolitical world in which we are all immersed, the averagechurch-goer--and most other people--go off and do things which areimmoral.  Not because they themselves are necessarily immoral, butbecause that is the way of the political world.  With many things whichare legal being immoral, and many things which are illegal being moral. Bearing in mind also though, that it is almost always irrational toseriously or strongly challenge the the political system, even when itsactions are immoral and irrational.<p>	To an objective observor, which would be one standing outsideof our Universe, they would be appalled at the contradictions in theChristian bible.  Some of the major statements are obviously promotingmorality and rationality, and then there are stories of people begatingall sorts of other people.  Probably with legalizing their relationshipwhich, in the eyes of the ever-moral state, is "bad."  Casting peopleout, and telling people to roast in hell.  Without always being clearof what crime, if any, they are alleged to have committed.	<center><h4>The Decline of Civilization</h4></center><p>	A vibrant, growing civilization--growing in the sense ofquality--requires clear thinking and intellectual honesty.<p>	This means that individuals cannot accept religious, mysticalthinking on any subject.   Unless perhaps for entertainment, althoughit seems a bit macabre.<p>	People can no longer accept the statements of a superb politicalmagician such as a Hitler, who can convince people that murder anddestruction is "beautiful" and "glorious."  That slavery, even of hisown people, is freedom.<p>	For the last fifty years especially, the concept of democracyhas somehow become equated with freedom. In reality, they are mutuallyexclusive concepts.  A democracy differs only in style from adictatorship, with the operative principle being the same.  They areboth societal structures based on coercion, without which they wouldcollapse.  So ingrained is the falsehood, that everyone--no doubt thereader included--will bristle at my statement.<p>	Do you really believe that the violation of a Nazi law wouldhave a different result than that of an American, British, or Europealaw?  Where the régimes say they are "democratic" rather than"dictatorial"?  Assuming you had in fact violated the law?  What arethe choices?  You obey the law, or must pay a fine and/or go to prison. And, if having received a sentence of some type, anywhere betweenprobation and death, you steafastly refuse to accept it, what will bethe result?  Even it involves a cat or dog license.  Or, as in NewZealand, not mowing your lawn.  Or perhaps opening your business onFriday, Sunday, or some other "holy" day when it is not permitted.<p>	Even when the "crime" is a very minor one.  They can not say,"Ah, well, it is a small offense, let's forget it."  Politicalsocieties can not allow that, else they will collapse.  And theirminions be required to find honest, moral employment.<p>	Within the two laws of human behavior, and widely used, acceptable,and moral business practices, lies the solution to the conundrum ofhaving societal rules which are either immoral and irrational, or moraland rational.  Meaning they will be accepted by free choice, ratherthan by coercion.  Because by so doing it will maximize the happinessof all members of society.<p>	Bearing in mind that it may not bring absolute happiness.  Suchas in the case where a person makes a mistake which costs them money. As long as the transactions related to the situation were moral, nocrime has been committed.   Yet, for a period, there will be someunhappiness.  Until volitional beings stop making mistakes, there isbound to occasional unhappiness.<p>	As an intellectual exericse, you might want to think about whether itis even desirable to have a situation in which people did not makemistakes. This would imply that we knew everything and, as AnatoleFrance said,<p><a name="10r"></p><p>	Ignorance is the necessary condition of life itself.  If weknew everything, we could not endure existence for a singlehour."<a href="#10">[10]</a><p>	I think this would tend to create a civilization similar to theEloi of The Time Machine, by H. G. Wells.  They didn't know everything.In fact the knew almost nothing, yet the result is similar...?<p>	There is only one area in which there is clear, right thinkingon this planet.  In the non-volitional area of our knowledge.  Even asthe quality of life continues to decline in a social sense, in atechnological sense it continues to increase.  Even when business andtechnology is hobbled by the political state.<p>	Yet, as further indication of the problems hindering a solutionto our societal problems, people decry the technological progress. They want it but the don't want it.  When, in reality, the "bad press"for technology is not the problems with technology, but the problemswith the political state related to technology.  To wit:</p><ul>	<li>	Greatly hindered and shackled "capitalism" builds more cars than	socialism can build roads to accomodate;<li>	Ever-advancing medical technology exists, but because the medical	delivery systems are increasingly controlled by the state it costs more	and more and is available to less and less people;<li>	Continually advancing communications technology would be more	widely available were it not controlled by restrictive, coercive monoplies	of the political state;<li>	Inflation, which can only occur through debasement of the currency by	the money-issuing authority continues to effect the quality of life;<li>	Only when you accept the mysticism of having a coercive political state	can the concept of war exist.  Without the state you have only a	disagreement between two people, neither of whom would have the coercive	authority to raise any army of millions to "settle" the argument.</ul><p>	In the same vein, if the individual were sovereign rather thanthe state, they would have hard time arranging for and funding borders,Customs posts, passport offices, police forces, anti-subversive controlauthorities, a trade regulation authority, "national" conscription,etc.	<p>As I have observed before,</p><p>	As the number of "sovereign states" approaches the total population,something interesting happens: It is called freedom.<p>	Think of from where it is in life that you truly receive value. Is it from the so-called "services" of the political state?  Some ofthe services they purport to provide are:</p><ul>	<li>	Education<li>	property protection<li>	medical services<li>	road services</ul><p>	Yet in reality are they providing them or hindering their provision? Yes, they control the mechanism that provides these services.  Yet whydo people find they need to hire private security companies, yearn forthe financial means to be able to pay for private medical services, andwant to send their children to other than state-provided, "free"schools?  And why are political entities pleading for accepting peopleto "adopt" potholes in the road and "sponsor" sections of roads andstreets?  While collecting ever-more taxes to do the things they can'tdo?<p>	In the final analysis, the political state hires individuals todo things just as a non-state company does.  Then they mismanage it tothe extent that it provides inferior services at an ever-increasingcost.<p>	Then you have absurd statements such as that of the American "leader"(for which the German word is führer) Clinton who claims that hecreated ten million jobs in four years (or whatever the number was). The more correct stat is that by gross interference in individual andbusiness life, only ten million new jobs were able to be created bybusiness during that time.<p>	Religious and political mysticism prevents people from seeing what istruly happening, allowing them to see only what the state tells them.In fact, so pervasive is the disinformation of the witch doctor andspin doctor that most people have stopped thinking of anything excepttaking refuge in the technology of television and entertainment, whilecontinuing to bad-mouth it.<p>	Heading toward the mindless world of the Eloi and Aldous Huxley'sBrave New World.<p>	This will be the destiny of a volitional specie which continuesto embrace "the opiate of the masses."  Perhaps Marx (or Engels-?) wasright after all...</p>	<hr><h4>Version History</h4><p>Version 1: 1996, September 16</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>	"If God did not exist, it would be necessary	to invent him."  Voltiare {1694 - 1778}		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>	The proper name for the plant commonly known as	"Earth," so named in honor of one of the first and most significant	people to explain its basic characteristics.		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>	For more details on this subject please read my	essay on "False Alternatives & Human Destiny."		<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>	This is based on tha fact that all political	societies offer false alternatives to their victims.  Such as,	would you rather pay a 40% tax or a 50% tax?  There is never an	alternative for a 0% tax.		<a href="#4r">Return</a><p><a name="5"><li>	Rick Gore, "The Dawn of Humans: Neanderthals,"	National Geographic magazine, 1996, January, p. 21		<a href="#5r">Return</a><p><a name="6"><li>	F&uuml;hrer is merely the German word for leader, as	"f&uuml;hrerschaft" is the German word for leadership, although for	some reason they don't care to use the word these days...		<a href="#6r">Return</a><p><a name="7"><li>	Hermann von Helmholtz {1821 -1894}	<a href="#7r">Return</a><p><a name="8"><li>	Thomas Paine, Introductionto Common Sense,	Penguin Books, 1983, p. 63		<a href="#8r">Return</a><p><a name="9"><li>	Improvised words...	<a href="#9r">Return</a><p><a name="10"><li>	The Garden of Epicurus - 1894.	<a href="#10r">Return</a>	</ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Origin-Purpose-Religions.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
