atements that I ask you to thinkabout, perhaps even stopping to think before you continue reading. Think about them as they relate to your own life, and to the worldaround you.	<p>In Political Societies:</p><ul><li>Today's opposition is tomorrow's ruler or ruling group;<li>Today's ruler or ruling group is tomorrow's opposition.</ul><p>	They switch back and forth, with names and perhaps even titleschanging, but the basic system continues: regulating individual actionsand relationships through coercion.	<p>It is fundamental fact of life that:</p><ul><li>Each and every thinking being has their own unique idea of what	represents success and happiness for them as an individual.<li>Thinking beings do not willingly accept that another person or entity 	may impose upon them a different route to success and happiness.</ul><p>The phenomena and dichotomy that:</p><ul><li>You would not want even your best friend to suddenly be allowed to take	total control of your life, telling you what you can do and not do.<li>You then allow people who are total strangers to do this.</ul><p>Political behavior consist mainly of:</p><ul><li>Finding fault with the concepts or actions of another;<li>wanting your view and concept to prevail;<li>seeking to acquire a position of political power so that you can impose	this differing view on others.</ul><p>	The concept of the political state--of societies ruled bycoercion--allows all of the above to happen in never'ending cycles.<p>The basic principle of politics is:</p><p>The control of the lives and property of others without their permission.</p><p>This is true of all political systems, regardless of the name attached to it.Whether they are:</p><center><table><tr>	<td>Communists</td>	<td>Conservatives</td>	<td>Democrats</td></tr><tr>	<td>Christian Democrats</td>	<td>Social Democrats</td>	<td>Reformed Democrats</td></tr><tr>	<td>Independent</td>	<td>Labour</td>	<td>Republicans</td></tr><tr>	<td>Nationalists</td>	<td>Socialists</td>	<td>Tories</td></tr>	<td>True Path</td>	<td>Reformed Socialists</td>	<td>Motherland Party</td></tr></table></center><p>	If you doubt this, try violating any political law, regardlessof who is in power, whether it relates to:</p><center><table><tr>	<td>abortion</td>	<td>business licenses</td>	<td>divorce permission</td></tr><tr>	<td>marriage permission</td>	<td>entertainment licenses</td>	<td>alcoholic beverage licensing</td></tr><tr>	<td>animal licensing</td>	<td>customs regulations</td>	<td>prostitution</td></tr><tr>	<td>taxes</td>	<td>automobile registration</td>	<td>social security</td></tr></table></center><p>	The political process is the only contractual process or agreement Iknow of in which you appoint someone to act as your agent, and even paythem for doing this, and then loss total control of the relationship. Almost as if by magic the roles are reversed.  The person you engagedto do something for you, to act on your behalf, now tells you what todo.  And you must continue paying them for this "service," and can notdischarge them regardless of how poorly or ineptly they conductthemselves.	<p>	To add insult to impertinence, even if your "agent" is replacedby a different individual, the charade continues.</p><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5 width="40%"><tr>	<td align=center>	The incumbent is replaced.<br>	Long live the incumbent.	</td></tr></table></center><p>As in a monarchy, names change but the system continues.</p><p><a name="1r"></p><p>	The perceptive person will need read no further, since theabove explains why political, coercion'based societies have neverworked during the millennia of mankind's history.  And, that since theyviolate basic natural laws<a href="#1">[1]</a> of human behavior, theynever will work.<center><h4>Discussion</h4></center><p><a name="2r"><a name="3r"></p><p>	Laying in bed on a Sunday morning I was wondering why all politicalsocieties experience continuing and accelerating strife.  Then itstruck me: the Hilary Factor<a href="#2">[2]</a>.  It suddenly becameobvious<a href="#3">[3]</a> to me that this factor and phenomena--andits results--was the reason history can be summed up by a generalizedversion of the title of Gibbon's monumental work, The Rise and Fall ofthe Roman Empire.<p>	That history is a never'ending litany and rendition of politicalstates rising and falling.   Conquering and being conquered.  Peacetreaties made and broken.  Of societies appearing almost from"nothing," rising to rule much of the world, and then going intodecline.  Sometimes the decline is long an agonizing, other timesswift.<p>	That strife and disorder is endemic to political societies.  Ina relatively less populated world it is low and small when the societyis young, but accelerates with age, reaching a climax that destroys orat least totally reshapes that particular entity.  It then goes intodecline as another one surpasses it in power and influence.  Or moreoften now, born of a strife that has reached an intolerable andunacceptable level which creates a call for a strong, dictatorial rulerto end it.  In both cases the cycle then repeats itself.<p>	Another observation is that with the passing of time and history, theviable lifetime of political societies is becoming shorter.  Just as abrief example and generalization:</p><p><a name="4r"><a name="5r"><a name="6r"><a name="7r"></p><center><table width="80%"><tr>	<th>Civilization</th>	<th>Duration<a href="#4">[4]</a><p></tr><tr>	<td>The Egyptian Civilization of the Pharaohs</td>	<td>2,000 years</td></tr><tr>	<td>The Roman Empire</td>	<td>1,000 years<a href="#5">[5]</a></td></tr><tr>	<td>The British Empire</td>	<td>600 years</td></tr><tr>	<td>The North American Empire<a href="#6">[6]</a></td>	<td>200 years<a href="#7">[7]</a></td></tr></table></center><p>	As indicated in the background section above, the reason concerns thevery nature of all thinking beings, and the attempt to contravene andoverride this basic nature.  Which, since it involves basic behavioralcharacteristics of thinking beings, does not work.<a name="8r"><p>	Most people will accept the idea that they are individuals,with their own unique definition of what constitutes success andhappiness for them.  That this definition is not exactly identical withthat of their friends or neighbors.  Often it is quite different and"opposite" or "opposing."<a href="#8">[8]</a>  Also varying withdistance, in that your idea of happiness and success for your own lifemay be very much different than that of a person on the other side ofthe planet.<p>	And the dichotomy of thought which says that we would not wantour best friend--even as an individual--to impose their idea of successand happiness on us and our life.  Yet we are willing to allowstrangers or a faceless entity known as the "government" or politicalstate to do just that.  And, as I said above, we then become opposed tothis entity, whether it is a "democratic" group or an individualdictator.<a name="9r"><p>	Since I have mentioned the word and concept of democracy, I wish tosay something about it.  Differences between so'called "democratic"societies and dictatorial ones are only cosmetic.  There is nodifference in the principle that the political state requires obedienceto its laws, and uses the mechanism of their monopoly on police powersto ensure it.<a href="#9">[9]</a><p>	Once they have decided what is legal, all that is left is foreveryone to obey.  Or protest?  With democracy there is the addeddelusion that you can change things, and that the state only rules byyour consent.  How true is this?  How well does it work?<p>	Disagreeing with things, we may then actually join an oppositionindividual or group for the purpose of asserting our idea and "rights." Seeking political power, and in the end imposing our idea(s) onothers, as they would impose theirs on us.  The very thing we don'twant someone else to do to us.  This willingness to accept a conceptfor society which contravenes ideas for our own individual behavior isthe cause of continuing strife in political, coercion'based societies.</p>	<p>Some people are naturally in favor of or opposed to:</p><ul><li>abortion<li>welfare<li>a minimum wage<li>euthanasia<li>monopolies</ul><a name="10r"><p>	And, since we have implicitly<a href="#10">[10]</a> acceptedthe notion that it is acceptable for some person or group to imposetheir will on all others, it is a simple step to do this.<p>	We would be outraged if an individual or group demanded we buya red colored car, an act which certainly does not concern them oreffect their life.  Yet we see no harm in preventing someone fromhaving an abortion, which is really no business of anyone except thetwo individuals directly involved.<p>	We would be outraged if an individual or group told us we couldnot go to Bali on our holiday, but instead had to go to Nigeria.  Yetwhen an individual is terminally ill and in pain, yet still with theirfull mental faculties, wishes to be allowed to die, we will not letthem.  We insist that someone else take control of their life anddestiny.<p>	If a private company, by offering the best products, prices,and service to their customers gets "too much" of a market share, thereare cries that they are a "monopoly," and must--by decree--give up someof their business.  Yet we plead for the creation and maintenance ofpolitically'mandated monopolies which provide poor service at highprices.  Or at artificially low prices, with the organizations thenbeing supported by money taken from everyone--even those who do notavail themselves of the "service."</p>	<p>George Orwell called this phenomena "doublethink," when he said:</p><center><table border=4 cellspacing=5 width="80%"><tr><td>"Doublethink means the power of holding two contradictory beliefs in one'smind simultaneously, and accepting both of them."</td></table><h4>The Hilary Factor</h4></center><p>	The Hilary Factor comprises a number of phenomena noted by greatthinkers of the past, all appearing in one person, who at this pointwill only be identified by a single name.  It explains why we fail tosee that there is a serious, fundamental problem with our socialstructure, are unable to ascertain the true nature of the problem, andunwilling and/or unable to accept the solution when it is obvious andapparent.</p><a name="11r"><ul><li>Acceptance of the status quo;	<p>	It has always been this way, and will always be this way.  Because we	have never really thought about something as being wrong ,we	accept it to be right.  As Thomas Paine said:	</p>	<ul>		<p>		"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong, gives it a		superficial appearance of being right…"<a href="#11">[11]</a>		</p>	</ul><a name="12r"><li>Unwillingness to accept new ideas;	<p>	This is illustrated by a statement by John Locke, when he said:	</p>		<ul>		<p>		"New opinions are always suspected, and usually opposed, without		any other reason but because they are not already		common."<a href="#12">[12]</a>		</p>	</ul><li>Inability to recognize the true, operative principle behind a concept or	action, and the result therefrom;	<p>	I have already mentioned the statement of Christian Morgenstern on this:	The obvious is that which is not seen until someone first expresses	it clearly.	</p>	<p>	There is another concept, elucidated by the great Frederic Bastiat, which	is characteristic of almost everything the politicians do:	</p></ul><a name="13r"><center>"That which is seen and that which is not seen."<a href="#13">[13]</a></center><ul>	<p>	They see only those things they wish to see when they force or delude	people into accepting one of their concepts.  How often is that a	politicians achieves the opposite to that which was intended?  Or that	the intended result was not achieved and there was an undesired side	effect?	</p><a name="14r"><li>An inability or unwillingness to use available	epistemological<a href="#14">[14]</a> tools to	determine what is right and what is not right.	<p>	This is best illustrated by the eloquent statement of Thomas Paine	as mentioned above.	</p>		<p>	A person is convinced they are right when they are not, and what	they are proposing is for the good of everyone.  The problem with this	view was illustrated by C. S. Lewis when he said:	</p><a name="15r">	<ul>		<p>		"Of all tyrannies a tyranny sincerely exercised for the good of		its victims may be the most oppressive.  It may be better to live		under robber barons than under omnipotent moral busybodies. The		robber baron's cruelty may sometimes sleep, his cupidity may at		some point be satiated; but those who torment us for our own good		will torment us without end, for they do so with the approval of		their own conscience."<a href="#15">[15]</a>		</p>	</ul></ul><p>All of these are illustrative of the factors that prevent everyone fromseeing:</p><a name="16r"><ul><li>That the same societal problems have existed for all of mankind's	history;<a href="#16">[16]</a>	<p>	Or did I miss something in the news recently which said that, after	5,000 or so years of political effort, one of the societal maladies such	a poverty, unemployment, inflation, crime, famine, or civil strife no	longer existed on the planet?	</p><li>that they all stem from the same, single cause;<li>that the concept upon which all political societies are based, which	everyone believes to be right simply because they never thought it	wrong, is in fact wrong;<li>that the single, true cause of our societal problems has been there	for all of us to see;<li>even when presented with the solution, seemingly intelligent people	reject it.</ul><p>	All of these factors were made clear to me by their embodimentin one person--Hilary.  Thus the name for the phenomena.</p>	<p>Now we must consider the possibilities:</p><ul><li>Continue on our present course;<li>Think, and learn from the lessons of history.</ul><center><h4>The Course of No Change</h4></center><p>	If the first course is followed, as both recent events and long'termhistory show us, there will be increasing disorder and decay in oursocietal structures, culminating in an end to viable, volitional lifeforms on this planet.<p>	This will occur, as I have stated above, because we will acquireincreasing technology--sufficient to destroy our specie--without thesocietal knowledge to prevent it.<p>	It should be obvious at the moment ,and also in the past, thatthere is a titanic struggle between political states and those who--forwhatever reasons--oppose them.  The state generally refers to themcollectively as "terrorists."  Their specific activities include:</p><center><table width="80%"><tr>		<td>bombings</td>	<td>child labor</td>	<td>drugs</td></tr><tr>	<td>fraud</td>	<td>kidnapping</td>	<td>money laundering</td></tr><tr>	<td>murder</td>	<td>pornography</td>	<td>prostitution</td></tr><tr>	<td>protest marches</td>	<td>tax evasion</td>	<td>welfare cheats</td></tr></table></center><p>Each side is using more sophisticated technology in the areas of:</p><center><table width="80%"><tr>	<td>biology</td>	<td>chemistry</td>		<td>communications</td></tr><tr>	<td>computers</td>	<td>cryptography</td>	<td>transportation</td></tr></table></center><a name="17r"><p>	While the political state has a "legal"<a href="#17">[17]</a>monopoly on force and fraud, and tries to achieve one in propaganda,those who challenge the political state are also very good at usingforce, fraud, and propaganda.<p>	As the structure of politics dictates, there are no winners,only losers.  Does the political state truly appear to be winning?  No. Although statistics can be made to lie, I don't think anyone wouldseriously say that the disruptive factors in society are declining. And that the quality of life is increasing.  The only area in whichthat is true is in the technology available to use, but this happens inspite of the political state, not than because of it.<p>	As the political state uses increasingly Draconian force andthe fraud of doublethink identified by Orwell, the intervention of thestate into personal life increases.  With the only two possible actionsbeing to comply or oppose.  What are the two possible outcomes of this?</p><h4>The State Wins</h4><ul><li>The state wins, and keeps the controls in force	<p>	This would be the "winning" scenario of 1984, as outlined by George	Orwell in his magnificent and very perceptive book of the same name.	</p>	<li>The state wins, and magically eliminates all intervention into private life,	there are no more disruptive influences in society, and we enter	into Utopia.	<p>	If you believe this, then you will also believe that elephants roost	in trees.	</p></ul><p>	The state can "win" by using such complete force (and fraud)that truly all individual activity--if that still has meaning--iscontrolled completely.<p>	They can also "win" through biological technology such as outlinedin <i>Brave New World</i>, in which there are alphas, betas, gammas, etc.,bred to do the bidding of "Our Ford." I believe was his name?  Certainlyless awe'inspiring and terrifying than "President'for'Life, Doctor,Field Marshall Ford," yes?  Almost as benevolent and harmless as First Secretary.<p>Will <i>this</i> be the future of mankind?</p><h4>The State Loses</h4><p>	If the state loses, it could mean that something like a Hitlerappears, wherein--as was often said--criminals acceded to the powers ofthe state.  But then, by definition, this is still a political state. A mechanism ruling through coercion, by whatever means the individualor group arrives in that position.  Hitler, as all politicians do, usedboth force and fraud, and actually became the führer or politicalleader by "democratic" means.<p>	Will <i>this</i> be the future of mankind?</p><p>	For mankind these are the only these two possible scenarios(with  indicated variations) if we continue to ignore the lessons ofhistory.	<center><h4>Learn the Lessons of History</h4></center><p>	First we must recognize and accept the lessons of history whichtell us that coercive societies have never survived in the long termand never will.  Then, and only then, can we start to think of why thishas happened, to learn from history, and to think of and considerpossible solutions.  And to then implement the obvious and onlysolution.<p>	There is an existing, ready'to'use, off'the'shelf concept andsolution. It is a system which does not involve:<ul><li>force<li>fraud<li>interference in the life or property of another person.</ul><p>And,</p><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5 width="85%"><tr>	<td>	It is a system which you should consider and adopt in your personal	life only if you believe it has the possibility for enhancing	the quality of your own personal life, without interfering in	the life and property of another person.	</td></tr></table></center><p>	To intelligently consider possible solutions, and to then acceptone which is correct, we must have a method for determining rightnessin the social sphere.  Something we have long had, but used only thenon'volitional sphere of mankind's knowledge.  There is a fullexposition of this subject in my essay, How Do You Know You Are Right?<p>	As mentioned here and in other essays, the above statement andincluded solution to our social problems is consistent with the basicbehavioral characteristics of all thinking beings.  This means it willwork, and have "no adverse side effects."<a name="18r"><p>	Does this sound different than other proposed "solutions?"Where you must "sacrifice"<a href="#18">[18]</a>?  And which involvesfurther curtailment of what is left of personal freedom?  And, as pasthistory and current events shows us, was not a solution. </p>	<center><h4>The Solution</h4></center><p>	The traditional solution is that there must be more laws, withexisting laws being more vigorously enforced.  Yet, as we know, thishas not solved a single one of our societal problems.<p>	The solution involves understanding and using the two universaland basic laws of volitional behaviour.  These laws are:</p><p>The First Law of Volitional Behaviour:</p><a name="19r"><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5 width="70%"><tr>	<td align=center>	All volitional beings live to create, use, and enjoy	property.<a href="#19">[19]</a>	</td></tr></table></center><ul><p>Corollary:</p>	<ul>	<p>	All volitional beings seek to acquire the most amount of property with	the least amount of effort.	</p>	</ul></ul><p>	If you think about the first law, things must be that way. The conceptof volitional life under any other terms is unthinkable.  In principlethere is nothing wrong with this basic trait, and in fact if you thinkabout it is seems almost mandatory for any thinking being to have thisattribute.  The opposite is almost unthinkable.  It would create totalapathy and lethargy, and is in fact what might be part of an operativedefinition of "hell."  Along with the possibility of knowingeverything.  What would be the purpose of living if you kneweverything?  As Anatole France said:</p><a name="20r"><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5 width="70%"><tr>	<td align=center>	"Ignorance is the necessary condition of life itself.  If we knew	everything, we could not endure existence for a single	hour."<a href="#20">[20]</a>	</td></tr></table></center><p>	Forcing or deceiving people into providing goods and services isalso a prescription for continuing strife, as this interferes withtheir basic desire of having the most for the least amount of effort.<p>	Although I don't want to discuss it in detail here, as it is coveredin other essays, there is another reason for an individual to beresponsible for acquiring the means of survival for themselves.  Itinvolves the concept of morality and that which is moral.  Interferencein, and control of the property of another.  Employing this concept orallowing this to happen also lays the foundation for continuing strifein a society.  It is what causes people to use force or fraud in theachievement of their objectives.<p>	Principle No. 1 might also be a major reason for the statementthat man is "war'like," and that war will always be a part of humanlife and existence.  If the above basic trait did not have a balancingone which is equally powerful, this would be so.  And the specie wouldbe doomed to eternal strife, disorder, and war.	<p>What is this balancing trait?</p><p>The Second Law of Volitional Behaviour:</p><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5 width="50%"><tr>	<td align=center>	All volitional beings seeks happiness	</td></tr></table></center><p>	Do you think that is true or not true?  Would you dispute it orquibble about it?  Doesn't it seem natural?  Would an individual,acting of their own free will and without coercion, voluntarily chooseto be unhappy?<p>	That can occasionally appear to be so, but to have it actuallybe so--and a principle of life--is also unthinkable.<p>	Because each individual has their own definition and image ofhappiness, the operation of this principle can sometimes be deceptive. Especially when people will say they or another person are doingsomething for someone else. After all, could it bring happiness to aperson to drown in the process of saving their child?  This is somewhatof an extreme example, and I think if we can handle this example we mayachieve partial belief in the principle?<p>	Let's look at it from the other side.  You go ahead and letyour child drown because obviously you might or will die, and who wantsto do that?  Yet any sane and rational parent would be devastated bythe thought they had let their child die while they lived.  If I lastedlong enough to shave the next morning and look at myself in the mirror,I would probably kill myself then and there.<p>	Of course you don't want to die, but the life you have createdis as precious or more so than your own.  And always the thought thatthey have almost their entire life ahead of them and have experiencednone of it, while yours is perhaps one'third finished.  Not to speak ofthat wonderful thing called "love," and of caring for someone.<p>	Further, what would your wife, children, relatives and friendsthink of a person who had been unwilling to make the effort?  Thisalone could create a lifetime of unhappiness.<p>	Granted, the decision to leap into the water is not prefaced byall of these thoughts, although undoubtedly for many parents thethought of giving up their life for their child has crossed their mind. The thought had been planted in their mind that, "Yes, I would dothat."  Also, we are surrounded by stories of people who have donethat. So, while our action is spontaneous and without thinking, thethinking and desire to take that action if necessary has already beendone.  We know that if we did not do it we would be truly unhappy.<a name="21r"><p>	The statement does not say that a person will find happiness,only that they will seek it.  Often to seek it in the sense of arelative happiness.  This is especially true in political societieswherein a person is presented with falsealternatives.<a href="#21">[21]</a>  Such as:</p><ul>	<li>Would you rather pay a 55% or a 50% tax?<li>Would you rather pay a $1,000 road tax or to not drive your car?<li>Would you rather go off and fight the régime's war, or go to prison?</ul><p>	If we are to have "laws" or rules for regulating society, whichdoes seem a necessity, would it not be better if they took intoconsideration the basics laws of human behaviour?  Rather than thecurrent system, which seems intent on trying to violate the laws ofhuman behaviour?<p>	Why not say something so simple as the fact that a person coulddo anything they wished as long as it did not involve interference inthe property of another person?  Would this not allow a person to tryto create, accumulate, use and enjoy property as long as they did notdo something which reduced the happiness of another person?  Or theirability to create, accumulate, use and enjoy property?	<p>This would seem to create a situation with minimal societal strife.</p><p>	Of course the next question is, how do we enforce such a situation?  Abetter way to phrase it might be to say "how do we ensure that such asituation will occur?"  That there will be minimal propertyinterference?  I say minimal to allow for mistakes, accidents, and thevicissitudes of human behavior.  That even under the best of conditionsthere may be some interference in the property of another.<p>	As soon as we think of "enforcing" something it implies force. Which is the current system that has not worked even with millennia of"tweaking" or adjusting the basic system of the use of force.  Isn'tthere something that might "control" the behaviour of individualswithout the use of force?  The answer is to be found in The Second Law. The principle upon which to base the system, while the system itselfis to be found in an existing, moral system for regulating behaviour. That is our credit system:  The system of recording and storing aperson's credit history, and in allowing them access to additionalcredit based on that credit history.<p>	All that is needed is to expand the concept of financial creditto include an individual's entire credit'worthiness.  Their credit as afunctioning, individual human being.  And, again, in principle it isvery easy to measure that.  The basic thing to measure is whether ornot they interfere in the property of another person.<p>	This can be modified by how they handle mistakes related to propertyinterference, recognizing that individual human beings--at least at thisstage of evolution--are not infallible and do make mistakes.<p>	If a person has a record of a few such mistakes and has alwayshandled them promptly and properly by admitting the mistake and makingoffers of and paying restitution, that is all to their positive credit. In a sense it can be like the present time, in which people who borrowmoney and pay it back sometimes have a higher credit rating than thosewho have never borrowed money.  You know how the act under the stressof an obligation.<p>	In a different sense, a person who performed a deliberate actof property interference and--eventually--also admitted the mistake, madean offer of restitution and paid restitution, would have a relativelylower rating.  But perhaps not one to cause them major credit problems.<p>	It is our failure to properly and completely understand thesignificance and concept of property that has prohibited us fromunderstanding the simplicity, elegance and utility of the concept ofcredit.  And how to apply it to the "regulating" of a society.<a name="22r"><p>	In a rational and durable society all property within the realm ofthe associated volitional specie will have an owner.  As I havediscussed elsewhere,<a href="#22">[22]</a> ownership is a moralconcept, and must be differentiated from control.<p>	Control of property is moral if you are the owner of that property orhave been delegated control of the property under terms specified bythe owner.<p>	But how can this actually be used to regulate society and limitproperty interference?  How can it regulate societal activities withoutthe use of force?</p>	<p>Simple.  "Simple, he says?!"  Yes.  Remember, and think…</p><ul><li>	All property has an owner;<li>	Access to property can be morally restricted by an owner;<li>	All individuals seeks happiness;<li>	A credit rating can be used to determine whether or not you would	want someone to have access to your property;<li>	Property may be	<ul>	<li>	a food store	<li>	a petrol station	<li>	a telephone company	<li>	a road or roads;	<li>	a school;	<li>	a park;	<li>	a library	<li>	an electricity company;	<li>	etc.	</ul><li>	There are existing "credit clearing houses" which can tell you the	credit rating of a person;</ul><a name="23r"><p>	How would you assemble these thoughts into a mechanism for regulatingbehaviour in a society without the use of coercion?  Without needing apolice force, prisons,<a href="#23">[23]</a> etc.? As said above, simple…<p>	Under the basic laws of nature, which our current societal systemsbased on coercion attempt to circumvent, all volitional beings haveaccess to the universe.  Restricted only by recognizing that allproperty has an owner.  And that volitional life will not survive ifeach individual does not allow access to their property consistent withthe market value of such access,<p>	In such a manner that maximizes the happiness of owner andprospective user.<p>	A person who owns a property cannot maximize their return ontheir investment--and thus their happiness--without allowing access totheir property at such a price that also maximizes the happiness ofusers.<p>	If you think this sounds "idealistic" it is.  It's the ideal conceptand situation.  It is based on valid thought processes, is rational andmoral--and thus right on an absolute basis--and will work.  It also meansit is the only system which will work in the long term.  I dislike anddistrust people who deprecate an idea or concept by saying it is"idealistic" when they don't know what they are talking about.  Such asHTB.<p>	All individuals would be allowed access to property on the samebasis that a person is now authorized access to products and servicesthrough the use of a credit card.  People are allowed access toproducts and services based on their credit rating.  As long as theyhave sufficient credit, they can avail themselves of products andservices based on the terms and conditions stated by the owner andprovider of those products and services.<p>	If a person interfered in the property of another, their creditrating would be "lowered."  Probably to zero.  Since all property hasan owner, this would restrict their access to many or all services.Electricity, telephone, road and school services, petrol stations, foodvendors, etc.  This would "reduce the happiness" of the person whowished to avail themselves of these products and services.<p>	This in turn would be a powerful incentive for the person tosay, "Hey, I'm sorry I did that. I propose an offer of (some amount) asrestitution, including for inconvenience, etc." When the victim of theproperty interference accepts such an offer and the restitution ispaid, then the person's credit rating is restored.  With appropriateannotations.</p>	<p>The same principle can handle all questions a person might raise,such as:</p><ul><li>	What happens in the case of false accusations;<li>	What do you do in the situation when the "property interference" is the	death or serious injury of a person;<li>	Next case</ul><p>	I could continue writing with examples and the answering ofobjections, but the maximum learning, understanding and comprehensiontakes place when a person thinks for themselves.<a name="24r"><p>	Bearing in mind that during the approximate 50,000 years ofevolution of Homo Sapien<a href="#24">[24]</a> our current system ofregulating societal behaviour has not worked.  And that one way ofexpressing the wonder and beauty of volitional life is to: </p><ul>	<li>	Think-	<ul>	<li>	of that which is	<li>	of that which could and should be	<li>	and of how to achieve it.	</ul></ul><p>This is the glory and, in a sense, the destiny of a thinking specie.</p><p>Our current world is the result and destiny of a specie which does not dothis.</p><p>Which destiny and world do we want for ourselves and our descendants? </p><center><h4>Copyright Information</h4></center><p>	You agree that no copies of this document may made or sent,transmitted, transported or delivered to any other person ororganization without prior written permission of the copyright holderand/or author of this document.  Such copies may not be made by anymethod now known or to be discovered in the future.<p>	If copies of this document or portions of this document are made withthe permission of the copyright holder, such copies must always carrythe copyright registration information on each page as is done with theoriginal.<a name="25r"><p>	Carlsoncopies<a href="#25">[25]</a> (photocopies) may not be made of any pages ofthis document</p>	<hr><h4>Version History</h4><p>Version 01: 1996, August 26<br>Version 02: 1996, September 06<br>Version 03: 1996, September 21</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>	As opposed to political laws.  Which, since	they propose to violate natural laws, will inevitably fail to	accomplish their intended objective, a statement that history	corroborates.		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>	To be discussed and credited later.	<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>	"Das Offensichtliche ist das, was man nicht	sieht, bis jeman es  erkl&auml;rt," Christian Morgenstern the Younger,	Lyric Poet.		<p>	The obvious is that which is not seen until someone first expresses it	clearly.	</p>		<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>	I don't claim these figures to be accurate,	but only representative to illustrate the principle		<a href="#4r">Return</a><p><a name="5"><li>	Or 1,600 years if you include the Eastern	Roman Empire, which neither Roman nor an Empire		<a href="#5r">Return</a><p><a name="6"><li>	South and Central Americans would object to	calling it merely the "American Empire," as they are Americans	also.		<a href="#6r">Return</a><p><a name="7"><li>	And already it is in a rapid, and almost	certainly terminal decline.		<a href="#7r">Return</a><p><a name="8"><li>	The foundation of the concept of "opposition" in	politics, and the reason for continuing and accelerating disorder in	political societies.		<a href="#8r">Return</a><p><a name="9"><li>	At this point people usually say, "… well,	there must be laws."  Yes, in a sense that is true, but I don't	wish to go into that in this essay, as I have covered that subject	elsewhere.  All I am trying to do here is to get you to see	that there is a very definite and basic problem which causes	all societies based on coercion to undergo continues protest	and disorder, and to eventually fail.  The solution is simple	and should be read and considered separately once you agree	that there is this basic, intractable problem with our current	system.		<a href="#9r">Return</a><p><a name="10"><li>	I cannot imagine anyone explicitly stating	that they wish to impose their ideas on someone else, using whatever	force is necessary to achieve that objective.  That is "dictatorial,"	and everyone hates dictators, right?  Yet that is also the process in	"democratic" societies, is it not?		<a href="#10r">Return</a><p><a name="11"><li>	Thomas Paine, Introduction to <i>Common Sense</i>,	Penguin Books, 1983, p. 63		<a href="#11r">Return</a><p><a name="12"><li>	<i>An Essay Concerning Human Understanding</i>	(1690, dedicatory epistle)		<a href="#12r">Return</a><p><a name="13"><li>	Frederic Bastiat (1800-1849), <i>That Which Is	Seen And That Which Is Not Seen</i>, 1849		<a href="#13r">Return</a><p><a name="14"><li>	The study of the nature of knowledge.	<a href="#14r">Return</a><p><a name="15"><li>	<i>The Freeman</i>, 1994, January, p. 3	<a href="#15r">Return</a><p><a name="16"><li>	To verify this you need only read Taylor	Caldwell's <i>A Pillar of Iron</i>, the biography of Marcus Tullius Cicero.	In this book, the societal problems of 2,200 years ago are the	same as today. Crime, war, pollution, unemployment, famine, poverty,	etc.		<a href="#16r">Return</a><p><a name="17"><li>	That which the political state decides is	an "acceptable" act.		<a href="#17r">Return</a><p><a name="18"><li>	Which is a "catchall" for more taxes, more	interference in your life, and a reduced quality of life.  While the	problem not only continues, but gets worse.  And those responsible	for not solving the problem are re'elected to office, or elected to a	higher office, and showered with honors.  For them there is no	unemployment or, if it happens, is brief.  And there is a nice	pension scheme.		<a href="#18r">Return</a><p><a name="19"><li>	Again, you must remember the concept of property,	which includes all of the attributes and derivatives of individual	life, such as beliefs, character, ideas, etc.  Not just the tangible	derivatives of individual life.		<a href="#19r">Return</a><p><a name="20"><li>	<i>The Garden of Epicurus</i> - 1894	<a href="#20r">Return</a><p><a name="21"><li>	Please refer to my essay "False Alternatives &	Human Destiny."		<a href="#21r">Return</a><p><a name="22"><li>	See my essay "The Concept of Property and	the Political State."		<a href="#22r">Return</a><p><a name="23"><li>	When you read and think, you may realize	that a moral regulatory system will create virtual prisons for	each person who interferes in the property of another…		<a href="#23r">Return</a><p><a name="24"><li>	Not to mention millions of years of hominid	evolution…		<a href="#24r">Return</a><p><a name="25"><li>	So named in honor of Chester Carlson, the creator	of the concept of the photocopy and xerography, and the photocopy	industry.		<a href="#25r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CE