<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-The Concept of Rightness</TITLE>	<META Name="AU" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META HTTP-EQUIV="KEYWORDS"		CONTENT="Galambos, government, coercion, capitalism,			history, Bedeman, epistemology, volition, Newton, Descarte">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corporation Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, August 24<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Concept-of-Rightness.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, August 24, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>How Do You Know You Are Right?</H3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4></center><hr noshade><center><h4>Synopsis</h4><table border=4 cellpadding=5 width="80%"><tr><td>The ability to determine right from not right has been the basis for ourmodern technological world.  The failure to use the same intellectualtool in the social sphere is the cause of all our societal problems. The solution to all of these problems is simple if we but clear awaythe pollution in our minds.</td></tr></table><h4>Background</h4></center><p>	This is a very profound question for any volitional specie.  Perhaps<i>the</i> most profound question of all.  More important than questions suchas "What is the purpose of life?"  Why this is so should be obvious. If there is no way to determine whether an idea is right or notright--correct or incorrect--then there is no way to accumulate usefulknowledge.  The specie would therefore be doomed to stay as they areor, more likely, to quickly self-destruct.  A viable civilization ofthinking beings could not develop, let alone survive.<p>	The need for such a tool--to know if you are right on anysubject--should be so obvious as to bring into question the sanity of aperson who would wonder at the need for such a concept or tool.<p>	To not have such a tool would--by default and definition--mean that anyresult was acceptable, whether it was desirable or undesirable, good orbad.  In fact, even the concepts of good and bad, desirable orundesirable, acceptable or not acceptable, could not have meaning andthus would not exist.<p>	Anyone who understands something about nature realizes that thelaws of nature are immutable and unchanging.  When they appear to bechanging or changeable it is only because we do not have a full andcorrect understanding of a particular law of nature or of the phenomenainvolved.<p>	If this were not so, nothing in the universe would work consistently.There would be true and total chaos.  Even assuming we could developthe concept of airplanes and television and the associated products(which by definition would be impossible), they would not perform thesame from one time to the next.  The television set would fly and theairplane would display pictures and sound and not fly.  One time youwould need to put petrol in the tank of your car and the next timesugar.<p>	Sometimes when you stepped off a cliff you would float or riserather than falling.  Water and fire could at different times be thesame or opposite things.<p><a name="1r"></p><p>	One reason why computers can sometimes be frustrating is that--whenthey are functioning as designed--they are <i>totally</i> consistent. For some people this can even be a wonderfully "intoxicating" thing. Unlike people, whose behavior may <i>appear</i> to be inconsistent<ahref="#1">[1]</a>, computers are obviously totally consistent, doingexactly the same thing for the same input.  The same result for a givenstimulus.  Which also makes them the basis for a wonderful teachingtool for children or adults.<p>	Computers are both a product of nature--or, more correctly, ofour understanding of nature--and a perfect example of nature in action.  Immutable and consistent. This also--in principle--makes them easy tounderstand, unlike people.<p>	If, for the sake of argument, we accept that it is true we needsome method of determining if something is right or not right, then wecould discuss two types of rightness:</p><ul>	<li>relative rightness	<li>absolute rightness</ul><p>Then we will consider it as it applies to;</p><ul>	<li>knowledge of our non-volitional world.		<p>	<a name="2r">	</p>	<p>	What is commonly called "science."<a href="#2">[2]</a>	</p>	<li>knowledge of our volitional world	<p>	<a name="3r">	</p>	<p>	What is commonly and incorrectly called "social	science.<a href="#3">[3]</a>"	</p></ul><center><h4>Relative Rightness</h4></center><p>	Relative rightness is similar to "situation ethics, " about which somepeople complain.  And rightfully so.  <i>Situation ethics</i> says thatwhatever is "ethical" changes depending on the subject of discussion oraction, perhaps even the time of action.<p>	A relative concept of rightness is in many ways worse than noconcept of rightness.  It presents the thinker with a "moving target." It provides the <i>illusion</i> that there <i>could</i> be rightness,but then says that it does not exist.  Which describes our currentsituation with volitional knowledge--knowledge concerning thebehavioral relationship of and between the members of our specie.<p>	In political societies, although most people would deny that itis true, "might" often determines what is acceptable in a society.  Irejected the idea of saying "... determines what is <i>right</i>, because Idon't wish to sully the term further.  The old saying of "Might MakesRight."  It is the acceptance of this concept that dooms ourcivilization and specie to endless strife. A rational and perceptiveperson should wonder why we reject the actions of a Hitler, and thenaccept--although sometimes reluctantly--someone such as a Kennedy whomakes war on the hapless Vietnamese.   And having the temerity to sayhe is doing it for "freedom."  Which, incidentally, was Hitler'sexcuse.<p><a name="4r"></p><p>	Although people profess outrage when a person uses force toaccomplish their ends, ultimately it is almost always accepted.  And isthe story of the history of our specie, which consists of anever-ending rendition of one person conquering the people of anothersocietal group, with the individuals doing the conquering being theleading politician (führer or ruler) of their particular politicalentity.  The "relativity" of the situation says that is okay forpoliticians to make war and kill people, but not okay for ordinarysubjects of the régime to do the same.<a href="#4">[4]</a>  This isrelativity in action.	<center><h4>Absolute Rightness</h4></center><p>	What do I mean by the concept of "absolute" as differentiatedfrom "relative"?  When a concept is <i>absolute</i> it means that it appliesunder all conditions, in all situations, and at any and all times. That there are no exceptions or cases under which it does not apply.<p>	With this short description we are now ready to discuss thesolution--the method for determining if anything is right or not right.	<center><h4>The Solution</h4></center><p>	Since most readers should have at least some intuitive understandingof how rightness is determined in the non-volitional world, I willdiscuss this first.<h4>Rightness in the Non-Volitional World</h4><p>	This is the first area of knowledge--and so far the only area--inwhich we have successfully applied the concept of rightness.  Itsapplication to this area of knowledge has produced our moderntechnological world.  Failure to apply it to our volitional world isthe reason for all our societal problems.<p>	It was Isaac Newton who first explicitly and grandly appliedthe concept to what is commonly called "science."  The result was his"System of the Worlds," as expressed in his monumental book <i>PrincipiaMathematica</i>.<p><a name="5r"></p><p>	It is generally thought that Newton's most important works were hislaws of motion and gravity.  While enormously important, his<i>method</i> of creating these laws was the truly significant part ofhis work. That and the message which accompanied it, saying that "theuniverse is comprehensible, and here is how to learn more about it." That it is full of knowable<a href="#5">[5]</a>, useful knowledge, andhere is the method for discovering it.  It was the application of thisconcept and the knowledge it created which was the proximate cause ofthe Industrial Revolution.<p>	This--the integration of the non-volitional sciences--representedthe first of two integrations of knowledge which are required for anyvolitional specie to make the transition to a rational and durablesocial structure.<p>	The tragedy in this is that everyone has always <i>assumed</i> thatthis method for determining rightness applies only to thenon-volitional world.  They do this with the deprecating comment that"... well, you can't apply this to human behavior."  What they are tryingto say with the statement is that human beings and their basicbehavioral characteristics are not part of nature--that human beings donot follow the laws of nature in their behavior.  Since we live in <i>this</i>world--and not another and different world--that statement is ignorant,supercilious, and ridiculous.  It is equivalent to the religious beliefthat our specie is the only intelligent life form in this universe, andthat this planet is the center of the universe.<p><a name="6r"></p><p>	Although I do not wish to discuss extensively here the creation ofknowledge--since it is covered in other writings--I would like tocredit the great R&eacute;ne Descartes<a href="#6">[6]</a> with his conceptthat "all theoretical science [knowledge] should be like Euclideangeometry."  In the sense that knowledge on any subject must be based on"axioms," similar to those used in geometry.  An equivalent conceptbeing the formulation of postulates as the basis for creating new anduseful knowledge on any subject..  That there must be a least two suchpostulates, but probably not three.  And that there can be no<i>meaningful</i> progress in any area of knowledge without such postulates.<p>	This is the reason that after millennia of experimenting withpolitics, our societal structures still have the same problems they hadthousands of years ago.  The reason it will continue, and become worse,with only two possible outcomes.  Mankind will abandon the concept thatsocietal structures based on coercion is an acceptable foundingprinciple for a volitional society, or our specie will continue itsinexorable decline into oblivion.<p>	Descartes thought that laws of nature could be seen to be truethrough the use of reason alone, which was elegantly proven--as if itneeded to be proven--by Einstein.  The only thing needed to accomplishthis is the use of the epistemological tool mankind has always used toacquire and validate new and useful knowledge.<p>	I hesitate to even mention the name for the method of determiningrightness in the non-volitional world, since--as alluded to above--allnon-thinkers will immediately say "Hah!  You are talking about scienceand we need to talk about the world of people, the behavior of people,and about out social structures!"  Please, bear with me...<p>	The epistemological tool we use in what is commonly called "science"is <i>The Scientific Method</i>.  Basically, this involves:</p><ol>		<li>Make one or more hypotheses that <i>may</i> explain a phenomena.	<li>Collect data which, when analyzed and processed <i>may</i> confirm		one of the hypotheses;	<li>Through observation, which can be as part of a planned		experiment or observing a process or phenomena in nature,		attempt to corroborate each hypothesis;	<li>If you can corroborate one <i>hypothesis</i>, then you have created a		<b>theory</b>.</ol><p>	I have somewhat altered the generally accepted steps of the scientificmethod--but not the principles themselves--to more accurately describethe order in which things are generally done.<p>	Assuming an innovator or discoverer makes no errors, then bydisclosing the theory and the method used to corroborate it, othersshould be able to repeat the process and also verify the event. Confirming that what was formerly a hypothesis is indeed a <i>theory</i>.<p>	If this in fact does determine that which is right in thenon-volitional world, how could we summarize this process in just a fewwords?<p>	We could summarize all of the above by saying that the definition of<i>rightness</i> in the non-volitional ("scientific") world is:</p><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5><tr><td>That which is true and valid</td></tr></table></center><p>In other words, that which is:</p><ul>	<li>Based on true premises,	<li>analyzed using valid logic processes, and	<li>corroborated by observation.</ul><center><h4>Volitional Knowledge</h4></center><p>	We have done most of the difficult work to apply the concept tothe volitional domain.  Rather it was done for us by people such asDescartes, [Francis] Bacon, and Galambos.  And in fact it was Galamboswho extended the concept of Bacon and Descartes from the non-volitionalsciences to the volitional sciences.  And, as is common in knowledgecreation, once someone explains the solution to a previously unsolvedproblem, that solution now seems "obvious." For, as ChristianMorgenstern the Younger said:<p><a name="7r"></p><center>"Das Offensichtliche ist das, was man nicht sieht, bis jeman es	erkl&auml;rt."<a href="#7">[7]</a></center><p>	We intuitively know what type of human behavior is "right," butyet--until Galambos--no one took the "simple and obvious" step ofapplying that concept and component to the non-volitional concept ofrightness.  Thereby adapting the principle so that rightness in thevolitional domain may be determined as easily as in the non-volitionaldomain of mankind's knowledge.  This is the concept of <i>morality</i>, orthat which is <i>moral</i>.<p><a name="8r"></p><p>	Galambos therefore performed the second and last integrationof knowledge required of any volitional specie to escape the tyranny ofcoercion-based societies and evolve a social structure whose time scaleof existence will be concomitant with that of their universe.<ahref="#8">[8]</a><p>	Therefore, rightness in the social domain may be expressed bythe statement:</p><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5><tr>		<td>	That which is true, valid, and moral.	</td></tr></table></center><p>	Of course a related problem is that mankind has never had an absolutedefinition of what was moral.  The perceptive person should havealready thought of the solution for this problem:  Use the scientificmethod to create and corroborate a definition for <i>morality</i> or <i>moral</i>.<p>	The integration of the non-volitional sciences before that ofthe volitional sciences creates a dangerous quandary for a volitionalspecie.  It allows them to create the technological ability to destroytheir own specie, while not having the behavioral and associatedsocietal knowledge of how to prevent this.<p>	It is only within the past fifty years or so that we have crossed thethreshold into the "twilight zone."  Prior to that, if one politicalgroup destroyed another, while representing the ultimate personalcatastrophe for each individual who died, it did not endanger thespecie itself.  That is no longer true.  We could destroy our speciewith biological, chemical, or nuclear weapons.<p>	So-called "environmentalists" hold out the concept of the apocalypsebeing caused by pollution.  I agree with them, but not in the sensethey would like.  Pollution will be the proximate cause of the demiseof any end to viable volitional life on this planet, but it will be thepollution of the <i>mind</i>, caused by accepting things which have not beenproven to be false, as being true.  As Thomas Paine said,</p><p><a name="9r"></p><center><table border=4 cellpadding=5><tr>	<td>	"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong,<br>gives it a superficial		appearance of being right"<a href="#9">[9]</a>	</td></tr></table></center><p>	The pollution of knowledge caused by not being able to tell thedifference between right and not right.</p>	<hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>My essay "Human Need" discusses the two basic	principles upon which all human behavior is based.		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>With a good definition of science being "organized,	useful knowledge."		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>This represents a contradiction in terms, since	"science" implies organized knowledge, and the information available	in that area (I do not wish to dignify it by calling "knowledge") is	definitely not organized and universally agreed upon.		<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>As Voltaire said, "It is forbidden to kill...unless	to trumpets."		<a href="#4r">Return</a><p><a name="5"><li>There is a very important difference between that	which is knowable but not yet known (or discovered), and that	which is unknowable.  And the concept itself is extraordinarily	important for the process of knowledge creation.		<a href="#5r">Return</a><p><a name="6"><li>R&eacute;ne Descartes {1596 - 1650} Discourse on	Method, 1637.		<a href="#6r">Return</a><p><a name="7"><li>[The obvious is that which is not seen until someone	first explains it clearly].		<a href="#7r">Return</a><p><a name="8"><li>As a minimum, since it may be possible to travel	between universes.		<a href="#8r">Return</a><p><a name="9"><li>Thomas Paine, Introduction to <i>Common	Sense</i>, Penguin Books, 1983, p. 63.		<a href="#9r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Concept-of-Rightness.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
