<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Universal Salvage Essays</TITLE>	<META Name="AU" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META HTTP-EQUIV="KEYWORDS"		CONTENT="Galambos, government, coercion, capitalism,			history, Bedeman, quality, innovation, invention">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corporation Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, August 13<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Long-Term-Profitability.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, August 13, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>Long-Term Profitability</H3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4></center><hr noshade><center><h4>Synopsis</h4><table width="80%" border=4 cellpadding=5>	<tr><td>Our current understanding of how to create and maximize profits is notcorrect.  This essay discusses the historic concept of the "job," andthe solution to our current problems of innovation, productivity, andquality.</td></table><hr><h4>Preface</h4></center><p><a name="1r"></p><p>	Nothing I say here should be new or startling to a person.  Infact, it may appear so "obvious and common" that the reader may wonderwhy I bother to say it.  As Christian Morgenster The Younger said:</p>	<ul>	<p>	"Das Offensichtliche ist das, was man nicht sieht, bis jeman es 	erkl&auml;rt."<a href="#1">[1]</a>	</p></ul><p>	In fact, a basic problem is that the ideas are so simple and obviousthat most people do not consider them a possible solution to theproblems of innovation, productivity, and quality.	<p><a name="2r"></p><p>This is generally because of a phenomena noted by Thomas Paine when he said:</p><ul>	<p>	"A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong, gives it a superficial	appearance of being right... "<a href="#2">[2]</a>	</p></ul><p>	Yet I have found that the more successful a company is, the moreof my ideas and concepts they are using.  Still, no one company isusing all of them, and certainly not using them explicitly or properly. And is thus not maximizing their long-term profits, which is thesubject of this essay.<p>	This is an attempt to bring the ideas together in a format which willbe understandable to the reader.  The astute and perceptive reader willimmediately grasp the simplicity and elegance of the concepts, and theease of application.	<center><h4>Background</h4></center><p>	As any rational person realizes, profits are essential to theviability of any organization purporting to offer products and servicesto a market.  They are necessary to provide the resources and incomefor, among other things,</p><ul>		<p>	<a name="3r">	</p>	<p>	<li>	New product research;	</p>		<p>	<li>	product improvement research;	</p>		<p>	<li>	funding production of prototypes, whether of a product or		service;<a href="#3">[3]</a>	</p>	<p>	<li>	funding market research and marketing during the early stages		of a product or possible product;	</p>		<p>	<li>	compensating investors.	</p></ul><p>	Profits however perform a more basic function than this.  Theyare a "marker" or indicator of successful company management.  There isa direct relationship between the profitability of a company and thenumber of things done right.  Such as,</p><ul>	<p>	<li>	Product quality;	</p>		<p>	<li>	productivity;	</p>		<p>	<li>	market acceptance and satisfaction.	</p></ul><p>	During the past approximately 100 years there has been an increasingawareness of the need to satisfy these criteria.  And, with it, anincreasing number of ways for accomplishing this, with many of thembeing fads of the moment.<p>	Interestingly, and probably accidentally since there is--as faras I know--no explicit and complete discussion of the subject, the bestsystem existed several hundred years ago.  The system in which a personwas engaged or contracted to do a "job," then being paid for successfulcompletion of the job.  Unfortunately, before explicit thinking and acohesive explanation of this process was written or published, it wasswamped by the system of mass production and companies ofever-increasing size.  Including the concept of putting workers intogroups or classes and then paying them the same amount on an hourlybasis.  And, although this would be and is denied, virtually regardlessof the quantity and quality of their work.  In principle this is whathappens.<p>	As is normal in the creation and evolution of knowledge, manyof these ideas and fads were at least partially correct.  For example,a production organization could benefit from:</p><ul>	<p>	<li>	Controlling costs;	</p>		<p>	<li>	"wellness and fitness" of individuals;	</p>		<p>	<li>	empowerment, and the associated individual initiative;	</p>		<p>	<li>	quality,  even if done in circles, and especially "zero-defects";	</p>		<p>	<a name="4r">	</p>	<p>	<li>	strategic planning;	</p>		<p>	<li>	entrepreneurship, both external and internal (so-called		"intrapreneurship<a href="#4">[4]</a>")	</p>		<p>	<li>	"job enhancement" (a great catch-all)	</p>		<p>	<li>	"sticking to your knitting";	</p>		<p>	<li>	"management by walking about" (see what's going on--or not		going on--in the company);	</p>		<p>	<li>	"the share economy" (a vain attempt, along with "profit		sharing," to compensate individuals according to their production);	</p>		<p>	<li>	theory x, y and z, which, as any mathematician knows, are variable;	</p>	<p>	<li>	training (no one can argue with that).	</p></ul><p>	I do not remember or have access to information on most of theabove concepts, but I wish to give credit to the creators of theconcepts.<p>	Before continuing with a detailed discussion of the above, Iwould like to return to a generalization I made above:<p>	There is a direct relationship between the profitability of a companyand the number of things it does correctly.<p><a name="5r"></p><p>Repeating myself,<a href="#5">[5]</a> long-term profitability can only be achieved through</p><ul>	<p>	<li>	Product quality;	</p>		<p>	<li>	product innovation;	</p>		<p>	<li>	market acceptance of the product(s).	</p></ul><p>	Of course other things are required, such as controlling costsand ensuring productivity, but I would put them under the bonnet ofbeing a successful entrepreneur.<p>	And in fact, I think everything can be summed up by the laststatement, with anything else being in a supporting role.  There willbe long term market acceptance of a company's products only when thecompany is doing virtually everything right.  Granted, as human beings,there is always the possibility of an occasional error or omission, butas these asymptotically approach zero, the profitability of the companyapproaches its maximum.<p>If this is agreed, then the "only" thing remaining is how to maximize:</p><ul>	<p>	<li>	Innovation;	</p>		<p>	<li>	quality;	</p>		<p>	<li>	productivity.	</p></ul><p>	As the discussion unfolds, you will see that the application ofa very simple principle and concept, easily employed, allows thesefactors to be maximized,  Further, as a byproduct, all the othernecessary activities or attributes are handled.  Such as:</p>	<ul>		<p>	<li>	Cost control;	</p>		<p>	<li>	training;	</p>		<p>	<li>	attendance at the workplace;	</p></ul><p>	Including even such problems as vacations and holidays, pensions,medical insurance and assorted other items now deemed to almostintractable.  I won't elaborate on that statement, but leave it to theperson who wishes to do some thinking on their own to realize how andwhy this is true.<p>	In employing the new process, all past and present fads--at least thevalid parts of them--will be covered, such as:</p><ul>		<p>	<li>	Management by objective;	</p>	<p>	<li>	operations research;	</p>	<p>	<li>	time & motion studies;	</p>	<p>	<li>	decentralization;	</p>	<p>	<li>	recentralization	</p>	<p>	<li>	empowerment;	</p>	<p>	<li>	job enhancement;	</p>	<p>	<li>	sticking to your knitting (and not sticking to it);	</p>	<p>	<li>	quality circles;	</p>	<p>	<li>	intrapreneurship;	</p>	<p>	<li>	the share economy (and profit sharing);	</p>		<p>	<li>	theory x, y, and z (which covers everything else).	</p></ul><p>	Let's examine some of the more serious concepts that almostanyone would consider as important to the success of a business. Wewill find that they are all much more closely related than is realized.<center><h4>Solution</h4></center>	<h4>Empowerment</h4><p><a name="6r"></p><p>For the purpose of this discussion, I will define this term as follows:</p><ul>	<p>	"Allowing the individual to maximize the decision(s) regarding how and	when something is to be done."<a href="#6">[6]</a>	</p></ul><p>	What is the optimum way to do this?  By providing the product orservice specification, and then allowing the person to make thedecision how it will be done.  For a tangible product this may be avery detailed specification, while for a service it may only specify adesired outcome.  Such as "increasing sales by 20%," or "satisfying thecustomer."  The latter of course being the required end-result for anyproduct or service.<p><a name="7r"></p><p>	The best way of doing this is the "job" concept of several hundredyears ago, or the system under which a person might contract for theservices of a gardener, baby sitter, or airline pilot today.<a href="#7">[7]</a></p><ul>		<p>	<li>	Provide the person with a product or service specification;	</p>		<p>	<li>	agree on when it must be completed;	</p>		<p>	<li>	agree on the price for satisfactory completion.	</p></ul><p>	The specification must include the quality, which for most productswould be the fabled, but no longer fabulous, "zero-defects," togetherwith the handling of the situation when and if there are defects.  Ofcourse any such defects must be for the account of the "defector"--theindividual who creates them.	<h4>Quality</h4><p>	In principle we have already covered this: The standard for jobcompletion and delivery is "no defects."  With the person creating aproduct with defects being responsible for rectifying them, includingreimbursement for wasted resources if this occurs.  Whether they arematerials, electricity provided by the contractor, the use ofmachine-aids, or anything else.<p>	Quality now becomes almost a non-consideration, with total qualitybeing an assumed attribute.  If not there initially, it appears soon orthere is no payment for task performance.  Which of course has a majorinput to profitability.  And of course end-customer satisfaction.<p>	When an individual is put in the position where they must recognizeand correct their own mistakes (not the mistakes of others, unless paidto do so), a wonderful thing happens.  It is called "learning byexperience," with the end result being constantly increasingcompetence.  And, in a system where a person is compensated basedalmost exclusively on their own, individual competence, their earningability is suddenly much less restricted than before.  And, any such"restrictions" on their earnings are not imposed on them by someoneelse.  The correction of which are under their own control.	<h4>Training</h4><p>	The astute reader will realize that training now takes care of itself. Why?  Because the better and faster the individual can perform a task,the higher their income.  There is now a direct and positiverelationship between education, ability, imagination, and drive.  Themajor attributes an individual brings to any task.<p>	The individual will now have a "burning interest" in their owneducation.  They may satisfy this by investigating and funding theirown, direct means of accomplishing this, or even by negotiating a dealwith the contractor or entrepreneur under which they work together fortheir mutual benefit.  As opposed to the current adversarial system inwhich the individual complains they are not getting adequate training. With the company then arranging and funding it with some degree oftrepidation, if not reluctance.	<h4>Innovation</h4><p>	This old-fashioned method of handling jobs also opens the doorto the main way in which innovation is encouraged and will flourish,and in which the individual truly assumes control of their own destiny. And becomes an entrepreneur in their own right, and not simply a"worker."<p>	When people are left to do a job on their own, an interestingthing takes place.  A basic law of volitional behavior comes into play:<p>	Individual thinking beings seek to acquire the most amount ofproperty for the least amount of effort.<p>	This is an elegant way of saying that individual human beingsare lazy.  A phenomena taken into consideration by Henry Ford. Undertaking  a new project, he would--in a sense--look for the laziest(but capable) person he knew.  He would put that person in charge ofthe project, knowing they would look for shortcuts.  A common way ofsaying the individual would "innovate."  Innovation is the key to:</p><ul>		<p>	<li>	New products;	</p>		<p>	<li>	improved products;	</p>		<p>	<li>	product manufacturing processes;	</p>		<p>	<li>	improved product manufacturing processes;	</p>		<p>	<li>	productivity;	</p>		<p>	<li>	quality.	</p></ul><p>	In fact, nothing happens without innovation.  There is no product orway to produce one.  Yet we do almost everything that could be done toprevent or inhibit innovation.  With the most significant being ourmethod of production compensation: Paying people on the basis of BeingThere.  By their presence in the workplace, almost regardless of thequantity and quality of work.  Rather than on the basis of:</p>	<center>		<p>		The market value of their error-free production.		</p></center><p>	It just slipped out.  I have given you the key to dramatic increasesin all factors of production:</p>	<ul>	<p>	<li>	Innovation;	</p>		<p>	<li>	productivity;	</p>		<p>	<li>	quality.	</p></ul><p>and therefore to long-term profitability</p><h4>Productivity</h4><p>I just gave you the answer to this problem in the section above on innovation.</p><h4>Profit Sharing</h4><p>	This also needs no further discussion, since--in any case--the conceptis a non-starter.  It is actually communism and/or socialism broughtinto the production environment.<p>	When each individual is compensated for their production according toits error-free market value, we no longer need the concept of "profitsharing."</p>	<center><h4>Conclusion</h4></center><p>	I believe the reader should do some thinking and draw their ownconclusion to the above statements.  In a sense I don't care what theyare.  If you agree with me, then you have learned something.  If youdon't, there can be no doubt about the validity of the ideas, so it isyour loss and not mine.  Except that I will lose also, because we willcontinue to do things in an irrational and immoral way, and it is nocomfort to be me that I am right while everything continues to limpalong as before.</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol>	<p><a name="1"><li>	"The obvious is that which is not seen until	someone first expresses it clearly."  Christian Morgensten the	Younger (Lyric Poet)		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>	Thomas Paine, Introduction to Common Sense,	Penguin Books, 1983, p. 63		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>Services is essentially a redundant term, being only	a specialized product form, however I will use the word service	to differentiate between tangible and less-intangible products.		<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>	With credit to Gifford Pinchot II for his	book Intrapreneuring (Harper and Row -224 p.)		<a href="#4r">Return</a><p><a name="5"><li>	Repetition is a valid from of teaching and	learning. Further, the more ingrained are incorrect ideas, the	more repetition required to dislodge them and point the individual	toward correct ideas.		<a href="#5r">Return</a><p><a name="6"><li>	By "when" I refer to the actual time in which the	person will perform the task, recognizing that the entrepreneur	may set a time frame in which it must be completed.  A completion	deadline, which would be part of the production contract.		<a href="#6r">Return</a><p><a name="7"><li>At least the way Southwest Airlines does  it, which	is to contract with the pilot to fly a sector or sectors.		<a href="#7r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Long-Term-Profitability.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
