<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Loopholes &amp; the Political State</TITLE>	<META Name="AU" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META HTTP-EQUIV="KEYWORDS"		CONTENT="Galambos, government, coercion, capitalism, 			history, Bedeman, freedom, liberty, justice, crime">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corporation Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, August 15<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Loopholes-Political-State.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, August 13, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>Loopholes and Political Societies</H3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4></center><hr noshade><table border=4 width="100%"><td><center><h4>Synopsis</h4></center><p>This essay will explain and discuss one of the two basic, motivationaland behavioral characteristics of volitional beings: The desire tocreate, accumulate, and use property.  And, how this is contrary to thewishes of the politicians, who want to control and limit theaccumulation and use of individual property.  How this creates thesearch for "loopholes" in the system, with the politicians also lookingfor them, but to close them.  How this creates increasing stresses inthe associated society, leading to increasing violence and the eventualdestruction of the society.</p></table><hr><p>	We hear a lot about loopholes.  Almost everyone looks for them. Individuals look for them.  Looking for a way to avoid or reduce thisor that tax.  Companies look for them.  A way to get around this orthat regulation.  Bureaucrats look for them of course, but fordifferent reasons.  Individuals and companies want to find them to gothrough them: Politicians and the sub-class "bureaucrat" want to findthem to close them.<p>	Each group has their own reason for finding loopholes, and theyoften search for different types of loopholes.  Almost like a treasurehunt, and there often is a treasure at the end of the hunt, which isthe reason for searching for loopholes.  It all seems like a jollygame, yet it is anything but funny, as it has vast implications for theviability and even the survival of political societies.  And,eventually, of the specie itself.<p>	Why do individuals and companies search for loopholes?	<p>	The answer is obvious and simple: Individuals wish to preserve,safeguard, augment, and enhance their property. And, although this issimple and obvious, it has a very profound meaning and consequences.<p>	The desire to create, accumulate, and enjoy property is a basictrait of all volitional beings.  The recognition of this and how it isimplemented in a society of volitional beings is crucial to itsprosperity and even to its survival, since it is <i>the</i> basic behavioralcharacteristic of an individual being and, therefore, of a society ofvolitional beings.<p>	When I refer to property I include all types of property, andnot just the obvious--tangible property.  I include ideas, or what isoften called "intellectual" property.  And even the pleasurable ideasof a human being, such as the enjoyment of a sunset, of seeing a childsmile, or smelling a rose, feeling the touch of another human being. This intangible property is in fact even more important than thetangible type, for it is a necessary precursor to the creation oftangible property.  The beauty of the sound of a symphony orchestra,the image of a ballerina such as Margot Fonteyn in <i>Nutcracker</i>, or anice skater dancing to <i>Swan Lake</i> may send the mind on a beautifulvoyage of new, wonderful, and useful ideas which will benefit all humanbeings.  Besides bringing enjoyment to the listener.<p>	If this concept of the importance of property and its functionis recognized by the societal structure and not hindered, that societywill flourish and survive in the long term.  Meaning a periodconcomitant with that of their universe.  If it is not recognized, andattempts are made to curtail this basic characteristic of volitionalbeings regarding property creation and use, then the associated societywill rise and then fall, to be replaced by another.  With the cyclerepeating itself until the end of the acceptance of coercion as a basisfor social structures, or the end of the associated specie. Thephenomena Gibbon recognized in his magnificent work "The Rise and Fallof the Roman Empire."  The fate of the Roman Empire can be generalizedfor all societies having the same operational principle as the RomanEmpire--that of a society based on coercion.<p>	The astute reader will immediately recognize the problem: That, since all individuals live to enjoy property, and</p><ul><p>	any curtailment of this desire will produce friction betweenthe individual and the controller(s).</p></ul><p>	The more friction, the more heat (another law of nature), andthe greater the disorder (a related law of nature).<p>	There are many pieces of evidence throughout history to supportthis.  The rise and fall of political societies.  The famous ones ofhistory such as Byzantium, the Egypt of the Pharaohs, the democracy ofGreece, the monarchy of the Romans, Spanish, Portuguese, and BritishEmpires.  In recent times the Austro-Hungarian Empire, the RussianEmpire, both that of the classic Czars and the Communist czars.  Andnow we watch with fascination and incomprehension as the formerYugoslavia is split asunder.<p>	Another piece of evidence is the subject of this essay: Loopholes. The struggle by individuals to find them and exploit them, and of thepolitical masters to close them. And, interestingly, each is trying topreserve and to augment their respective property.<p>	For the individual it might be to save some money on taxes, orto prevent confiscation of some real property such as a car or house. The politician is preserving their own personal job and the system inwhich they function.  I won’t dignify it by saying "... the system inwhich they ‘work’," as <i>work</i> is a positive and useful concept.  Itinvolves the creation of property, whereas the activity of thepolitician and bureaucrat involves the control, destruction ordissemblement of property.<p>	This has always gone on in political societies--social structuresbased on  coercion--and will always do so because it is basic to thebehavior of a volitional being.<p>	In the early stages of coercive societies there is relatively less ofthis activity, as the coercion is relatively less with more opportunityto protect individual property.  A good example of this is the earlydays of what is commonly called "the United States."  There wasrelatively little coercion, since the US was largely founded on thebasis of getting away from the rigid and relatively much higher levelof coercion in Europe and other places.<p>	The kings and other rulers of Europe during the period preceding andduring the mass exodus to the United States would be green with envy ifthey could see the level of coercion in the United States now.  Thearea of less or no coercion to which their subjects fled has changedconsiderably.<p>	When even this mild level of coercion in the 1700s and early 1800s ofthe United States became too much, individuals moved west to get awayfrom it.  The result of this relatively low level of coercion was thecreation of the foundation for the economic power of the United States. It was an atmosphere in which interest in the creation of propertyvastly exceeded interest and willingness in controlling and curtailingit.<p>	One way of curtailing property accumulation is through inheritancetaxes.  Politicians consider this necessary, since if there were nocontrols on property accumulation, the power of individuals outside ofthe control mechanism could become a threat to those inside it--thepoliticians.  Even with their monopoly on police powers.<p>	The relatively low level of coercion during the early years ofthe United States was also fostered by the political constitution andthe construction of the associated political régime.  Especially duringthe term of the first five presidents, in whom the founding principlesof property sanctity and non-interference in the property of others wasvery strong.<p>	At first the constitution made it difficult to create and focuspolitical, coercive power.  Individuals of the House of Representativesand the Senate had worthwhile things to do with their lives, and tookrelatively less interest in interfering in the lives and property ofothers.  But, slowly, they began talking and working with each other totheir mutual benefit and the detriment of those they purported torepresent.<p>	As those who cherished freedom and the sanctity of propertypassed away and--coincidentally--individuals got as far west as theycould go and the bureaucrats had them cornered--the level of coercionslowly began to increase.  Yet the level of coercion was stillrelatively quite low with loopholes hardly needed, and the needed oneslarge and tolerant.  The bureaucrats and politicians (B&Ps) not sonumerous and dedicated.  [I originally used "professional" (withquotation marks), rather then <i>dedicated</i>, but do not like to call theactivity of B&Ps "professional."]  And, as I said, many of the earlyB&Ps were themselves entrepreneurs and creators of property, and sowere relatively less interested in interfering in the life and propertyof others.<p>	But as the B&Ps became more numerous and dedicated to "taking care ofthe people and the business of the people," they begin to close theloopholes.  They become more and more difficult to find and to use.  Asthe B&Ps interfere more and more in individual life and begin to assumeresponsibilities which should rest with the individual, individualsbecome less interested in, and less capable of handling theseresponsibilities for themselves.  After all, "... the state will takecare of me."<p><a name="1r"></p><p>	Politics and political power became an obsession in itself.  The B&Psacquired Acton's Disease<a href="#1">[1]</a> and, seeing the ability to fulfill theirneeds through satisfying the "needs" of the masses, they startedstroking these needs.  Subliminally, they recognized the basicbehavioral characteristic of human beings and exploited it.  A bit likecigarette companies do with cigarettes, with the politicians creatingthe cancerous growth of the political state.  A growth that they nowseem unable to stop, it having gotten beyond even their control.<p>	With this comes an increasingly large, dysfunctional and unproductiveelement of the society, dependent on those who <i>are</i> producing. Forgetting it is not possible to consume that which has not beenproduced.  The decay of individual responsibility and--with it--of theeducational system, creates unemployment.  Worse, it creates a largegroup of <i>unemployable</i> people.  Add to this a minimum wage system andvastly increased interference in what is left of the free marketprocess and the number of productive people begin to decline relativeto the unproductive.  Factor in a so-called "democratic" system underwhich a majority clamors for and votes for B&Ps who will provide themwith what they feel they need, and you have a recipe for disaster.<p>	Voting for someone who promises to provide you with propertywith little or no effort on your part is consistent with the basicnature of volitional beings, yes?  It is also easy for the politician,as they need not work for it either.  Merely create a law saying thatthose who produce must share with those who do not.  This works lesswell as the number of non-producers increases relative to the number ofproducers.<p>	The number of loopholes become less at the same time as the envy anddissatisfaction with everyday life increases.  Both for those notreceiving as much as they think they should, and for those required togive part of their property to others.  It becomes more and moredifficult for the productive element to create and to hold onto theirproperty, while at the same time such activity is decried by theunproductive and dysfunctional element who want such production to be"shared" with them.<p>	They--the receivers as opposed to the creators--now control thelevers of power through the political voting system, and the B&Psanswer their siren call by plugging more and more holes and giving awaymore and more of what is produced.<p>	They are able to sustain this in spite of dissatisfaction as they nowcontrol the financial system and can tinker with it as required toachieve their ends.  Substituting fraud for force.  Even when it defiesall reason, such as the so-called "social security" system, which isneither a "social" system nor a system of "security."  And blaminginflation on price increases, rather than the debasement of thecurrency by the politicians.<p>	Frustration increases on all sides.  Individuals and businessestake greater and greater risks in finding and exploiting loopholes,while the minions of the régime fight back with ever-more Draconian,immoral, irrational, and ridiculous rules.  Another, and very basicreason the B&Ps can get away with this is because they also have amonopoly on police powers.  With the dichotomy of thought thatmonopolies are "bad" unless created by the state, and then they are"good." As George Orwell said,</p><ul>	<p>		"In our time, political speech and writing are largely the defence of	the indefensible."	</p></ul><p>and,</p><ul>	<p>	"<i>Doublethink</i> means the power of holding two contradictory	beliefs in one's mind simultaneously, and accepting both of them."	</p></ul><p>	Orwell was very perceptive, elegantly describing the "basic behavioralcharacteristics" of politicians with those two statements...<p>	Eventually some individuals begin to feel that the only way toobtain redress for and alleviate their frustrations is by the samemechanism used by the political state: Force.  It is irrational, andonly results in increasing and more stringent laws, and more vigorousenforcement of them.<p>	Yet this is the proximate cause for the disorder in coercivesocieties.  And, since those are the only type of societies on thisplanet, it is a planet-wide problem.  And thus a specie-wide problem. The natural desire of volitional beings to create, accumulate and enjoythe use of their property, but living in a coercive society whose mainfunction is the control of this property, its creation, accumulationand use.  Even its enjoyment, with laws restricting almost all aspectsof such enjoyment.  Opening hours and licensing requirements for placesof entertainment, control of the alcoholic beverage industry, controlof gambling and an associated myriad of laws, rules, regulations,measures, bills, and all the other euphemisms for the decrees anddictates of the political régime.<p>	Of course this control is for the "good" of the people, and certainlynot to satisfy the habit and "high" that comes to those with politicalpower.  Right?<p>	There is only one solution to this problem.  That is to createa societal structure whose characteristics are consistent with thenature of man (the specie), and not with those characteristics whichtry to deny or change nature.  This means a social structure in whichall forms of property are protected completely,  Not by a coercive,police-state mechanism, but by a mechanism which takes intoconsideration and is based on the nature of volitional beings<p>	This, the solution to the crises of our societal structures, isdiscussed in "False Alternatives & Human Destiny," a limiteddistribution essay.<p>	In the meantime, you might do some thinking of your own on thesubject.</p>	<hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>"Power tends to corrupt and absolute power corrupts	absolutely."  J. E. E. D. Acton {1834-1902}, Letter to Bishop Mandell	Creighton, 1887, April 3.		<a href="#1r">Return</a></ol> <HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Loopholes-Political-State.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
