<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Protest &amp; Human Survival</TITLE>	<META Name="Author" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META Name="Keys"		CONTENT="Galambos,government,coercion,capitalism,			history,Bedeman,property,human behavior,equality,			responsibility">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corporation Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, August 3<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Protest-Human-Survival.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, Month Day, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>Protesting &amp; Human Survival</H3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4></center><hr noshade><center><h4>Synopsis</h4><table width="80%" border="4"><tr><td><a name="1r">In political societies, in which the rulers and their minions try tocreate "equality," protesting is the attempt by individuals to maintaintheir own identity and pursue their individual aspirations in a sea ofsameness.  This leads to increasing disorder in which the societalstructure either self-destructs or is taken over by another politicalentity.  The only solution to this basic dilemma is the creation of arational and social structure based on the nature of man<ahref="#1">[1]</a>.</td></tr></table></center><p>	There is a very interesting connection between the attempt tocreate equality in political societies and political protesting. Protesting in the form of marches, strikes, and assorted other things.And between those things and disorder in political societies, and eventhe survival of the specie.<p>	Several days ago when I jotted down the title on my computer screen Ihad a totally different thought concerning how I would start thisessay, and what would be the main example or examples I would use.  Itwas only while watching one of the daily renditions of societaldisasters--euphemistically referred to as the television "news"--that theconnection between protesting and equality struck me.<p>	I believe someone was complaining about "fat cat" salaries, implyingthat the money paid to various business managers was too much.  Theimplication being that either their salary should be greatly reduced,or the salary of others should be raised to that level.  To achieve amore "equitable" situation.<p>	I think I know where this original concept of "equality" originated,at least in modern times, and what fosters it.  What makes it fester,like a sore that refuses to heal.  I believe it originated from thestatement in the American Declaration of Independence, stating that "...all men are created equal, that they are endowed by their creator withcertain inalienable rights... ," etc.<p>	Many of the so-called "founding fathers" of the United Stateswere very well educated men.  Men of great intellectual ability and asweeping understanding of history.  More importantly, many of them hadstudied what at that time was termed "natural philosophy"--the study ofnature and the natural sciences.  Unlike the intellectuallydisadvantaged of today's American political scene.<p>	Unfortunately, the founding fathers assumed succeeding generationswould be as well or better educated than themselves, and that they neednot explain what being "created equal" meant.  That it meant "createdequal under the laws of nature."  That this "equality" of creationmeant each individual was different from every other.  And that their"pursuit of happiness" would embody this difference.  That each andevery individual would have a different idea of what constitutedhappiness for them.  That each would have their own, differentaspirations in life.<p>	This "equality" is ensured--as we know now, and which they couldonly feel at the time--by that wonderful spiral helix of our DNA.  Whichsays that, practically speaking, there is virtually no chance that anytwo human beings will be identical in their genetic makeup.  Add tothat a slightly different environment and upbringing for eachindividual child, and you have as many interpretations of happiness astheir are people on the planet.<p><a name="2r"></p><p>	In a free society, a truly free society, in which each individualcould do whatever they wished as long as it did interfere in theproperty of another person<a href="#2">[2]</a>, people would be able tofollow their own individual dreams and paths to "pursue" their owndefinitions of happiness.  This is nature, and--in the absence ofcoercion--this is what will happen.<p>	Probably the best example of this actually happening on thisplanet is during the approximate time from 1700-1850 in what is nowknown as the United States.  People were generally more interested increating and building things than interfering in each other's lives. They were too busy for that.  And if that began to happen, they couldmove some distance west and there would be no one to bother them.<p>	The problem began when they reached the Pacific Ocean and therewas nowhere else to go. And the society became increasingly moreaffluent, with the possibility of more leisure time.  And observethat--according to the laws of nature--there were some people who werebetter off than others.  And, sadly, that there were some people whotook advantage of others.  This is also consistent with a basic law ofhuman behavior, which states that:</p><center><table width="60%" border="4"><tr><td>	<b>	Individual volitional beings seek to acquire the most amount of	property for the least amount of effort</b>.</td></tr></table></center><p>	As explained in other essays, this would be a problem for a freesociety were it not for a basic, counter-balancing behavioralprinciple.  I will state this principle without comment so that youwill do some thinking on your own:</p><center><table  border="4"><tr><td>	<b>	All individuals seek happiness</b>.</td></tr></table></center><p><a name="3r"></p><p>	If you need an explanation of this I commend to you my essay entitled<i>Need and Morality in Society</i>.<a href="#3">[3]</a><p><a name="4r"><a name="5r"></p><p>	The situation of everyone having a different definition ofhappiness for themselves, of different hopes and aspirations and meansof achieving them, is anathema to political societies.  To societiesbased on coercion.  Whether they are so-called "democracies"<ahref="#4">[4]</a> or a blatant dictatorship<a href="#5">[5]</a>.  Therequirement for sameness and conformity increases with the age ofpolitical entities.<p>	By controlling the lives of all their subjects political societiesprevent individuals from realizing their full potential.  This isfurther exacerbated by primitive concepts of production and innovationcompensation that group everyone into rather rigid groups.  In thissituation, individuals who are "achievers" regardless of theconstraints are marked as "different" and often attract envy.<p>	A societal structure that controls behavior and creates an atmospherein which there is less and less ability to be different also createsincreasing frustrations for the associated individuals.  Regardless ofhow hard or well the individual works, there is less and lesspossibility for them to express their individuality through positiveachievements.<p>	The society becomes more and more rigid, with more and morelaws saying what you can not do.  And, eventually, the feeling thatnothing is permitted or may done unless specifically allowed.  Andtalking to your "representative" from the ruling group does not do anygood.  Some of them may truly want to help you, but then there areother supplicants with identical or conflicting problems.  And, intruth and practically, your agent or representative can not alter thepolitical state to suit each of the million "clients" they mayrepresent.<p>	The political laws are there for everyone to obey, or there will bedisorder.  Although it appears there is disorder even when they areobeyed.  Which of course brings the call for both more laws, and morecomplete and rigid enforcement of existing ones.<p><a name="6r"><a name="7r"></p><p>	When the individual can not persuade their representative tohandle their problem for them, they begin to look for other ways tohandle the problem.  Perhaps by banding together with people who have asimilar problem or outlook.  Not being able to just ignore the law<a href="#6">[6]</a>, they begin to seek to change it by whatever meansthey can.  First "legally<a href="#7">[7]</a>" and in accordance withthe political laws and, when that doesn't work, "taking the law intotheir own hands."<p>	As every political society matures its laws become moreall-encompassing and restrictive.  It even becomes more difficult toascertain whether a given action is proscribed or permitted.  When theso-called "Supreme Court" of the United States votes 5-4 on somethingit means even they do not agree.  Probably because they also do noteven understand the problem and the associated laws.<p>	Further, their decision does not mean there will be there willbe no more protests.  Because, after all, the decision requiresindividuals follow some other persons' definition of "happiness," andto forego their own aspirations for their life.<p>	This is why, as political societies mature, they experienceincreasing internal disorder.  In the old days, when the specie stilllacked the technological ability to destroy itself, the "only" thinkthat happened was the a younger political society--taking advantage ofthe internal disorder--conquered the decaying society.  With increasingtechnology this becomes less of a probability than a mistake ormisunderstanding resulting in a cataclysmic end.<p>	The only way out of this is through the construction of a rationaland durable social structure based on an understanding of the basicbehavioral characteristics stated above.  It happens this is available,off-the-shelf knowledge, although no one seems interested.</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol>	<p><a name="1"><li>The specie, not the male of the specie.	<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>This is the defining characteristic of a rational	and durable society.  Of a truly free society.		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>Available at &lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Human-	Need.html&gt;		<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>Democracy: "A societal structure in which a	minority of the people control the lives and property of all members	of the society."		<a href="#4r">Return</a><p><a name="5"><li>Dictatorship: "A societal structure in which one or	several individuals control the lives and property of members	of the society."	<p>	If you disagree with these definitions, think about the operative	principle of all political societies.  The basic principle, not	the image.	</p>		<a href="#5r">Return</a><p><a name="6"><li>Political laws must be obeyed else the political	state will collapse.  In truth, all political laws must be enforced	at whatever cost--even up to and including death for the violator.	Were this not so, they and the concept could not survive.  The	problem is, as history tell us, the concept itself can not survive	when it is based on that principle.		<a href="#6r">Return</a><p><a name="7"><li>Legal:  "Any action that is permitted under a	political law."	<p>	The concept has not connection with rationality and morality,	these concepts being generally mutually exclusive with the concept of	legality or illegality.	</p>		<a href="#7r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Protest-Human-Survival.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
