one other thanthe "needee" or the needy <b>must</b> satisfy the need.  A pleading"must" and a demanding "must."<p>	All of this without defining the word "need," and certainly with nouniversal agreement how it is to be done or by whom.  Except that--asstated above--it is certainly not the needy who must handle thesituation.<p>	To discuss the subject of need we must break it into two parts: Those required to sustain life, and "discretionary" needs.  The latterare things that would be nice to have, but not absolutely necessary tosustain life.<P>The things necessary to sustain life are:</p><ul>	<li>Water;	<li>food;	<li>shelter from the elements of nature.</ul><p>	Without water a human being will die within a few days.  Withoutfood they will die in some period less than three months, and probablyless than two.<p>	Shelter may be a bit optional in a sense if a person lives in atemperate climate, although in this discussion we will assume that someform of shelter is necessary for all human beings.<p>	Who should provide the water, food, and shelter?  Or, morespecifically, who has the <b>responsibility</b> for providing it?<p>	For very primitive, early man, it would seem obvious that individualshad to provide for themselves.  There were very few individuals andcertainly no organization to do it for the individual.  There waslittle or no concept of "specialization of labor."  No capitalaccumulation and concept of investment and businesses to provideproducts or services.<p>	Given this simple societal structure we could ask ourselves howone individual would get others to provide these services for them? There are only two ways.  One is through a voluntary agreement amongthe few individuals.  To trade services and the associated provision ofa product such as food, water, and shelter.  Which course is a"specialization" or "division" of labor system, although they wouldhave been doing what seemed natural and mutually profitable withoutarticulating the concept.<p>	The only other method possible is through force or fraud.  Requiringsomeone to do it under threat of some specified or unspecifiedundesirable action, or by tricking and deceiving them into doing it. This would be consistent with one basic trait or characteristic of allvolitional beings, which is:<ul><p>Principle No. 1:</p><ul><p><b>The desire to accumulate the most amount of property<br>for the least amount of effort</b>.</p></ul></ul><p>	In <b>principle</b> there is nothing wrong this basic trait, and in fact ifyou think about it is seems almost mandatory for any thinking being tohave this attribute.  The opposite is almost unthinkable.  It wouldcreate total apathy and lethargy, and is in fact what might be part ofan operative definition of "hell."  Along with the possibility ofknowing everything.  What would be the purpose of living if you kneweverything?  As Anatole France said:</p><ul><p><a name="1r"></p><p>	"Ignorance is the necessary condition of life itself.  If weknew everything, we could not endure existence for a single hour."<a href="#1">[1]</a></p></ul><p>	Forcing or deceiving people into providing goods and services is alsoa prescription for continuing strife, as this interferes with <b>their</b>basic desire of having the most for the least amount of effort.<p>	Although I don’t want to discuss it in detail here, as it iscovered in other essays, there is another reason for an individual tobe responsible for acquiring the means of survival for themselves.  Itinvolves the concept of <b>morality</b> and that which is <b>moral</b>. Interference in, and control of the property of another.  Employingthis concept or allowing this to happen also lays the foundation forcontinuing strife in a society.  It is what causes people to use forceor fraud in the achievement of their objectives.<p>	Principle No. 1 might also be a major reason for the statementthat man is "war-like," and that war will always be a part of humanlife and existence.  If the above basic trait did not have a balancingone which is equally powerful, this would be so.  And the specie wouldbe doomed to eternal strife, disorder, and war.<p>What is this balancing trait?</p><ul><p>Principle No. 2:</p><ul><p><b>All individuals seek happiness</b>.</p></ul></ul><p>	Do you think that is true or not true?  Would you dispute it orquibble about it?  Doesn’t it seem natural?  Would an individual,acting of their own free will and without coercion, voluntarily chooseto be unhappy?<p>	That can occasionally <b>appear</b> to be so, but to have it actuallybe so--and a principle of life--is also unthinkable.<p>	Because each individual has their own definition and image ofhappiness, the operation of this principle can sometimes be deceptive. Especially when people will say they or another person are doingsomething for someone else. After all, could it bring happiness to aperson to drown in the process of saving their child?  This is somewhatof an extreme example, and I think if we can handle this example we mayachieve partial belief in the principle?<p>	Let's look at it from the other side.  You go ahead and letyour child drown because obviously you might or will die, and who wantsto do that?  Yet any sane and rational parent would be devastated bythe thought they had let their child die while they lived.  If I lastedlong enough to shave the next morning and look at myself in the mirror,I would probably kill myself then and there.<p>	Of course you don't want to die, but the life you have createdis as precious or more so than your own.  And always the thought thatthey have almost their entire life ahead of them and have experiencednone of it, while yours is perhaps one-third finished.  Not to speak ofthat wonderful thing called "love," and of caring for someone.<p>	Further, what would your wife, children, relatives and friendsthink of a person who had been unwilling to make the effort?  Thisalone could create a lifetime of unhappiness.<p>	Granted, the decision to leap into the water is not prefaced byall of these thoughts, although undoubtedly for many parents thethought of giving up their life for their child has crossed their mind. The thought had been planted in their mind that, "Yes, I would dothat."  Also, we are surrounded by stories of people who have donethat. So, while our action is spontaneous and without thinking, thethinking and desire to take that action if necessary has already beendone.  We know that if we did not do it we would be truly unhappy.	<p>I promise--I will get back to the subject of "need"!</p>	<p>	I could provide many examples to illustrate the truth of theabove two principles.  It will be better though if you think about themand whether they influence your actions.  And look at the world aroundyou and see if you can corroborate them.  Don't assume them to betrue--or false--just see if the actions of you and your fellow humanbeings corroborate the principles.<p>	The next thing to do is to see how these two principles work togetherto influence human behavior.  This might also help your understandingof the individual attributes or principles.  It is the principlesworking together that explains both the problems of our societalstructures and provides the answer for solving those problems.<p>	While Principle No. 1 would create the havoc with everyone "outfor themselves," Principle No. 2 prevents that from happening. Stealing something from your neighbor might appear to be easier thanmaking it yourself or creating something that you could trade for it. It might appear to require the least amount of effort.  And, to have itmight even make you "happier."  But it might also make your neighbormuch less happy to lose his property.  In fact, so unhappy that he isangry with you.  And ready to bash in your skull.  Further, he willtell everyone in the neighborhood that you are a thief.  The resultbeing that you may not be as happy as you initially thought you wouldbe.<p>	Perhaps you could withstand the bash on the head, and maybe even giveas good or better than you got.  But there is still the matter ofeveryone in the neighborhood knowing you are a thief, and not to betrusted.  Maybe they wouldn't even want to associate with you in thefuture.  In the long term such thoughts could be more important and thedeciding factor.<p>	All thinking beings, even people who may not always be rationalor totally rational make value judgments regarding their actions.  Thatprocess tells them whether they will happier, or at least less unhappy,but taking one action as opposed to another.  Or not taking any action. Such as not stealing something from the neighbor.<p>	Principle No. 2 guides us in doing those things which bring positiverewards, and prevents us from doing those things which provide negativerewards.  The things which makes us happier or less unhappy, and thethings which would not make us happy.  And, besides our own happinessis that reflected from others, especially the opinion or feeling ofthose people important to us.  There is also the matter of how we"feel" about ourselves, which is generally called self-esteem.  Ouropinion of our own self-worth.<p>	Principle No. 2 might even be called a "regulating" mechanism,in that it regulates our behavior to that which please ourselves orincreases or maintains our self-esteem and provides in image forourselves in society.  Whether a person appears to honest andtrustworthy, or the opposite.  In this sense it is like a "creditrating" for ourselves and our lives.<p>	Although I will not give examples to substantiate it here, thisis the only regulatory mechanism or "law" required in a free society. And the only way a society can be free.  Operating under such aconcept, a society has no need for a vast system of regulations and anauthority which has a monopoly on police powers to enforce theregulations.<p>	The perceptive reader may realize that such a system works againstboth of these principles of human behavior.  Which is why societalsystems based on coercion do not work, and why the history of thesocietal structures on this planet can be summarized by "The Rise andFall of (blank)," putting in the name of a dearly departedcivilization.  Byzantium, Macedonia, ancient Egypt and Greece, Rome,etc.<p>	Think about that later, while I now continue with our originalsubject, <i>need</i>. Yes, I will finally continue with it...<p>	Principle No. 1 essentially states that what a person may wishto acquire is virtually without limit as long as there is little or noeffort to do so.  Certainly if a human being were given everything theywanted, they would accept it, yes?  Even if you could not use it allyourself, you might want to give it to a friend or relative.<p>	The only thing that puts a limit on your interest and abilityin acquiring property is the effort required, <b>or</b> the disapprovalacquired if it decreases the happiness of another person.  Such as whensomeone steals something from a person.  Or defrauds them of it.<p>	This explains why welfare systems rapidly go out of control. The recipient expends little effort in acquiring "property."  Which maybe in the form of money with which they can actually acquire tangibleitems or pay for services (which are merely a class of property). Perhaps they are "given" a place to live.  A flat or apartment, or ahouse.<p>	In the beginning they may expend some effort in acquiring thisproperty, having to complete forms and justify their "right" to theproperty of others. Taken from them in the form of taxes.  Of coursesome people don't mind this.  Even if they weren't required to supportthe welfare recipient they would gladly do so of their own free will. Even if at the expense of making their life, or the life of theirfamily, more difficult and less enjoyable.  Yes?<p>	In another sense we return to Principle No. 2, because a personcan truly be happy when they give something to someone, but usuallythey want this person to be someone they know, or to at leastappreciate it.  And to not want more because it is has suddenly becometheir "right" by virtue of having received what to them is only thefirst installment.<p>	I have given money and tangible items to friends that seemed toneed it.  And even given money and items anonymously to a group (acharity) for distribution however they saw fit.  I did it because Iwanted to, and because I felt good or "happy"  for having done it.  ButI do not feel happy when someone <b>requires</b> me to give up some of myproperty to someone I do not know and who never thanks me for it.  Evenif they did thank me, I do not accept or am not happy with being forcedto do anything.<p>	And this, dear reader, is a basic reason--if not <b>the</b>main reason--for the disorder and chaos in coercive politicalsocieties, whether they are outright and naked dictatorial societies,or so-called "democracies."  Both of which operate on the same basicprinciple of controlling the lives and property of their subjects.<p>	This concept directly conflicts with Principle No. 1--the desireto acquire property.  It then causes the individual to seek loopholesfor preserving their property and any other reasonable action topreserve their property.  Including their life.<p>	Then, obviously, it is Principle No. 2 which causes the individual tomake a value judgment and not go so far as to cause them to be evenmore unhappy.  This is why people will pay their taxes and endure otherterrorism against their property--the knowledge that if their oppositiongoes too far, they will be much worse off than if they just submit tothe immoral actions of the political régime.<p>	Most people have a breaking point though, and reach a point whereinthey feel they "have nothing to lose."  They cross over the thresholdand Principle No. 2 no longer become operative.  This is when peopleindulge in violent, anti-social behavior.<p>	A clear understanding of Principles 1 & 2 explain virtuallyeverything about human behavior, excepting only those individuals whotruly do not understand the difference between right and wrong, do notunderstand cause and effect, and do not have the ability to make valuejudgments.  People who have this ability can be pushed beyond the pointwhere they will use the process, or do not accept the conclusionarrived at by their mind.  This concept might be useful in thoughtsconcerning what is commonly called "temporary insanity."<p>	Lastly, I would say that when we as individuals, or as a societalgroup, allow one person's perception of their "need"--or of the needs ofothers--to become a claim on the property of another, we try to alterthe behavior which would normally result from Principles 1 & 2, and arethus tampering with nature.  A very dangerous thing.<p>	If we take the other approach--that of understanding that Principles 1& 2 do exist, and are fundamental to all human behavior--we can see whatis wrong with our current and previous attempts to create a workablesocietal system.  And to then construct a new system which will beconsistent with the nature of human beings.  And will therefore work.</p><hr><h4>End Note</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>The Garden of Epicurus - 1894	<a href="#1r">Return</a></ol><hr>Copyright &copy; 1996--WWMorgan<HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Human-Need.html&gt;