sion causes us to <i>assume</i>many things to be correct when they are not.<a href="#1">[1]</a>  Thatit is responsible for our ever-increasing technological knowledge andassociated products, and for the fact that we have never truly solvedany of our social problems.<p>	For corroboration of the latter statement I commend to youTaylor Caldwell's magnificent historical biography of Marcus TulliusCicero, entitled <i>A Pillar of Iron</i>.  In this book she recounts everydayRoman life of about 2,200 years ago.  If you did not know the timeperiod or place, you would assume it was a description of life incurrent-day Washington, D.C., London, Paris, Tokyo or any other majorcity.  Why?<p>	Because all of the problems of our present societies are the same asthose of 2,200 years ago.</p><table width="100%">	<tr>		<td><li>declining educational standards</td>		<td><li>depressions and recessions</td>	</tr>		<tr>		<td><li>famine</td>		<td><li>inflation</td>	</tr>		<tr>		<td><li>pollution</td>		<td><li>crime</td>	</tr>		<tr>		<td><li>poverty</td>		<td><li>social disorder</td>	</tr>		<tr>		<td><li>too many regulations</td>		<td><li>corruption</td>	</tr>		<tr>		<td><li>unemployment</td>		<td><li>wars</td>	</tr></table>		<p>and a myriad of other social problems.</p><p>	None of them have been solved.  In fact, they have only gottenworse as the social deviants of today have access to ever-greatertechnology in pursuit of their objectives.  Which of course begs thequestion of why the knowledge of our technological world is increasingexponentially, while our societal systems are in continuous decline. While the answer to that question will be in this essay, it is not itssubject and it will be unlikely that anyone will see or comprehend thatanswer.<p>	To talk intelligently about the subject of this essay we mustdefine <i>terrorism</i>.  What is it?  As I alluded to in the beginning, thereis a big difference between the <i>image</i> of terrorism and a succinct andabsolute <i>definition</i>.  Between the image and the operative principle.<p>	Precise definitions and semantic precision are very important,as I have discussed at length in a separate essay on the subject. Often when a definition for something is offered, and especially whenthe listener or reader does not like it, they say:</p><ul><li>That's only your definition;<li>it is only words;</ul><p>	or something similar.  In a sense these are true, but they arealso unimportant and not germane to the problem.  If the definition isconsistent with the way something works or explains a natural phenomenaand may be used to acquire additional new and useful knowledge then itmakes no different whose definition it is.  And the statement that "…it is only words" is supercilious.<p>	Semantic precision is important because it would be impossibleto create new and useful knowledge without it.  Volitional life wouldbe unthinkable and untenable   Can you imagine each individual having adifferent definition for everything?<p>	If you don't believe that semantic precision is important,then I assume you would allow me to assign what is commonly known as<i>sugar</i> the new name of <i>petrol</i>?  And to then fill yourpetrol tank with this "petrol"?  Free of charge of course, just as afriendly gesture.  Or to assign the name <i>salt</i> to <i>arsenic</i>and then season your dinner with it?<p>	Our specie has made great strides in technology since the 1600sbecause it was about that time there was an implicit--and not veryexplicit--understanding that standard, precise, agreed definitions wereimportant.  And, more significantly, that there was an epistemologicaltool that was available for determining whether something was right ornot right.  Although that is a separate subject also discussedelsewhere.<p>	Let's talk specifically about the subject of terrorism and whatit is that constitutes an act of terrorism.  What is the obvious? Often it is a bomb that destroys property and usually kills people.  Orit may be more restrictive in that it "only" destroys property, orsomeone is killed with no other property destruction.  And of course itis often an attack on or against a political r&eacute;gime, whether it is adictatorship or a so-called "democracy."<p>	Does it really make any difference who committed the act, orwho or what it is directed against?  In any case, the people killedoften have nothing to do with the "complaint" of the terrorists.  Suchas the people on TWA-800 or PanAm-103.  Most of whom were holidaygoers, business people, or women and children.  People who had nothought in interfering in the life of the terrorists.<p>	Does it make any difference if the terrorists are male or female?  Orthat they might even represent some "good" cause?  Suppose they are infavor of limiting chemical pollution, or do not want animals to be usedfor purposes of medical research?  Does this then make their actionsacceptable?<p>	Or the case of someone trying to attain more freedom for themselvesand others?  And they murder people associated with the presentr&eacute;gime? Many of whom may only be relatively harmlessfunctionaries of the r&eacute;gime, for whom it is just a job and wayof earning money to support their families. Does this "good" causeentitle them to kill such people?  Or to damage the property of someoneelse?<p>	What would be the implications of this if there were certain cases inwhich it was considered acceptable to kill people or destroy property? One would be that someone then must prepare a list of the acceptablemurders and acts of property destruction.  The Nazis were good atmaking such lists, and then acting on them.  If this were the case,then it would be best if you were one of the people who created thelist, so that you could make certain that you or your friends--and theirproperty--were not in the eligible categories. Of course you would befair, but others might not be.<p>	Yet there is a much more important question than this.  Is itever acceptable to destroy the property of another person, includingthat property known as life?  If you say no, then this raises a veryimportant question.  Why do we tolerate it under any circumstances? Or,phrased another way, why do we tolerate it under some circumstances? Such as when it is sanctioned by our own political r&eacute;gime?  Ofcourse if it were sanctioned by another political r&eacute;gime thanagainst us, that would be war, yes?<p>	If it is sanctioned by our own political r&eacute;gime againstanother, it is war on the other r&eacute;gime, but then it is ourpatriotic duty to fight, yes?  As Voltaire said,</p><center><p>"It is forbidden to kill...unless to trumpets."</p></center><p>	Ah, yes, trumpets make it okay.  Or do they?  This again bringsup the "list," and the thought of who creates it.  Of course we knowwho it is.  It is always the political r&eacute;gime or, as some people callit, the "government."<p>	But we still have not generalized the concept of terrorism orof a terrorist act.  At least not explicitly.  We have begun to headtoward the fact that it is an attack on property; something resultingin the destruction of property, including human life.  But we have alsosaid that human life is itself property--the property of the personwhose life it is. Your life is your property, and my life is mine.  Anydeviation from that and we have the concept known as slavery.  If yourlife isn't yours and under your control, then it must be under thecontrol of someone else, which forms the operative concept of the wordslavery.<p>	It is becoming apparent that the concept of property is basicto our discussion of life, terrorism, and slavery. In fact, it is oneof the most fundamental definitions and concepts, central to andforming the basis of knowledge related to volitional beings and theirsocial structures, although I do not want to discuss it fully here.  Ithink you already have a feeling for the necessity of an understandingof property in discussing terrorism?<p>	If, as we have said, it does not make any difference why theact of terrorism is committed, or who it is committed by for it to bean act of terrorism, then this means no one can stand behind the shieldof their organization.  Not even so-called governments.  Politicalr&eacute;gimes.  And, if it means that what we are really talking about iscontrol or destruction of the property of another--with "life" being aspecial class of property obviously belonging to the "owner"--then wehave some very serious thinking to do.<p>	Because this means that any act by a political r&eacute;gimeor government to kill people, or to interfere in their property, is infact an act of terrorism.<p>	Does it make any difference that a majority of people haveagreed that such interference is okay?  As the Germans did underHitler.  Who was elected to office by a majority of the people.  And healso believed in freedom, as indicated by his writings.  Although therecould be a problem here with definitions also.  His definition seemedto involve taking land away from other people for his own people. Lebensraum.  Surely this was a selfless act on his part for the good ofhis people?  But does it really make any difference why he did it?  Orthat he was a duly elected Head of State, exercising the "rightfulprerogatives of such people to declare war on others?  Perhapsdefinitions do matter...?<p>	If a majority of the people--those having brown hair forexample--vote to shave the head of everyone having blonde hair, is thisokay?  If it is under a "democratic" system, with things being decidedby the majority?  If we accept the concept of allowing the majority todecide what is best for everyone, or what they must do,  this is alsocondoning an act of property interference. Shielding it behind thecloak of "the greater good" and the "will of the majority."  Ratherthan being led down this additional path, I will let you do somethinking about this is you wish.<p>	So far I have not mentioned the subject morality and what is moral. But it now seems simple--and the appropriate time--to discuss morality. From out short discussion the perceptive person will immediately seethe connection between morality, property, and terrorism.<p>	Clearly, we could use the concept of property and propertyinterference to create a new, better, more simple, universal andabsolute definition of the word moral:</p><p><a name="2r"></p><center><p>	"<b>Any act that does not involve property	interference</b>"<a href="#2">[2]</a></p></center><p>	This would include the killing of someone, theft of their property, orcontrolling their property without their permission.  Including thecontrol of their life, which--again--forms the operative concept anddefinition of slavery.<p>	My goodness!  Starting out to discuss terrorism, we drifted offto property as a necessary component of a definition for that, and as abyproduct have defined the words moral and slavery.<p>	But what have we done, and where have we found ourselves?  Indeep trouble.  Because it should now be obvious that there are not just"private" terrorists, but also government-sponsored terrorists. Indeed, any government, political r&eacute;gime or entity or-- indeed--anyorganization which engages in war or the killing of people is aterrorist organization, and immoral.  With our new understanding ofproperty, any person or organization that controls or interferes in theproperty of another is a terrorist and acting immorally.<p>	While we are at it and so close to the concept, we might aswell discuss crime.  Might that definition not also be simplified usingour understanding of property?  With interference in the property ofanother being a crime?  This is in fact the operative definition of theword crime.<p>	The common definition of "crime" is violation of a politicallaw.  But since all political laws involve property interference, wewould seem to have another problem.  One for you to think about.<p>	Although it would open a new subject, which I will not truly do, youmust see that the English language is not very precise.  Indeed, anylanguage that has a dictionary of synonyms must be imprecise accordingto the percentage of synonyms existing related to that total number ofwords in the language.  Of course poets and others would say that thisadds to the "richness" of the language, but it also adds to theconfusion and is a burden on those learning the language.<p>	We have also unlocked the door to proper definitions of ethicsand that which is ethical, but I will leave that to the reader as anexercise.  Although, as you might by now suspect, I have written aseparate essay on that subject...<p><a name="3r"></p><p>	When we understand the concept and definition of property manythings become simple and "obvious."<a href="#3">[3]</a><p>	The purpose of this essay was to put terrorism into perspective, andto illustrate some of the misconceptions, falsehoods, and errorsrelated to our understanding of our social structures.  To encouragethought on the problems created by this, and perhaps even thought to asolution involving the creation of a rational and durable socialstructure.</p><p>	It should not be surprising to you that an essay already existson that subject also...</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4>	<ol><p><a name="1"><li>As Thomas Paine said, "A long habit of not thinking a	thing wrong, gives it a superficial appearance of being right..." 		<p>	[Thomas Paine, Introduction to <i>Common 	Sense</i>, Penguin Books, 1983, p. 63]	</p>		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>A person can not interfere in their own property. 	This refers only to interference in the property of another	person.		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>As Christian Morgenstern the Younger (Lyric Poet)	said, ".Das Offensichtliche ist das, was man nicht sieht, bis	jeman es  erkl&auml;rt." [The obvious is that which is not seen	until someone first expresses it clearly].  Often and incorrectly	ascribed to Khalil Gibran.		<a href="#3r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Terrorism-is-Okay.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
