<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Universal Salvage Essays</TITLE>	<META Name="AU" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META HTTP-EQUIV="KEYWORDS"		CONTENT="Galambos, government, coercion, capitalism, 			history, Bedeman, property, theft, expropriate, theft, 			expropriation, ethics">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corp Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, August 2<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Property-and-Politics.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, July 28, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 2.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>The Concept of Property & the Political State</H3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4></center><hr noshade><p>	I started to write an essay on the subject of ethics, but thenrealized I could not do that until I had covered the concept ofproperty and the political state.  A proper understanding of theconcept of property is essential to a discussion of ethics.  And,contrasting a rational and moral concept of property with that used inpolitics and by the political state provides a good contrast toillustrate a rational definition of property.  Also essential to, andimplicitly included in a proper definition of property is the conceptof ownership.<p>	In fact, discussing the concept of ownership and working backwards isperhaps the best way to define and illustrate the concept of property.<p>	Everyone probably feels they understand the concept of property, andeven its definition, yet I contend that virtually no one has orunderstands a rational and defensible definition of property.  Andcertainly no one associated with politics or the political state has oruses an absolute, durable, rational, and moral concept and definitionof property.  The proof of this, although I will not discuss that here,is that the political state even exists as a concept, and the associatedchaos and disorder evidenced by history and current events.	<h4>Ownership</h4><p>	Almost everyone has a feeling for what constitutes evidence ofownership, but let's list the factors:</p><ul>		<li>Total and complete control of the property;<li>the ability  to use the property as the owner wishes;<li>the ability to sell the property when and if the owner wishes;<li>the ability to not sell or dispose of the property<li>the ability to sell the property at any price agreeable to both seller and	purchaser.</ul><p>	Some people might already dispute this, especially the first item, butremember--I am talking about a rational and moral definition in a freesociety.  An absolute concept, and not a relative one.<p><a name="1r"></p><p>	With credit to Frederic Bastiat<a href="#1">[1]</a> and the conceptof "that which is seen, and that which is not seen," there is also avery important component missing here.  That is how the property wasacquired.  Was it acquired in a moral transaction, in which theprevious owner--acting in the absence of any coercion and withoutfraud--offered it for sale? And, did the current owner agree topurchase it at the offered and/or negotiated price, free of anycoercion or fraud?  Or was it acquired by paying for it with stolenmoney?  Does such an act constitute ownership?<p><a name="2r"></p><p>	If coercion or fraud was involved it creates serious questions. For example, did the previous "owner" acquire the property morally? Was he<a href="#2">[2]</a> in fact the true owner, which is the reason for the quotationmarks?  Because, if he did not, then he was not the owner of theproperty, but merely the controller.  What if the previous "owner"acquired the property through theft--he stole the property?  Does thatmean he is the owner of the property, or merely that he hadacquired control of it through immoral means?<p>	This is a very important consideration, and at the heart of theproblem concerning property and the political state.<p>	Does theft of property confer ownership?  What would be theimplications of this if it were true?<p>	It would certainly make it much easier to acquire and to ownproperty.  It would no longer be necessary to produce or to createproperty, since all that would be necessary would be to steal it.  Totake it by force or fraud.  Taking it at the point of a gun, or throughdeception, confusion, etc.  You could steal you neighbors car andthereby become the "owner."<p>	But what would this do to a society which operated on this basis?  Itwould mean chaos and murder. And the eventual--probably sooner ratherthan later--end to the creation of products and property.  Why botherwhen all that was necessary was to steal it?  And why go to the troubleof creating property if it would only be stolen anyway?  Of course eachperson could create a fortress to safeguard their property, but youprobably could not trust anyone to help you guard it.<p>	"What are you talking about?"  "Why are we having this discussion" "Obviously this would not work, so what is the purpose of thediscussion?"<p><a name="3r"></p><p>	Because this is the way the political state works.  Any politicalstate, whether it is "democratic" or something else.  In the beginning,almost all modern political states acquired control over vast amountsof property through force, taking it from local native inhabitants, Such as in the United States, where it was taken by force--and lessoften through fraud--from the original inhabitants, known commonly butincorrectly as "Indians."<a href="#3">[3]</a><p>	Then, later, they acquired control (I avoid the use of the word"ownership") over more property by paying for it with stolen money. Money taken from individuals through taxation.<p>	I don’t want to get into a full discussion of theft and taxeshere, as I have discussed it at length in other essays.  To keep itshort here, do you freely, and without reservation, give the moneyknown as "taxes" to the political state?  Would you do so if there wereno adverse consequences for not doing so?  All of it, or just some ofit?<p>	Would you rather keep the school tax money so you could pay forand use a school of your choice?  Would you freely join the"subscription plan" for keeping a foreign army in some foreigncountry?  Would you freely, voluntarily, and with great enthusiasm,contribute to a bridge or road being built in some foreign country? Would you endow a pension for some person or persons who had failed tosave for their own?  Or pay the living expenses of one or more peoplewho could not find a job?  While you yourself have a hard time makingends meet?<p>	Would you pay the medical expenses of another person, perhapseven though it meant you could not afford proper medical care foryourself or a member of your family?  Or in lieu of a holiday in thesun during the unusually cold Winter?	<p>Enough of that.<p>	The principle is that ownership can not be acquired by payingfor something with money stolen from another person or persons.  Oracquired through fraudulent means.  This is again tantamount to sayingthat theft confers ownership, and I hope you realize by now that thisdoes not and would not work.<p>	Even the US government would appear not to agree with this, althoughthey are very hypocritical about it.  For example, they have justpassed the much-publicized--and criticized, but not for the rightreasons--Helms-Burton Act.<p>	Basically, this says that since the Castro r&eacute;gime"expropriated" the property of Americans in the 1960s, anyone who nowacquires the "ownership" of this property from the Castro r&eacute;gimemay be sued in American political courts.  Further, that the Americanr&eacute;gime may also deny entry permits to the American tribal areas. The ones they stole from the "Indians."<p><a name="3r"></p><p>	There would appear to be a "statute of limitations" on thisexpropriation<a href="#3">[3]</a> business.  The fact that the Americanr&eacute;gime stole the property centuries ago seems to make it "okay"? Doesn’t it?<p>	One problem with accepting that theft confers ownership is thatthere are then many other questions to answer.  Then you must decidewho is allowed to do this.  May everyone participate, or only a selectfew?  Such as those who work for the political state?<p>	And, if you steal property and manage to maintain control of itfor specified period of time, will this then constitute ownership?  Ifso, what is the period?<p>	Should the period be several hundred years as the case with theAmerican Indians?  Of should we have a "party caucus" or a group ofcommittees decide it, and perhaps come up with a compromise period of62 1/2 years?  Surely that would please the majority of the people. And if not, well, just tell them " ... that’s the law."  Surely that willthen make it acceptable to all.  Which is the "<a href="Glossary.html#DEMOC">democratic</a>" way.  I willresist the temptation to define and discuss "democratic," which--in anycase--has been done in other essays.<p>	Based on this brief discussion, what might be a rational definitionof property?  I will not provide the ultimate, final, and absolutedefinition of property here, but rather an "operative" definition withwhich to carry on the discussion of ethics.</p><center>	<p>	"Any tangible or intangible item acquired through moral means."	</p></center><p>	By including "intangible" we cover the concept of ideas, whichare in fact the first, most important, and highest form of property. Nothing happens until there is first an idea of what and how somethingis to happen.<p>	Of course we do have an open item here, and that is the word"morally" and the concept of morality and what is moral.<p>	Rather than go into that subject, I will leave it hanging for anotheressay, and say only that in this context--the concept of property--itmeans it can not be acquired through theft or fraud.<p>	Does this provide some food for thought, or would you just prefer toaccept the status quo and continue with a system in which theft doesseem to confer ownership?<p>	Now, I am ready to write the definitive essay on the concept of<a href="Ethics.html">ethics</a>. Hopefully you will be interested inreading it…<p>	I know--this is "not long enough for this subject."  Yet it isquite sufficient for anyone capable of rational thought and theextrapolition of ideas.  I am sorry for any reader who does not fallinto this category.</p><hr><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>French economist, 1800-1849, author of "That Which Is	Seen And That Which Is Not Seen," 1849.		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>Generic for a human being, whether male or female.	<a href="#2r">Return</a>	<p><a name="3"><li>This is because early explorers--especially Columbus--	stumbled onto what is now known as the United States and thought	they had reached India, thus calling the natives "Indians."		<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>Remember, "expropriation" is a bureaucratic	euphemism for stealing or theft.		<a href="#4r">Return</a></ol><hr><p>Copyright &copy; 1996--WWMorgan</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Property-and-Politics.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
