tate</a><p>	I can define "ethical" in five words.  A definition which is absolute(covering any situation in any time frame) and totally definitive. Then of course the word "ethics" would be defined as:</p><center>	<p><b>Anything that is ethical</b></center><p>	So, we have a very simple situation, do we not?  All we need dois define "ethical," with the definition covering any type of act inany area of knowledge or endeavor.  And it can only cover and beappropriate for acts  and not thoughts or ideas in the sense that theconcept of morality can only apply to acts.  Thoughts and ideas areamoral, meaning they have no morality content.  They can only have sucha content when the thought or idea is converted into action.  Anotherfact that confuses the majority of people, who view things such as theknowledge of atomic energy as being "immoral," which of course isridiculous--it is amoral.<p>	However, I don't want to pursue the concept of morality--and even ofdefinitions--in this essay.  They are fully covered in their own essays.<p>	Somewhat against my better judgment--as it requires a reader tothink clearly--I will give the definition of ethics forthwith, and thencarry on with a brief discussion, since that is all that is requiredfor the subject.</p><ul>	<p>Ethical<ul><p><b>Any act that is moral</b>.</ul></ul><p>What does this mean?<p>	It means any act which does not interfere in the property of anotherperson is ethical.  It means that if an act involves the property ofanother person, that you must have their prior, freely-given consent.<p>	It is as simple as that, as nature itself is very simple andnot deceptive.  I could stop writing now and, for the thinking person,would have said enough.<p>	This covers all aspect of ethics, whether it relates to medicine,business, psychology, the Internet, sheep ranching, art,computer-related matters, or anything else.  There is no such thing as"medical" ethics, or "business" ethics, or "computer" ethics.  There isonly ethics, and a rational, durable, and absolute definition of it,which applies to all areas of human endeavor.<p>	With one exception, I must admit.  And that is the subject ofso-called "legal" ethics.  The reason it does not apply to that area isbecause the area itself is immoral and irrational, and it approachesthe impossible to apply the concept of ethics to that subject.<p>	I had to pause and struggle for a number of minutes to decideon how to end that last sentence, as I could not say "profession," as Ido not consider the study of political law to be a profession.  Norcould it be called an "area of knowledge," unless you perhaps prefix"knowledge" with "pseudo."  If a person was involved in that subjectthe only ethical thing to do is to get out of it.<p>	The only thing that approaches rationality and morality in thatarea is in what would normally be called "corporate law," in which theperson is defending the property of the company from the onslaught ofthe political state, which would presume to control, confiscate, orotherwise interfere with it.<p>	But we are getting off the track here, and I have probably eliminatedmost all non-thinkers, and perhaps even a few thinkers who are victimsof the problem so elegantly illustrated by Thomas Paine when he said:<p><a name="1r"></p><p>	A long habit of not thinking a thing wrong, gives it a superficialappearance of being right... <a href="#1">[1]</a><p>	The definition clarifies the problem of what do about criticallyinjured or terminally ill patients.  Since, if the patient is consciousand able to make a rational decision, their request to terminatetreatment must be honored and complied with.  To do otherwise isimmoral.<p>	Of course there is still the question of whether the patient iscapable of a rational decision, but if someone to whom they havedelegated that task and the associated responsibility and authority isavailable, then their decision is acceptable and final.  And, again, tonot comply with it is immoral, and in fact a criminal act, as itrepresents property interference.<p>	It becomes almost pointless to discuss other areas of human endeavor,since with the proper definition there is no need to do so.  Unless itis to repetitiously illustrate the principle and definition for peoplewho have not understood the implications of the definition.<p>	With that in mind, we might go to the subject of the Internet,which has been a recent subject of contention.  Especially by thosewhose specialty is property interference, such as politicians.<p>	It is ethical and moral to put anything "onto the Internet," ormake it available through the medium known as the Internet.  It is notrational to put what is commonly called "pornography" in the Internet,but rationality and morality are two different concepts and subjects.To make such material available is certainly ethical, and in fact it isimmoral for anyone to interfere in the act of putting it on theInternet as long as it is not their property.  Clearly however, it ismoral for an "Internet Provider"--one who provides Internet services tocustomers--to refuse to accept such material on their computer system ornetwork.  On the computer system or network which they own.<p><a name="2r"></p><p>	With one exception, interference with this process is an immoralact.  This one exception is between parents and their own (but notowned<a href="#2">[2]</a>) children.  A parent has an implied contractual relationshipwith a child until the child reaches a stage when they are able todetermine right from wrong, and have reached what is generally called"maturity."<p>	In this situation, a parent may, as part of their contractualrelationship with a child, prohibit them from doing certain acts.  And,in fact, they have a responsibility to do so, and are derelict in theirresponsibilities if they do not do so.  The root of many problems inthe current societies on this planet.<p>	"Computer" ethics.  Again simple.  Anything can be done whichdoes not involve intentional interference in the property of another. This means that "hacking" into the computer of someone else is immoraland unethical (since they are the same).  And of course taking moneyfrom a bank by this means is unethical.<p><a name="3r"></p><p>	Notice I used the word "intentional" above, which was deliberate andintended.  Accidents can and do happen.  As my great and wonderfulteacher said, "To err is human.  To rectify is divine."<a href="#3">[3]</a><p>	People do make mistakes.  The really important thing then ishow it is handled.  If a person finds they have made a mistake andinterfered in the property of another, it is incumbent upon them tocontact the person, tell them what happened, offer them an apology, andrestitution.  For accidents which do not seriously or irretrievablydamage property, and there was no intent, often the apology is quitesufficient,  Although absolutely necessary.  I will not continue withthe subject of errors and restitution since, as usual, there is aseparate essay on this subject.<p>	Do we need more discussion on the subject of ethics?  I don'tthink so.  All that is required now is some thought on the subject, andthe application of the principles to your daily life.<p>	One thing I have not discussed and will do so only briefly here, andthat is the matter of ethics and the political state.  Rationality mustalso be discussed.  The reason being that almost everything thepolitical does or requires is immoral, and thus effects the subject ofethics.  Rationality is important because it is not rational to--byaction--oppose the political state.  They have a monopoly on policepowers, and make short work of anyone challenging them by action.  Theonly way to challenge them effectively and rationally is through thecreation of new and useful knowledge. The creation of an alternativeconcept to the coercion of the political state.<p>	If there is a question of doing something which is ethical, butwhich is illegal, rationality must be employed.  Sadly, many thingswhich are moral and therefore ethical, are also illegal.  And of coursemost things which are legal are in fact immoral.<p>	This presents a thinking person with a dilemma, but rationalitymust in this case take precedence over morality and ethics.  Notunlike--in principle--the situation of the Nürnberg Trials.  Where thedefense was that "I did it under orders," or--more appropriately--that"I would have been shot had I not done it."  Such it is with the lawsof the political state.  Rational or not, moral or not, they must befollowed.</p><hr><p>Something else to think about.  If you wish to read more on thesubject of the principles upon which the political state operates,read my essay <a href="Essays.html#CAT">Cat License or Death</a></p><hr noshade><h4>End Notes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>Thomas Paine, Introduction to Common Sense, Penguin	Books, 1983, p. 63		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>Explicit in a proper and complete definition of	property is the concept that a person owns their own body, and	but cannot own the body of another person--not even their biological	child.		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>Andrew J. Galambos	<a href="#3r">Return</a></ol><hr><p>&copy; 1996--WWMorgan</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Ethics.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
