<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Govt Against the People</TITLE>	<META Name="Author" CONTENT="William W. Morgan">		<META Name="Keys"		CONTENT="Galambos,government,coercion,capitalism,			history,Bedeman,keyword,keyword,keyword,keyword">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Essays.html">Universal Salvage Corporation Essays</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, August 2<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Govt-Against-People.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, July 28, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 2.</P><hr noshade><h2>The Universal Salvage Corporation essays</h2></center><hr><p>If you should wish to comment on this essay please send an<a href="mailto:essays@freedom-server.co.uk">E-mail Message</a> toThe Universal Salvage Corporation.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>On...Government of the People, Against the People</H3><hr><h4>William W. Morgan</h4></center><hr noshade><p>	What was it that the "founding fathers" of the United States wanted?What did they hope to achieve as expressed in the Declaration ofIndependence and the Constitution?<p>	Almost without exception they had with them the image of thecountries from which they came, which were largely those of GreatBritain and Europe.  The image of what is generically called a "feudalsystem," in which a feudal lord controlled all the property and peoplein his area.  To be more correct, it was the <i>system</i> that oftenprovided the control, rather than person, Whether this was a relativelysmall, local area, or whether it was a king or emperor controlling vastdominions.<p>	In this feudal system it was very clear that most people, exceptingonly the aristocracy and their minions, were essentially slaves of thearistocracy, represented by the dominant, local, feudal "Lord andMaster."  It was a system characterized by control by force, with onlyminor use of fraud.  The people were under no illusions that they were"free" men.  Even in Great Britain, where there was a designated,formal class of individual known as a <i>freeman</i>, these people also trodwith caution and respect for the rulers and their representatives.<p>	What was the main, operative factor of this system?  Control ofthe life and property of the individual--of all individuals under theircontrol.  The operative concept of being "under the control" of someone,or of a system.  Life and property is a redundant expression, as the lifeof each individual <i>is</i> their <b>sole</b> property.  It would be sufficient tosay only "property," by such is the sad state of semantic precision andabsolute definitions in what is euphemistically called the "socialsciences" that it is sometimes necessary to use redundant expressions.<p>	It was this they hoped to change.  How did they propose to dothis? They wanted to create a system in which the individual would havecontrol of their life, property, and individual destiny. The best thingthey could imagine, for which we can not fault them at that point inthe history of the specie, was a system in which all individuals wouldhave access to their ruler or rulers, albeit through a system ofrepresentatives.  With our vantage point several hundred years on, withmore knowledge of history available--and hindsight that the proposedsystem does not work--we have an advantage over our antecedents.<p>	One reason they wanted middlemen, rather than direct <a href="Glossary.html#DEMOC">democracy</a>,was their fear of the consequences of direct democracy.  Most of the"framers" and "founders" were men (and they <i>were</i> mostly men) with agreat knowledge of history.  They knew that direct democracy had neverworked, and probably would not work.  They still believed in a "class"system in the sense that there were those who were literate and welleducated, and those who were not.<p>	They were very correct in that understanding, as the large majorityof people were illiterate.  And, such people, although illiterate andwithout "formal" education were predominantly men of high principlesand moral integrity as well as they understood the concept.  Muchdifferent than the politicians of today.  They would undertake to bethe "moral guardians" of those who were less well educated.<p>	Although I don't know if it was explicit in their thinking,they obviously felt that only "the educated" should vote.  Only thosewho were producers and creators in society.  And they would then securethe property rights of those who were not formally educated orliterate, and thus did not vote.  In summary, it was a "republic"system, with:</p><ul>  <p>  <li>Government of the people, by the people, for the people  </p>    <p>  <li>One man, one vote, with each vote carrying the same weight as any     other.  But with voting limited to the "educated."     </p></ul><p>	With the exception of who is allowed to vote, the system is thesame as exists today in the United States and other so-called"democracies."  Which of course are not true democracies, although theeffect is the same.<p>	The problem that the "framers and founders" did not and couldnot foresee, is that their cherished "republic" would--overtime--become the functional equivalent of a "democracy," with all ofthe bad characteristics they feared.<p><a name="1r"></p><p>	How did this happen?  It happened over time because of Acton'sDisease.  "Power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely."<a href="#1">[1]</a> The same problem they thought they had eliminated byeliminating the king.  They thought that their class of educatedindividuals--people with an understanding of history and withindividual integrity--would continue in perpetuity.  They did notforesee that each "representative" or agent of the people would succumb toActon's Disease. And that--to stay in power--they would adopt the worstaspects of democracy.  Such as appealing to the masses and looking forthe lowest common denominator.  Of finding out what it is people "need"(please refer to the essay on this subject) and then offering toprovide it to them.  And that in order to do this, there would beincreasing control of individuals through increasing property controland confiscation.  And, when this is not popular, additional controls overindividuals and an increasing use of fraud to make sure they comply.<p>	This requires levels of taxation that would have caused anarmed rebellion and overthrow of the r&eacute;gime in the seventeenth andeighteenth centuries.  The proximate, "last straw" that caused therebellion against King George III.  And, as I said, the tax then wasminuscule compared to today.  Why doesn't it cause a rebellion now?<p>	Because fraud has replaced force in the American system.  Thefraud takes many forms:</p><ul>	<li>You are free when you are not 	<li>It is all for the "public good" 	<li>It is needed to support our position in the world 	<li>It is needed to keep foreign products out (Customs taxes) 	<li>It is necessary to place our goods in other countries (where they are		foreign goods) 	<li>It is necessary for a war to protect "democracy" and "the American		way of life" (Vietnam) 	<li>It is necessary to "fight" to eradicate poverty in America 	<li>It is necessary to "fight" to eradicate poverty in (your favorite		country) 	<li>It is necessary to assure an independent supply of oil, or make		America independent on oil (petrol taxes and control of oil		companies) 	<li>It is necessary to make the rich less rich (excise taxes, wealth		taxes) 	<li>It is necessary to make the poor more rich (money transfer) 	<li>It is necessary to support a nationalized industry (postal		services, etc.)	<li>It is necessary to prepare a nationalized industry for		"privatization," since the politicians are now wrong that such an		industry was needed for "the people," and therefore nationalized		by an earlier r&eacute;gime	<li>It is necessary to support a commodity price so that it can then		be sold at less than market price 	<li>It is necessary to pay farmers not to grow something 	<li>It is necessary to pay farmer to grow something else	<li>It is needed for education 	<li>It is needed to create space stations, and to satisfy the fantasies		of our "representatives" (see a following discussion on this		subject) 	<li>It is needed for a myriad of supplemental programs		for education, since the educational system does not work</ul><p>	Nor did they foresee the development of a truly Draconian legalsystem, in which there would be a myriad of laws which would not onlyprohibit or control almost everything, but even laws to permit things. The result being that unless something was expressly permitted, peoplewould begin to assume it was prohibited.  This is beyond even themadness that George Orwell could foresee.<p>	The thing the framers and founders were trying to avoid was theold system of laws so broad that--literally--almost any deed would becriminal or even seditious.  Sedition being the veiled threat behindstatements such as "...you must be against the 'American way of life'."Again, the thing they feared the most came in through a hiddenentrance.<p>	Something I did not see until several days ago (1995, August12) illustrates the formidable--and probably hopeless--task the framersand founders faced, and how they could not possibly have foreseen thetraps awaiting their best efforts at eliminating the tyrannies of thepast.<p><a name="2r"></p><p>	It occurred to me while doing sit-ups on a slant board, a dayor so after reading an otherwise innocuous press report (not a "news"article.)  Because this is fresh in my mind and very important, I willgive full credit to <i>Newsweek</i> magazine for this revelation.  In theirarticle "Pork Goes Republican,"<a href="#2">[2]</a> they discussed theso-called "space station" program of the regime, mentioning a notionalcost figure of US$30.4 billion.<p>	Please note that this is more than thirty million times the amount ofmoney expended by Wilbur & Orville Wright in the development,fabrication and testing which led to powered, controlled-flight.  It isalso more than 500,000 times the amount of money needed to create bothHewlett-Packard Corporation and Digital Equipment Corporation. It isalso interesting to note that, in connection with the invention of theairplane by the Wright Brothers, the U. S. Army paid Samuel LangleyUS$50,000 (fifty times what it cost the Wright Brothers) in a failedattempt to try to develop a flying machine <b>after</b> the Wright Brothershad successfully flown.<p>	They thought it would be simple to develop a flying machine. Just copy the appearance of the Wright <i>Flyer</i>.  Then they wouldn't needto deal with them.  They--the U.S. Army and their associated politicalmasters--would have "invented" their own airplane.  Even AlexanderGraham Bell, after successfully copying and stealing the idea for thetelephone from Philipp Reis and Elijah Grey, failed in his attempt to stealsufficient knowledge from the Wright Brothers with which--in collaborationconspiracy with Glen Curtis--he could build a successful flyingmachine.<p>	But, back to the space station.  It seems that there was a veryreal chance that this bit of pork was going to go off to the place fromwhich no pig returns.  Then, 'lo and behold, Melanie Griffith appearsbefore our salivating "representatives" in a tight-fitting, whiteVersace suit.  It now appears that out of the revelation, visions, anddreams of this visit, the pork is going to be alive and well. Our"representatives" may now be willing to spend the US$30.4 billion. There is only one problems with this.<p>	It is not their money.  Not money they have individually savedfrom moral employment in the creation of property.  Rather, it is moneythey propose to acquire through the mechanism of "voluntary compliance"of those they represent.  It would make this essay too long to discussthis travesty of justice further.<p>	What has now happened to the original intent of the framers andfounders to protect the property of individuals from control andconfiscation by the "Lord of the Manor"?  And what has happened to theconcept that the "vote" and "rights" of each individual are equal? And, that the "representative" will <b>truly</b> represent the wishes of <b>each</b> individual who entrusted them with their wishes?  And theirproperty?  There has been a total perversion of the concepts.<p>	The representatives in question are part of the same group thatproposes to protect young and immature minds from "prurient"influences.  From doing rash and immoral things when an attractiveperson of the opposite sex flashes their "attributes" before them. Thisagain begs the question of, "Who will protect us from our <i>protectors</i>"?	<p>	This is the failed system of regulating societies through coercionthat has been with us for millions of years.  Wherein the strongestindividual, or the one with the most coercive powers at his command,controls all others in the society.</p><p>We must ask ourselves several questions.</p><ul><p> <li> Does this system really work to the advantage of each individual     in a society?    </p>    <p><li> Has such a system ever really worked in history?  Or is the     dustbin of history filled with failed civilizations based on this     concept?     </p>     <p><li>Is this the system we want for ourselves, and to saddle future     generations with?     </p></ul><p>	If there were a system available which would guarantee that eachindividual had full control of their own property, and could do whateverthey wished as long as it did not involve interference with theproperty of another, would you be interested in thinking about such asystem?<p>	Bearing in mind that no societal system should be acceptedunless each individual believes that it will in fact improve thequality of their own individual life, and that of those who depend onthem. And, further, that the adoption of such a system can not result inproperty inteference.</p><p>We should think of two other things:</p><ul>  <p>  <li>We should have learned from history that property creation     based on prior property destruction is <b>not</b> a workable concept.     </p>     <p><li>Property must first be created before it can be destroyed.  And     which group in society does which?     </p></ul><p>If you are interested in thinking about such things, I encourage youto read the existing and forthcoming essays from The FreedomServer<sup>&copy;</sup></p><p>And then:</p><ul><p><li>Look at the world around you to see if there is a possibility that    the concepts will work;</p><p><li>think whether the existing concepts do and can achieve what you      want for yourself and your family;</p><p><li>decide if you want to do something to improve your individual      life, and that of others in our society;</p><p><li>think if you want to create a better world for those who come      after us.</p></ul><hr><h4>Footnotes</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>With credit to Lord Acton.	<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>"Pork Goes Republican," by Thomas Rosenstiel. 	<i>Newsweek</i> magazine, Aug. 14, 1995, p. 36        <a href="#2r">Return</a></ol><hr><p>Copright &copy;1995--Universal Salvage Corporation</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Govt-Against-People.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
