sappoint Mr. Sullivan, but I am afraid hedoesn't have the correct question either.  But then he should not beupset, as no one ever does ask the correct question.<p>	The correct question is whether individual members of a volitional orthinking specie should be responsible for the conduct of their ownindividual lives, or whether--as political systems assume--they needsomeone to control most aspects of their life for them.  Presumablybeing incapable of doing this on an individual basis. And assumingthere is a group of people in such a specie who are especially endowedwith abilities to perform this function for individuals who areincapable of doing it for themselves.<p>	Even more basic--and central the solution to the problem offailed societal mechanisms--is the question of whether or not it isever moral and rational for someone to control the property of anotherperson without their permission.  And lest someone say that in aso-called "democratic" society the permission is granted through thevoting process, I say they are not thinking clearly.  It is alwaysmoral to appoint someone else to control your own property, but whatyou are doing through political voting is appointing someone to alsocontrol the property of others. Perhaps millions  or hundreds ofmillions of others.<p>	Mr. Sullivan also mentions that the appeal of a "simple solution" isvery great.  And, since this is a political system, he also invokes the"enemy."  Politics is a system of winners and losers, and of friendsand enemies. In fact, political elections seem to be more about makingthe opponent out to be an enemy rather than to state one's own policiesand position.  Which, in any case--since they involve interfering inand controlling the property of others without their permission--isimmoral. Such actions may appear to be rational in the short term, butare never rational in any period of time.  As millennia of failedpolitical societies attest.<p>	The simple solution--and the moral solution--is a situation inwhich each person is responsible for the conduct of their own life andnon-interference in the life and property of others.  This is bothmoral and rational.<p>	People say such a concept is "idealistic" or "Utopian," but itis neither of these.  The reasons they say this is because it isassumed that in a situation in which anyone can do anything they wishas long as it does not interfere in the property of another will resultin just that--everyone interfering in the property and lives ofeveryone else. Yet if that were so, could it be worse than today'ssituation?  Of course being only the same as today would not be animprovement, and hardly worth discussing.<p>	I think that many people would say that what is lacking today isa proper concept of justice and a situation in which justice prevails.And, in fact, a proper definition of justice can come from this conceptof interference in the property of others without theirpermission--which is the operative concept of "crime."  Justice mightbe defined as "lack of recourse from crime."  Of course the supremeconcept of justice would be a situation in which there is no crime.  Isthat possible?<p>	Yes, and it is not idealistic or Utopian.  In fact it is the currentsystem--which assumes that people will be content in a situation inwhich they are told what they may and may not do--is the one which ishopelessly idealistic.  Why?  Because it goes against the fundamentalnature of man, the specie.<p>	Every thinking being is an individual, with individual hopesand dreams.  An individual and unique concept of what will bring themhappiness.  Any system which presumes to over-ride this is doomed tofailure.  There will never be contentment with such a system, asindicated by the plethora of problems facing all the politicalsocieties of this planet.<p>	As political elections should show us, political societiesoffer their subjects nothing but unacceptable alternatives, and falsealternatives. The classic multiple choice examination question, inwhich you are presented, say, four possible answers, with one of thembeing "none of the above."  The problem is, that option is never reallyallowed in a political election.  You must select one of the choices,or just not vote at all. The problem is, one of the choices will end uprunning your life.  It is the system that is the problem, not theindividuals. Individuals come and go, but the system seems eternal.<p>	A classic statement of monarchy is that "The King is Dead; LongLive the King."  What people forget is that the King is only thetitular head of the system.  The name can be president, prime minister,shah, czar, or even the innocuous title of "first secretary."  Ageneralized version of the above would  be "The Ruler is Dead; LongLive the State."<p>	The one choice that is never offered or even thought of is: "Doyou wish to have a societal system in which someone will control mostof the aspect of your individual life?"  That is never asked because noone even conceives of the alternative as a possibility, since there hasbeen a state and someone to rule the tribe or state since timeimmemorial.   It is sort of a "macro version" of what happened in theUSSR; most people found it hard to cope with the fact that theParty--which had  been omnipresent and omnipotent in individual lifefor several generations--was no longer there.  "How will we functionwithout the Party telling us what to do?"<p>	Yet nothing in principle has changed in Russia.  There is stillsomeone telling people how to run most aspects of their life, althoughit does have a touch of the "Wild West" of the United States, in which"outlaws" also had their place in society.<p>	Yet the question returns: How do you control society if thereis no political state with its monopoly on police powers?  Won't"crime" just proliferate, and "lawlessness" reign supreme?  Never mindthat life is very chancy even now under the current system.<p>	How would you ensure that, in a society in which each could exploreand pursue there own concept of happiness, that it was not like thedays of the "Wild West"?<p>	Earlier I mentioned the very powerful concept of volitionallife which states that--as fingerprints and genetic makeup createunique individuals--each person has their own concept of happiness andhow to conduct the functioning of their life.<p>	There is another very fundamental aspect of volitional lifewhich balances that concept, and which is at the heart of the failureof political mechanisms.  It is actually the corollary of the previousstatement.<p>	It is the concept that--given an alternative--a volitional beingwill not willingly do that which has the potential of degrading thequality of their life.  That is, given the alternative to freely chosefrom various courses of action, an individual will not do that whichreduces or has the possibility of reducing their quality of life.<p>	This provides us with the answer to how a society or societiesof volitional beings can regulate their civilization without requiringan organization with police powers.  It is the system which allowspolitical regimes to survive until they become totally dysfunctionaland collapse from within.  The fact that people will chose to obeysilly, harmful, irrational and even immoral rules rather than gothrough the unpleasantness associated with disobeying a political law.Being fined, going to jail, perhaps even being murdered by thepolitical state.  Yet, if there is the opportunity and possibility,they may seek a "loop hole" if they believe the chance of gettingcaught is very small.<p>	Yet it is this desire to not do something that will have a negativeimpact on their quality of life that can be used to regulate a societywithout resorting to police powers.  To do this, you need only adoptthe concept of the credit mechanism.  But not in the narrow form offinancial credit as now used, but in the broader form of positivecredit for not interfering in the property of another, and negativecredit when an individual does interfere with the property of anotherperson.<p>	The only thing needed for this to work is a proper understanding ofproperty.  The concept that everything-- even intellectualproperty--has an owner.  Ownership is a moral concept, meaning thatproperty ownership cannot be acquired through immoral means.  Throughtheft of the property, or purchasing the property using stolen funds. If theft were a valid way to acquire ownership of property it wouldmean that if someone stole your car they thereby became the acceptedowner.  Such a system would produce chaos.  As does the current systemwhich allows so-called "public ownership."<p>	Such a concept is ludicrous.  The ability to freely sell a property isone evidence of ownership.  Yet if you and 200 million other people"own" a "public" park, can you reasonably expect to sell your 200millionth of it? Try it.  This means you do not truly own it.Furthermore, the ability to exercise control over your property isevidence of ownership.  Such as being able to get in your car and drivesomewhere whenever you wish to do so.  But can you enter "your" publicpark and use it as you wish?<p>	In a rational and durable societal structure all property wouldhave an identifiable owner or owners.  Which, according to theagreement under which the property was acquired, it could also be soldand used as specified by the purchaser(s) at the time of purchase.<p>	This means that streets and roads would be owned by individuals, justas telephone companies, food stores and associated other "public"facilities and/or services are owned now.  Albeit often bycorporations, empowered by their stockholders (owners) to operate, use,and dispose of the property as mutually agreed.<p>	For people who say that roads and streets and such things wouldno longer be "free," I must say again that anyone who believes in theconcept that such things are "free" now is living under a delusion.Roads and streets and their use are not free now.  They are constructedand maintained using money extracted from people in the form of taxesand only have the illusion of being free.  You have access to theseroads and streets by virtue of paying your taxes and remaining in goodstanding in your societal group.<p>	And you often pay a hefty surcharge for this.  Witness the manystate-controlled telephone companies, where service was poor and pricescontrolled and high.  Of course they are sometimes controlled with bothservice and usage cost being low, which provides a different illusion.With telephone service being a "requirement" of modern life, why isn'tit totally "free," as road and street usage is?<p>	The reason I contrast road and street usage with telephone services isthat it is part of the answer to the "credit mechanism" for controllingbehavior in a rational society without need for police.<p>	With everything having an owner, access to all property can becontrolled by the owner.  Just as the political state does, but in thiscase it is moral.  It is always moral for an owner to be in totalcontrol of their own property, but not of the property of anyone else(without that owner's permission).<p>	If someone interferes in the property of another, it would bemoral--and rational--to prevent access by that person to your property. If, for example, someone were a thief, why would you want to let themuse roads or streets you owned?  Or the use of telephone services youowned and provided.  Or to shop in a food market you owned?<p>	If a person who had committed a crime suddenly found that theycould not buy food, use roads and streets, have electrical andtelephone service, they might begin to think twice about what they haddone. About the consequences of their actions.  If they also knew theycould reverse this process, but admitting their mistake and offering toprovide restitution for their actions, there would be a powerfulincentive for them to do so and rejoin mainstream society.  Their"prison" would have been a lifestyle which had suddenly becomeunacceptable.<p>	No need to build a network of prisons which--it has been shown--neverreally stops crime.  And certainly never provides restitution to thevictim(s) of crime.  No need to have an ever-expanding police force totry vainly to counter ever-increasing crime.  With the expansion of thepolice force and associated laws representing ever-greater intrusionsinto individual life and liberty, degrading the quality of life forall.<p>	The foregoing is the answer to the question that is never asked:Is there something wrong with  the basic principle upon which allsocial structures on this planet are based?  The usual thought is that"… we need more and better laws.  And better enforcement of existinglaws." But we have been doing this for millennia, and things onlybecome worse.  The only thing that has changed for the better isincreasing technology, making life easier and better in a constantlydeteriorating social structure.  The why and how this occurs is anothersubject much to long for this short essay.<p>	This essay also indicates the solution to the current problemsof mankind through the application of the concepts of property sanctityand the credit mechanism<p>	By careful consideration of the foregoing it is possible to constructa rational and durable social structure to replace the one which is inwhat is probably a terminal decline.  It will be terminal if not soonreversed.</p><hr><p>Copyright &copy; 1989--WWMorgan</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/The-Correct-Question.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
