<a href="#ADMIN"><h4>II - Administration of Antidumping Laws</h4></a><ul>	<a href="#VIEW"><h4>A. Overview</h4></a>	<a href="#COMP"><h4>B. Computational Problems</h4></a>	<ul>			<a href="#CCP"><h4>1. Computing the Cost of Production</h4></a>		<a href="#PC"><h4>2. Price Comparisons</h4></a>		<a href="#UAP"><h4>3. Using Average Prices</h4></a>		<a href="#SER"><h4>4. Shifting Exchange Rates</h4></a>	</ul></ul><a href="#AAC"><h4>III - Antidumping Actions in the						Computer Industry</h4></a>	<ul>	<a href="#64K"><h4>A. 64K DRAM Chips</h4></a>	<a href="#256K"><h4>B. 256K DRAM Chips</h4></a>	<a href="#1MB"><h4>C. 1MB DRAM Chips</h4></a>	<a href="#FPD"><h4>D. Flat Panel Displays</h4></a>	<a href="#MD"><h4>E. Microdisks</h4></a>	<a href="#PWP"><h4>F. Personal Word Processors</h4></a>	</ul></ul><a href="#SHE"><h4>IV. - Some Harmful Effects of the Antidumping	Laws</h4></a><a href="#TPA"><h4>V. - The Philosophy of Antidumping</h4></a><a href="#CR"><h4>VI - Conclusions and Recommendations</h4></a></p><hr><a name="INTRO"><h4>Introduction</h4><p><a name="1r"></p><p>	This article reviews some recent antidumping and countervailingduty investigations that involved various segments of the computerindustry.<a href="#1">[1]</a>  Part I provides an overview of theantidumping laws.  Part II discusses administration of the antidumpinglaws.  Part III reviews recent antidumping investigations involvingsegments of the computer industry.  Part IV points out some of theharmful effect of the antidumping laws.  Part V presents somephilosophical issues.  Part VI offers conclusions and recommendations. The authors conclude that the antidumping laws violate property andcontract rights, are harmful to the computer industry in particular andto trade in general, and should be repealed, the sooner the better. 	<a name="OV"><h4>I. An Overview of the Antidumping Laws</h4><p><a name="2r"><a name="3r"></p><p><a name="4r"><a name="5r"><a name="6r"></p><p>	The antidumping laws assess penalties if there is a reasonableindication that an industry in the United States is materially injured,or is threatened with material injury, or the establishment of anindustry in the United States is materially retarded because someimport is being sold in the United States for less than fair value.<a href="#2">[2]</a> One of the first antidumping laws was incorporatedinto the Revenue Act of 1916,<a href="#3">[3]</a> which was at timesreferred to as the Antidumping Duty Act of 1916,<a href="#4">[4]</a>but it is really the Tariff Act of 1930,<a href="#5">[5]</a> also knownas the Smoot-Hawley Tariff, and later amendments,<a href="#6">[6]</a>which serve as the basis for present-day antidumping law.<p><a name="7r"><a name="8r"></p><p>	The legal standard for a preliminary or final determinationin an antidumping investigation requires the U.S. International TradeCommission (USITC) to determine whether there is a reasonableindication of material injury or threat of material injury to adomestic industry because of the import under investigation, based onthe best available information available at the time of the preliminaryinvestigation.<a href="#7">[7]</a>  The USITC sometimes also looks atwhether the establishment of an industry in the United States ismaterially retarded.<a href="#8">[8]</a><p>	To determine whether there is a reasonable indication that a domesticindustry is materially injured because of the imported item beinginvestigated, the USITC is to consider:</p><ul>	<li> The volume of imports of the merchandise which is the subject of	the investigation,	<li>The effect of imports of that merchandise on prices in the United	States for like products, and	<li>The impact of imports of such merchandise on domestic producers of	like products, but only in the context of production operations	within the United States.<a href="#n9n">[9]</a></ul><p><a name="10r"><a name="11r"><a name="12r"></p><p><a name="13r"><a name="14r"><a name="15r"><a name="16r"></p><p>	It may also consider other relevant factors,<a href="#10">[10]</a>concerning the volume, price effects and impact of imports.  Thesefactors are to be evaluated in the context of the business cycle andcompetitive conditions that are distinctive to the affected industry.<ahref="#11">[11]</a>   The USITC may also consider other factors itdeems relevant, but if it chooses to evaluate other factors, it mustexplain why they are relevant.<a href="#12">[12]</a>  It may consideralternative causes of injury, but may not weigh causes.<ahref="#13">[13]</a>  It does not need to determine that imports are thesole, or even a principal or substantial cause of material injury butmust merely determine whether imports are a contributing cause of thematerial injury.<a href="#14">[14]</a>  It may also consider whetherfactors other than the less than fair value imports have made theindustry more vulnerable to the effects of the less than fair valueimports.<a href="#15">[15]</a> And while it may take the departuresfrom an industry into account, it must assess the condition of theindustry as a whole and not on a company-by-company basis.<ahref="#16">[16]</a><p>To determine whether there is a threat of material injury, theUSITC considers, among other things,</p><ul><p>	<li>If a subsidy is involved, such information as may be presented to	it by the administering authority as to the nature of the	subsidy,<p>	<li>Any increase in production capacity or existing unused capacity in	the exporting country that is likely to result in a significant	increase in imports of the merchandise to the United States,<p>	<li>Any rapid increase in United States market penetration and the	likelihood that the penetration will increase to an injurious	level,<p>	<li>The probability that imports of the merchandise will enter the	United States at prices that will have a depressing or suppressing	effect on domestic prices of the merchandise,<p>	<li>Any substantial increase in inventories of the merchandise in the	United States,<p>	<li>The presence of underutilized capacity for producing the	merchandise in the exporting country,<p>	<li>Any other demonstrable adverse trends that indicate the probability	that the importation (or sale for importation) of the merchandise	(whether or not it is actually being imported at the time) will	be the cause of actual injury,<p>	<li>The potential for product-shifting if production facilities	owned or controlled by the foreign manufacturers, which can be	used to produce products subject to investigation(s) under section	701 or 731 or to final orders under section 706 or 736, are also used	to produce the merchandise under investigation,<p>	<li>In any investigation under this title which involves imports of	both a raw agricultural product and any product processed from	such raw agricultural product, the likelihood that there will	be increased imports, by reason of product shifting, if there	is an affirmative determination by the USITC under section 705(b)(1)	or 735 (b)(1) with respect to either the raw agricultural product or	the processed agricultural product (but not both), and	<a name="17r"><p>	<li>The actual and potential negative effects on the existing	development and production efforts of the domestic industry,	including efforts to develop a derivative or more advanced version of	the like product.<a href="#17">[17]</a></ul><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><a name="ADMIN"><h4>II.  Administration of the Antidumping Laws</h4><a name="ADMIN"><h4>A. Overview</h4><a name="18r"><a name="19r"><p>	The structure and administration of the antidumping laws canbe criticized on a number of counts.  The present antidumping lawallows the Commerce Department and/or U.S. International TradeCommission to serve a massive discovery request (demand) for theproduction of documents and interrogatories.  The serving party alsohas the sole authority to set the time by which the response must bemade and the format of the response.  It can demand that a small,foreign producer translate everything into English,<ahref="#18">[18]</a> and can act as the sole judge of whether theresponse is adequate.  It can also act as the sole arbiter ofobjections regarding relevancy or burdensomeness of the request.  Itcan impose sanctions for failure to comply and can act as the ultimatedecisionmaker.  Such a system raises major questions of due process,not to mention fairness.  Yet such a system is allowed to exist underthe present rules.<a href="#19">[19]</a><p><a name="20r"><a name="21r"><a name="22r"></p><p><a name="23r"><a name="24r"><a name="25r"></p><p>	In addition to the administrative burden that target companies orindustries may be subjected to, the time for processing the request canbe extremely short, given the amount of information that must beprocessed and discussed.<a href="#20">[20]</a> The target company oftenmust provide detailed information about all of its U.S. sales as wellas home country sales for a six month period.  The information must beprovided on computer tape that is compatible with IBM systems.<ahref="#21">[21]</a>  And much of the information demanded isirrelevant, but is demanded anyway so that the petitioner cannotcomplain that the investigation is not sufficiently thorough.<ahref="#22">[22]</a>  There is no effective appeal if the target companythinks the demand for documents is too onerous because the CommerceDepartment decides what is required and when it must be produced.  Andif documents are not produced, the Commerce Department can make upnumbers<a href="#23">[23]</a>  using the "best information available"(BIA).<a href="#24">[24]</a> But in some cases, the information theCommerce Department uses is not even remotely accurate.  In manyinstances, it uses the information provided to it by the petitioningcompany, which has a high probability of being biased.  And because ofthe way the rules work, it is possible for the Commerce Department toconclude that a product was dumped even if the selling price for theproduct under investigation is the same worldwide.<a href="#25">[25]</a><p><a name="26r"></p><p>	If the target company does not provide exactly and completelythe information the Commerce Department demands, it can totallydisregard all that has been submitted and make up its own numbers.  Inone case, SKF, a Swedish manufacturer, supplied more than 150,000 pagesof information covering more than 100 million separate sales.  The datasupplied weighed more than three tons and included more than 4 billionpieces of information.  The information was delivered within about aweek of the Commerce Department's request, since that was all the timethe Commerce Department gave the company to respond.  About one percentof the data was in a form that was not acceptable to the CommerceDepartment, so it totally disregarded all three tons of information andmade up its own numbers.<a href="#26">[26]</a><p><a name="27r"><a name="28r"></p><p>	In another particularly outrageous case, the Commerce Departmentdemanded that Matsushita translate 3,000 pages of financial documentsfrom Japanese into English.  The request (demand) was made on a Fridayafternoon, and the project was supposed to be completed by thefollowing Monday morning.  Rather than comply, Matsushita decided toabandon its small business telephone system sales<a href="#27">[27]</a>to the United States, thus losing more than $50 million in exportsales.<a href="#28">[28]</a><p><a name="29r"><a name="30r"><a name="31r"></p><p>	A number of other criticisms could also be made about the way theantidumping laws are administered.  For one thing, the CommerceDepartment often examines just the numbers for the larger companies,then determines the antidumping margin that is to be assessed againstsmaller companies based on those numbers.<a href="#29">[29]</a>  Andalthough the smaller companies can offer their own data in theirdefense, the Commerce Department is free to reject their data for anyreason.  In one case, hundreds of Hong Kong textile companies wereassessed a penalty because one of the companies under investigationearned less than an 8 percent profit.<a href="#30">[30]</a>  And it isnot entirely clear which entity, the Commerce Department or the U.S.International Trade Commission, has the authority to do what, sincethey are both involved in the administration of the antidumping laws.<a href="#31">[31]</a> <a name="COMP"><h4>B. Computational Problems</h4><a name="CCP"><h4>1. Computing the Cost of Production</h4><p><a name="32r"><a name="33r"></p><p>	The Commerce Department looks at a company's cost of production inabout two-thirds of the cases it investigates.<a href="#32">[32]</a> Inorder to avoid a charge of dumping, foreign companies must charge aprice at least equal to the cost of production plus a "reasonableprofit," which it defines as 8 percent.<a href="#33">[33]</a>  A pricethat meets this standard is considered "fair." Any lower price isconsidered unfair.  So a company that has a profit of only 7.9 percentcan be found guilty of dumping even though it is making a profit.  Yetmany companies and many industries, both domestic and foreign, do notachieve an 8 percent profit level for many of their products, whichmeans that numerous products could be deemed sold at less than a "fair"price.<p><a name="34r"><a name="35r"><a name="36r"></p><p>	The cost of production is computed by estimating the materialproduction cost,<a href="#34">[34]</a> then adding 10 percent foradministrative overhead.<a href="#35">[35]</a>  Companies that have anadministrative overhead of more than 10 percent are not penalized, butthose that can keep their administrative overhead below 10 percentcould find themselves in trouble.  In other words, the more efficient acompany is, the greater is the probability that it will be penalized. Inefficiency is rewarded and efficiency is penalized.<a href="#36">[36]</a><p><a name="37r"></p><p>	Aside from the fact that assigning 10 percent to overhead istotally arbitrary, it is also possible that a company with overhead ofmore than 10 percent might be selling its product on the U.S. market ata loss, yet not be found guilty of dumping.  And the costing methods ituses are far from scientific.  In one case, it determined theproduction cost of red raspberries by taking a random sample of justten farmers.<a href="#37">[37]</a> But a USITC study found thatproduction costs for raspberries varied by almost 100 percent.<p><a name="38r"></p><p>	Another problem with the way the Commerce Department computesproduction cost is that it is not consistent in its methodology.  Ithas been known to shift its cost accounting methods from case to case,and even within the same investigation.  In one case involving someBrazilian companies, it used ten different methods to measure theircost of production, which makes it impossible for a company todetermine whether it might be guilty of dumping, since it has no way ofknowing in advance which of several cost accounting methods theCommerce Department might use.<a href="#38">[38]</a><p><a name="39r"><a name="40r"></p><p>	Another problem with the Commerce Department's methodology isthat it sometimes compares the price charged in one period with thecosts for another period.  This approach is questionable in even thebest of circumstances, but is especially flawed in cases like thesemiconductor investigations, where costs were dropping an a high rateof speed.  In one semiconductor case, the Commerce Department comparedthe current selling price to a cost of production figure that was threemonths old. <a href="#39">[39]</a>  But the average variable cost ofproducing semiconductors dropped by sixty-six percent between 1984 and1985 -- from $8.0313 to $2.7376. And costs dropped by another fifty-twopercent the following year -- from $2.7376 to $1.2989.<a href="#40">[40]</a>  So a three-month time lag between revenues andcosts can make a substantial difference, especially when a company isdealing with slim profit margins.  It could turn a profitable sale intoone that appears to be made at a loss, or at a profit of less than 8percent.<p><a name="41r"></p><p>	Allocating fixed costs can also be a problem.  If a companymanufactures several items, the fixed costs attached to those itemsmust somehow be allocated.  But any method of allocating fixed costs isarbitrary.  And a number of assumptions are inherent in any suchcalculation. The depreciation method used, the time period used todepreciate, and a number of other factors also enter into the picture. Yet fixed costs are a substantial part of a semiconductor company'stotal production cost -- perhaps as much as seventy-five percent.<a href="#41">[41]</a><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE>	<a name="PC"><h4>2. Price Comparisons</h4><p><a name="42r"><a name="43r"></p><p>	The Commerce Department has been accused on many occasions ofcomparing apples to oranges in the course of an antidumpinginvestigation.  This apples to oranges approach has taken severalforms.  It sometimes compares prices of products that are not similar,as when it compared one kind of pads for woodwind instruments sold inthe United States with another, larger kind of pad for instruments soldin Italy.<a href="#42">[42]</a>  It has considered the price of a freshflower in Amsterdam and a wilted flower in New York to be equivalent.<ahref="#43">[43]</a><p><a name="44r"></p><p>	Another criticism in the Commerce Department's methodology is thatit sometimes compares prices in dissimilar markets.  Some Koreancompanies were penalized for selling sweaters in the United States forone percent less than what they sold them for in Mexico, Canada and theUnited Kingdom.  The Commerce Department ignored the fact that therewere significant differences in the sweaters shipped to differentcountries and that each shipment was a custom order.  It also ignoredall cases where the sweater prices were higher in the United Statesthan in the third country.<a href="#44">[44]</a><p><a name="45r"></p><p>	The Commerce Department has also been known to compare wholesaleprices in the United States with foreign retail prices, which has atendency to distort price comparisons.  For example, in an antidumpingcase initiated by Motorola against Toshiba for selling cellular mobiletelephones and subassemblies for less than fair value, the CommerceDepartment did not take into account the fact that when Toshiba sold inthe Japanese market, it sold to small dealers directly, whereas when itsold in the United States, it sold to a single wholesaler, which thenresold to distributors.<a href="#45">[45]</a><p><a name="46r"><a name="47r"></p><p>	The price comparisons the Commerce Department makes sometimes donot take volume discounts into account, which can lead to anantidumping penalty when none is warranted.<a href="#46">[46]</a>  Andthe Commerce Department's method of classifying costs as direct andindirect has also been criticized, as has its practice of sometimessubtracting the sales costs a company incurs when it computes the U.S.sales price, but including similar sales costs when it computes theforeign market value, which results in having the U.S. priceconsistently understated when compared to the foreign price.<a href="#47">[47]</a> 	<a name="UAP"><h4>3. Using Average Prices</h4><p><a name="48r"></p><p>	Another major criticism of the Commerce Department's methodology isthe way it computes average prices.  As a result, it is sometimespossible for a foreign company to be hit with an antidumping penaltyeven when it sells its product for the same price in the United Statesand the home country.  This can happen when it computes average foreignprices over a six-month period and compares that average to individualdomestic prices.  A foreign company can run afoul of the antidumpinglaws if it sells any product in the United States for a price that isless than the average foreign price for the period underinvestigation.<a href="#48">[48]</a>  So if the company sells itsproduct at a range of different prices over some period of time, whichis the normal case, it is probable that about half of the sales will beat prices that are below the average price and half will be sold forabove the average price.  This is exactly what happened in one of theDRAM chip antidumping cases, as we shall see below. 	<a name="SER"><h4>4. Shifting Exchange Rates</h4><p><a name="49r"><a name="50r"><a name="51r"></p><p>	Problems sometimes result because of shifts in exchange rates. Inorder to compare the domestic price to the foreign price it isnecessary to convert the foreign currency into dollars.  But the methodthe Commerce Department uses to convert from one currency to anothersometimes results in a finding of dumping where none, in fact,occurred.<a href="#49">[49]</a>  And the Commerce Department has beenknown to use the official exchange rate even when it is much lower thanthe market exchange rate, which can result in a finding of dumpingwhere no dumping occurred.<a href="#50">[50]</a>  And companies incountries that are experiencing hyperinflation can also face exchangerate problems when the Commerce Department computes relative prices,<a href="#51">[51]</a> especially if it uses one rate to determine therevenue earned at the sale date and another rate to determine the costof production at the export date a few months later.<ahref="#52">[52]</a> 	<a name="AAC"><h4>III.  Antidumping Actions in the Computer Industry</h4><p><a name="53r"><a name="54r"></p><p>	Most antidumping and countervailing duty investigations inthe United States have involved the hardware end of the industry ratherthan the software end.  But software is not immune from prosecutionunder the antidumping and countervailing duty laws.  At least onecountervailing duty investigation concluded that software conveyed bycertain media can be considered merchandise (rather than services).<ahref="#53">[53]</a> So foreign software suppliers must be careful notto run afoul of the U.S. antidumping and countervailing duty laws.  ButU.S. software companies must also be careful not to run afoul of theantidumping and countervailing duty laws of other nations, especiallyin cases where their software development was subsidized by the federalgovernment.<a href="#54">[54]</a> This article will confine itself to adiscussion of the hardware end of the computer industry.	<a name="64K"><h4>A.  64 K DRAM Chips</h4><p><a name="55r"><a name="56r"></p><p><a name="57r"><a name="58r"><a name="59r"></p><p>	The USITC has investigated allegations of DRAM chip dumpingon at least three occasions.<a href="#55">[55]</a>  The firstinvestigation<a href="#56">[56]</a> was initiated by Micron<ahref="#57">[57]</a> on June 24, 1985.  This investigation coveredimports from Japan of assembled 64 kilobit<a href="#58">[58]</a> DRAMsof the N-channel metal oxide semiconductor (NMOS) type.  The USITCreached an affirmative final determination in this case.<a href="#59">[59]</a> <HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><a name="256K"><h4>B.  256K DRAM Chips</h4><p><a name="60r"><a name="61r"><a name="62r"></p><p>	The second investigation was initiated by the USITC on December 11,1985 and covered Japanese imports of 256K and above DRAMs of both theNMOS and complementary metal oxide semiconductor (CMOS) varieties.<ahref="#60">[60]</a>  This investigation was suspended after theJapanese producers/exporters agreed with the Commerce Department toraise their prices.<a href="#61">[61]</a>   The agreement caused theprice of 256K chips to double within a month<a href="#62">[62]</a> andto increase from about $2 to more than $7 per chip by mid-1988.<a href="#63">[63]</a><p><a name="64r"><a name="65r"><a name="66r"><a name="67r"></p><p>	At the time this investigation was initiated, American memorychip producers were incurring tremendous losses -- about $2 billion for1985 and 1986 combined.<a href="#64">[64]</a>  They attributed theselosses to Japanese producers, who were dumping their integratedcircuits (ICs) on the domestic market.  Domestic producers also claimedthat the Japanese market was closed to them in spite of the fact thattheir prices were lower.  The worldwide market for memory chips at thetime was about $7 billion, out of a total semiconductor market of $32billion.<a href="#65">[65]</a> Although American firms had dominatedthe market, Japanese firms were gaining market share because they wereinvesting heavily in research and development while American firms werecutting back due to the economic downturn.<a href="#66">[66]</a> Japanese firms had captured 65 percent of the 256K market and 98percent of the 1MB market.<a href="#67">[67]</a><a name="68r"><a name="69r"><p>	The purpose of the 1986 U.S.-Japan Semiconductor Arrangementwas to stop the alleged dumping of DRAM chips in the United States andelsewhere.  In the then-existing "gray market," DRAM chips were beingshipped to third countries, which would then re-ship the chips to theUnited States.  The agreement<a href="#68">[68]</a> called for theJapanese Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) to gatherquarterly data on transaction prices and costs.  Japanese producerswere supposed to set their prices high enough to cover their costs plusan 8 percent profit margin.<a href="#69">[69]</a><a name="70r"><p>	But the gray market did not dry up.  It kept humming along nicely, aschip brokers smuggled DRAMs out of Japan, had them implanted into dummycircuit boards (which were not covered by the Agreement), then sold inthe United States for 20 to 40 percent less than the "worldwide" pricecalled for in the Agreement.<a href="#70">[70]</a><a name="71r"><a name="72r"><a name="73r"><a name="74r"><p>	Another provision of this Agreement called for an opening ofthe Japanese market.  In 1986, foreign producers had a 10.3 percentshare of the Japanese market, most of which was held by Americanproducers.<a href="#71">[71]</a>  By late 1987, the foreign-held shareof the market increased to slightly more than 12 percent.<ahref="#72">[72]</a>  One reason why American firms could not capturemore market share in Japan is because the 1986 Agreement, which raisedthe price of Japanese chips, caused the demand for them in the U.S.A.to drop drastically.  As a result, the Japanese market experienced aglut of chips, which made it impossible for American firms to increasetheir market share to any great extent.<a href="#73">[73]</a> And theglut in Japan produced some other side-effects, such as giving theJapanese even more incentive to sell their chips in other markets, thusgaining market share, or to purchase American companies.<a href="#74">[74]</a>  So the 1986 Agreement had detrimental effects onthe very people the Agreement was designed to protect.<a name="75r"><a name="76r"><a name="77r"><p>	Since most DRAMs are used by computer firms, and since thechips they use in their computers now cost much more than before,American computer companies are much less able to compute with foreignrivals, which can buy cheaper chips on the world market.<ahref="#75">[75]</a>   Japanese computer manufacturers were thus given acompetitive cost advantage as a result of this Agreement because theycould buy lower priced chips in the Japanese market.<ahref="#76">[76]</a>  American computer manufacturers had to buyhigher-priced chips.  According to one estimate, the 1986 Agreementcost American consumers $568 million a year.<a href="#77">[77]</a><a name="78r"><a name="79r"><p>	Another aspect of the 1986 Agreement that is often overlooked isthe effect it had on Japanese sovereignty and individual freedom. Ineffect, the Japanese government was forcing MITI to do what Americanproducers demanded.  Which basically means that the Japanese governmentwas dictating to Japanese companies.<a href="#78">[78]</a>  And forcingthe Japanese to set up a cartel worked against the interests ofAmerican consumers.<a href="#79">[79]</a>  Had such a cartel beenestablished by companies in the United States, they would have been inviolation of the antitrust laws.  So, by forcing the Japanese to form acartel to monitor chip prices, the United States was encouraging themto do something that would have been a crime if done in the UnitedStates.<a name="80r"><ul>	<p>	... there is the possibility that Japanese semi-conductor exporters	and their related parties in the United States will be exposed	to liability because Japanese exporters and their related parties	restrict sales at prices not less than company-specific fair value in	the United States market.  Such restrictions of sales are undertaken	by these exporters and related parties in response to measures	imposed by the Government of Japan in accordance with the Agreement. 	From the Japanese perspective, this is "multiple legal harassment". 	The exporter is under the control of the Japanese Government's	monitoring, and might also be liable to prosecution for violation of	United States anti-trust laws.<a href="#80">[80]</a>	</p>	</ul><a name="81r"><a name="82r"><a name="83r"><p>	And it is possible that Japanese courts might find compliancewith administrative guidance to be an invalid antitrust defense, whichmeans that Japanese producers might find themselves in violation ofJapanese antitrust laws if they comply with the 1986 Agreement.<ahref="#81">[81]</a>   The U.S. doctrine of sovereign compulsion<ahref="#82">[82]</a> might be a sufficient defense in U.S. courts, butwhether this defense would be recognized in the case of semiconductorsis not at all clear.<a href="#83">[83]</a>   In the case ofsemiconductors, not only are exporters involved, but so are relatedparties, and it is questionable whether it is the Japanese governmentor the exporters that are restricting sales.<a name="84r"><a name="85r"><p>	This Agreement has been compared to a Voluntary Export Restraintagreement (VER).<a href="#84">[84]</a>  But it should be pointed outthat voluntary export restraints are not voluntary.  They are betweengovernments and require some government to prevent a portion of itscitizenry (Japanese steel companies or auto manufacturers, for example)from selling to the citizens of some foreign country.<ahref="#85">[85]</a><a name="86r"><a name="87r"><p>	Another harmful side-effect of this Agreement has to do withthe relative reliability of Japanese versus domestic producers.Japanese firms are vertically integrated,<a href="#86">[86]</a> whichmeans that there is common ownership of the firms that make chips andthe firms that make computers.  The computer chip firms act assuppliers to the computer manufacturing firms, so the computermanufacturing firms are assured of a steady supply of computer chips. But American computer manufacturers are not assured of a steady supplyof computer chips.  Sometimes they have to cancel orders or are unableto meet deadlines because they cannot get all the computer chips theyneed.  Thus, Japanese computer manufacturers have acquired a reputationfor being more reliable suppliers, which hurts American firmcompetitiveness.<a href="#87">[87]</a><a name="88r"><p>	There is also a question of quality.  If quality is measuredby the number of chips that are rejected, then Japanese producersmanufacture higher-quality chips than American producers.  For everymillion semiconductors manufactured, the reject rate for Japanesesemiconductors is between 70 and 100.  For American-madesemiconductors, the reject rate is between 500 and 1,500.<ahref="#88">[88]</a>  So by making it more difficult or more expensivefor American companies that use DRAM chips to purchase from theJapanese, the law is putting pressure on them to purchase inferiorAmerican-made chips -- which helps to make American-made computersinferior as well.<a name="89r"><a name="90r"><a name="91r"><a name="92r"><p>	Halting the inflow of cheap chips also has an employment effect. One study estimated that the price increase in chips resulted inemployment gains in the semiconductor industry of 5,000 jobs, andemployment losses of 7,000 jobs in the industries that use computerchips, for a net employment loss of 2,000 jobs.<a href="#89">[89]</a> In other words, 1.4 jobs were lost for each job gained.<ahref="#90">[90]</a>  A more sophisticated analysis by the sameresearcher estimated job losses in the computer industry to be 11,300,for a job loss/gain ratio of nearly 2.3 to 1.<a href="#91">[91]</a> Another interesting side-effect of the U.S.-Japanese Semi-conductorArrangement is that it may well have accelerated Japanese and Koreanentry into the integrated circuit market, which was previouslydominated by U.S. firms.<a href="#92">[92]</a><a name="93r"><a name="94r"><p>	Another interesting aspect of this case has to do with themethod by which computer chips were priced.  Japanese companies usedwhat is called learning curve pricing.<a href="#93">[93]</a>   If thecost of producing a computer chip declines by 28 percent a year, whichwas the case before this Arrangement according to one estimate, it ispossible for a Japanese company to give a price quote that is belowcurrent cost and still make a profit, because delivery will not occuruntil three or eight months later, when the cost of production hasdeclined.  So, at the time of delivery, the cost of production isactually less than the price charged, even though the selling price washigher than the cost of production at the time the price quote wasgiven.<a href="#94">[94]</a><a name="95r"><a name="96r"><p>	For example, let's say that a Japanese chip manufacturer agrees tosell some chips for $5.00 a unit on January 2, when its costs ofproduction are $5.50.  It is agreed that delivery will be on June 30,six months later.  Based on these costs and revenue figures, theJapanese company is selling for $0.50 less than production cost.<a href="#95">[95]</a>  But by the time June 30th rolls around, productioncosts have declined to $4.73, so it is actually making a $0.27 profitby selling for $5.00.<a href="#96">[96]</a><a name="97r"><a name="98r"><a name="99r"><p>	Which cost should be used when attempting to determine whether thechips were dumped on the market for less than production cost?  If theJanuary 2nd cost of production is used, then the company is guilty ofdumping.  But if the June 30th cost of production is used, it is notguilty of dumping.  Since the revenue is earned on June 30, at the timeof delivery, the more rational choice would be to use the June 30production cost.<a href="#97">[97]</a>  But the Commerce Department andthe U.S. International Trade Commission do not always follow what isrational, or what is considered to be a generally accepted accountingprinciple, as was pointed out above.  So a company in this situationcould be found guilty of dumping when no dumping actually occurred.<a href="#98">[98]</a>  The 1986 Agreement did not address this issue,although a subsidiary agreement provided that costs should bedetermined on an average quarterly basis.<a href="#99">[99]</a><a name="100r"><p>	The 1986 Arrangement could have other unintended detrimentaleffects, too.  At present, the United States has a comparativeadvantage in the area of design and software.  But if this Arrangementreduces the benefits that Japanese manufacturers receive in the DRAMend of the business, it could cause them to shift more resources intothe design and software end of the business, which will put morecompetitive pressure on American designers and software producers.<a href="#100">[100]</a><ul><a name="101r">	<p>	... to the extent that any force has worked to produce monopoly	profits in the semiconductor industry it is the 1986 Semi-conductor	Agreement itself, which requires the Japanese to set world-wide	prices in accord with "fair" market levels to be determined quarterly	by Commerce.<a href="#101">[101]</a>	</p></ul><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><a name="1MB"><h4>C.  1MB DRAM Chips</h4><a name="102r"><a name="103r"><a name="104r"><a name="105r"><a name="106r"><a name="107r"><p>	The most recent USITC DRAM chip dumping investigation involvedKorean exports of computer DRAM chips of one megabit or more to theUnited States.<a href="#102">[102]</a>  The investigation wasinstituted in response to a petition filed on behalf of MicronTechnology, Inc. of Boise, Idaho<a href="#103">[103]</a> on April 22,1992.<a href="#104">[104]</a>  The petitioner alleged that dynamicrandom access memory (DRAM) semiconductors of one megabit<ahref="#105">[105]</a> or more<a href="#106">[106]</a> from the Republicof Korea were being, or were likely to be, sold in the United Statesfor less than fair value within the meaning of Section 731 of theTariff Act of 1930, and that these imports were materially injuring, orwere threatening to materially injure a U.S. industry.<a href="#107">[107]</a><a name="108r"><a name="109r"><a name="110r"><a name="111r"><a name="112r"><p>	Micron alleged that three Korean companies -- Hyundai, Goldstarand Samsung -- were selling their chips in the United States for lessthan the cost of production.<a href="#108">[108]</a>  It determined theU.S. price based on price quotes for DRAMs made by distributors in theUnited States.  It then subtracted the distributors' markup andmovement expenses from these quoted prices.<a href="#109">[109]</a>  Itused average market prices obtained from Dataquest and company-specifichome market price quotes from an unidentified firm to demonstrate homemarket price.<a href="#110">[110]</a>  Based on these calculations, thepetitioner alleged that the range of DRAM dumping margins, based on acomparison of constructed value to U.S. price, was: between 94.29% and170.89% (one meg) and 278.63% and 282.51% (four meg) for Hyundai;between 132.11% and 165.29% (one meg) and 273.25% (four meg) forGoldstar; and between 0.62% and 3.83% (one meg) and between 93.18% and97.39% (four meg) for Samsung.<a href="#111">[111]</a>   Courts haveheld that the USITC could consider dumping margins as a factor indetermining injury, since neither the statute not legislative historyspecifically prohibited the use of margin analysis as a factor indetermining injury.<a href="#112">[112]</a><a name="113r"><p>	One interesting aspect of this investigation is the manner inwhich the conclusion that the Korean companies were selling at lessthan fair value was determined.  One hundred comparisons were madebetween U.S. prices and Korean prices that export manufacturerscharged.  In 47 cases, U.S. prices were less than Korean prices, byamounts ranging from 0.1 percent to 28.0 percent.  In 48 cases, theKorean companies charged a higher price in the U.S. than in Korea, bymargins of between 0.3 percent and 69.2 percent.  In the other fivecases, the prices charged in the Korean and U.S. markets wereidentical.<a href="#113">[113]</a><p>	To most rational observers who are familiar with the way business isconducted, such a pricing pattern would indicate that there was nodumping, but merely competitive pricing.  If the Koreans were intent ondumping, then all, or at least the vast majority of prices, would beless in the U.S. market than in Korea.  But such was not the case.  Inabout half of the comparisons, the price charged in the United Stateswas actually higher than the price charged in Korea.<a name="114r"><p>	A comparison of prices charged in the franchise distributormarket and the value-added reseller/aftermarket reseller market wouldlead to the same conclusion -- that there was no dumping, but merelycompetitive pricing.  Sixty-seven comparisons between U.S. prices andKorean prices were made in the franchise distributor market.  In 23cases, the Korean product was sold for less than the U.S. product, bymargins ranging from 0.7 percent to 53.0 percent.  In 42 cases, theKorean product sold at a higher price than the U.S. product, withmargins ranging from 0.1 percent to 66.7 percent.  In the two othercases, the products were sold at the same price.<a href="#114">[114]</a><a name="115r"><p>	Six price comparisons were made in the value-addedreseller/aftermarket reseller market.  In one case, the Korean productsold for less than the U.S. product.  In four cases, the Korean productwas priced slightly higher than the U.S. product.  In one case, the twoproducts sold for the same price.<a href="#115">[115]</a><a name="116r"><p>	In all three markets, the price comparisons do not support theallegation that dumping occurred.  But, as was pointed out above, whatappears to be price competition to the average observer might bedumping to the USITC.  In fact, the preliminary investigation concludedthat dumping had indeed occurred.<a href="#116">[116]</a><a name="117r"><a name="118r"><a name="119r"><a name="120r"><a name="121r"><p>	In its preliminary determination,<a href="#117">[117]</a> theUSITC concluded that the weighted-average dumping margins for Goldstar,Hyundai, Samsung and Others were 52.41 percent, 5.99 percent, 87.40percent and 81.88 percent, respectively.<a href="#118">[118]</a>  Inits final determination, these dumping margins were reducedsubstantially, to 4.97 percent for Goldstar, 7.19 percent for Hyundai,0.74 percent for Samsung and 3.19 percent for all others.<a href="#119">[119]</a>  The percentages in the final determination werelater revised due to a clerical error that occurred in the originalcalculation of the dumping margins at the final determination level.The revised final determination percentages were 4.97 percent, 11.45percent, 0.82 percent and 3.89 percent.<a href="#120">[120]</a>  Thefinal determination also concluded that an industry in the UnitedStates was materially injured because of the Korean imports that weresold for less than fair value.<a href="#121">[121]</a>	<p>The dissenting opinion makes an interesting point regarding these pricecomparisons.</p><ul>	<p>	The fact that prices for domestic DRAMs decreased during the period of	investigation tells us nothing about whether the subject imports	caused price depression or suppression.... DRAM prices decline	as more firms progress along a learning curve, and so in the	later stages of the product life cycle, as more firms move down	the curve, DRAM prices will fall regardless of unfair trade	practices.  Later entrants will receive lower prices.  These	market forces, combined with the other factors discussed in	this opinion, lead us to conclude that the price depression or	suppression, if any, caused by the subject imports is not	significant.	</p>	<a name="122r">	<p>	Although the underselling/overselling	comparisons are almost evenly split, we do not place much weight on	evidence of underselling.... the confluence of demand for memory and	the point in the product life cycle largely explain the price	of DRAMs at any particular point in time.  As a result of these	market forces, price comparisons are only meaningful if they	are contemporaneous, i.e. at the same point in the DRAM product	life cycle.  In this investigation, the price comparisons between	domestic DRAMs and subject imports are not contemporaneous. 	Accordingly, the price comparisons do not constitute substantial	evidence that any underselling is significant.<a	href="#122">[122]</a>	</p></ul><a name="123r"><a name="124r"><p>	The dissenting opinion also concluded that the domestic DRAMindustry was not materially injured as a result of the less than fairvalue DRAMs from Korea,<a href="#123">[123]</a> and that theprobability of actual injury from future increased market penetrationis small.<a href="#124">[124]</a><a name="125r"><a name="126r"><a name="127r"><p>	Korean DRAM chip exporters do a large business in the UnitedStates. Their U.S. sales were $800 million in 1992.<ahref="#125">[125]</a>  So this USITC decision will have a large,negative impact on them.  But the USITC decision is likely to have anegative impact on others as well.  The most obvious victim of thisdecision will be any company that uses DRAM chips, since they will haveto pay more for the chips,<a href="#126">[126]</a> regardless ofwhether they use Korean or American chips.  The Korean manufacturerswill have to raise their price, which reduces the price competitiondomestic producers face.  Domestic producers will therefore be morelikely to raise their prices since the Korean companies will no longerbe as competitive pricewise.  And U.S. customers say that the Koreanchips are as good as or better than the Japanese chips, and the servicethey receive from the Korean suppliers is better than that received byJapanese, U.S. or European suppliers,<a href="#127">[127]</a> so thequality of both product and service will likely be adversely affectedby this decision, as U.S. customers shift some of their business tonon-Korean companies.<a name="128r"><a name="129r"><p>	Less obvious victims are the employees in unidentified industrieswho stand to lose their jobs as a result of this decision.  Severalstudies have found that protectionist policies destroy more jobs thanthey save, as was pointed out above.  So if this decision protects4,000 jobs (which is the number of jobs that Micron's vice presidentsays will be protected),<a href="#128">[128]</a> then perhaps 6,000 or12,000 jobs will be destroyed in other industries if the job loss/gainratio is 1.5 to 1 or 3 to 1.<a href="#129">[129]</a><a name="130r"><a name="131r"><a name="132r"><p>	AST Research Inc. of Irvine, California is particularly upsetwith this decision, for a number of reasons.  For one thing, it seesthe paperwork required to keep track of where the chips it buys comefrom as an administrative burden.<a href="#130">[130]</a>  And it mayhave to ship more of its manufacturing overseas to keep prices down,since the decision also applies extra duties to imported subassembliesthat use Korean chips. Seven hundred of AST's production jobs are thusin jeopardy.<a href="#131">[131]</a>   And AST is only one of manycompanies in the domestic computer industry that stand to be harmed bythis antidumping action.  Any company that makes computers will beharmed because of the increased price of computer chips, and chipsaccount for one-third of the total production cost of a computer, whichis a substantial percentage.<a href="#132">[132]</a><a name="133r"><a name="134r"><a name="135r"><a name="136r"><p>	Japanese producers, who had 53 percent of the U.S. chipmarket before this decision,<a href="#133">[133]</a> stand to be bigwinners.<a href="#134">[134]</a> Their market share is likely toincrease, as well as their profit margins, since prices are likely togo up.  Dataquest predicted that the prices of semiconductor chips inthe United States will rise between 10 and 15 percent as a result ofthe preliminary determination.<a href="#135">[135]</a>  And the factthat the Korean DRAM chip exporters will have to pay dumping chargeswill cause them to lose market share.  According to one estimate, anypenalty over 10-15 percent could cause the Korean companies to lose aconsiderable share of the U.S. market.<a href="#136">[136]</a><a name="137r"><a name="138r"><a name="139r"><a name="140r"><p>	Another problem the Korean manufacturers face has to do withthe accounting procedures they must use to compute their costs.  Theantidumping law requires them to include an 8 percent profit in theircosts.<a href="#137">[137]</a>  But computer industry sources doubtthat any DRAM chip maker is making that high a profit,<a href="#138">[138]</a> which means that, to be safe, the Koreans willhave to raise their prices to a point where they will not becompetitive with the Japanese and domestic producers.  And the Koreanaccounting rules for R&D, depreciation and facilities investments areless restrictive than U.S. accounting rules.<a href="#139">[139]</a>Forcing the Korean companies to use U.S. accounting rules could raisetheir costs of production (on paper, that is) considerably, thus makingthem even less competitive and more likely to run afoul of theantidumping rules unless they raise their prices to uncompetitivelevels.  And the fact that DRAM prices have been dropping will make iteven harder for the Korean producers to compete.<a href="#140">[140]</a> <HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><a name="FPD"><h4>D. Flat Panel Displays</h4><a name="141r"><a name="142r"><a name="143r"><a name="144r"><p>	Another interesting antidumping investigation involved flatpanel displays (FPD)<a href="#141">[141]</a> and subassemblies fromJapan.<a href="#142">[142]</a>  This investigation was initiated by theAdvanced Display Manufacturers Association  and its individual membercompanies, Planar Systems, Inc., Plasmaco, Inc., OIS Optical ImagingSystems, Inc., The Cherry Corporation, Electro-Plasma, PhotonicsTechnology, Inc., and Magnascreen Corporation, on July 18, 1990.<a href="#143">[143]</a>    The investigation was initiated to determinewhether Japanese imports of high information content flat paneldisplays and subassemblies were being, or were likely to be, sold inthe United States at less than fair value, and whether there is areasonable indication that an industry in the United States ismaterially injured, or is threatened with material injury, or theestablishment of an industry in the United States is materiallyretarded, by reason of the imports.<a href="#144">[144]</a><a name="145r"><a name="146r"><p>	The petitioners based their estimates of U.S. price onrepresentative prices for several FPD technologies and products.  Theyobtained the prices from individuals at the petitioners' companies thathave contact with customers, independent market analysts, suppliers andother knowledgeable persons within the industry.  They then adjustedthe prices for foreign inland freight, foreign inland insurance, oceanfreight, U.S. duties, brokerage and U.S. inland freight.<a href="#145">[145]</a> After constructing values to arrive at foreignmarket value and comparing these values to domestic prices, theyalleged that the dumping margins ranged from 70 to 318 percent.<a href="#146">[146]</a><a name="147r"><a name="148r"><p>	The USITC was unanimous in its preliminary finding that "there is areasonable indication that an industry in the United States ismaterially injured by reason of imports from Japan of high-informationcontent (HIC) flat panel displays and subassemblies thereof that arealleged to be sold in the United States at less than fair value(LTFV).<a href="#147">[147]</a> The petitioner urged the USITC to findthat all HIC flat panel displays are one like product.  The respondentscontended that there are really four like products because there arefour principal technologies used to make HIC flat panel displays -- (1)passive matrix liquid crystal display (LCD), in which liquid crystalsact as optical shutters and allow the passage of light when a smallvoltage is applied; (2) active matrix LCD, similar to but far morecomplex than the passive form and containing a transistor at eachpixel; (3) plasma displays, in which voltage causes pixels of a gas toemit light; and (4) electroluminescent (EL) displays, in which voltagecauses pixels in a solid EL material to emit light.<a href="#148">[148]</a><a name="149r"><a name="150r"><p>	This threshold question was important because there are nodomestic producers of passive matrix LCDs, and so there cannot be aseparate like product consisting of passive matrix LCDs.<a href="#149">[149]</a>  In previous cases, the USITC rejected the notionthat a like product could be defined as a product not produced by aU.S. industry,<a href="#150">[150]</a>so separating the products intofour separate categories would make the Japanese producers less liable. What domestic company can allege injury when no domestic company makesthe product?<a name="151r"><a name="152r"><a name="153r"><a name="154r"><a name="155r"><p>	The USITC ruled that the four categories in question constituteone like product.  Although the LCD, EL and plasma displays exhibitednoticeable differences, such as the type of medium used to activate thedisplay pixels, it did not consider such differences sufficient towarrant dividing the like product along technological lines.<ahref="#151">[151]</a>  The fact that the different display types lackabsolute interchangeability also did not preclude a finding that theyconstituted a single like product.<a href="#152">[152]</a>  Nor did thefact that the production processes for the various types of displaysdiffered somewhat (the similarities between the processes weresignificant)<a href="#153">[153]</a> or that prices differedsomewhat.<a href="#154">[154]</a> The fact that all types of HIC flatpanel display appeared to have the same general distribution channelsupported the argument that they were a like, single product.<a href="#155">[155]</a><a name="156r"><a name="157r"><a name="158r"><a name="159r"><a name="160r"><p>	The domestic industry had been experiencing a period of increasingunderutilization of capacity during the 1987-90 period.  Althoughconsumption of HIC flat panel displays and subassemblies rose rapidly,their capacity to produce the items expanded even more rapidly.<a href="#156">[156]</a> Operating losses within the industry increasedsteadily from 1987 to 1990 and cash flow remained negative.<a href="#157">[157]</a> Capital expenditures by domestic producersdeclined throughout the period of investigation.<a href="#158">[158]</a> And the petitioning companies were severelyhampered in their research and development efforts because they foundit extremely difficult to obtain financing.<a href="#159">[159]</a> Based on these facts, the USITC found that the industry was materiallyinjured.<a href="#160">[160]</a><a name="161r"><a name="162r"><a name="163r"><a name="164r"><p>	However, just being injured is not sufficient.  It is alsonecessary to find that there is a reasonable indication that thematerial injury was caused by the subject imports underinvestigation.<a href="#161">[161]</a>  To make this determination, theUSITC considers the volume of imports, their effect on prices of thelike product, and their impact on domestic producers.<a href="#162">[162]</a>    It examines whether import volumes orincreases in volume are significant, whether there has been significantunderselling by imports, whether imports significantly depress orsuppress prices for the like product, and affect such factors asdomestic production, sales, capacity utilization, inventories,employment, and profits.<a href="#163">[163]</a> It may consider otherfactors as well, but if it does, it must explain why they arerelevant.<a href="#164">[164]</a><a name="165r"><a name="166r"><a name="167r"><a name="168r"><a name="169r"><a name="170r"><a name="171r"><a name="172r"><p>	The Japanese share of the market during the period underinvestigation fluctuated up and down but never fell below 90 percent.<a href="#165">[165]</a>  Thus, it was easy for the USITC to conclude thatthe volume of imports was significant.<a href="#166">[166]</a> Althoughit received only scanty price data, in the few instances where pricecomparisons were possible, the Japanese products were priced below theU.S. products.<a href="#167">[167]</a>  And there was some evidencethat there was price depression and suppression in the sense thatdomestic prices generally declined or remained flat during the periodunder investigation.<a href="#168">[168]</a>  And the petitioners wereable to find one domestic purchaser to testify that a domestic producerhad to cut its price because a Japanese producer offered its product ata lower price, thus losing revenue.<a href="#169">[169]</a>  Thepetitioner also argued that the fact that stiff Japanese competition caused customers to decide to purchase Japanese HIC flat panel displaysat the design stage, thus stunting the domestic industry's growth bydrying up funding for both building capacity and increasing researchand development.<a href="#170">[170]</a>  The petitioner argued thatlost sales and lost revenue were particularly damaging because theyoccurred at a crucial point in the industry's growth cycle, when theindustry was seeking the large purchases that would permit commercialproduction to begin.<a href="#171">[171]</a>  The petitioner alsopresented evidence to show that several firms left the industry duringthe period of investigation, and that at least one departure was due insignificant part to Japanese competition, which discouraged investorsfrom considering investment in the domestic industry.<a href="#172">[172]</a><a name="173r"><a name="174r"><a name="175r"><p>	Based on the evidence presented, the USITC concluded that (1) therecord as a whole does not contain clear and convincing evidence thatthere is no material injury or threat of material injury; and (2)additional and perhaps contrary evidence is likely to arise in a finalinvestigation.<a href="#173">[173]</a>  Thus, the USITC was required tomake an affirmative determination,<a href="#174">[174]</a>becauseaccording to case law, an affirmative finding must be found unless "(1)the record as a whole contains clear and convincing evidence that thereis no material injury or threat of material injury; and (2) nolikelihood exists that contrary evidence will arise in a finalinvestigation."<a href="#175">[175]</a><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><a name="MD"><h4>E. Microdisks</h4><a name="176r"><a name="177r"><a name="178r"><p>	On February 26, 1988, a petition was filed by Verbatim Corp.of Charlotte, North Carolina requesting the USITC to investigatewhether there was a reasonable indication that an industry in theUnited States was materially injured, or threatened by material injury,or if the establishment of an industry in the United States wasmaterially retarded, by reason of imports from Japan of unrecordedflexible magnetic disk recording media that are alleged to be sold inthe United States for less than fair value.<a href="#176">[176]</a> The USITC found that there was such a reasonable indication, and issuedan affirmative determination.<a href="#177">[177]</a>  It based itsdetermination primarily on the poor financial condition of the domesticindustry, the significant volume and large market penetration ofimports from Japan, and the apparent adverse impact of these imports onprices in the U.S. market.<a href="#178">[178]</a><a name="179r"><a name="180r"><a name="181r"><a name="182r"><a name="183r"><p>	There were eight domestic companies in the industry duringthe time under investigation.<a href="#179">[179]</a>  Losses in thissegment of the industry were significant, which led the USITC toconclude that there was a reasonable indication that the domesticindustry was materially injured.<a href="#180">[180]</a>  Althoughsales increased dramatically during the period under investigation --29.2 percent from 1985 to 1986 and 53.0 percent from 1986 to 1987 --operating losses as a percentage of sales were 165.7 percent in 1985,138.1 percent in 1986 and 71.1 percent in 1987.<a href="#181">[181]</a> Capital expenditures dropped significantly in the domestic industry inspite of increased demand for the product.<a href="#182">[182]</a> Research and development expenditures also dropped during part of theperiod under investigation.<a href="#183">[183]</a><a name="184r"><a name="185r"><a name="186r"><a name="187r"><a name="188r"><a name="189r"><p>	The next question the USITC addressed was whether this materialinjury was caused by Japanese imports.  Japanese imports of 3.5 inchmicrodisks during the period under investigation increased by 500percent.  Imports of media for 3.5 inch microdisks increased by 116percent.<a href="#184">[184]</a>  U.S. producers' share of themicrodisk market was less than 25 percent throughout the period.<a href="#185">[185]</a> The domestic producers' share of the U.S. marketfor microdisk media increased steadily, from 55.4 percent in 1985 to74.4 percent in 1987.<a href="#186">[186]</a>  Prices for both disksand media declined throughout the period.<a href="#187">[187]</a>Prices for certain categories of Japanese microdisks were often lowerthan the prices of U.S. disks.  The exact percentages in which Japanesedisks had lower prices than U.S. disks depended on the subcategory ofdisk.  For one category, the Japanese price was lower in each quarterexamined.  In another case, the Japanese price was lower in one-thirdof the quarters examined.  In a third category, Japanese prices werelower more than half of the quarters.  In a fourth category, Japaneseprices were lower in half of the quarters.  In a fifth category, theywere lower in less than half of the quarters.<a href="#188">[188]</a> Underselling by Japan was found consistently in the more profitable,growth segments of the market.<a href="#189">[189]</a></p><ul>	<a name="190r">	<p>	The underselling by imports indicates that the pricing of allegedly	LTFV imports has contributed to price declines during the period of	investigation.  Price declines have contributed to the industry's	inability to generate the profits needed for expansion, capital	expenditures, and continuing product development.  The magnitude of	these price declines is particularly troublesome in light of	increasing demand for 3.5 inch microdisks during the period of	investigation. Consequently, we conclude that there is a reasonable	indication that allegedly LTFV imports are a cause of material	injury to the domestic industry producing 3.5 in microdisks and	media therefor.<a href="#190">[190]</a>	</p></ul><a name="PWP"><h4>F. Personal Word Processors</h4><a name="191r"><a name="192r"><a name="193r"><a name="194r"><p>	This investigation was instituted as the result of a petitionfiled on November 6, 1990 by Smith Corona Corp. of New Canaan,Connecticut alleging that certain personal word processors from Japanwere being sold in the United States for less than fair value.<a href="#191">[191]</a>   The USITC's determination was affirmative.<ahref="#192">[192]</a>  The Japanese producers were found guilty on thebasis of the best information available.  Some of the respondents hadrefused to supply information to the USITC.<a href="#193">[193]</a> The weighted average dumping margin percentage for all foreignsuppliers was 58.71 percent.<a href="#194">[194]</a>  <HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE> <a name="SHE"><h4>IV.  Some Harmful Effects of the Antidumping Laws</h4><p>[To be completed by Yeomin]</p><a name="TPA"><h4>V.  The Philosophy of Antidumping</h4><p>	Antidumping policy is irrational.  It cannot be supported by anyphilosophical (or even economic) argument.  Antidumping is basically aweapon to protect consumers from low prices.  It is a tool used bydomestic producers to protect themselves from foreign competition.  Itis an example of class conflict. But unlike the Marxist version ofclass conflict, which pits the proletariat (the good guys) against thebourgeoisie (the bad guys), antidumping laws pit producers againstconsumers.  Antidumping laws are tools in the weapons arsenal ofproducers to extract higher prices for their products, at the expenseof consumers.  It is a method producers use to obtain wealth by forcethat they could not get through voluntary exchange.  There are only twoways to obtain wealth -- by voluntary exchange or by force -- andantidumping laws take the road of force.  They use the force ofgovernment to prevent foreign competitors from doing business withcustomers that might otherwise be theirs, or to increase their sellingprices by putting a damper on price competition.<a name="195r"><p>	It might be argued that there must be some balancing of interests.The interests of the producers must be balanced against the interestsof consumers.  But such arguments do not hold up to analysis.  For onething, the balancing of interests is utilitarian at its base.  Andutilitarian arguments all suffer from the same weakness -- there is noway to measure gains and losses.<a href="#195">[195]</a> One mightargue that 100 million consumers stand to lose and 100,000 auto workersstand to gain as a result of some protectionist auto industrylegislation.  And one can even argue that the 100,000 auto workersstand to gain a lot, whereas the 100 million consumers stand to loseonly a little, if Congress passes some kind of protectionist tariff orquota.  But it still is not possible to determine whether the gainsexceed the losses.  Of course, economists can calculate deadweightlosses, but these losses do not account for all pieces of the piebecause they leave out qualitative factors, and they do not include theeffects that a particular policy would have on the hundreds of otherindustries that stand to be affected by the policy.<a name="196r"><p>	The argument can also be made that an antidumping policy is for thecommon good or is in the common interest.  But this argument also fallsapart upon analysis.  There is no such thing as the common good. Whatis good for one (a semiconductor company employee) may not be good foranother (a consumer of computer products). Individuals have their owninterests.  There is no common interest.  Individuals have competinginterests that sometimes conflict.<a href="#196">[196]</a>  One cannotarrive at a common interest by adding together the interests ofindividuals because their interests conflict.  Attempts to addconflicting interests merely degenerate into utilitarian, majoritarianarguments.  But majoritarian arguments are defective because someminority (or at times an unorganized majority) must sacrifice somethingso that the majority (or an organized minority) can prevail.<p>	The real issue is one of property rights.  A property rights approachis superior to a utilitarian approach because, under a property rightsapproach, there is no need to measure gains and losses.  All that needbe done is determine whether someone's rights are violated.  If apolicy would result in the violation of someone's rights, then it is abad policy.  If no one's rights are violated, then perhaps it is a goodpolicy.  If the purpose of government is to protect life, liberty andproperty and otherwise leave individuals alone to make their ownchoices, then a policy that sacrifices the rights of some individualsso that other individuals can have something they otherwise would notbe entitled to is a bad policy.  Frederic Bastiat, a nineteenth centuryFrench philosopher, had the following test for determining whether alaw was a good one or a bad one:<ul>	<p>	See if the law takes from some persons what belongs to them, and	gives it to other persons to whom it does not belong.  See if the law	benefits one citizen at the expense of another by doing what	the citizen himself cannot do without committing a crime.	</p></ul><a name="197r"><p>	Then abolish this law without delay, for it is not only an evilitself, but also it is a fertile source for further evils because itinvites reprisals.<a href="#197">[197]</a><p>	How do the antidumping laws hold up to Bastiat's test?  Domestic DRAMchip producers, by using the antidumping laws, are getting protectionfrom competition at the expense of consumers.  They are using the forceof government to prevent willing buyers and willing sellers fromentering into voluntary exchange.  If they tried to prevent suchvoluntary exchanges by using force themselves, they would be guilty ofa crime.  So they let the government do the dirty work for them.According to Bastiat's test, such a law -- the antidumping law -- is abad one, and should be abolished immediately, before its enforcementleads to reprisals.<a name="198r"><a name="199r"><p>	Economists of the Public Choice School view the situation somewhatdifferently.  They would call those who stand to benefit by anantidumping law "rent seekers."  Rent seeking might be defined asseeking special privileges or protection from government or gettingothers to pay for your benefits.<a href="#198">[198]</a>  Rent seekingactivity is likely to appear wherever the costs are low and thepotential benefits are great. Almost all of the antidumping actionsthat have been filed were initiated by some company or group ofcompanies that stood to gain if a foreign competitor were forced toraise prices or incur the cost of complying with a Commerce Departmentrequest for information.<a href="#199">[199]</a><a name="200r"><p>	Using the antidumping laws is a very inexpensive way to harass acompetitor and to convince competitors to raise their prices.  All apetitioning company has to do is write a letter to the CommerceDepartment stating that some foreign competitor is selling some productfor an unfairly low price. The Commerce Department will take it fromthere and send its fleet of lawyers into the field to investigate attaxpayer expense.  The accused company or companies must expend perhapsmillions of dollars to defend themselves.  And even if they win thecase, they still lose because they must divert their resources awayfrom sales and production and into a defense of their actions.<a href="#200">[200]</a>  And any antidumping action has a chilling effecton future behavior. Foreign competitors that have been through anantidumping investigation will think twice about being aggressive pricecompetitors.  Some foreign producers may even decide that trying tocompete in the American market is just not worth it because of theharassment they might get from the Commerce Department. The loser, ofcourse, is the American consumer, who must be content with a reducedchoice of products that cost more than would be the case under a fullycompetitive system.<p>	Applying the antidumping laws to the computer industry can haveespecially detrimental effects on American competitiveness.  TheAmerican companies that manufacture computers need computer chips.  Ifthey must pay substantially more for them than what manufacturers inother countries have to pay, their costs will be higher, which willmake it difficult for them to sell their computers in the internationalmarketplace.  And any American company that uses computers -- and whichones don't these days -- will also incur extra costs because the costof the computer chips they have in their computers has been inflateddue to the antidumping laws and these inflated prices are reflected inthe cost of their computers.<a name="201r"><a name="202r"><p>	Some ethical issues also need to be discussed in connectionwith initiating antidumping actions.  One might legitimately askwhether it is ethical to initiate an antidumping action.  As a rule ofthumb, one might say that an action is ethical if no one's rights areviolated and unethical if rights are violated.<a href="#201">[201]</a>Which leads to the question: Are anyone's rights violated if a foreignproducer sells something in the domestic market for less than fairvalue?<a href="#202">[202]</a><a name="203r"><a name="204r"><p>	Assuming for the moment that something can be sold for lessthan fair value, it does not follow that someone's rights are therebyviolated. While it is true that some domestic producer stands to beharmed, being harmed is not the same as having one's rights violated. A mom and pop grocery store stand to be greatly harmed if a supermarketchain opens a store across the street.  But this does not mean thattheir rights are violated<a href="#203">[203]</a> because thesupermarket chain has every right to open a store wherever it wants.<a href="#204">[204]</a>  So just because a domestic producer stands to beharmed if a foreign producer is allowed to sell in the domestic marketdoes not mean that the domestic producer has any moral right to preventthe sale from taking place.  On the contrary, if a domestic producerdoes something to prevent an otherwise willing seller and willing buyerfrom entering into a voluntary exchange, the domestic producer isviolating their right to contract and their right to exchange theirproperty.  And by initiating an antidumping action, the domesticproducer is doing just that -- violating the rights of willing buyersand sellers to enter into contracts and exchange their property.<a name="205r"><p>	Yet the antidumping laws state that there is liability if "there is areasonable indication that an industry in the United States ismaterially injured, or is threatened with material injury, or theestablishment of an industry in the United States is materiallyretarded by reason of imports."<a href="#205">[205]</a>  There are at least three problemswith holding a foreign competitor liable under these conditions.  Forone thing, it is almost certain that some domestic producer will beharmed if a foreign competitor is permitted to sell in the UnitedStates, because the foreign seller is likely to take a sale that wouldotherwise go to a domestic producer.  So it then becomes a question ofwhether the injury is material, which is subjective.  The only way tobe sure that a domestic producer is not harmed is to prevent theforeign competitor from making any sales in the United States in thefirst place, which is a highly protectionist policy.  But the realissue should not be whether someone has been "harmed" but whethersomeone's rights have been violated.  With the present rule, punishmentcan be meted out even though no rights have been violated.  There isnothing wrong with harming someone in the marketplace if the harmresults from consumer choice.  If consumers decide to buy from aforeign producer rather than a domestic producer, that is their choiceand their right.<p>	The second problem with the present standard is that punishmentcan be meted out if there is merely a threat of material injury.  Inother words, a foreign producer can be punished even before it hascaused material injury.  A good case can be made that there is a threatof material injury if a foreign producer is permitted to make sales inthe United States.  The solution, then, is to not allow such sales,because they may result in material injury to some yet unidentifieddomestic producer.  The only way to insure that no material injuryresults is to close our borders to foreign trade.  The fact that therights of consumers to purchase the products of their choice isviolated by such a policy is totally ignored.<a name="206r"><a name="207r"><p>	The third problem with this policy has to do with the possibilitythat the establishment of an industry in the United States might beretarded because of an import.  Obviously, a domestic industry's growthmight be retarded if foreigners are allowed to compete for consumerdollars.  But so what?  Domestic industries have no inherent right tothe dollars of domestic consumers.  Yet this policy gives them such aright.  As Bastiat would say, this law "takes from some persons whatbelongs to them, and gives it to other persons to whom it does notbelong."<a href="#206">[206]</a>  Thus, the law fits Bastiat'sdefinition of legal plunder and should be abolished immediately becauseconsumer dollars, which might otherwise go to a foreign producer, arechanneled into the coffers of a domestic producer because the lawprevents foreign producers from entering into voluntary exchange withdomestic consumers.  In a free society, consumers determine whichindustries grow and which shrink by their dollar votes.  Thoseindustries that receive the most dollar votes will prosper and thosethat receive few dollar votes will shrink.<a href="#207">[207]</a><a name="208r"><p>	Initiation of an antidumping action also causes foreign producersto incur a great deal of expense to defend themselves.  In a sense, thestockholders of the foreign company are having their resourcesdissipated due to the antidumping action that has been initiated by thedomestic producer.  Domestic producers that file antidumping petitionsare, in effect, destroying the wealth of the shareholders of theseforeign companies.  And destroying wealth is unethical,<ahref="#208">[208]</a> or at least it is unethical under certaincircumstances.<p>	One instance where destroying someone else's wealth is not unethicalis the case where a company gains market share by selling a betterproduct at a lower price.  Higher priced companies are harmed by doingso, and the value of their stock is likely to decline, thus destroyingwealth.  But selling a better product at a lower price is not unethicalbecause no one is forcing consumers to buy their product.  Buttriggering an antidumping investigation unleashes the force ofgovernment against a competitor.  And using force to destroy wealth, bycausing a competitor to spend millions of dollars to defend itself, isunethical.<p>	Another question also needs to be asked: What is wrong with sellingbelow fair value?  While it is true that domestic producers may beharmed by the practice, in the sense that they lose sales, being harmedis not the same as having your rights violated.  Willing buyers andwilling sellers should be able to exchange their property at whateverterms they agree on.  But antidumping laws, or the threat of bringingan antidumping action, prevent them from doing this.<p>	A more basic question is: What exactly is fair value, anyway? The antidumping laws define fair value as the cost of production pluseight percent.  But aside from the fact that eight percent is anarbitrary number -- not to mention a profit margin that is oftenabnormally high -- the cost of production is different for differentcompanies.  And the calculation of the cost of production is highlyarbitrary, especially when it must be decided how fixed costs are to beallocated.  This being the case, it logically follows that fair valuefor one company may not be fair value for another company.  Thus, fairvalue is gibberish, a meaningless term.<a name="209r"><p>	The only thing that can be said about fair value is that itis the price that a willing buyer and a willing seller agree on.  Andthat price is not uniform.  Many prices may be charged for the same canof beans in the same city on the same day.  There are a number ofreasons for this,<a href="#209">[209]</a> but it cannot be said thatsome cans of beans are selling for less than fair value and some areselling for more than fair value because, in each case, there is awilling buyer and a willing seller. To have some law revolve around theconcept of fair value is insane. Yet that is exactly what theantidumping laws do.<HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><a name="CR"><h4>VI.  Conclusions and Recommendations</h4><p>	A number of things can be said about U.S. trade policy in general, andas applied to the computer industry in particular.  For one thing,dumping, if it exists, is good for American consumers. It increases thesupply of products that American consumers want and it reduces theprices they must pay.  Subsidies that foreign governments provide totheir manufacturers also help American consumers by reducing the pricethey pay for foreign products.  In effect, foreign governments thatsubsidize their manufacturers are subsidizing American consumers.  Andwhile it is probably a breach of Japanese politicians' fiduciary dutyto their constituents to use Japanese yen to subsidize Americanconsumers, it is probably not something that the United States shouldtry to stop.<a name="210r"><p>	Any kind of protectionism is paid for by consumers.  Punishingforeign producers for receiving subsidies from their governments, orpunishing them for selling their products at low prices, is irrationaland stupid.  While the argument is often made that protecting Americanindustry saves jobs, numerous studies have shown that just the oppositeis true.  While some jobs may be saved as the result of someprotectionist policy, the job losses exceed the job gains -- sometimesby a ratio of more than three-to-one.<a href="#210">[210]</a><p>	But all these arguments are merely utilitarian.  For a utilitarian, apolicy is good if the gainers exceed the losers, or if the goodoutweighs the bad.  Utilitarians totally ignore the real issue, whichis one of property rights.  Whenever some government preventsconsenting adults from entering into contracts and trading what theyhave for what they want, it violates their right to property, sincethey cannot do with their property as they see fit. It is a violationof their human rights, since property rights are one of the most basichuman rights.<p>	The only conclusion that can be drawn, whether from a utilitarian orrights perspective, is that any law that punishes foreign producersfrom selling their products to American consumers at low prices must beabolished, the sooner the better.  The antidumping and countervailingduty laws must be abolished at once, not over some phase-out period. Rights will continue to be violated as long as these laws exist. American producers that cannot produce what American consumers want ata price they are willing to pay should not be able to use the force ofgovernment to squeeze out sales that they cannot get by voluntaryexchange.  American producers have no right to prevent Americanconsumers from buying the products of their choice for any reason.	<hr><p>	An earlier version of this Policy Analysis appeared in theTemple International and Comparative Law Journal, Vol. 8, No. 2 (1994),219-256.  Nothing written here is to be construed as necessarilyreflecting the views of the Dumont Institute or as an attempt to aid orhinder the passage of any bill before Congress.</p><hr>	<h4>End Notes:</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>Although this paper is confined to antidumping	actions initiated in the USA, it is worth pointing out that	other countries also have initiated antidumping actions against	various segments of the computer industry. For example, in 1993, the	Council of the European Communities determined that Korean DRAM	exporters caused material injury to the EC DRAM industry, and imposed	24.7 percent dumping margins on the offending companies.  the	EC decision mandated that the offending companies not sell DRAMs in	the European Community at a price that is less than the price	established pursuant to a minimum price based on each company's	lowest cost of production for five years.  Commission Decision	93/157 (EEC), 93 O.J. (L66) 37, discussed in Pub. 2629, infra,	at 33-34.  Also see Stuart A. Christie, Anti-Dumping Policy of	the European Community and the Growing Spectre of Protectionism	in Technology-Related Goods, 16 Rutgers Computer & Tech. L. J.	475-507 (1990).		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>19 U.S.C. 1673b(a).	<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a nam