ilicon	Valley, Pub. No. 86, Center for the Study of American Business,	Washington University, St. Louis, August, 1988, at 1.		<a href="#92r">Return</a><p><a name="93"><li>Learning curve theory states that the cost of	producing something continues to drop over time, as you learn	how to produce more efficiently.  This concept is discussed in	most general economics texts, as well as in microeconomics	texts, management accounting texts and cost accounting texts.		<a href="#93r">Return</a><p><a name="94"><li>Arthur Denzau, Trade Protection Comes to Silicon	Valley, Pub. No. 86, Center for the Study of American Business,	Washington University, St. Louis, August, 1988, at 8.  Another	source estimated the learning curve to be 27 percent using a	different methodology.  "As the number of chips that a company	produces doubles, the cost of producing chips falls 27 per	cent." Kikuji Ohe, A Case Study of the United States -- Japan	Semiconductor Agreement, 17 Australian Bus. L. Rev. (April, 1989), at	131, citing Chip Wars, Asahi Shinbun, March 29, 1987, at 9, col. 4. 	The methodology using the doubling of production (the methodology	cited by Ohe) is actually the more generally accepted way to compute	a learning curve, although the methodology used by Denzau, which is	based on time (a year) is perhaps easier for the layperson to	understand.		<a href="#94r">Return</a><p><a name="95"><li>$5.00 selling price - $5.50 cost of production =	$0.50 loss.		<a href="#95r">Return</a><p><a name="96"><li>If the learning curve causes production costs to	decline by 28 percent a year, which Denzau says was the case	before this Agreement, then costs would decline by 14 percent	in six months, the timespan of this hypothetical example.  $5.50 x	14% = $0.77 [the decline in production costs] and $5.50 - $0.77	= $4.73 [the cost of production as of June 30].   Profit =	$5.00 selling price - $4.73 production cost = $0.27.		<a href="#96r">Return</a><p><a name="97"><li>The matching concept is applied here.  Costs are	matched as closely as possible to revenues.  The matching concept is	a basic concept in accounting and is discussed in any accounting	principles text.		<a href="#97r">Return</a><p><a name="98"><li>In the dissenting opinion in a later DRAM case, the	dissenters pointed out the logic of using contemporaneous price	comparisons when a learning curve is involved, which the majority of	USITC commissioners did not do.  See Pub. 2629, infra , at	48-49.		<a href="#98r">Return</a><p><a name="99"><li>Kikuji Ohe, A Case Study of the United States --	Japan Semiconductor Agreement, 17 Australian Bus. L. Rev. (April,	1989), at 131.		<a href="#99r">Return</a><p><a name="100"><li>Denzau points out this possibility in Trade	Protection Comes to Silicon Valley, Pub. No. 86, Center for the	Study of American Business, Washington University, St. Louis, August,	1988, at 11-12.		<a href="#100r">Return</a><p><a name="101"><li>Howard Gruenspecht, Economic Adviser to the	Chairman, U.S. International Trade Commission, Self-Defeating	Trade Policy, Wall Street Journal, June 8, 1989, at A19, col.1.		<a href="#101r">Return</a><p><a name="102"><li>United States International Trade Commission,	DRAMs of One Megabit and Above from the Republic of Korea,	Determination of the Commission in Investigation No. 731-TA-556	(Preliminary) Under the Tariff Act of 1930, Together With the	Information Obtained in the Investigation, USITC Publication	2519, June 1992, hereinafter referred to as Pub. 2519;  United	States International Trade Commission, DRAMs of One Megabit and	Above From the Republic of Korea, Determination of the Commission in	Investigation No. 731-TA-556 (Final) Under the Tariff Act of	1930, Together With the Information Obtained in the Investigation,	USITC Publication 2629, May, 1993, hereinafter referred to as	Pub. 2629.		<a href="#102r">Return</a><p><a name="103"><li>Micron and Texas Instruments are the only two U.S.	companies that still produce DRAMs for the U.S. merchant market. 	Arthur T. Denzau, Trade Protection Comes to the Valley -- Silicon	Valley, Occasional Paper 70, Center for the Study of American	Business, June, 1988, at 2.  Most American companies left the	market in the early 1980s because the Japanese dropped their	prices faster than domestic companies could reduce their costs.	 Id. at 4.  In the merchant market, merchants sell DRAM chips	to other companies, as opposed to captive producers like IBM,	which produce for internal consumption.  Arthur Denzau, Trade	Protection Comes to Silicon Valley, Pub. No. 86, Center for the	Study of American Business, Washington University, St. Louis, August,	1988, at 2.  Merchant producers in the United States had 100 percent	of the DRAM market in 1975.  By 1986, their share of the market	had dropped to 5 percent.  Office of the Under Secretary of Defense	for Acquisition, Report of the Defense Science Board Task Force	on Defense Semiconductor Dependency (U.S. Department of Defense,	Washington, DC, February, 1987), at 5, as cited in Eugene Volokh, The	Semiconductor Industry and Foreign Competition, Cato Institute	Policy Analysis No. 99, January 28, 1988, at note 1.		<a href="#103r">Return</a><p><a name="104"><li>57 Fed. Reg. 18163, April 29, 1992, reprinted in	Pub. 2519, supra, at B-2.		<a href="#104r">Return</a><p><a name="105"><li>One Meg equals about 1,045,376 bits.  Technical	references equate 1 Meg to 1,048,576 bits.  57 Fed. Reg. 18163,	April 29, 1992, at n. 1, reprinted in Pub. 2519, supra, at B-2.		<a href="#105r">Return</a><p><a name="106"><li>The merchandise under investigation consisted of	all 1 Meg and above DRAM semiconductors, whether assembled or	unassembled.  The following products were included in this	investigation: processed wafers, uncut die, cut die, and assembled 1	Meg and above DRAMs produced in Korea and imported directly or	indirectly into the United States.  Processed wafers produced	in Korea and further processed into finished or semi-finished 1	Meg and above DRAMs in a third country before exportation to	the United States are also included in the scope of this petition, as	are finished or semi-finished DRAMs assembled in Korea from	wafers produced in another country.  It also included memory modules,	such as Single In-Line Processing Modules (SIPs) and Single In-Line	Memory Modules (SIMMs) containing more than one 1-Meg or above	DRAMs mounted on their own small printed circuit board, as well	as memory cards, which are memory modules about the size of a	credit card that are designed to be easily inserted into portable	computers, printers and similar applications.  The petition	also included so-called video random access memory (VRAM) which	is DRAM designed to improve the video performance of computers.	 It also included any future packaging and assembling of DRAMs.	 57 Fed. Reg. 18163, April 29, 1992, at n. 2, reprinted in Pub.	2519, supra, at B-2.		<a href="#106r">Return</a><p><a name="107"><li> 57 Fed. Reg. 21231, May 19, 1992, reprinted in	Pub. 2519, supra, at B-4.  The consideration of alleged material	injury is discussed in Pub. 2519 starting at A-14.		<a href="#107r">Return</a><p><a name="108"><li>57 Fed. Reg. 21231, May 19, 1992, reprinted in	Pub. 2519, supra, at B-4.		<a href="#108r">Return</a><p><a name="109"><li>57 Fed. Reg. 21231, May 19, 1992, reprinted in	Pub. 2519, supra, at B-4.  The computations are discussed in	detail in Pub. 2519, supra, starting at A-7.		<a href="#109r">Return</a><p><a name="110"><li>57 Fed. Reg. 21231, May 19, 1992, reprinted in	Pub. 2519, supra, at B-4.		<a href="#110r">Return</a><p><a name="111"><li>57 Fed. Reg. 21231, May 19, 1992, reprinted in	Pub. 2519, supra, at B-4.  Also mentioned in Pub. 2519 at A-8.		<a href="#111r">Return</a><p><a name="112"><li>Copperweld Corp. v. United States, 682 F.Supp. 552	(CIT 1988).		<a