u, Trade Protection Comes to the Valley -- Silicon	Valley, Occasional Paper 70, Center for the Study of American	Business, June, 1988, at 2.  The issue has been raised that perhaps	this retaliatory action was in violation of GATT.  For more on	this point, see Kikuji Ohe, A Case Study of the United States	-- Japan Semiconductor Agreement, 17 Australian Bus. L. Rev. (April,	1989), at 151-2.		<a href="#126r">Return</a><p><a name="127"><li>Korean Fabs: The Secret of Success, Econ. Rep.,	June, 1992, at 51.		<a href="#127r">Return</a><p><a name="128"><li>Keatley, supra.	<a href="#128r">Return</a><p><a name="129"><li>Denzau estimated the job loss/gain ratio in this	segment of the computer industry to be 2.3 to 1.  See Arthur Denzau,	Trade Protection Comes to Silicon Valley, Pub. No. 86, Center for the	Study of American Business, Washington University, St. Louis, August,	1988, at 7 and 17.  So if 4,000 jobs in the DRAM end of the industry	are saved, 9,200 jobs in the computer manufacturing end of the	industry will be destroyed [4,000 x 2.3 = 9,200], for a net	employment loss of 5,200 jobs [9,200 - 4,000].		<a href="#129r">Return</a><p><a name="130"><li>Keatley, supra.	<a href="#130r">Return</a><p><a name="131"><li>Keatley, supra.	<a href="#131r">Return</a><p><a name="132"><li>Malcolm Gladwell, The Big Blue Computer Firm	Overlooked in the Trade War, Insight, April 27, 1987, 42, as cited in	Eugene Volokh, The Semiconductor Industry and Foreign Competition,	Cato Institute Policy Analysis No. 99, January 28, 1988, at note 5.		<a href="#132r">Return</a><p><a name="133"><li>The Japanese had 90 percent of the U.S. DRAM	market in 1988, but Samsung has since overtaken Hitachi and NEC	to become the second-largest DRAM producer in the world.  This	antidumping action will put a damper on Samsung's expansion. 	Korean Fabs: The Secret of Success, Econ. Rep., June, 1992, at 51.		<a href="#133r">Return</a><p><a name="134"><li>Keatley, su