="180"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 22, 24.	<a href="#180r">Return</a><p><a name="181"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 23.	<a href="#181r">Return</a><p><a name="182"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 24.	<a href="#182r">Return</a><p><a name="183"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 24.	<a href="#183r">Return</a><p><a name="184"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 25.	<a href="#184r">Return</a><p><a name="185"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 25-26.	<a href="#185r">Return</a><p><a name="186"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 26.	<a href="#186r">Return</a><p><a name="187"><li>Pub. 2076, supra , at 26-27.	<a href="#187r">Return</a><p><a name="188"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 27.	<a href="#188r">Return</a><p><a name="189"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 28.	<a href="#189r">Return</a><p><a name="190"><li>Pub. 2076, supra, at 28.	<a href="#190r">Return</a><p><a name="191"><li>56 Fed. Reg. 21392, May 8, 1991, reprinted in	United States International Trade Commission, Certain Personal	Word Processors from Japan, Determination of the Commission in	Investigation No. 731-TA-483 (Final) Under the Tariff Act of	1930, Together With the Information Obtained in the Investigation,	Pub. 2411, August, 1991, at B-3-4, hereinafter referred to as	Pub. 2411.		<a href="#191r">Return</a><p><a name="192"><li>56 Fed. Reg. 31101, July 9, 1991, reprinted in	Pub. 2411, supra, at B-7.		<a href="#192r">Return</a><p><a name="193"><li>56 Fed. Reg. 31103, July 9, 1991, reprinted in	Pub. 2411, supra, at B-9.		<a href="#193r">Return</a><p><a name="194"><li>56 Fed. Reg. 31111, July 9, 1991, reprinted in	Pub. 2411, supra, at B-17.		<a href="#194r">Return</a><p><a name="195"><li>For a discussion of the weaknesses of utilitarian	arguments, see Murray N. Rothbard, Man, Economy and State: A Treatise	on Economic Principles 260-68 (1970).		<a href="#195r">Return</a><p><a name="196"><li>Michael Novak points this out in Free Persons and	the Common Good (1989), especially in ch. 1.		<a href="#196r">Return</a><p><a name="197"><li>Frederic Bastiat, The Law 21 (1968).	<a href="#197r">Return</a><p><a name="198"><li>For more on rent-seeking, see Towards a Theory of	a Rent-Seeking Society (James M. Buchanan, Robert Tollison and	Gordon Tullock eds. 1980); The Political Economy of Rent-Seeking	(Charles K. Rowley, Robert D. Tollison and Gordon Tullock eds.	1988); Gordon Tullock, Private Wants, Public Means: An Economic	Analysis Of the Desirable Scope Of Government (1970; 1987);	Gordon Tullock, The Economics of Special Privilege and Rent Seeking	(1989).		<a href="#198r">Return</a><p><a name="199"><li>I.M. Destler lists hundreds of antidumping actions	that were filed between 1979 and 1990 in his book, American	Trade Politics 326-403 (2d ed. 1992).  Only seven of the hundreds of	antidumping investigations during this time period were initiated by	the government -- six that dealt with the trigger price mechanism for	steel and one for semiconductors.  All the other investigations	were initiated by rent-seekers, parties that stood to gain by	having the Commerce Department investigate some competitor's domestic	sales records.		<a href="#199r">Return</a><p><a name="200"><li>Another area where rent-seeking has been prevalent	is the area of antitrust.  As with antidumping, all a competitor need	do to start an antitrust investigation is write a letter to the	Justice Department.  The Justice Department conduct the investigation	at its own expense.  More than 90 percent of the antitrust	cases filed in recent years were initiated by a private company	rather than by the government.  D.T. Armentano, Antitrust Policy: The	Case for Repeal 11 (1986).  William F. Shughart II, in his	book, Antitrust Policy and Interest-Group Politics 139 (1990),	places the figure at about 95 percent.		<a href="#200r">Return</a><p><a name="201"><li>Some actions might be considered sinful by some	religions even if they do not meet this definition of ethics. 	For purposes of this discussion we shall ignore these possibilities	and stick to ethics in the business ethics sense of the term.		<a href="#201r">Return</a><p><a name="202"><li>The concept of selling for less than fair value is	an interesting one, which we shall discuss below.  The concept	of what constitutes fair value is also worth discussing.		<a href="#202r">Return</a><p><a name="203"><li>We would like to thank Walter Block for providing	us with this example.		<a href="#203r">Return</a><p><a name="204"><li>Environmental fanatics and no-growth types would	dispute this assertion, but the scope of this article does not	allow for a detailed response to these groups.		<a href="#204r">Return</a><p><a name="205"><li>55 Fed. Reg. 33146, August 14, 1990, reprinted in	Pub. 2311, supra, at B-4.		<a href="#205r">Return</a><p><a name="206"><li>Frederic Bastiat, The Law 21 (1968).	<a href="#206r">Return</a><p><a name="207"><li>This process is called consumer sovereignty and is	discussed in all economics textbooks.		<a href="#207r">Return</a><p><a name="208"><li>Unless it is your own wealth you are destroying,	which you have every right to do.  But destroying the wealth of	others is different.		<a href="#208r">Return</a><p><a name="209"><li>There are a number of reasons why prices for	identical products are not identical.  Texts on price theory go	into the reasons in detail.  One reason for the differences in	prices is because consumers do not have perfect information.  If they	all knew who was selling cans of beans for the lowest price,	they would all go there to buy their beans -- unless, of course, the	lowest price seller was a few miles away, in which case they	would prefer to pay a few more cents to go across the street. 	But they do not know who the lowest price seller is anyway. 	And beans sold in a ghetto grocery store often cost more than	beans sold in a suburban grocery store for a number of reasons.	 Insurance costs may be higher in the ghetto.  There may be	less competition, so the ghetto store has a captive audience,	and so forth.		<a href="#209r">Return</a><p><a name="210"><li>One study found that 16,900 jobs in the steel	industry would be saved by a particular protectionist policy,	but implementation of that policy would destroy 52,400 jobs in	the industries that use steel, for a loss/gain ratio of 3.1 to	1.  Arthur Denzau, How Import Restraints Reduce Employment,	Publication No. 80, Center for the Study of American Business,	Washington University, St. Louis, 1987.		<a href="#210r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Computer-Trade-Policy.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
