<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Korea Japan Protectionism</TITLE>	<META Name="Author" CONTENT="Robert W. McGee,Yeomin Yoon">		<META Name="Keys"		CONTENT="Galambos,government,coercion,capitalism,			trade,Bedeman,environmentalism,poverty,export,			import,keyword,voluntary restraint,super 301,hypocrisy			MFA,VRA,dumping">			<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Second Edition</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Dumont-Essays.html">Dumont Essays Page</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, July 28<BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Korea-Japan-Protectionism.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, July 28, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h2>Dumont Institute Essays</h2></center><hr><p>These essays have been published with the permission of the individualauthors. If you wish you may contact Dr. McGee at the <a href="mailto:info@dumontinst.com">Dumont Institute</a> toobtain information on the organization or comment on this essay.</p><hr noshade><center><h4>Policy Analysis No. 16 - 1996, July</h4><H3>A Discussion of Protectionist Trade Policiesin the USA, Japan and Korea</H3><hr><h4>Robert W. McGee</h4><h4>Yeomin Yoon</h4></center><hr><p>The Dumont Institute for Public Policy Research, 236 Johnson Avenue,Dumont, NJ 07628     Telephone: (201) 501-8574    e-mail:info@dumontinst.com   http://www.dumontinst.com</p><hr noshade><h4>1. The Present Japanese-American Trade Policy</h4><p><a name="1r"></p><h4>A.  Introduction<a href="#1">[1]</a></h4><p><a name="2r"><a name="3r"></p><p>	Hardly a day goes by that the national press does not have atleast one article about trade relations with Japan.  The articlesgenerally take a somber tone, and discuss things like trade imbalances,protectionism, Japanese unwillingness to compromise, and thepossibility that the United States (or Japan) might retaliate forsomething the Japanese (or United States) either did or failed to do.Japan has accused the United States of reneging on its pledge to lowertariffs on electronics and other goods, and has threatened to retaliateby narrowly targeting U.S. exports of computer components<ahref="#2">[2]</a>  A U.S. trade official said that the U.S. wastargeting items that are made almost exclusively in Japan so that othercountries would not be adversely affected by the U.S. policy<ahref="#3">[3]</a><p><a name="4r"><a name="5r"></p><p>	But even selective targeting can be harmful to U.S. interests.<ahref="#4">[4]</a> Domestic companies that use Japanese parts in theirproducts stand to be adversely affected if U.S. trade policy causes theprice of these parts to increase or, worse yet, to make Japaneseproducts unavailable. For example, Tech Data Corp., a wholesaledistributor of microcomputer hardware and software, sells products thatcontain as much as 30% Japanese parts.  Steven Raymund, its chairmanand chief executive officer, has said that "If we can't get their[Japanese] products anymore, it's going to bring our industry to itsknees."<a href="#5">[5]</a><p><a name="6r"></p><p>	What they often fail to point out is that American consumerslike Japanese products because they are often cheaper than Americanproducts and of a higher quality as well.  And they fail to discuss thereasons why Japan can undersell domestic companies.  These reasons,according to one commentator at least, include a lower cost of capital,differences in national savings rates and a lower level of governmentborrowing (Japan doesn't have massive budget deficits, so privateborrowing is not crowded out by government borrowing needed to financethe deficit.)<a href="#6">[6]</a><p><a name="7r"></p><p>	The tone of the press reports often makes it sound like tradeis war instead of voluntary exchange.  The Japanese have been accusedof "invading" American shores with their cheap (and high quality)products.  Their goods are "flooding" the market.  They are "dumping"their products on us.  Senator Donald Reigle has stated: "Thecontinuing Japanese attack on our basic industries is another PearlHarbor.  The time has come to close America's door to the flood ofJapanese imported products."<a href="#7">[7]</a>  This "trade as war"mentality might lead one to conclude that someone can win a trade war. But such is not the case.  All parties lose because of higher prices,reduced trade and selection of products.	<h4>B. The Trade Deficit Mentality </h4><p><a name="8r"><a name="9r"></p><p>	One of the most popular topics regarding trade policy with Japan isthe fact that Japan has a large trade surplus with the United States. Press reports usually take the position that an increase in Japan'strade surplus is something to be alarmed about, and a reduction iscause for celebration.  The popular press uses language such as: "Japansaid its trade surplus ballooned again in January, a development thatis likely to aggravate tensions with the U.S.<a href="#8">[8]</a>  Theobvious conclusion to be drawn is that Japan's trade surplus is goingto cause some kind of harm to the U.S. economy.<a href="#9">[9]</a></p><p><a name="10r"></p><ul>	<p>	The figures don't bode well for relations with Washington, coming on	the heels of the failed U.S.-Japan trade talks and U.S. charges	that Japan has violated a pact to open its cellular phone market.	Washington has said Japan may face trade	sanctions.<a href="#10">[10]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="11r"></p><p>	The press also occasionally points out that Japan has a tradesurplus with other Asian countries as well as the European Union, whichmay lead one to conclude that Japan is a worldwide trade bully.<a href="#11">[11]</a><p>	The belief that trade deficits are bad and trade surpluses aregood is based on the eighteenth century mercantilist philosophy.  Andalthough the view that trade deficits are bad has been refuted for morethan a hundred years, the belief is still will us, and has a stronginfluence on present-day trade policy.  Adam Smith has the followingcomment:</p><p><a name="12r"></p><ul>	<p>	Nothing ... can be more absurd than this whole doctrine of the balance	of trade ... When two places trade with one another, this doctrine	supposes that, if the balance be even, neither of them either	loses or gains; but if it leans in any degree to one side, that	one of them loses, and the other gains in proportion to its	declension from the exact equilibrium.  Both suppositions are	false ... that trade which, without force or constraint, is naturally	carried on between any two places, is always advantageous ...	to both.<a href="#12">[12]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="13r"></p><p>	It is unrealistic to expect Japan and the United States tohave a zero trade balance.  For one thing, Japan has about half thepopulation of the United States.  That means that, in order to have azero trade balance, every Japanese citizen would have to buy twice asmuch from the U.S., on a per capita basis, as U.S. citizens buy fromJapan.  That is not likely to happen regardless of what kind of tradepolicy we adopt.  And it is of no importance.  California residentsprobably buy more from Arizona, in total, than Arizona residents buyfrom California, since the population of California is much more thanthe population of Arizona.  Yet there is no movement in Congress toforce Arizonans to buy more California products.  I run a trade deficitwith the local grocery store because I buy more from it than it buysfrom me.  Yet we are both prospering.<a href="#13">[13]</a>  The wholeconcept of viewing a trade deficit as bad is sheer idiocy.  It is basedon the mistaken belief that trade is a zero-sum game.  If one partywins, the other must necessarily lose.  But trade is a positive-sumgame because both parties gain.  Otherwise, they would not trade.<p><a name="14r"></p><p>	Interestingly enough, part of the trade deficit the UnitedStates has with Japan is the result of short-sighted U.S. trade policy. Special interest groups such as the seamen's unions and domesticshipbuilding companies lobbied Congress to pass a law that requiresAlaskan oil producers to use high-cost American tankers to carry theircargo to uneconomic domestic ports first, before they can transport oilto a foreign country.  Japan produces no oil of its own.  Whatever oilit has it must purchase from some foreign oil producer.  But becauseAmerican oil is high-cost oil (due to this law), the Japanese find itcheaper to buy their oil from other countries that have lower transportcosts.  Had the Alaskan oil producers been allowed to ship their oildirectly to Japan instead of first shipping it to some other Gulf orwestern U.S. port, they could have sold enough oil to Japan to fullywipe out the trade deficit we have with Japan.<a href="#14">[14]</a><p><a name="15r"><a name="16r"></p><p>	U.S. policymakers also shot themselves in the foot when theyallowed domestic lumber interests to dictate lumber policy.  In 1968,Congress passed a law requiring that all logs harvested on federal land(65% of all logs) first be processed in an American mill before export. But Japan has its own mills and does not need processed lumber.  So itbuys raw lumber from Canada and other countries instead of the UnitedStates.<a href="#15">[15]</a>  Environmentalists like the ban becauseof the mistaken belief that limiting logging will preserve naturalresources (they forget that lumber is a renewable resource).  Lumbermills like the ban because they think it will induce Japan to havetheir logs processed in the United States.  Private forest owners likethe ban because they are not subject to it.<a href="#16">[16]</a><p><a name="17r"></p><p>	There are a number of other problems with allowing trade balancesto influence policy.  For one, it is not at all clear that a deficit isbad and a surplus is good.  Throughout much of the nineteenth centurythe United States had a negative balance of trade as well as more orless continuous rapid growth.  During the depression years of the1930s, we had a trade surplus.  One reason why a trade balance isnegative is because a rapidly expanding economy consumes more than itproduces.  It needs foreign products to continue its expansion.  Ratherthan being a sign of poverty, trade deficits can be a sign of healthand wealth, as economists have been pointing out for years.<ahref="#17">[17]</a><p>	Yet in spite of the evidence, and the logic, policymakers andthe press continue to talk about the trade deficit is though it weresomething that should be reduced.  One international economist whoshould know better says the following:</p><p><a name="18r"></p><ul>	<p>	We have an extraordinary nonmeeting of minds on the trade issue:	The Japanese don't feel they are responsible for the U.S. trade	deficit. The U.S. feels the Japanese are responsible.  But anybody	with experience in doing business with Japan knows their markets	aren't as open to us as ours are to them....One of the few levers the	U.S. can use to put pressure on Japan is to cause the dollar to	depreciate against the yen.<a href="#18">[18]</a>	</p></ul><p>	Ironically, much of what this economist says is true.  In asense, the Japanese are not responsible for the U.S. trade deficit.  Isit their fault that they have just half the population of the U.S.? Should they be forced to buy twice as much, per capita, from Americansas Americans buy from them?  On the other hand, Japan is partlyresponsible for the deficit because their markets are not as open asours.  But American manufacturers also manufacture products that theJapanese don't want, such as cellular telephones tuned to the wrongfrequency and gas guzzling cars that have the steering wheels on thewrong side.  But even if everything this economist says is true, itdoes not follow that we have to put pressure on the Japanese to reducethe deficit because the deficit is an irrelevant statistic.  All thatreally matters is that consenting adults be allowed to enter intovoluntary exchange.  And raising trade barriers prevents them fromdoing that.	<h4>C. Antidumping</h4><p><a name="19r"><a name="20r"></p><p>	The U.S. antidumping laws have been used on numerous occasions topressure Japanese companies to raise the prices they charge to Americanconsumers or to punish them for selling at prices that are deemed to betoo low.  In the last few years, antidumping or countervailing dutyactions have been initiated against Japanese makers of all-terrainvehicles,<a href="#19">[19]</a> aspherical ophthalmoscopy lenses,automobiles, benzyl paraben, bimetallic cylinders,  brass sheet andstrip, butt-weld pipe fittings, color picture tubes, commercialmicrowave ovens, copier toner, distribution systems, drafting machines,dry film photoresist, erasable programmable read only memories,flat-rolled carbon steel products, forged steel crankshafts, granularpolytetrafluoroethylene resin, gray portland cement and cement clinker,high-information content flat panel displays, industrialnitrocellulose, laser light-scattering instruments, light-dutyhydrostatic transmissions, malleable cast-iron pipe fittings,mechanical transfer presses, minivans, new steel rails, nitrile rubber,offshore platform jackets and piles, personal word processors,polyethylene terephthalate film, sheet and strip, professional electriccutting, sanding/grinding tools, salmon gill fish netting, silicafilament fabric, stainless steel butt-weld pipe fittings,thermostatically controlled appliance plugs, probe thermostats, 3.5"microdisks and media, and unfinished mirrors.  This paper does notpermit a full discussion of the harmful effects that antidumping lawshave on an economy.  However, this topic has been explored elsewhere.<a href="#20">[20]</a></p><h4>D.  Auto Industry Protectionism</h4><p><a name="21r"><a name="22r"><a name="23r"><a name="24r"></p><p>	The Japanese Voluntary Export Restraint (VER) program of theearly 1980s added more than $1,114 to the options-adjusted price of anew Japanese car and transferred approximately $2 billion from Americanconsumers of Japanese cars to dealers and producers.<ahref="#21">[21]</a>  It also generated $166.4 million in efficiencycosts.<a href="#22">[22]</a>  All to protect at most 1,500 domesticauto jobs.<a href="#23">[23]</a>  That comes to more than $1.4 millionfor every job saved.<a href="#24">[24]</a>  It would have been muchcheaper to pay each displaced auto worker $50,000 or $100,000.<p><a name="25r"><a name="26r"><a name="27r"></p><p>	A Brookings Institution study found that voluntary exportrestrictions on automobiles cost American consumers about $14 billionin 1984, while U.S. auto manufacturers gained $9 billion in profits,for a deadweight loss of $5 billion.<a href="#25">[25]</a>  Anotherstudy estimated the annual cost to be $16.75 billion.<ahref="#26">[26]</a> Because the supply of autos was cut, the unit pricewas able to rise by almost one-third.<a href="#27">[27]</a>  Domesticauto dealers were able to raise their prices because of the reducedJapanese competition.<p><a name="28r"></p><p>	Another factor that affected auto prices was upgrading.  WhenJapan got hit with quotas, Japanese automakers increased the size,horsepower and amount of luxury equipment on the autos it sent to theU.S. market, which added $1,500 to the cost of the average Japanesecar.<a href="#28">[28]</a>  Another interesting effect of imposingquotas on Japanese autos is the effect it had on the domestic autoindustry.  Because of the quotas, Japanese auto manufacturers found itmore enticing to locate plants in the United States, thus avoiding thequotas and giving domestic automakers even more competition, which isthe exact opposite effect that the quotas were intended to have. 	<h4>E. Exchange Rate Manipulation</h4><p><a name="29r"></p><p>	Another tool of protectionism that the United States has used ismanipulation of the exchange rate.  A weak dollar makes foreign goodsmore expensive, thus making domestically produced goods more attractivepricewise.  One major difference between the exchange rate "tool" andthe other tools of protectionism such as tariffs, quotas and use of theantidumping laws is that exchange rate manipulation makes it moredifficult for all foreign producers to sell their goods in the UnitedStates, whereas use of the other tools can be more selective. Threatening to raise a tariff, reduce a quota or initiate anantidumping action can be targeted to a particular product, industry orcompany.  But shifting the exchange rate to make the dollar relativelyweak acts as a form of aggression against all foreign suppliers.  Manydomestic industries benefit, at least in the short-run, at the expenseof the consumers.<a href="#29">[29]</a><p><a name="30r"><a name="31r"><a name="32r"></p><p><a name="33r"><a name="34r"><a name="35r"></p><p><a name="36r"><a name="37r"><a name="38r"></p><p>	Using exchange rate manipulation to raise the prices of foreignproducts and punish foreign producers has been called the mostinsidious form of protectionism.<a href="#30">[30]</a>  TreasurySecretary Lloyd Bentsen has been leading the charge.<ahref="#31">[31]</a>  In December, 1992, the exchange rate was 124 yento the dollar.<a href="#32">[32]</a>  Since then, Secretary Bentsen hasbeen telling the financial press that he would like to see a strongeryen (which also means a weaker dollar).<a href="#33">[33]</a>  Currencytraders took the hint and started trading, which pushed up the value ofthe yen against the dollar. By April, 1993, the yen was trading atabout 113 to the dollar, which causes Japanese goods to rise in priceby 9 percent.<a href="#34">[34]</a>  Japanese trade officials becameextremely angry at the way Clinton administration officials had talkedup the yen.  Currency traders continued to sell dollars in theinternational market until the value of the dollar dropped to just over100 yen in August, 1993, which represented an 18% drop in just sevenmonths.  Some Japanese industry analysts estimate that barely one infifty Japanese exporters can make a profit in the U.S. market when theyen is trading at 115 to 117 to the dollar,<a href="#35">[35]</a> whichcomes as bad news for Japan's economy, which is already in arecession.<a href="#36">[36]</a>  Some of Japan's growing number ofbusiness bankruptcies are directly attributable to the manipulation ofthe yen.<a href="#37">[37]</a> For each of the first six months of1993, more than 1,000 Japanese firms have gone bankrupt.<ahref="#38">[38]</a> 	<p><a name="39r"></p><ul>	<p>	In a way, allowing the dollar to slide is the ultimate trade sanction,	affecting the Japanese economy indiscriminately.  Compared to	the stiletto of formal sanctions, the high yen is a sort of bomb in	the world of trade weapons. Auto makers stand to bear much of	the brunt.  Already, Japanese car makers are pricing their cars	some $2,000 more than U.S. models.  Mr. Toyoda and other auto	executives say that because of the yen's strength, there is no	end in sight to the gap.<a href="#39">[39]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="40r"><a name="42r"></p><p>	Secretary Bentsen is not the only U.S. official to be pleasedwith the dollar's slide relative to the yen.  Commerce DepartmentSecretary Ron Brown has also said that he is not displeased with theslide.<a href="#40">[40]</a>  And this recent case of dollar exchangerate manipulation is not the first time that rates have beenmanipulated for trade purposes.  The U.S. pulled a similar stunt in1987 to punish the Germans for their "sins."41  The result was a WallStreet crash. 	<p><a name="42r"></p><h4>F. Super 301<a href="#42">[42]</a></h4><p><a name="43r"></p><p>	The United States has decided to make use of Super 301 toforce Japan to open up its markets to U.S. products.<ahref="#43">[43]</a>  Super 301 is a weapon the U.S. can use to targetcountries that it deems are engaged in a pattern of unfair tradepractices.  If the targeted country does not change its ways within 18months, the U.S. could retaliate by imposing punitive tariffs ofJapanese imports.<p><a name="44r"><a name="45r"></p><p><a name="46r"><a name="47r"><a name="48r"></p><p>	Super 301 was passed by Congress in 1988 as part of the OmnibusTrade and Competitiveness Act<a href="#44">[44]</a> to force PresidentBush to get tough with countries that appeared to be unfair traders.<a href="#45">[45]</a>  The original targets of the law were Brazil, Indiaand Japan, each of which had its name placed on the Super 301 unfairtrade list.<a href="#46">[46]</a>  Brazil and Japan eventually gottheir names removed from the list and were not punished for theirprotectionist policies,<a href="#47">[47]</a> before the law expired in1990.<a href="#48">[48]</a><p><a name="49r"><a name="50r"></p><p>	Some trade experts claim that the President can get tough withintransigent countries through executive order without the need forCongress to pass another Super 301 law.<a href="#49">[49]</a>  But trade experts also pointout that such an approach could be counterproductive, since exercisingSuper 301, in whatever form, would cause nationalistic sentiment toincrease in Japan, thus undercutting the goal of reducing tradebarriers.<a href="#50">[50]</a><p><a name="51r"><a name="52r"><a name="53r"><a name="54r"></p><p>	Since 1974, when the original Section 301 became law, 78 cases havebeen brought against foreign governments by the United States.<a href="#51">[51]</a> Of these, only 13 have resulted in market openings,and those were generally minor.52  One of the more controversial Super301 cases launched against Japan involved Motorola, which went whiningto the U.S. government because it was not able to capture as large ashare of the Japanese cellular telephone market as it thought itdeserved.  Part of the problem was that the United States and Japan areon different frequencies.  The Japanese companies that export to theUnited States change the frequencies to meet U.S. specifications. Motorola ships phones that do not meet Japanese specifications.<a href="#53">[53]</a>  But that fact was totally ignored when the U.S.government threatened to slap sanctions on several hundred milliondollars worth of Japanese imports if the Japanese  didn't stop"discriminating" against foreign companies.<a href="#54">[54]</a><p><a name="55r"><a name="56r"><a name="57r"></p><p>	Another 301 case involved Japanese citrus quotas.  The Floridacitrus industry estimated that Japanese consumers could enjoy pricesthat were one-third lower if only Japan would remove its unfair tradebarriers.  The fact that the United States imposes a 40% tariff on theimportation of Brazilian orange juice was totally ignored.<ahref="#55">[55]</a>  In 1985, the United States forced Japan to controlits prices for semiconductors both in the U.S. and in other countries. As a result, semiconductor prices in the United States jumped by up to300%, creating a disaster for the U.S. electronics industry and leadingto the loss of as many as 11,000 domestic jobs at companies that usedsemiconductors.<a href="#56">[56]</a>  In 1985, the U.S. concluded acase to remove Japanese leather import quotas.  As part of the deal,the U.S. raised its tariffs on Japanese leather imports from 12% to40%.<a href="#57">[57]</a> 	<h4>G. The Hypocrisy of the United States Position</h4><p><a name="58r"><a name="59r"></p><p>	This "Super 301" mentality, aside from being irrational (cuttingoff one's nose to spite the face), is also hypocritical.  The UnitedStates is far from being a free trade bastion.<a href="#58">[58]</a> We erect numerous trade barriers ourselves, such as tariffs, quotas and"voluntary" trade restraints.  One commentator has said that our tradelaws "are simply a lynch law for foreign businesses."<ahref="#59">[59]</a>  Furthermore, we don't give foreign consumers whatthey want.  For example, Japanese cars have the steering wheel on theright side.  But American auto manufacturers don't make cars with thesteering wheel on the right side.  All the cars they ship to Japan havethe steering wheel on the left side.  And most of the cars we do shipto Japan are gas guzzlers compared to Japanese cars.  Furthermore,Consumer Reports shows that Japanese cars have a consistently lowerdefect rate. It is any wonder that the Japanese won't buy Americancars?<p><a name="60r"><a name="61r"></p><p>	Where U.S. companies make products that Japanese consumerswant, they do buy our products.  American music and tee-shirts sellwell in Japan. So do a wide range of products, including M&Ms,Snickers, Hall's cough drops, Clorets, Wrigley's gum, Polident,Kentucky Fried Chicken, Wendy's, McDonalds, Domino's Pizza, Johnson &Johnson products, Q-Tips, Band-Aids, Pampers, Colgate toothpaste,Gillette razors, Kleenex, Pedigree, KalKan and Gaines dogfood, Denny's,Shakey's Pizza, Dunkin' Donuts, Subway, Famous Amos, Mrs. Fields'cookies, Coke, Jolly Green Giant products, American tobacco products,Visa, MasterCard and American Express.<a href="#60">[60]</a>  Americantobacco companies have more freedom to advertise in Tokyo than they doin New York.<a href="#61">[61]</a><p><a name="62r"><a name="63r"><a name="64r"><a name="65r"><a name="66r"></p><p>	Six of the last eleven Japanese public supercomputer bids have beenawarded to American companies.<a href="#62">[62]</a>  But U.S. agencies"rarely, if ever, buy foreign supercomputers, partly because they knowsuch purchases will cause them political grief."<a href="#63">[63]</a>"U.S. government agencies have been called before congressionalhearings simply for inviting Japanese firms to bid on supercomputerwork."<a href="#64">[64]</a>  And U.S. hypocrisy is not limited tosupercomputers.  Various "Buy American"<a href="#65">[65]</a> and"domestic content"<a href="#66">[66]</a> laws require governments atall levels to give preference to U.S.-made products, even if thequality is lower or the price is higher.  If Japan had a Super 301 ofits own, it would find the United States guilty.<p><a name="67r"><a name="68r"><a name="69r"></p><p>	Various U.S. administrations have resorted to protectionistpolicies to protect a wide range of domestic industries from foreigncompetition.  President Reagan imposed a 100% tariff on certainJapanese electronics products in 1987 to punish the Japanese forselling their products to American consumers at low prices.<ahref="#67">[67]</a>  The Japanese were punished for failing to keeptheir microchip prices high, as they had promised.<ahref="#68">[68]</a>  The Reagan administration also slapped anadditional 45% tariff on Japanese heavy motorcycles as a favor toHarley Davidson.<a href="#69">[69]</a><p><a name="70r"><a name="71r"><a name="72r"></p><p>	Various "voluntary" restraint agreements, which are not voluntarybecause they require the Japanese government to restrict the exports ofcertain Japanese companies, have been used to protect the domesticauto,<a href="#70">[70]</a> textile<a href="#71">[71]</a> and steel<ahref="#72">[72]</a> industries over the years, at the expense ofconsumers, who must pay higher prices for both foreign and domesticproducts as a result.<p><a name="73r"><a name="74r"><a name="75r"></p><p>	U.S. trade hypocrisy is not limited to trade with Japan.  Itextends to all trading partners.  In 1990, the U.S. initiated a Section301 case against Canada for placing high tariffs and other restrictionson U.S. beer exports, ignoring the fact that many of our states andlocal governments place their own restrictions on alcohol shipments andsales.<a href="#73">[73]</a>  The U.S. forced Canada to impose a 15%export tax on its lumber because the Canadian government was supposedlysubsidizing the lumber industry.  But Canadian provincial governmentswere merely following many of the same practices as the U.S. ForestService.  The tax destroyed up to 16,600 U.S. jobs and added more than$1,000 to the cost of building a house in the United States.<ahref="#74">[74]</a>  In 1988, the U.S. launched a Section 301 caseagainst Korea for having quotas on beef imports, while ignoring thefact that the U.S. has its own beef import quotas that cost Americanconsumers $873 million annually in higher prices, according to aDepartment of Agriculture estimate.<a href="#75">[75]</a><h4>2. The Present Korean-American Trade Policy</h4><h4>A.  Introduction</h4><p><a name="76r"><a name="77r"><a name="78r"><a name="79r"></p><p>	Since the end of World War II, South Korea and the UnitedStates have had a special relationship.  At first, the U.S.-Korearelationship was dominated by their common military and foreign policyinterests, but in recent years, the trade relationship between the twocountries has gained more importance.  Korea is the USA's eighthlargest trading partner and the USA is the largest trading partner ofKorea.<a href="#76">[76]</a>  The trade relationship has grown inimportance primarily because of the rapid growth experienced by theKorean economy.  As one of the four newly industrialized countries inAsia -- the so-called "four Asian tigers" -- Korea has experienced inthe past quarter century extremely rapid economic growth on the basisof export-oriented industrialization.  Because of this growth, percapita GNP rose to $7,000 in 1992, compared to $80 per capita GNP in1961.<a href="#77">[77]</a>  In 1988, when South Korea sponsored a16-day, $3 billion festivity -- the 24th Summer Olympic Games --Fortune magazine called Korea "tomorrow's power house."<ahref="#78">[78]</a>  Korea's industrialization was so rapid andremarkably successful that it was proclaimed as "Asia's next giant" byAlice H. Amsden, a noted American economist.<a href="#79">[79]</a><p>	Much of Korea's economic growth is attributable to very rapidgrowth in its exports. The United States has been instrumental inKorea's export-led growth because the United States has been the singlemost important market for Korea's exports.  Korea's rapid economicgrowth has, in turn, produced a burgeoning demand for imported goodsand services, including those produced in the United States.	<h4>B. U.S. Trade Barriers to Korean Exports</h4><p><a name="80r"></p><p>	Although the United States is one of the world's most openeconomies ,<a href="#80">[80]</a> it still impeded trade in a number ofindustries through high tariffs and/or import quotas.  In addition tothese more traditional forms of protection, the United States has beenemploying administered production more frequently and with greaterimpact over the past decade. 	<h4>C. Tariffs</h4><p><a name="81r"><a name="82r"></p><p>	While the average U.S. tariff is quite low and now stands atabout 5%, tariffs remain quite high in a several industries, especiallythose with labor intensive production, such as textiles, apparel,footwear, and leather products.  The average U.S. textile tariff is 11%while the average apparel rate is 20% (and ranges up to 35%).<ahref="#81">[81]</a>  Footwear tariffs vary between 10% and 40%. Leather goods such as gloves, handbags and luggage have tariffs rangingfrom 12% to 16%.<a href="#82">[82]</a>  Unfortunately for Korea, itscomparative advantage vis a vis the United States lies at least in partin the production of these types of goods.  Its apparel, textile,footwear, and leather product exports accounted for nearly 40% of itstotal U.S. exports in 1991.  There can be little doubt that these highrates impede Korean exports to the U.S. significantly. 	<h4>D. Quantitative Restrictions</h4><p><a name="83r"><a name="84r"></p><p>	The United States also limits imports with quantitativerestrictions such as the Multifiber Arrangement (MFA) and voluntaryrestraint agreements (VRAs).  The MFA is used by the developedcountries to limit developing country textile and apparel imports.  TheUnited States and Korea have negotiated several bilateral agreementssince the inception of the MFA in 1974.  Under the bilateralagreements, Korea's exports of textile and apparel to the United Statesare allowed to grow at an annual one percent rate.<ahref="#83">[83]</a>  Korea's share of textiles and apparal exports tothe United States has declined as a result, because exports of othercountries to the United States are allowed to grow more rapidly. Between 1989 and 1991, Korea's share of all U.S. imports subject to theMFA has declined to 8.5% from 11%.<a href="#84">[84]</a><p>	The second quantitative restraint involves Korea's steel industry. In the mid-1980s, the United States negotiated "voluntary" restraintagreements (VRAs) with the major steel exporting countries, includingKorea.  Before the expiration of these VRAs in March, 1992,negotiations began on a multilateral steel agreement (MSA) that wouldapportion global steel trade.  As of this writing, MSA negotiationshave been unsuccessful.  In the absence of an agreement, morerestrictive measures are likely to be taken, thus impeding the world'ssteel trade.	<h4>E. Antidumping and Antisubsidy Duties</h4><p><a name="85r"></p><p>	Other non-tariff barriers deployed by the United States to restrictimports are antidumping and antisubsidy duties.  Antidumping andantisubsidy duties are imposed against imports that are determined tobe dumped (i.e., sold at "less than fair value") or subsidized.  Thereis a widespread view among international trade experts that the purposeof antidumping and antisubsidy duties imposed by the United States isto protect domestic industries from import competition.<ahref="#85">[85]</a>  This is particularly true of antidumping duties. In theory, dumping by foreign firms should be penalized if its purposeis to limit competition by driving other producers out of the domesticmarket. Under this circumstance, antidumping duties are welfareimproving because they help maintain competition.  In practice,however, it is widely recognized that dumping rarely occurs and thusantidumping duties are welfare reducing rather than welfare enhancing.<p><a name="86r"></p><p>	Over the past decade, a number of Korean industries have been hitwith antidumping actions for allegedly selling their products in theUnited States at prices that are too low.  Products that Koreaallegedly dumped on the United States market include automotivebatteries,<a href="#86">[86]</a> ball bearings, brass sheet and strip,cast-iron pipe fittings, cold-rolled carbon steel,  color picturetubes, computer chips, flat-rolled carbon steel, industrial belts,motorcycle batteries, nitrocellulose, offshore platform jackets andpiles, photo albums, polyethylene terephthalate film, sheet and strip,stainless steel butt-weld pipe fittings, steel pipes and tubes, sweaters, telephone systems and subassemblies, tubular goods, andwelded stainless steel pipes.<p><a name="87r"></p><p>	A major question to be answered is whether these antidumping actionswere justified, and if not, what should be done to prevent thecontinuation of an improper antidumping policy. Space does not permit afull discussion of this point.  However, this question has beenaddressed in depth elsewhere.<a href="#87">[87]</a>	<h4>F.  Korean Protectionism</h4><p><a name="88r"></p><p>	While the United States trade policy toward Korea is protectionist,the same can be said of Korean trade policy toward the United States.Korea has also been guilty of a number of protectionist trade policiesthat affect trade both with the United States and other countries.<a href="#88">[88]</a><p>	The U.S. trade deficit with Korea was $1.6 billion in 1994, anincrease of more than $700 million over the previous year.  And whiletrade deficits don't matter, the fact that they have been increasing asled policymakers in the United States to become concerned, and to focusmore attention on trade with Korea.<p>	In early 1994, Korea concluded its five-year autonomous tariffreduction, which resulted in reducing its average tariff rate to 7.9%,compared to a previous average of 12%.  However, tariffs on manyhigh-value agricultural and fishery products continue to be high, asmuch as 25% or more.  Imports of distilled spirits are subject to atariff of 15% or 30% plus an "education tax."   This tax, which is 120%as of 1995, is scheduled to be reduced to 100% in 1996.<p>	U.S. producers continue to complain that the combination of Korea'stariffs and non-discriminatory value-added taxes for agricultural andmanufactured products are often sufficiently high to either keepimports out of the Korean market or raise import prices touncompetitive levels.  Although the Uruguay round of GATT will reducethese tariffs eventually, more than half of the tariffs supposedlyreduced by GATT will not go into effect for ten years, which provideslittle consolation for foreign producers that want to do business inKorea (or numerous other countries, for that matter).<p>	However, there is also good news.  Korea abolished all tariffson many or all products in the paper, toy, semiconductor, steel andpharmaceutical industries in early 1995.  It also reduced tariffs onchemicals and scientific equipment.  The less than good news is thatKorea is harmonizing its tariffs on textile and apparel products withU.S. rates, which can be as high as 35%.  This puts American textileand apparel producers in the curious position of accusing Korea ofbeing protectionist when these same U.S. producers support identicaltariffs rates for similar U.S. products.<p>	Korea also imposes import quotas on certain products, especially inthe agricultural and fishery industries.  Some items are banned fromimportation completely.  Some of these barriers are being liberalized. However, a GATT panel ruled in 1989 that Korea's quantitativerestrictions on beef imports were not in compliance with its GATTobligations.  The United States and Korea have since concluded a seriesof bilateral agreements on the importation of beef to remedy thissituation.  These agreements call for increasing minimum access levelsannually, guaranteeing direct commercial relations between Koreanretailers and distributors and foreign suppliers, and guaranteeing thatgrowing volumes of beef will be sold in the private sector rather thanthrough a government corporation.  By the year 2001, Korea is supposedto remove all non-tariff barriers to the importation of beef, includingstate trading.<p>	The Uruguay Round also requires Korea to start phasing out itsimport restrictions on a number of agricultural items of interest toU.S. exporters, including beef jerky and offals, frozen pork, frozenchicken, oranges, orange juice, dairy and whey products, apples andapple juice, grapes and grape juice and other fruit juice. Restrictions remain on a number of other agricultural products,however.  Korea is also required to lift its import ban on rice.  The1995 quota of 51,307 tons is to rise to 205,228 tons by 2004.  Itsorange quota of 15,000 tons in 1995 is to rise to 25,000 tons in 1997,and will increase by 12.5% per year thereafter.  Korea has more than 18laws that allow various government ministries to ban or place quotas onvarious products.  Korea has agreed to phase-out these laws as part ofthe Uruguay Round.<p>	Korean import clearance procedures have been criticized forbeing slow and arbitrary.  It often takes considerable time to getimported items out of port.  Timeliness is especially critical foragricultural products, since long delays can result in making the goodsunmarketable.  It does little good to liberalize import restrictions ifthe products rot in port before clearance.  Agricultural imports inKorea take between two and four weeks to get clearance, compared to aclearance time of three to four days in other Asian countries. "Luxury" goods such as chocolate products, cosmetics and electronicstake as long as three to five weeks to get clearance even though theyare not subject to any restrictions under Korean law.  The Ministry ofHealth and Welfare and the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry andFisheries impose numerous barriers to entry that effectively prohibitaccess or inhibit port clearance.<p>	Another oft-cited secondary barrier involves Korea's policiesconcerning standards, testing, labeling and certification.  Regulationsthat are supposedly intended to protect health and safety often deviatesubstantially from international practices in both method andsubstance.  These practices do not appear to be based on any riskassessment or scientific basis, and are often drafted in ways thataffect only imported goods.	<h4>3. Concluding Observations</h4><p>	Numerous studies have found that protectionist policies resultin a deadweight loss -- there are more losers than winners.  But somegroups do gain by the passage of a protectionist policy.  And it isthese gainers who have the ear of the legislature.  Economists pointout that this phenomenon can exist because the benefits areconcentrated but the costs are diffused.  This fact makes it profitablefor the special interests who stand to gain or lose by a particularpolicy to concentrate their efforts on persuading the legislature tosee things their way.  For example, protectionist policies might causethe price of a shirt to be $5 higher than would be the case undertotally free trade, requiring millions of consumers to pay $5 more forevery shirt they buy.  But such a small cost does not make itworthwhile to organize a consumer march on Washington because the cost,in terms of time, effort and out-of-pocket dollars, just is not worthit.  Consumers are acting rationally when they do not protest the factthat some protectionist policy causes them to pay $5 more for a shirt. Indeed, the vast majority of consumers probably do not even know thatgovernment policy results in higher shirt prices.<p><a name="89r"><a name="90r"><a name="91r"></p><p>	But domestic producers know.<a href="#89">[89]</a>   And itis in their interest to make sure that such policies are continued,since abolishing tariffs, quotas or other trade regulations would costthem money and jobs, at least in the short run.  So special interestshave a built-in advantage when it comes to influencing trade policy andconsumers have a built-in disadvantage.  This tendency to use the forceof government to feather one's own nest at the expense of the generalpublic is called rent-seeking.<a href="#90">[90]</a>  But"rent-seeking" is really a misnomer.  A better term might bebooty-seeking, since it is really an attempt to gain at the expense ofsomeone else rather than by voluntary exchange.<a href="#91">[91]</a><p><a name="92r"><a name="93r"><a name="94r"></p><p>	Protectionism can take many forms.  Tariffs act like salestaxes in that they raise the price of imported goods.  But tariffs havea disparate impact because they are levied only on imports, which givesdomestically produced products a built-in advantage.  Quotas have asimilar effect.  In the sense that they prevent goods from crossing theborder, they cause prices to be higher than would be the case underfree competition.<a href="#92">[92]</a>  Economists would describe thisphenomenon by pointing out that the supply has been cut back, therebyleading to an increase in price.<a href="#93">[93]</a>  Antidumping andcountervailing duty laws also have been used to protect domesticproducers from foreign competition.<a href="#94">[94]</a><p><a name="95r"></p><p>	Protectionism also has nonmonetary costs. Adopting a protectionistpolicy to aid this industry or that actually destroys more jobs than itsaves.  For example, President Reagan's voluntary restraint agreement,which was aimed at reducing steel imports from 26 percent to 22 percentof domestic sales, caused employment in the steel industry to increaseby 17,000.  But this policy caused some adverse effects as well.Employment in the industries that used steel declined by 52,000 becausethe higher prices they had to pay for steel cut into their profitmargins, forcing them to lay off employees and reduce the number of newjobs that would otherwise have been available.<a href="#95">[95]</a> Thus, about 3.1 jobs were destroyed (or never permitted to come intoexistence) for every job saved by the restraint policy.<p>	Present trade policy in countries that adopt protectionist policiesis a form of class conflict because it pits the special interestsagainst consumers.  Special interests such as the steel industry, DRAMchip industry, and so forth, are using the force of government tofeather their own nests at the expense of consumers and the generalpublic, which tears at the fabric of government.  Rather than being aservant of the people, government is being used as a tool of specialindustrial interests to reduce competition and raise prices.  Thismisuse of governmental power reduces social harmony.<p>	Another nonmonetary cost that consumers must bear is the reduction inchoice that results when quotas or dumping duties are imposed offoreign goods like Korean DRAM chips or steel.  If goods are preventedfrom entering the country, consumers might have to settle for theirsecond or third choice, which reduces their utility.  This cost isintangible, but it is real.  The loss in utility is the differencebetween the utility they would gain by purchasing their first choice ofproduct and the utility they receive by settling for their second orthird choice.<p>	The arguments put forth so far have been mostly utilitarian. Consumers stand to lose utility and reduce their standard of livingbecause protectionist trade policies raise the cost they must pay forgoods or reduces their consumer choice by preventing certain productsfrom entering the country.  We have also argued that our protectionisttrade policies are bad because they destroy more jobs than they save,which is also a utilitarian argument.<p><a name="96r"><a name="97r"></p><p>	But the utilitarian approach suffers a fatal flaw because itignores individual rights.<a href="#96">[96]</a>  A utilitarian wouldapprove of a policy if the good outweighs the bad.  If the evidenceshowed that protectionism saves more jobs than it destroys, autilitarian would conclude that the protectionist policy is good andwould advocate its adoption, while ignoring the fact that such a policyprevents consumers from buying the products of their choice.  By whatmoral right does some government prevent consenting adults fromentering into contracts or prevent them from trading the fruits oftheir labor?  In effect, protectionist policies serve to transferwealth from consumers to domestic producers. Consumers have theirproperty and contract rights violated whenever they are prevented fromtrading their property as they see fit.  Their rights are beingsacrificed so that domestic producers, who would not otherwise be ableto make a sale, can make a sale.  Protectionist policies are merelyforms of redistribution.<a href="#97">[97]</a>  But whereas wegenerally think of redistributionist policies as transferring wealthfrom the rich to the poor, protectionist redistribution transferswealth from consumers to producers.<p>	Rather than argue that a particular policy is good if the beneficialeffects outweigh the detrimental effects, as a utilitarian would do, wesuggest that a better approach to use to determine whether a particularpolicy is good or bad is to determine whether anyone's rights areviolated.  A policy that violates property or contract rights ismorally bankrupt even if the good outweighs the bad because it uses theforce of government to allow one individual or group to live at theexpense of another.  It allows some individual or group to act as aparasite by using the force of government, which is an immoral andillegitimate use of governmental power.<p>	The only proper trade policy is one of total, immediate andunilateral free trade.  The economic literature is clear that a policyof free trade -- even if it is unilateral -- benefits the vast majorityof the population.  Free trade expands the quantity of goods availableto consumers and keeps prices low, thus increasing the standard ofliving for practically everyone.  The studies that have been madeindicate that a policy of free trade also results in a net employmentgain, as free trade allows more jobs to be created than those that aredestroyed.  But more importantly, a policy of free trade is the onlypolicy that does not violate the rights of consenting adults to enterinto contracts and trade the fruits of their labor -- their property --for the property of others.  Free trade is the only policy that doesnot use the force of government to reduce social harmony.<p>	Some commentators take the position that free trade is the bestpolicy, but that we cannot afford to open our borders unilaterally. But such arguments are off the mark.  Domestic consumers will benefitimmediately under a unilateral free trade regime because the absence oftariffs, quotas and the chilling effect of the antidumping andcountervailing duty laws will result in price declines, thus resultingin an increase in the standard of living.  While it would be nice ifother nations followed our lead, it is not necessary.  Unilateral freetrade will result in an increase in the standard of living no matterwhat other nations do.  And waiting for other nations to agree toreduce their trade barriers -- or worse yet, to threaten retaliation ifthey do not reciprocate -- will only postpone the fall in prices thatwould result from a unilateral free trade regime.  Taking the positionthat we cannot afford to drop our trade barriers until others do isakin to arguing that we must continue to shoot ourselves in the foot aslong as other nations shoot themselves in the foot.  Any nation thatadopts protectionist policies shoots itself in the foot, or ratherreduces the standard of living for the vast majority of its people. The fact that they do does not mean that we have to, too.<p>	An earlier version of this Policy Analysis appeared in theInternational Journal of Korean Studies, Vol. 2 (1995), 45-74.  Nothingwritten here is to be construed as necessarily reflecting the views ofthe Dumont Institute or as an attempt to aid or hinder the passage ofany bill before Congress</p><hr>	<h4>End Notes:</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>Although this section is primarily about	Japanese-American trade policy, the underlying theories discussed in	this part could equally be applied to Korea and other	countries.		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>Japan Accuses U.S. of Breaking Pledge on Tariff,	Wall Street Journal, February 17, 1994, A3, col. 1.		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>Ibid.	<a href="#3r">Return</a><p><a name="4"><li>There are other ways to punish Japan for allegedly	unfair trade practices.  One way that has been suggested is to	draw out the inspections of Japanese imports.  Bob Davis and Jacob M.	Schlesinger, Trade War? Unlikely, But Shifting Relations Do Increase	the Risk, Wall Street Journal, February 18, 1994, A2, col. 6.		<a href="#4r">R