3 Rutgers Law	Journal 137-67 (1991); James Lawrence Kenworthy, The	Constitutionality of State Buy-American Laws, 50 University of	Missouri at Kansas City Law Review 1-20 (1981); Caroline J. Hasson,	Constitutional Law -- State "Buy American" Statute Held a Valid	Exercise in Economic Protectionism, 36 Villanova Law Review	905-26 (1991).		<a href="#65r">Return</a><p><a name="66"><li>For more on the theory and practice of domestic	content, see Bob Davis and Jacob M. Schlesinger, Dispute on Parts For	Cars Stalls Talks on Trade, Wall Street Journal, February 7,	1994, A2; Michael P. Maxwell, Formulating Rules of Origin for	Imported Merchandise: Transforming the Substantial Transformation	Test, 23 George Washington Journal of International Law & Economics	669-93 (1990); N. David Palmeter, Pacific Regional Trade	Liberalization and Rules of Origin, 27 Journal of World Trade	49-62 (October, 1993); Richard G. Dearden and David Palmeter,	The Honda Decision: Rules of Origin Turned Upside Down, Free	Trade Law Reports, Issue 32A, June, 1992, 513-23; Frédéric P.	Cantin and Andreas F. Lowenfeld, Rules of Origin, the Canada-U.S.	FTA, and the Honda Case, 87 American Journal of International	Law 375-90 (July, 1993).		<a href="#66r">Return</a><p><a name="67"><li>Sheldon L. Richman, The Reagan Record on Trade:	Rhetoric vs. Reality, Cato Institute Policy Analysis No. 107, May 30,	1988, 1, 5.		<a href="#67r">Return</a><p><a name="68"><li>Ibid. at  5.	<a href="#68r">Return</a><p><a name="69"><li>Ibid. at  6.	<a href="#69r">Return</a><p><a name="70"><li>Ibid. at 9; Michael F. Bryan and Owen F. Humpage,	Voluntary Export Restraints: The Cost of Building Walls, Economic	Review, Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland 17-37 (Summer, 1984);	Jose A. Ibanez, Robert A. Leone and Stephen A. O'Connell, Restraining	Auto Imports: Does Anyone Win? 2 Journal of Policy Analysis and	Management. 196-219 (Winter, 1983); Robert W. Crandall, The Effects	of U.S. Trade Protection for Autos and Steel, 1 Brookings Papers on	Economic Activity 271-88 (1987); Elias Dinopoulos and Mordechai	E. Kreinin, Effects of the U.S.-Japan Auto VER on European Prices and	on U.S. Welfare, 70 Review of Economics & Statistics 484-91	(1988).		<a href="#70r">Return</a><p><a name="71"><li>Carl B. Hamilton, Jaime de Melo and L. Alan	Winters, Who Wins and Who Loses from Voluntary Export Restraints? The	Case of Footwear, 7 World Bank Research Observer 17-33 (January,	1992); Carl Hamilton, An Assessment of Voluntary Restraints on	Hong Kong Exports to Europe and the USA, 53 Economica 339-50 (1986);	Thomas Grennes, The Collision Course on Textile Quotas, Cato	Institute Policy Analysis No. 140, September 12, 1990.		<a href="#71r">Return</a><p><a name="72"><li>Robert W. Crandall, The Effects of U.S. Trade	Protection for Autos and Steel, 1 Brookings Papers on Economic	Activity 271-88 (1987); United States International Trade Commission,	The Effects of the Steel Voluntary Restraint Agreements on U.S.	Steel-Consuming Industries, Report to the Subcommittee on Trade	of the House Committee on Ways and Means on Investigation No. 332-270	Under Section 332 of the Tariff Act of 1930, USITC Pub. 2182,	May, 1989; Arthur Denzau, The Unlevel Playing Field: How High	Steel Prices and Trade Protection Help Deindustrialize America,	Working Paper 128, Center for the Study of American Business,	Washington University, St. Louis, August, 1989; José A. Méndez,	The Short-Run Trade and Employment Effects of Steel Import	Restraints, 20 Journal of World Trade Law 554-66 (September-October,	1986).		<a href="#72r">Return</a><p><a name="73"><li>James Bovard, A U.S. History of Trade Hypocrisy,	Wall Street Journal, March 8, 1994, A16, col. 3.		<a href="#73r">Return</a><p><a name="74"><li>Ibid. at A16, col. 4.  While this portion of the	paper discusses U.S. protectionist policies toward Japan, Japan	also has protectionist policies.  For a discussion of some of	these policies, and the effects they have, see Yoko Sazanami, Shujiro	Urata and Hiroki Kawai, Measuring the Costs of Protectionism in	Japan (Washington, DC: Institute for International Economics,	1995).		<a href="#74r">Return</a><p><a name="75"><li>James Bovard, A U.S. History of Trade Hypocrisy,	Wall Street Journal, March 8, 1994, A16, col. 4.		<a href="#75r">Return</a><p><a name="76"><li>Korea Economic Report, September, 1993, at 22, col. 1.	<a href="#76r">Return</a><p><a name="77"><li>Ibid.	<a href="#77r">Return</a><p><a name="78"><li>Louis Kraar, Korea: Tomorrow's Powerhouse, Fortune,	August 15, 1988.		<a href="#78r">Return</a><p><a name="79"><li>Amsden's book, entitled Asia's Next Giant: South	Korea and Late Industrialization, was published in 1989 and	became one of the best-sellers in the field of economic	development.		<a href="#79r">Return</a><p><a name="80"><li>According to the estimate by the Korean Central	Daily, one of the leading newspapers in Seoul (with daily circulation	of 8 million copies), the "degree of import liberalization" as	of the end of 1992 was 78% for the United States, 58% for Korea, 54%	for Japan, 80% for Germany, 88% for Singapore, and 89% for Hong	Kong, respectively.  Joong Ang Ilbo, The Korean Central Daily,	September 22, 1993, at 2, row 5.		<a href="#80r">Return</a><p><a name="81"><li>United States International Trade Commission, The	Economic Effects of Significant U.S. Import Restraints, Phase	I: Manufacturing, USITC Publication 2222, 1989, at 4-2 and 4-3.		<a href="#81r">Return</a><p><a name="82"><li> Ibid., at 2-7.	<a href="#82r">Return</a><p><a name="83"><li>United States International Trade Commission,	Operation of the Trade Agreements Program, 41st report, USITC	Publication 2317.		<a href="#83r">Return</a><p><a name="84"><li>United States International Trade Commission,	Operation of the Trade Agreements Program, 43rd report, USITC	Publication 2554.		<a href="#84r">Return</a><p><a name="85"><li>See Down in the Dumps: Administration of the Unfair	Trade Laws (Richard Boltuck and Robert E. Litan eds. 1991).		<a href="#85r">Return</a><p><a name="86"><li> For the specifics of each of these antidumping	cases, contact the United States International Trade Commission	in Washington, DC.		<a href="#86r">Return</a><p><a name="87"><li>Yeomin Yoon, Korean Dumping in the United States: A	Fictitious Crime? International Journal of Korean Studies (1994),	40-58.		<a href="#87r">Return</a><p><a name="88"><li>For a summary of some of these policies, see United	States Trade Representative, 1995 National Trade Estimate Report on	Foreign Trade Barriers, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington,	DC, 1995, at 209-222.		<a href="#88r">Return</a><p><a name="89"><li>For expositions on the topic of protectionism in	the textile industry, see William R. Cline, The Future of World	Trade in Textiles and Apparel, 2d ed. (1990); James Bovard, The	Fair Trade Fraud 35-64 (1991).		<a href="#89r">Return</a><p><a name="90"><li>Rent-seeking might be defined as seeking special	privileges or protection from government or getting others to pay for	your benefits.  For expositions of rent-seeking behavior as applied	to trade policy, see Anne O. Krueger, The Political Economy of	the Rent-Seeking Society, 64 American Economic Review 291-303 (1974),	reprinted in International Trade: Selected Readings, 2d ed. 291-309	(Jagdish N. Bhagwati ed. 1987); Robert E. Baldwin, Rent Seeking	and Trade Policy: An Industry Approach, 120 Weltwirtschaftliches	Archiv 662-76 (1984), reprinted in Robert E. Baldwin, Trade Policy in	a Changing World Economy 121-36 (1988).  For detailed discussions of	the theory of rent-seeking in general, see Gordon Tullock, Private	Wants, Public Means: An Economic Analysis Of The Desirable Scope Of	Government (1970; 1987); Gordon Tullock, The Economics of Special	Privilege and Rent Seeking (1989); Public Choice (Julien Van	Den Broeck ed. 1988); The Political Economy of Rent-Seeking (Charles	K. Rowley, Robert D. Tollison and Gordon Tullock eds. 1988); Towards	a Theory of a Rent-Seeking Society (James M. Buchanan, Robert	Tollison and Gordon Tullock, eds. 1980).		<a href="#90r">Return</a><p><a name="91"><li>Walter Block makes this point in Freedom, Democracy	and Economic Welfare (Michael A. Walker ed. 1988), Proceedings	of an International Symposium, at 208.  At 207-208, Block	states:	<p>	I would like to put in a plea with regard to another phrase that	has been used around this room.  I don't like the concept "rent	seeking." As far as I am concerned, "rent" is an ancient and	honourable tradition, part of the free enterprise system.  Rent	is a contract between consenting adults, and there is nothing evil or	vicious or depraved about rent.  Yet, when we use the phrase	"rent seeking" and apply it to what we do, we demean the word	"rent" and lose its meaning.  Let's call it "booty seeking" or	"theft seeking" or "loot seeking" or something else of this sort to	distinguish it from legitimate forms of "rent seeking."  I am	trying to save the word "rent" from this association with what	is really, in effect, theft.  So I put in a plea that we try to	adopt this usage.	</p>		<a href="#91r">Return</a><p><a name="92"><li>For a general discussion of tariffs and quotas, see	any general economics textbook.  For more detailed discussions,	see any text on international economics, including John Jackson, The	World Trading System: Law and Policy of International Economic	Relations (1989); Richard Pomfret, International Trade: An	Introduction to Theory and Policy (1991); Shelagh Heffernan and	Peter Sinclair, Modern International Economics (1990); Bela Balassa,	Comparative Advantage, Trade Policy and Economic Development (1989). 	For general discussions of protectionism, which includes discussions	of tariffs, quotas and non-tariff barriers to trade, see Jan Tumlir,	Protectionism: Trade Policy in Democratic Societies (1985);	Louis E.V. Nevaer and Steven A. Deck, The Protectionist Threat	to Corporate America: The U.S. Trade Deficit and Management Responses	(1989); James Bovard, The Fair Trade Fraud (1991); I.M. Destler	and John S. Odell, Anti-Protection: Changing Forces in United	States Trade Politics (1987); Melvyn B. Krauss, The New	Protectionism: The Welfare State and International Trade (1978);	Jagdish Bhagwati, Protectionism (1988); Gary Clyde Hufbauer, Diane T.	Berliner and Kimberly Ann Elliott, Trade Protection in the	United States: 31 Case Studies (1986).		<a href="#92r">Return</a><p><a name="93"><li>As the quantity of a particular good available	increases, price decreases.  If the supply is cut back, the	price increases.  Common sense would lead us to this conclusion. 	This "law of supply" is also discussed in any general economics	text.		<a href="#93r">Return</a><p><a name="94"><li>For some treatises on the antidumping and	countervailing duty laws, see James Bovard, The Fair Trade	Fraud 107-195(1991); Down in the Dumps: Administration of the	Unfair Trade laws (Richard Boltuck and Robert E. Litan eds.	1991); Michael S. Knoll, United States Antidumping Law: The Case for	Reconsideration, 22 Texas International Law Journal 265-90(1987);	Note, Managing Dumping in a Global Economy, 21 George Washington	Journal of International Law & Economics 503 (1988).		<a href="#94r">Return</a><p><a name="95"><li>Arthur Denzau, How Import Restraints Reduce	Employment, Pub. No. 80, Center for the Study of American Business,	Washington University, St. Louis, 1987, at 5-6; Richard B. McKenzie,	The American Job Machine 148-9 (1988).		<a href="#95r">Return</a><p><a name="96"><li>Another flaw with the utilitarian approach is that	it is impossible to precisely measure the gains and losses from	adopting any particular policy.  Economics textbooks use an imaginary	unit called "utils" to illustrate how utilitarian theory can be	applied to particular situations, but utils do not exist in the	real world.  Choices cannot be quantified, but only ranked in	order of desirability.  And the utility of one consumer cannot	be measured against the disutility of another.  For Murray N.	Rothbard's critique of the utilitarian approach, see For a New	Liberty 15-16, 26-27, 30, 40 (1978); The Ethics of Liberty	10-11, 210-13 (1982); and Man, Economy and State 260-8 (1970).		<a href="#96r">Return</a><p><a name="97"><li>For a moral critique of the redistributionist	philosophy, see Bertrand de Jouvenel, The Ethics of Redistribution	(1952).		<a href="#97r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Korea-Japan-Protectionism.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
