thored oredited more than 30 books and monographs and has written more than 300articles and reviews for a variety of professional and scholarlyjournals in economics, law, accounting, taxation and philosophy.</p><hr noshade><p><a name="1r"><a name="2r"><a name="3r"></p><p><a name="4r"><a name="5r"><a name="6r"></p><p><a name="7r"><a name="8r"><a name="9r"></p><p>	Various studies have estimated the annual cost of product liabilitylitigation alone (not to mention other kinds of liability litigation)in the United States to be between $80 and $117 billion.<a href="#1">[1]</a>  That's more than the combined gross nationalproducts of Bolivia, Chile, Costa Rica, Ecuador, El Salvador,Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua, Panama, Paraguay, Peru and Uruguay<a href="#2">[2]</a>  or about equal to the annual profits of the top 200corporations in America.<a href="#3">[3]</a> But that's only the directcost. When you add the indirect costs that are incurred in order toavoid liability -- needless testing, excessive liability insurancecosts, etc. -- the total could reach as much as $300 billion a year<ahref="#4">[4]</a> -- the combined gross national products of Austria,Luxembourg, the Philippines, Portugal and Switzerland.<a href="#5">[5]</a>  Yet a major study by the Brookings Institution foundthat litigation does not lead to increased product safety.<a href="#6">[6]</a>  While safety has increased over the past twodecades, it is because of market pressures and government regulations,not litigation.<a href="#7">[7]</a>  And the potential costs oflitigation are causing some companies to halt research and theintroduction of new products and manufacture products abroad, whichdestroys jobs, stifles economic growth and causes America to lose itscompetitive edge.<a href="#8">[8]</a> Liability costs in the UnitedStates are fifteen times higher than in Japan and twenty times higherthan in Europe.<a href="#9">[9]</a>  How can America compete with thiskind of drag on the economy?<p><a name="10r"><a name="11r"><a name="12r"><a name="13r"></p><p>	As a result of this system, consumers lose in several ways.They can't  always get the products they want because some products aretaken off the market because of excessive litigation risks.  Forexample, WEPCO had to close because it could not get liabilityinsurance to insure the driving aids that it manufactured for thehandicapped.<a href="#10">[10]</a>  And even when products areavailable, manufacturers pass the litigation costs on in the form ofhigher prices when they can get away with it.  It is as if thegovernment placed a product liability tax on every product.  In thecase of the DPT vaccination, for example, 40 percent of the cost goesto cover liability costs.<a href="#11">[11]</a> And some products areactually less safe as a result of the present product liability laws. For example, Volvo will not sell its cars with built-in safety seats inthe USA because it might open itself up to liability, although thissafety feature is available in the cars it sells in other countries.<a href="#12">[12]</a>   One reason why health care costs are goingthrough the roof is because some medical specialists have to pay up to$250,0000 a year in malpractice premiums.<a href="#13">[13]</a><p><a name="14r"><a name="15r"><a name="16r"></p><p>	But what is really outrageous is what happens to the moneythat defendants have to pay.  According to a study by the GeneralAccounting Office, more than half of it goes to attorneys rather thanvictims.<a href="#14">[14]</a> For complicated cases like asbestoslitigation, the lawyers' slice can be two-thirds.<a href="#15">[15]</a> For Superfund pollution cases, they get up to 80%.<ahref="#16">[16]</a><p><a name="17r"><a name="18r"></p><p>	There are several reasons for the high legal costs.  For one,it takes years to get a case through the legal system.  The averagesuit takes more than a year, and in Chicago, the civil case backlog iseight years.<a href="#17">[17]</a>   And all the while, the legalmeters are running.  One partner in a large law firm bragged to a lawschool audience that, for one long case, "My firm's meter was runningall the time -- every month for 14 years."<a href="#18">[18]</a><p><a name="19r"><a name="20r"><a name="21r"><a name="22r"></p><p>	It is in the best interest of lawyers to keep the meter runningand they use several means to do it.  One of the most effective ways toprolong a trial and wear down the opposition is by the abuse of"discovery," the rule that allows courts to demand practically everydocument that a company has on file that has anything remotely to dowith the case.  Courts have asked auto companies to submit everycomplaint about faulty headlights that they have ever had, forexample.<a href="#19">[19]</a>  In one IBM antitrust suit, discoveryproduced 64 million pages of documents and took five years.<ahref="#20">[20]</a>   There are practically no limits to discovery, andlawyers often use it not to get at the truth but to use it as a weaponto wear down the opposition and prolong the trial.  In fact, discoveryaccounts for 60% of the time and money that is spent on lawsuits.<ahref="#21">[21]</a>  In 1988, a Louis Harris poll of lawyers found thatalmost one half of those surveyed admitted that they use discovery todrive up their own fees.<a href="#22">[22]</a>  Attempts have been madeto limit discovery, but those attempts have failed because of the veryvociferous efforts of the plaintiff's bar.<p><a name="23r"><a name="24r"></p><p>	Litigation costs are high for other reasons as well.  Contingencyfees,<a href="#23">[23]</a> which allow lawyers to take a percentagerather than get paid on an hourly basis, encourage lawyers to takecases they would never consider on a straight fee basis.  And clientsare much more apt to let a lawsuit proceed if they are liable to payonly if they win.  And in the American system, each side pays its ownlegal fees, which encourages frivolous suits because there is nodownside risk for plaintiffs.  Attempts have been made to limit oreliminate contingent fees and make lawyers charge by the hour, butthese attempts have failed.  Attempts to adopt the "English rule,"<ahref="#24">[24]</a> by which the loser pays for all legal fees of boththe winner and the loser, have also failed.<p><a name="25r"><a name="26r"></p><p>	The potential awards for winning a lawsuit also make suingmore appealing.  The system of joint and several liability makes ittempting to go after "deep pockets," companies that have a lot of cash,even though they may be responsible for only a small portion of thedamage. And the possibility of receiving punitive damages also providesincentive to go forward with a lawsuit, since the award received may befar in excess of the amount of damages actually suffered.  With allthese factors working together, it is no wonder that the number ofproduct liability suits has exploded.  In the federal court system, thenumber of such suits jumped 1,183% between 1974 and 1990 -- to about19,000.<a href="#25">[25]</a>  And that is only the tip of the iceberg. About 95-96% of all product liability cases are settled out of court,and thus are not included in these statistics.<a href="#26">[26]</a>And each of the 50 state court systems also hear product liabilitycases -- and they each have different sets of rules.  As a result,litigators engage in forum shopping, the practice of looking around forthe court system that is most likely to give them the result they want. Efforts to establish a standard federal rule have failed, againbecause of the efforts of the plaintiff's bar.  Attempts to limitpunitive damages and replace the joint and several liability rules withproportional liability also have failed because of the efforts of thispowerful group.<p><a name="27r"><a name="28r"><a name="29r"></p><p>	But such litigation is not exploding on a worldwide basis, just inthe United States.  Britain has less than 500 product liability cases ayear.<a href="#27">[27]</a>  Holland has had just five cases since1940.<a href="#28">[28]</a> Malpractice insurance premiums cost lessthan 10% as much in Europe as in the United States.<ahref="#29">[29]</a><p><a name="30r"><a name="31r"></p><p>	Who are these people who are resisting tort reform, and whyare they doing it?  One might guess without much effort.  It is aclassic case of what Public Choice economists call rent-seeking, theuse of government to feather one's own nest at the expense of someoneelse.<a href="#30">[30]</a> In this case, it is the plaintiff's barthat is feathering its own nest, and it is at the expense of everyoneelse, consumers as well as producers.  The present tort liabilitysystem is retarding economic growth and destroying jobs, not to mentionlives.  Yet the plaintiff bar insists that the present tort system isin the public interest, protects the little guy and costs nothingbecause insurance companies are picking up the tab, and that is whatinsurance companies are in business for.  Yet they don't explain why,if insurance companies are making a killing by charging high premiums,so many of them are pulling out of some risk areas.<ahref="#31">[31]</a>  And they fail to point out that little guys -- momand pop businesses -- can be driven out of business by a singlelawsuit.  Even if they win the suit, five or more years down the road,they still have to pay the lawyers, and that can be enough to bankruptthem.<p><a name="32r"><a name="33r"><a name="34r"><a name="35r"><a name="36r"></p><p><a name="37r"><a name="38r"><a name="39r"><a name="40r"><a name="41r"></p><p>	The plaintiff bar, led by the Association of Trial Lawyers ofAmerica (ATLA) and various Ralph Nader groups, wants the system to stayjust the way it is.  If a Coca-Cola delivery truck collides with aschool bus, like it did in Alston, Texas a few years ago, they want tobe able to take $25 million of the $67.5 million settlement forthemselves -- that amounts to between $10,000 and $40,000 an hour -- inthe name of protecting the little guy.<a href="#32">[32]</a>   Yet, aslaw professor Lester Brickman points out, "These lawyers are stealingmoney for doing nothing more than getting clients to sign on theline."<a href="#33">[33]</a>  According to Brickman's estimate,<ahref="#34">[34]</a> plaintiff's attorneys earn a whopping $10 billionon personal injury suits alone.<a href="#35">[35]</a> With that kind ofvested interest, it is no wonder that they are pouring money intoCongressional campaigns so that those members of Congress who supportthe status quo will be re-elected.  One lawyer in Florida paid $600,000for an ad campaign to defeat a referendum to cap medical malpracticeawards.<a href="#36">[36]</a>  More than a dozen California lawyers andlaw firms each contributed $100,000 to $300,000 to defeat a ballotinitiative to curb a plaintiff's ability to collect.<a href="#37">[37]</a>  Shortly aftervice president Dan Quayle blasted the tort system at the American BarAssociation convention in 1991, California lawyer William Lerachinvited the San Diego trial lawyers to attend a $1,000 a plate dinnerat his home (at which seven U.S. Senators would be present) to raisefunds to fight tort reform.<a href="#38">[38]</a>  According to WalterOlson, an expert on the liability crisis, "In some states they [triallawyers] constitute the entire fund-raising arm of the Democraticparty."<a href="#39">[39]</a>   According to one estimate, the ATLAPolitical Action Committee, various law firm PACs and individualattorneys gave the Democratic party and individual candidates perhapsas much as $10 million or more for the 1989-90 election cycle.<ahref="#40">[40]</a> If true, that might make trial lawyers the largestsingle-issue giver in national politics.<a href="#41">[41]</a><p><a name="42r"><a name="43r"><a name="44r"></p><p><a name="45r"><a name="46r"><a name="47r"></p><p>	In 1989, Ohio Senator Howard Metzenbaum received $123,000from personal injury law firms as far away as Albany and Houston <ahref="#42">[42]</a>.  At the state level, the trial bar raises money tofinance the campaigns of candidates to oppose advocates of no-faultlaws.<a href="#43">[43]</a>  When Jim Florio was elected governor ofNew Jersey, somewhere between $700,000 and $1 million of his campaignwar chest came from the trial bar, in a campaign where total spendingwas limited to $1.7 million.<a href="#44">[44]</a>  The Louisiana TrialLawyers Association spent at least $1.2 million on the 1991 electionsthere and bragged to its membership that 30 of the 39 members of thenew state Senate got there with LTLA backing. And in the LouisianaHouse, 22 LTLA candidates won and seven lost.<a href="#45">[45]</a> And the Louisiana legislature is now pushing through a bill that willlegalize the awarding of punitive damages.<a href="#46">[46]</a>  Yetthey insist they are defenders of consumer rights and aren't in it forthe money.<a href="#47">[47]</a><p><a name="48r"><a name="49r"></p><p>	Ralph Nader has been especially good at camouflaging theself-interest of trial lawyers.  It is more than mere coincidence thatNader never endorses any consumer causes that conflict with theinterests of trial attorneys.  Nader has been getting large sums ofmoney from the trial bar since at least the early 1970s.<ahref="#48">[48]</a>   Yet he continues to deny it.  According to RobertJoost, who was the Senate Commerce Committee's chief counsel during theno-fault auto insurance debates in the 1970s, trial attorneys regularlypay tithes to Nader, the national ATLA PAC and the state ATLAorganization out of their cut of court settlements.<ahref="#49">[49]</a><p><a name="50r"><a name="51r"><a name="52r"></p><p>	Nader and company do not hesitate to use their influence tokill consumer legislation when it would reduce the plaintiff bar'sincome.  Numerous consumer groups supported Senator Robert W. Kasten,Jr.'s 1986 amendment that would have required plaintiff's attorneys tooffer to work on an hourly basis and to disclose their hours worked.But Public Citizen and Congress Watch -- both Nader groups -- opposedit.<a href="#50">[50]</a>  Nader has even resorted to smear campaigns(such as calling Senator Kasten a drunk)<a href="#51">[51]</a> whendoing so would help the plaintiff bar. Every election year, he blastsRep. Donald L. Ritter, one of the strongest proponents of tort reformin Congress, and has accused him of being anti-consumer because hetakes contributions from nuclear energy interests.  Ritter calls thisapproach dishonest, since he comes from a coal and steel district.<ahref="#52">[52]</a><p><a name="53r"><a name="54r"><a name="55r"></p><p>	The plaintiff bar can bring much pressure to bear against membersof Congress who don't see things their way, and they don't hesitate touse it.  ATLA threatened to raise $500,000 in PAC money to defeatSenator Russell B. Long if he continued to support no-fault.  And itmade the threat public in order to intimidate other no-faultsupporters.<a href="#53">[53]</a>  Yet it never threatened SenatorErnest F. Hollings, who bragged that his contingency case winnings madeit possible for him to finance his own campaigns for office and that hewasn't going to let anyone put limitations on it.<a href="#54">[54]</a> When the no-fault vote was taken, six moderate Republicans quicklychanged their votes and opposed the bill. Coincidentally, they changedtheir positions shortly after receiving contributions from the ATLAPAC.<a href="#55">[55]</a><p>	From the mounds of evidence that have accumulated over the pastfew decades, it is clear that the plaintiff bar is the majorbeneficiary of the present tort system -- as well as its creator.  Theybenefit at the expense of the rest of us -- consumers as well asproducers.  The plaintiff bar has been able to accumulate the bestlegislators that money can buy to hold back the floodgates of reform. And they have the audacity to say that they are doing it to protect thelittle guy.  In fact, they are feathering their own nests, and it istime that they stopped.  A fair system would compensate victims fortheir wrongs without treating them like lottery winners, and would notpunish producers of goods and services when they have done no wrong. It's time to restore justice and fairness to the tort system inAmerica.<p>	An earlier version of this paper was published by the WashingtonLegal Foundation in August, 1992.  Nothing written here is to beconstrued as necessarily reflecting the views of the Dumont Instituteor as an attempt to aid or hinder the passage of any bill beforeCongress.</p><hr>	<h4>End Notes:</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>Product Liability Coordinating Committee, Product	Liability Fairness: The Time is Now, (Arlington, VA: Product	Liability Coordinating Committee, n.d.), 6. Hereinafter referred to	as Product Liability Fairness.  The $117 billion figure is also	mentioned in Order in the tort, The Economist, Special Section:	The Legal Profession, July 18, 1992, 8-13, at 13.  This study	was conducted by Tillinghast, an insurance industry consultant,	in 1987.  A 1991 Brookings Institution study estimates the	annual cost to be $100 billion.  The President's Council on	Competitiveness estimated the cost to be $80 billion.		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>The gross national products for each of these	countries are (in billions of dollars): Bolivia (4.6), Chile (19.4),	Costa Rica (4.2), Ecuador (9.4), El Salvador (4.1), Guatemala	(9.6), Honduras (4.4), Nicaragua (2.1), Panama (4.2), Paraguay	(7.4), Peru (19.6) and Uruguay (7.5), for a total of $96.5 billion.	The World Almanac and Book of Facts 1991 (1990).		<a href="#2r">Return</a><p><a name="3"><li>Peter W. Huber cites this figure