f theactual agreement reveals something far different.  Indeed, any tradeagreement that is more than 22,000 pages in length might lead one toquestion why an agreement that demolishes trade barriers has to be solong.<p>	While the new GATT agreement does reduce tariffs and eliminatesmost quotas, the long-phase out period in many cases guaranteesprotected markets for as long as a decade or more—and that means higherprices for consumers.  The tariffs that were abolished outright were onproducts that don't account for much trade anyway.  The"liberalization" of textile quotas is almost a joke.  Quotas werelifted immediately on products that accounted for only 16% of the totalvolume of 1990 imports.  Quotas on the remaining 84% of products willbe lifted over a ten-year phase-out period—17% after 3 years, 18% moreafter 4 more years, and the remaining 49% three years later, or tenyears after the GATT agreement was signed.<p>	For agriculture, nontariff barriers are converted into tariffs,which are then added to existing tariffs.  These tariffs are then cutby 6% a year for 6 years (or 24% over ten years in the case of adeveloping country).  But most import-sensitive products are subjectonly to a 15% reduction over six years.  New negotiations, which are tobegin by the year 2,000, could slow the pace of change.<p>	Tariffs on industrial products are reduced an average of 38%. The five-year phase-in started January 1, 1995.  But tariffs ontextiles and apparel will remain at above-average levels.<p>	Perhaps the most protectionist component of the new GATT roundis the expansion of antidumping laws.  Before GATT, only about 40countries had antidumping laws.  Now, all 123 signatories to the GATTagreement can use antidumping laws to punish foreign producers.<p>	The theory behind the antidumping laws is simple.  A foreign producerthat sells its product in a domestic market for less than the cost ofproduction can be found guilty of dumping.  Likewise, a foreignproducer that sells its product in the domestic market for a lowerprice than it sells for in some foreign market can also be found guiltyof dumping.  The reason for these rules is to prevent predatorypricing—the practice of selling far below cost with the intent ofdriving competitors out of business, then raising prices to recoupprior losses.<p>	The problem with this theory is that it never works that way inpractice.  Numerous studies over the past few decades have attempted tofind predatory pricing.  For the most part, they have found none.  Inthe few cases where predatory pricing might have existed, it alwaysbenefitted consumers, the group that is supposedly protected by theantitrust laws.<p>	Predatory pricing just doesn't make economic sense.  It isirrational.  That's why it doesn't exist.  Producers that try to drivetheir rivals out of business by selling below cost lose money on everysale.  As they gain market share, their losses accelerate.  Even ifthey are successful in driving every competitor out of the market, theonly way to keep them out is by keeping prices so low that newpotential competitors are not tempted to enter the market.<p>	That's not to say that companies never sell their productsbelow cost.  Sometimes they have to.  The fresh flower market is aperfect example.  We import fresh flowers from Latin America and Europein vast quantities.  They arrive fresh, but after some time they startto wilt.  When that happens, the flower mongers sell them for whateverthey can get.  It's better to sell a wilting flower for somethingrather than nothing.  But when they do sell at a deep discount, itlooks like they are dumping because they are selling below cost.  Yetselling below cost is the rational thing to do in this case, since thealternative is to throw the flowers away and get nothing for them.  Fordumping purposes, though, the Commerce Department treats a wiltingflower in New York as the equivalent of a fresh flower in Amsterdam. And since the wilting New York flower sells for less than a freshAmsterdam flower, the foreign producer is guilty of selling for lowerprices in the United States than in a foreign market, and is thusguilty of dumping, even though there was no predatory intent.<p>	The burden of proof in antidumping cases is much less than inantitrust cases involving a charge of predatory pricing.  Whereas in anantitrust case, the plaintiff must generally prove predatory intent, inan antidumping case the plaintiff (the Commerce Department) need onlyfind that the domestic price was lower than the price charged on someforeign market, or that the domestic price was lower than the cost ofproduction.<p>	Over the last decade or so, more than 90 percent of the antidumpingcases that were brought in the United States resulted in a finding ofdumping.  That's because it's easy to find at least a few cases wherethe foreign producer sold its product on some foreign market for morethan it charged in the U.S. market.  In fact, it's possible to be foundguilty of dumping even if the foreign producer charged the same pricein all markets, because of exchange rate fluctuations.  For example, ifa German producer makes something for 2DM in January, when the exchangerate is 2DM = $1, and sells it in the United States in June, when theexchange rate is 2DM = $0.90, it is selling below cost, since the costof production was $1 and the selling price in the domestic market wasonly $0.90.<p>	Foreign producers can be found guilty of dumping whenever theysell in the United States for less than the average worldwide sellingprice, too.  Let's say that a certain foreign product sells for a rangeof prices between $8 and $12, with the average price being $10.  Anyproducts sold in the United States for less than $10 are considereddumped, because the Commerce Department compares average foreign pricesto specific domestic prices.  Sales above $10 are ignored.  So if theaverage price in the United States is identical to the $10 averageworldwide price, about half of the sales in the United States will bebelow the average worldwide price, and thus subject to dumpingpenalties.<p>	From a consumer perspective, there is nothing wrong with dumping. Dumping, were it does exist, results in lower prices, which benefitsthe general public.  Yet the present antidumping laws, which are beingspread as the result of GATT, penalize foreign producers when they sellat low prices in domestic markets.  Thus, the law places a chillingeffect on price competition.  Foreign producers tend to keep theirprices high in order to avoid or minimize a charge of dumping.  Studieshave estimated that the antidumping laws cost U.S. consumers billionsof dollars each year.  The new GATT agreement not only did nothing tocorrect this situation, but made things worse by spreading theantidumping laws to the 123 countries that signed the GATT agreement. As other countries apply the antidumping laws, American companies willoften find themselves on the receiving end, since the United States isone of the largest exporters in the world.<p>	At best, antidumping laws benefit a few domestic producers atthe expense of the general public.  At worst, they can be used as aweapon against American companies that try to sell their productsabroad.  Antidumping laws merely protect consumers from low prices. Thus, they should not be reformed.  They should be abolished, thesooner the better.</p><hr><p>Nothing written here is to be construed as necessarily reflecting theviews of the Dumont Institute or as an attempt to aid or hinder thepassage of any bill before Congress.  An earlier version of this PolicyBrief appeared in <i>Commerce</i>, September, 1995, pp. 48-50.</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server<sup>&copy;</sup> please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/GATT-Protectionist-Club.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
