ENT, The Use of Local Ordinances to Combat Private	Club Discrimination, 23 U.S.F.L. Rev 473-98 (1989); L. McKenna,	Freedom of Association or Gender Discrimination? New York State	Club Association v. City of New York, 38 Am. U.L. Rev. 1061-92	(1989); New York State Club Association v. City of New York:	Ending Gender-Based Discrimination In Private Clubs -- Are	Associational Rights Still Protected? 16 Hastings Const. L. Q. 	623-37 (1989).		<a href="#51r">Return</a><p><a name="52"><li>108 S.Ct.  at 2228.	<a href="#52r">Return</a><p><a name="53"><li> Id.	<a href="#53r">Return</a><p><a name="54"><li>Id.	<a href="#54r">Return</a><p><a name="55"><li>Roberts v. United States Jaycees, 468 U.S. 609, 104	S.Ct. 3244, 82 L.Ed.2d 462 (1984).		<a href="#55r">Return</a><p><a name="56"><li>Board of Directors of Rotary Int'l v. Rotary Club,	107 S.Ct. 1940, 95 L.Ed.2d 474 (1987).		<a href="#56r">Return</a><p><a name="57"><li>108 S.Ct. at 2228, 2232-2235.	<a href="#57r">Return</a><p><a name="58"><li>Id.	<a href="#58r">Return</a><p><a name="59"><li> Local Law No. 63 of 1984, § 1, App. 14-15, cited	at 108 S.Ct. at 2230.		<a href="#59r">Return</a><p><a name="60"><li>Id.	<a href="#60r">Return</a><p><a name="61"><li>Space does not permit a detailed analysis of this	argument. However, it should be pointed out that this argument	suffers from a number of weaknesses. For example, it might be	said that just because the market does not provide a good or service	does not mean that the government should provide it. The argument	that the government should provide what the market does not is	a non sequitur.   For a detailed discussion of the theory of	market failure, see  The Theory of Market Failure: A Critical	Examination (T. Cowen ed. 1988).  For a devastating critique	that completely dismantles the public goods argument, see D.	Schmidtz, The Limits of Government: An Essay on the Public	Goods Argument (1991). Another argument that does not hold up	to analysis is that government can provide goods or services cheaper	than the market.  If that were the case, governments all over	the world would not be rushing to privatize government functions. 	The many studies that have been done indicate that the market	can provide just about any good or service cheaper than government --	up to 100% cheaper in some cases.  For details, see Privatization &	Development (S. Hanke ed. 1987); R. Fitzgerald, When Government	Goes Private: Successful Alternatives to Public Services (1988);  R.	poole, Cutting Back City Hall (1980); T. Ohashi and T. Roth,	Privatization: Theory and Practice (1980); J. Goodman, Privatization	(1985); E. Savas, Privatizing the Public Sector: How To Shrink	Government (1982).		<a href="#61r">Return</a><p><a name="62"><li>M. Friedman, Capitalism & Freedom 25 (1962).	<a href="#62r">Return</a><p><a name="63"><li>Utilitarian arguments -- the greatest good for the	greatest number -- suffer from several philosophical weaknesses. For	instance, they tend to ignore or discount minority rights.  If	the majority decides on a certain rule, the minority must comply or	face the consequences. If the majority decides to elect a Hitler, the	minority has no recourse other than to live with it, move or	assassinate. Also, it is impossible to measure utility, since utility	is subjective and changes from person to person. There are a	number of other weaknesses inherent in the concept of utility.	For a good summary of these weaknesses, see M. Rothbard, Man,	Economy, and State 260-68 (1962; 1970).		<a href="#63r">Return</a><p><a name="64"><li>For a defense of the minimal (nightwatchman) state	that takes a natural rights approach, see R. Nozick, Anarchy,	State, and Utopia (1974).  For other detailed analyses of the	relationship between the individual and the state that take a natural	rights approach, see M. Rothbard, For a New Liberty (1973; 1978); M.	Rothbard, The Ethics of Liberty (1982).		<a href="#64r">Return</a><p><a name="65"><li>L. von Mises, Human Action 272 (1966).	<a href="#65r">Return</a><p><a name="66"><li>F. Bastiat, The Law 17 (1968). This work first	appeared in French in 1850 as a pamphlet, La Loi and was reprinted in	Sophismes Économiques, Vol. I, Oeuvres Complètes de Frédéric Bastiat,	4th edition 343-94 (1878).		<a href="#66r">Return</a><p><a name="67"><li>For a modern interpretation of Bastiat's views, see	D. Russell, Government and Legal Plunder: Bastiat Brought Up to	Date (1985).			<a href="#67r">Return</a><p><a name="68"><li>The Public Choice School of Economics refers to	this phenomenon of trying to live at someone else's expense as	rent seeking. For an exposition of this view, see G. Tullock,	The Economics of Special Privilege and Rent Seeking (1989); The	Political Economy of Rent-Seeking (C. Rowley, R. Tollison and	G. Tulock eds. 1988).  An approximate definition of rent seeking	might be "Seeking special privileges or protection from government or	getting others to pay for your benefits."		<a href="#68r">Return</a><p><a name="69"><li>F. Bastiat, The Law 21 (1968).	<a href="#69r">Return</a><p><a name="70"><li>For detailed discussions on this point, see R.	Nozick, Anarchy, State, and Utopia (1974); T. Machan, Individuals and	Their Rights (1989).		<a href="#70r">Return</a><p><a name="71"><li>Unfortunately, such takings are common and courts	have not generally ruled that such takings violate the takings	clause. For a detailed discussion of this point, see R. Epstein,	Takings: Private Property and the Power of Eminent Domain	(1985).		<a href="#71r">Return</a><p><a name="72"><li>The "public accommodations" argument, that you must	serve everyone if you are open to the public, is another positive	rights argument. Under a negative rights regime (which holds property	rights inviolate), you can serve anyone you want or refuse service to	anyone for any reason you want.		<a href="#72r">Return</a><p><a name="73"><li>This is not to say that there should be no laws	outlawing discrimination, but only that there should be no laws	preventing private discrimination. Obviously, government should	not be able to discriminate, since it should treat all citizens	equally. Thus, if a black gets on a government owned bus, he or	she has every right to be there and should not have to walk or	sit in the back. Likewise, the state university system in California	(which practices race norming) should not be able to admit	blacks when more qualified whites and orientals are refused	admittance. Equal protection means equal protection. Businesses	that engage in discriminatory practices have to pay a price for	their choice, as is pointed by Walter Block, The Economics of	Discrimination, 11 Journal of Business Ethics (1992), 241-254.		<a href="#73r">Return</a><p><a name="74"><li>It may also be unethical, or a sin, according to	some religions, but we will leave a discussion of these questions for	another day.		<a href="#74r">Return</a><p><a name="75"><li>It should also be pointed out that the market tends	to punish bigots, since refusing to serve someone results in a	loss of business, which adversely affects the bottom line. 	Thus, bigots may have to pay a price for their discrimination. 	Boycotts might also be used to punish such bigots, which could	result in the loss of nonblack business as well.		<a href="#75r">Return</a><p><a name="76"><li>A. Rand, The Virtue of Selfishness 116 (1964); Also	in The Ayn Rand Lexicon: Objectivism From A To Z 396 (H. Binswanger	ed. 1986).		<a href="#76r">Return</a><p><a name="77"><li>A. Rand, Capitalism: The Unknown Ideal 170 (1966). 	Also in The Ayn Rand Lexicon: Objectivism From A To Z 396 (H.	Binswanger ed. 1986).		<a href="#77r">Return</a><p><a name="78"><li>For more on this point, see M. Novak, Free Persons	and the Common Good (1989), especially 19-22.		<a href="#78r">Return</a><p><a name="79"><li>Political scientists would call these minorities	who gain control of an issue a "political elite."  Actually,	majorities do not rule even in a democracy. Rule is always by	some political elite. In a democracy, that political elite consists	of elected representatives and the special interest groups who	influence them. In a dictatorship of the proletariat, it is the	nomenklatura.		<a href="#79r">Return</a><p><a name="80"><li>J. Hospers, Libertarianism: A Political Philosophy	for Tomorrow 84 (1971).		<a href="#80r">Return</a><p><a name="81"><li>For more on this point, see R. McGee, Mergers and	Acquisitions: An Economic and Legal Analysis, 22 Creighton L.	Rev.  665-93 (1988/89).		<a href="#81r">Return</a><p><a name="82"><li>For more on this point, see R. McGee, The Trade	Policy of a Free Society 19 Cap. U. L. Rev. 301-41 (1990);  J.	Bovard, The Fair Trade Fraud: How Congress Pillages the Consumer and	Decimates American Competitiveness (1991).		<a href="#82r">Return</a><p><a name="83"><li>J. Bovard, The Farm Fiasco (1989).	<a href="#83r">Return</a><p><a name="84"><li> D.T. Armentano points out that most antitrust	suits are filed not by the Justice Department but by competitors, who	see their market share eroded by more efficient competitors.	They want government to come to their aid and they use the antitrust	laws as a club to beat up the competition. The result is less	aggressive competition and higher prices, all in the public interest.	For more on this point, see D. T. Armentano, Antitrust and Monopoly:	Anatomy of a Policy Failure (1990); D. T. Armentano, Antitrust	Policy: The Case for Repeal (1986); D. T. Armentano, The Myths	of Antitrust (1972).  At the turn of the century, railroad magnates	came to Congress, hat in hand, to ask for legislation to prevent	competitors from cutting rates because the competition was wiping out	their profit margins.  Leaders in other industries did the same	thing. The result was the Interstate Commerce Commission and a	plethora of other federal agencies, which were created to regulate	rates and keep them high enough so that small, aggressive companies	would not be able to reduce the profit margins of the big,	long-established companies in a particular industry. The result, of	course, was that consumers had to pay higher prices, since government	regulation kept prices artificially high, all in the "public	interest." For more on this point, see G. Kolko, Railroads and	Regulation 1877-1916 (1965); G. Kolko, The Triumph of Conservatism	(1963).  For an analysis of the public interest theory as applied at	the Federal Communications Commission, see W. Mayton, The	Illegitimacy of the Public Interest Standard at the FCC, 38 Emory L.	J. 715-69 (1989).		<a href="#84r">Return</a><p><a name="85"><li>M. Friedman, Capitalism & Freedom 137-60 (1962);	Occupational Licensure and Regulation (S. Rottenberg ed. 1980);	S. Young, The Rule of Experts: Occupational Licensing in America	(1987); Occupational Regulation and the Public Interest (R. Albon and	G. Lindsay eds. 1984); S. Gross, Of Foxes and Hen Houses: Licensing	and the Health Professions (1984).		<a href="#85r">Return</a><p><a name="86"><li>F. Bastiat, supra.	<a href="#86r">Return</a><p><a name="87"><li>Scales v. United States, 367 U.S. 203, 270-272	(1961).		<a href="#87r">Return</a><p><a name="88"><li>The specific cases Justice Douglas referred to were	Dennis v. United States, 341 U.S. 494, 508-509; Communications	Assn. v. Douds, 339 U.S. 382, 399-400; N.A.A.C.P. v. Alabama,	357 U.S. 449, 463-466; Uphaus v. Wyman, 360 U.S. 72, 78-79;	Barenblatt v. United States, 360 U.S. 109, 126-134; Bates v.	Little Rock, 361 U.S. 516, 524; Shelton v. Tucker, 364 U.S.	479; Wilkinson v. United States, 365 U.S. 399; Braden v. United	States, 365 U.S. 431; Konigsberg v. State Bar, 366 U.S. 36; In	re Anastaplo, 366 U.S. 82.  Douglas also discusses the right of	association and the balancing test in W. Douglas, The Right of	Association, 63 Colum. L. Rev. 1361-83 (1963).		<a href="#88r">Return</a><p><a name="89"><li>Scales v. United States, 367 U.S. 203, 270-272	(1961).		<a href="#89r">Return</a><p><a name="90"><li>For a discussion of this point, see R. Cass, The	Perils of Positive Thinking: Constitutional Interpretation and	Negative First Amendment Theory, 34 U.C.L.A. L. Rev. 1405-91	(1987).		<a href="#90r">Return</a><p><a name="91"><li>It should also be mentioned that employers might	recognize this drawback to their employees' career advancement	and make it a corporate policy not to support organizations that do	not admit women or minorities.  But that is a matter of individual	choice.		<a href="#91r">Return</a><p><a name="92"><li>The probability of adopting an amendment that	guarantees the freedom of association for United States citizens	seems slim at the moment. However, such is not the case for	other countries. In the emerging democracies of Eastern and Central	Europe, Asia and Africa, in particular, such an amendment might	easily be adopted, since the people in those countries are not	saddled with the decades of American case law that has limited	this right.  As they adopt new constitutions, it would be very	easy to slip in a few words to guarantee this basic right.  In	newly emerging states having a high degree of ethnic diversity	and animosity, such a move might be regarded as highly favorable to	the vast majority of the population.		<a href="#92r">Return</a><p><a name="93"><li> F. Kendall and L. Louw, After Apartheid: The	Solution for South Africa 216 (1987). This book was published	by the Institute for Contemporary Studies in the United States.	An earlier version was published  in 1986 in Ciskei by Agami	Publications under the title South Africa: The Solution. The language	regarding freedom of association appears at page 160 in this	edition.		<a href="#93r">Return</a><p><a name="94"><li>U.S. Const. amend. I.	<a href="#94r">Return</a><p><a name="95"><li> Mishkin v. New York, 383 U.S. 502, 518 (1966).	<a href="#95r">Return</a><p><a name="96"><li>Yates v. U.S., 354 U.S. 298, 343-44 (1957).	<a href="#96r">Return</a><p><a name="97"><li> Bransburg v. Hayes, 408 U.S. 665, 713, 716 (1972).	<a href="#97r">Return</a><p><a name="98"><li>For example, see Meiklejohn, The First Amendment is	an Absolute, 1961 Sup. Ct. Rev. 245.			<a href="#98r">Return</a><p><a name="99"><li>For example, see Schenck v. United States, 249 U.S.	47 (1919); Whitney v. California, 274 U.S. 357 (1927); Stromberg v.	California, 283 U.S. 359 (1931); Near v. Minnesota, 283 U.S.	697 (1981); De Jonge v. Oregon, 299 U.S. 353 (1937); Herdon v.	Lowry, 301 U.S. 242; Cantwell v. Connecticut, 310 U.S. 296 (1940).	Some writers have argued that the extent of free speech should	be based on the purpose of the speech. For an exposition of	this view, see F. Canavan, Freedom of Expression: Purpose as	Limit (1984), especially 1-40.		<a href="#99r">Return</a><p><a name="100"><li>Konigsberg v. State Bar of California, 366 U.S. 36	at 49-51 (1961).  This "weighing of the governmental interest	involved" is just an application of the balancing test, which,	as pointed out, is invalid.		<a href="#nnr">Return</a><p><a name="101"><li>Chaplinsky v. New Hampshire, 315 U.S. 568, 571-2	(1942). Some commentators point to the famous example that no one has	the right to falsely yell "fire" in a crowded theater as evidence	that the right of free speech is not absolute. But, as Rothbard	points out in Rothbard, For a New Liberty 43-44 (1978) [45-46	of the 1973 edition], this argument is a false one because it	confuses free speech with property rights. Rothbard's position	is that there are no human rights that are separate from property	rights and that the right of free speech is merely the property	right to hire an assembly hall from someone or to own one oneself.	The right of free speech is not an extra right apart from the	property rights that can be enumerated in a given case. In the	theater example, anyone who falsely shouts "fire" is violating	someone's property rights. If the theater owner falsely shouts	"fire," he is breaching his contract with the patrons to let them see	the performance they have paid for. He has, in effect, stolen	their money. If a patron is the one who shouts fire, the property	rights of both the owner and the patrons are being violated. As	Rothbard says at page 44 of the 1978 edition:	<p>	There is no need, therefore, for individual rights to be restricted in	the case of the false shouter of "fire." The rights of the individual	are still absolute; but they are property rights. The fellow	who maliciously cried "fire" in a crowded theater is indeed a	criminal, but not because his so-called "right of free speech"	must be pragmatically restricted on behalf of the "public good"; he	is a criminal because he has clearly and obviously violated the	property rights of another person.	</p>	<p>	Rothbard discusses the same point in The Ethics of Liberty 113-17	(1983) and Power and Market 177 (1970). Justice Black agrees	with Rothbard on this point. See One Man's Stand for Freedom	477-78 (Irving Dillard ed. 1963), cited in Rothbard, The Ethics	of Liberty 114-15, 119 n. 6 (1982). Black points out that the	issue is not whether one has a right to shout "fire" in a crowded	theater but whether one has a right to shout at all.	</p>		<a href="#101r">Return</a><p><a name="102"><li>Konigsberg v. State Bar of California, 366 U.S. 36,	61-62 (1961); In re Anastaplo, 366 U.S. 82, 110-12 (1961); Scales v.	U.S., 367 U.S. 203, 261, 270-71 (1961); Time v. Hill, 385 U.S.	374, 399-400 (1967); Garrison v. Louisiana, 379 U.S. 64, 80-83	(1964).		<a href="#102r">Return</a><p><a name="103"><li>U.S. Const. amend. V.	<a href="#103r">Return</a><p><a name="104"><li>For an exposition of this view, see R. Epstein,	Takings: Private Property and the Power of Eminent Domain (1985); R.	Epstein, Rent Control and the Theory of Efficient Regulation,	54 Brooklyn L. Rev. 741-74 (1988).  For an economic critique of	rent control, see Walter Block and Edgar Olsen, Rent Control: Myths &	Realities (1981).		<a href="#104r">Return</a><p><a name="105"><li>U.S. Const. art. I, § 10.	<a href="#105r">Return</a><p><a name="106"><li>For expositions on this point, see  H. Butler and	L. Ribstein, The Contract Clause and the Corporation, 55 Brooklyn L.	Rev. 767-808 (1989);  The Contract Clause: The "Regulated Industry"	Exception, 8 U. Hawaii L. Rev. 135-61 (1986); The Contract Clause: Is	There Life After Death? -- U.S. Trust Co. v. New Jersey, 30 Baylor L.	Rev. 191-8 (1978); Revival of the Contract Clause, 39 Ohio St.	L.J. 195-213 (1978); A Procedural Approach to the Contract Clause, 93	Yale L. J. 918-37 (1984); B. Siegan, Rehabilitating Lochner, 22	San Diego L. Rev. 453-97 (1985); C. Sunstein, Lochner's Legacy,	87 Colum. L. Rev. 873-919 (1987); R. Epstein, Toward a Revitalization	of the Contract Clause, 51 U. Chi. L. Rev. 703-51 (1984); J.	Baker, Has the Contract Clause Counter-Revolution Halted? Rhetoric,	Rights, and Markets in Constitutional Analysis, 12 Hastings Const. L.	Q. 71-104 (1984); E. Mack, In Defense of Unbridled Freedom of	Contract, 40 Am. J. Econ. & Soc. 1-15 (Jan. 1981).		<a href="#106r">Return</a></ol><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>[<A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A>]</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><center><P>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation</p><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I></center><HR NOSHADE><p>For information on The Freedom Server&copy; please contact the <a href="mailto:administrator@freedom-server.co.uk">Administrator</a></p></p><hr><p>The URL of this page is:</p><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Right-of-Non-Association.html&gt; </CENTER><HR NOSHADE></BODY></HTML>
