<HTML><HEAD>	<TITLE>The Freedom Server-Pollution Trading</TITLE>	<META Name="Author" CONTENT="Robert W. McGee,		Walter E. Block">		<META Name="Keys"		CONTENT="Galambos,government,coercion,capitalism,			regulation,Bedeman,political,property rights,			ivory,Zimbabwe,Hayek,Clean Air Act,MPPs,CFC">						<META HTTP-EQUIV="Reply-to"		CONTENT="administrator@freedom-server.co.uk"></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><hr noshade><center><H1>The Freedom Server&copy;</H1><H3>Selected Essays</H3><hr noshade><h4>| <a href="index.html">Home</a> | <a href="Contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | </h4><h4>| <a href="Other-Essays.html">Other Essays Page</a> |</h4></center> <hr noshade><p>Created: 1995, August 1<BR>Revised: 1996, July 15 <BR>Version: 002k</p><hr><center><P>This page has been visited</P><IMG SRC="/cgi-bin/Counter.cgi?www.freedom-server.co.uk.Pollution-Trading.html" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> <P>since 1996, July 16, although The Freedom Server was createdon 1995, August 1.</P><hr noshade><h3>Other Essays</h3></center></center><hr><p>These essays have been published with the permission of the individualauthors. If you wish you may contact Dr. McGee at the <a href="mailto:info@dumontinst.com">Dumont Institute</a> toobtain information on the organization or comment on this essay.</p><hr noshade><center><H3>Pollution Trading Permits as a Half-Way Solution</H3><h4>Robert W. McGee and Walter E. Block</h4></center><hr noshade><center><h4>I.  Introduction</h4></center><p><a name="1r"><a name="2r"><a name="3r"></p><p>	The concept of marketable pollution permits (MPP)<ahref="#1">[1]</a> has become an increasingly popular topic ofdiscussion for environmentalists in recent years, although the idea hasbeen around since at least 1968, when J.H. Dales published a book onthe issue.<a href="#2">[2]</a>  This approach was given addedcredibility when the Congress passed the Clean Air Act of 1990,<ahref="#3">[3]</a> which made the concept an official part ofenvironmental regulatory policy.<p>	A typical solution in this regard is for the government to mandatethat a certain kind of pollutant in a specified geographic area bereduced by a defined target percentage within a certain time period.Basically, such nostrums are based on a centralized command systemrather than the market place.<p>	Establishing a market in tradeable pollution permits triggers"quasi" market forces. This leads to a more efficient allocation ofresources than command and control alternatives and makes it possibleto achieve the goal of reducing emissions at less cost. Firms thatcannot achieve the targeted level can purchase a permit from the personwhose reduction exceeds the mandated amount. There is an incentive foreach person to reduce pollution below the legally required level sothat the permits not being utilized can be sold.<p><a name="4r"><a name="5r"><a name="6r"></p><p>	However, this solution has encountered some problems. Excessiveregulations and regulator attitudes have practically destroyed theevolution of a well-functioning permit market. And the system, aspresently advocated and applied, is structurally unsound, since itplaces reliance on command rather than market incentives -- which isreally just a form of market socialism, a system that Mises<ahref="#4">[4]</a> and Hayek<a href="#5">[5]</a> criticized in the 1920sand 1930s.<a href="#6">[6]</a> 	<p>	This paper applies market theories to the problem of pollution. It maintains that while market socialism (e.g., tradeable emissionrights) is preferable to central commands, a system of fully protectedprivate property rights is superior to both.	<center><h4>II.  The Pollution Trading Permit Approach</h4></center><p><a name="7r"><a name="8r"><a name="9r"></p><p>	Strictly speaking, there are only two economic systems, themarket and socialism.  Capitalism relies on voluntary exchange and therecognition of property rights.  The socialist alternative relies onforce or the threat of force, and necessarily entails the violation (ornonrecognition) or property rights.  The market system has been shown<ahref="#7">[7]</a> to be more effective in allocating scarce resourcesfor a number of reasons.  For one thing, it relies on a price system,which acts as a signalling mechanism to convey information to  marketparticipants.<a href="#8">[8]</a> Socialism, on the other hand, relieson centrally directed command. But because information is dispersed, itis impossible for a central authority to gather and digest thenecessary information and to make decisions that result in theefficient allocation of resources.  Yet free enterprise performs thisfunction automatically. A number of commentators have discussed thisphenomenon in depth, so there is no need to repeat it here.<ahref="#9">[9]</a><p>	Until recently, the command system was used almost exclusivelyto control pollution.  As a result, the problem is still with us.  Butin recent years, researchers have been trying to find ways to injectmarket forces into the area of pollution abatement, in recognition ofthe fact that it works better at solving problems than does centralplanning.<p>	One way to unleash market forces is by the use of tradeable emissionsrights (TERs), which are permitted under the 1990 Clean Air Actamendments.  Whereas under a command system, all businesses andcommunities would have to collectively and individually meet whatevertests and pollution reductions government commanded, under a marketpermit trading system, reduction goals could be achieved more flexibly. For example, let's say that some law required all electric powerplants to reduce sulfur dioxide emissions by 30% over a two-year periodand that the decrease would have to be achieved by using smokestackscrubbers.  Under the command system, every power plant would have toachieve the 30% reduction regardless of cost.  Plants with oldertechnology might find it very difficult and expensive to meet thetarget.  Newer ones might achieve it at much smaller cost.<p><a name="10r"><a name="11r"></p><p>	But under a market-driven system, the goal could be achievedmore efficiently.  Here, the goal could still be a 30% overallreduction, but individual plants would have more flexibility in tryingto meet it.  They could each try to find the least costly way toachieve the goal.  Assume that there are ten power plants of equal sizein the region that produce a total of 100 million tons of emissions, or10 million tons each.<a href="#10">[10]</a>  Under a permit tradingregime, plants have several options.  While the total emissionreduction must be 30 million tons, the individual plants do notnecessarily have to use scrubbers to achieve their allocable share ofthe reduction.  They can use other means if they can find a better way. For example, they might be able to switch from burning coal to usingnatural gas, electricity or water power.  Or they might find ways toburn their coal more efficiently. The price system will send them thesignals they need to make the correct decision.<a href="#11">[11]</a><p>	Each plant does not have to achieve a 30% reduction.  Efficientones could find ways to reduce their emissions by 40%, and could selltheir excess 10% to one that is having difficulty achieving its 30%required reduction.  In effect, efficient plants could sell pollution"rights" to their inefficient colleagues.  And because of this marketincentive, efficient plants might find it profitable to reduceemissions in their facility by more than that required by law so thatthey could sell their right to pollute to someone else.  For example,if a plant could reduce its emissions by an extra ton at a cost of $300and could sell this pollution right for $1,000, the incentive to reduceemissions would result in turning liabilities and expenses into assetsand revenues.  If the price of MPPs becomes sufficiently attractive,some polluters may find it more profitable to shut down their facilityand sell their permits than to remain open.  This is a furtherincentive that does not exist under a command system.<p><a name="12r"></p><p>	Pollution could also be reduced by another market force. Environmental groups could use the funds they now expend on litigation,public relations and advertising to purchase some emission rightsthemselves.  If such groups bought 10% of the total permits in an areaand then just sat on them, so to speak, total pollution could bereduced by that amount.  These organizations might even be able toincrease the amount of private funding they receive (thus making morefunds available for buying yet additional trading permits) if theyengaged in this kind of activity, since some individuals hesitate tocontribute to them now because the motives of some environmental groupsare suspect.<a href="#12">[12]</a><p><a name="13r"></p><p>	If it appears that MPPs are a good investment, speculatorsmight enter the market and purchase some permits in the hope that theprice would rise.  While they are waiting, the permits lie dormant,which also would serve to reduce discharges.<a href="#13">[13]</a><p><a name="14r"></p><p>	Once these quasi market forces are allowed to function, mutuallybeneficial exchange will trigger the free enterprise system to find newways to achieve goals at minimum cost.  Specialization and division oflabor, coupled with the unanticipated discovery of more efficientproduction methods, will expand the market, causing benefits toincrease and costs to fall.  According to one conservative estimate,adopting the trading permit approach to sulfur dioxide emissions in theUSA may lead to as much as a 20% decline in electric utility costs overwhat would have been the case under a command system.<ahref="#14">[14]</a><p><a name="15r"></p><p>	Several studies have found that changing from commands to markets canproduce dramatic cost reductions.  Below are summaries of someempirical studies of air pollution control.<a href="#15">[15]</a></p><center>	<table border width="100%">	<tr>		<th>Pollutant</th>		<th>Industry</th>		<th>Percent Cost Reduction</th>	<tr>		<tr>		<td>Paritulates</td>		<td>Power</td>		<td  align="center">83%</td>	</tr>		<tr>		<td>Sulfur Dioxide</td>		<td>Power</td>		<td  align="center">50%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Sulfates</td>		<td>Steel, Petroleum, Power</td>		<td  align="center">9%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Nitrogen Oxide</td>		<td>Steel, Chemicals, Oil</td>		<td  align="center"d>83%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Hydrocarbon</td>		<td>DuPont Chemical</td>		<td  align="center">76%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Particulates</td>		<td>All Sources</td>		<td  align="center">76%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>CFC</td>		<td>Refrigeration (Plastics)</td>		<td  align="center">50%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Nitrogen Oxide</td>		<td>Power, Steel, Oil</td>		<td  align="center">93%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Sulfur Dioxide</td>		<td>Power, Steel, Oil</td>		<td  align="center">44%</td>	</tr>	<tr>		<td>Particulates</td>		<td>Power, Steel, Oil</td>		<td  align="center">95%</td>	</tr>	</table></center><p>	Another advantage for markets vis a vis command concerns the behaviorof managers.  Rather than spending their time and energy dealing withgovernment bureaucrats and trying to manipulate the system to theiradvantage, they can plow their resources and energy into finding moreefficient ways to run their businesses.  Whereas a command systemrewards politically gifted managers, the market rewards production andresults.  Over time, this difference in incentives produces a newbreed.  Entrepreneurial managers tend to take the place of bureaucratsand bureaucrats tend to change into entrepreneurial managers.	<center><h4>III.  A Property Rights Approach</h4></center><p><a name="16r"><a name="17r"><a name="18r"><a name="19r"><a name="20r"></p><p><a name="21r"></p><p>	While marketable trading permits are a definite improvementover commands, they can be criticized on a number of counts.<ahref="#16">[16]</a>  One fault is that government dilutes theeffectiveness of the permit trading system through regulation,<ahref="#17">[17]</a> which replaces the market with a bureaucraticcommand structure.  As a result, whenever there is a "failure," it islabeled a "market failure," when in fact it is a government failure.<ahref="#18">[18]</a> Another difficulty is that if we took the Project88 approach<a href="#19">[19]</a> in a world of pervasiveexternalities, there would be a need for thousands ofgovernment-created and monitored markets for specific pollutants suchas SO<sub>2</sub>, CO, CO<sub>2</sub>, particulates, NO and NO<sub>2</sub>, not to mention the hundredsof "toxics" that are regulated one way or another.  Also, at presentthere are no proposals to allow cross-trading of various pollutionpermits and there will be great restrictions on the marketability ofrights of the same sort by geography.<a href="#20">[20]</a>  Thus,great rigidities would be introduced into the process.  We could nottake advantage of a drop in the seriousness of acid rain, for example,because the political process moves too slowly.  The result is animposition of an increasing series of side constraints on an economywith massive potential benefits of cross-trade (such as more NOX andless ozone) but no ability to handle these.<a href="#21">[21]</a>  Such government failures are endemic to the system.<p><a name="22r"></p><p>	To state this criticism in Coasian terms, the problem is thatmarkets have more to do with the terms of trade, with the opportunityof creating new linkages and new tradeoffs than with the production ofa rigid bundle of nontradeable goods. Coase's "problem of socialcost"<a href="#22">[22]</a> is relevant to all this debate and has yetto be understood by the market socialist school -- most andenvironmentalists.<p>	But perhaps the major fault with trading permits is that, whilethey allow market forces to allocate resources, they involve a basicand pervasive violation of property rights.  Basically, MPPs arelicenses to pollute, licenses to violate property rights.  Thus,trading permits are a form of market socialism because they allowmarket forces to operate, yet ignore property rights.  Martin Andersonexpresses the following view: Fortunately, there is a simple, effectiveapproach available -- long appreciated but underused.  An approachbased solidly on ... private property rights.</p><ul>	<p>	At its root all pollution is garbage disposal in one form or another. 	The essence of the problem is that our laws and the administration of	justice have not kept up with the refuse produced by the exploding	growth of industry, technology and science.	</p>		<p>	If you took a bag of garbage and dropped it on your neighbor's lawn, we	all know what would happen.  Your neighbor would call the police and	you would soon find out that the disposal of your garbage is	your responsibility, and that it must be done in a way that does not	violate anyone else's property rights.	</p>		<p>	But if you took that same bag of garbage and burned it in a backyard	incinerator, letting the sooty ash drift over the neighborhood,	the problem gets more complicated. The violation of property	rights is clear, but protecting them is more difficult. And when the	garbage is invisible to the naked eye, as much air and water	pollution is, the problem often seems insurmountable.	</p>		<p>	We have tried many remedies in the past. We have tried to dissuade	polluters with fines, with government programs whereby all pay	to clean up the garbage produced by the few, with a myriad of	detailed regulations to control the degree of pollution. Now	some even seriously propose that we should have economic incentives,	to charge polluters a fee for polluting -- and the more they pollute	the more they pay.  But that is just like taxing burglars as an	economic incentive to deter people from stealing your property,	and just as unconscionable.	</p>		<p>	The only effective way to eliminate serious pollution is to treat it	exactly for what it is -- garbage. Just as one does not have	the right to drop a bag of garbage on his neighbor's lawn, so	does one not have the right to place any garbage in the air or	the water or the earth, if it in any way violates the property	rights of others.	</p>		<p>	What we need are tougher clearer environmental laws that are enforced	-- not with economic incentives but with jail terms.	</p>		<p>	<a name="23r">	</p>	<p>	What the strict application of the idea of private property rights will	do is to increase the cost of garbage disposal. That increased	cost will be reflected in a higher cost for the products and services	that resulted from the process that produced the garbage. And that is	how it should be. Much of the cost of disposing of waste is already	incorporated in the price of the goods and services produced.	All of it should be. Then only those who benefit from the garbage	made will pay for its disposal.<a href="#23">[23]</a>	</p></ul><p>	A true market system would include both components -- a pricesystem and recognition of property rights.  Thus, TERs are a half-wayhouse.<p><a name="24r"><a name="25r"></p><p>	Is there a true market solution, one that depends on theprice system yet does not violate property rights?  There is. The firststep that must be taken in this direction is to establish a system ofclearly defined and enforceable property rights.<a href="#24">[24]</a> Once clearly defined, market forces will take over to determine whatlevel of pollution is optimal.  If firms pollute first, before enteringinto an agreement, the court system could be used to assess damages ifthe parties could not agree to a price. Such a system would provideincentives for companies to reduce the amount of discharge because theywould have to pay the full cost of their actions.<a href="#25">[25]</a><p><a name="26r"><a name="27r"><a name="28r"></p><p><a name="29r"><a name="30r"></p><p>	Such a system was in use in the USA until the nineteenth century.<ahref="#26">[26]</a> But then, in a series of cases, individuals'property rights were taken away when the courts sided with the propertyrights violators in a number of nuisance cases.<a href="#27">[27]</a> For example, if sparks from a passing train caused a farmer's field orbarn to burn, judges started to hold that the company that owned thetrain should not be liable for the damage for public policy reasons,<ahref="#28">[28]</a> the view being that it is better that a few farmersgo uncompensated than that trains stop running or be forced to pay thefull cost of their actions.<a href="#29">[29]</a>  This position, ofcourse, results in a basic violation of property rights, becausefarmers were being damaged but not compensated.  It is a classicexample of what Public Choice economists call rent-seeking,<ahref="#30">[30]</a> since some groups (farmers, in this case) areforced to pay for the benefits of other groups (railroad owners).  Ifcourts had held in favor of the farmers instead, railroad owners wouldhave been forced to find a way to reduce the amount of sparks theirtrains emitted, or pay the full cost of their activity.  In effect,then, farmers were being forced by the legal system to subsidizerailroads.<p><a name="31r"><a name="32r"></p><p>	In one early case, sparks from a locomotive caused a house toburn down.  But the judge found the railroad innocent anyway, because"in a commercial country, each man, to some extent, runs the hazard ofhis neighbors' conduct, and each, by insurance against such hazards, isenabled to obtain a reasonable security against loss."<ahref="#31">[31]</a>  The railroad was obviously guilty of causing thedamage, yet it was let off the hook.<a href="#32">[32]</a><p><a name="33r"><a name="34r"></p><p>	Of course, there must be some <i>de minimis</i> exception.  Victimsshould not be able to sue for slight invasions of their property, aswhen a single particle of pollutant, which is undetectible withoutexpensive scientific instruments, and harmless, crosses the victim'sproperty line.  Or where an airplane passes over a property owner'sproperty at a height of 35,000 feet. This principle is well-establishedin the law, both in England and the USA.<a href="#33">[33]</a>  Thisprinciple, sometimes called the "live and let live> rule, waselaborated upon in <i>Bamford v. Turnley</i>.<a href="#34">[34]</a><p><a name="35r"></p><p>	The instances put during the argument, of burning weeds, emptyingcess-pools, making noises during repairs, and other instances whichwould be nuisances if done wantonly or maliciously, nevertheless may belawfully done.  It cannot be said that such acts are not nuisances,because of the hypothesis they are; and it cannot be doubted that if aperson maliciously and without cause made close to a dwelling house thesame offensive smells as may be made in emptying a cess-pool, an actionwould lie.  Nor can these cases be got rid of as extreme cases, becausesuch cases are properly used for testing a principle.  Nor can it besaid that the jury settle such questions by finding there is nonuisance, though there is .... There must be, then, some principle onwhich such cases must be excepted.  It seems to me that that principlemay be deduced from the character of these cases, and is this, viz.,that those acts necessary for the common and ordinary use andoccupation of land and houses may be done, if conveniently done,without submitting those who do them to an action .... It is as muchfor the advantage of one owner as of another; for the very nuisance theone complains of, as the result of the ordinary use of his neighbour'sland, he himself will create in the ordinary use of his own, and thereciprocal nuisances are of a comparatively trifling character.  Theconvenience of such a rule may be indicated by calling it a rule ofgive and take, live and let live ....<a href="#35">[35]</a><p><a name="36r"></p><p>	Where the nuisance is slight,<a href="#36">[36]</a> courtsand legislatures might absolve the perpetrator of liability, especiallywhere no damage can be proven. But where it is more than slight, orwhere there is measurable or detectable damage, the courts shouldrecognize liability and define the method by which the perpetrator isto be dealt with (pay damages, cease and desist, etc.). The importantthing is that the legal system clearly define property rights and howviolations of property rights are to be dealt with.  And the decisionmust not be based on utilitarian or public policy considerationsbecause this disparages individual and property rights and leaves thedoors wide open for rent-seeking by powerful special-interest groups.<p>	Epstein suggests that allowing private causes of action mightbe counterproductive where the following four factors are present:</p>	<ol>	<p>	<li>	High administrative costs for claim resolution.	</p>		<p>	<li>	High transaction costs for voluntary reassignment		of rights. 	</p>		<p>	<li>	Low value to the interested parties of		the ownership rights whose rearrangement is mandated by public		rule.	</p>		<p>	<a name="37r">	</p>	<p>	<li>	Presence of implicit in-kind compensation from all to all		that precludes any systematic redistribution of wealth among		the interested parties.<a href="#37">[37]</a>	</p></ol><p><a name="38r"><a name="39r"></p><p>	There are several facets to the analysis of nuisance law, andhow it can be used to regulate pollution.  Where the emissions arecaused by just one person and the trespass is committed against justone person, the solution is simple.<a href="#38">[38]</a>  The perpetrator and the victimcan be clearly identified and they can trade.  The polluter can perhapsagree to pay the victim some mutually agreed upon price.  If theparties cannot agree, the pollution cannot occur.  But what about themany situations where the solution is not so simple?<a href="#39">[39]</a><p><a name="40r"><a name="41r"><a name="42r"></p><p>	Much pollution is the result of the "tragedy of the commons."<ahref="#40">[40]</a> In cases where ownership is in common, such aslakes, streams and air, nobody owns it.  Transferring these commonlyowned properties to private ownership<a href="#41">[41]</a> could go along way toward solving these externality problems.  While it may notbe politically feasible to privatize the Pacific Ocean in the nearfuture,<a href="#42">[42]</a> it is possible to privatize smallerbodies of water.  Government-owned lakes could be sold to the highestbidder, or could be given to the natural homesteaders: whoever owns theland at the shoreline.  In cases where such a lake is owned by morethan one owner, they could form a cooperative or corporation todetermine how the lake shall be used -- for boating, fishing,recreation, and so forth. They could collect fees in exchange forallowing nonowners to use their lake.  If someone wanted to dump wasteinto this holding, they could determine the amount they wished toaccept and the price.  If environmental groups do not want anyone todump any waste into a particular lake, they could enter into anagreement with the owner to pay a certain amount in exchange for theowner's promise not to allow such activity.  Or they could purchase thelake themselves.  In the case of streams, similar arrangements could bemade.<p><a name="43r"><a name="44r"><a name="45r"></p><p>	Property rights in water has evolved over many years and ismost highly developed in the Western United States, where water isscarce.<a href="#43">[43]</a>  Much of the property law that hasevolved in this area could be adapted to a private property regimeinvolving pollution.<a href="#44">[44]</a> Unfortunately, in the caseof water allocation in the Western United States, the state has oftenstepped in to prevent the market from functioning.  Government oftendecides how water rights should be allocated on the basis of interestgroup pressure rather than sound economics.<a href="#45">[45]</a><p><a name="46r"></p><p>	A similar system of property rights could be allowed to evolve inthe area of auto emissions.  At present, nearly all roads and highwaysare owned by government, another tragedy of the commons.  Yetgovernment ownership is by no means necessary.  Highways and roadscould be turned over to private parties,<a href="#46">[46]</a> whocould then establish rules for the use of their roads.  Autos that spewforth too much pollution could cause neighboring households to sue theowner of the road for nuisance.  It is easier to sue one of hundreds ofroad owners in the country than one of millions of drivers. This wouldprovide the proper incentive to the owners to regulate the amount offumes permitted on their property.  Autos that pollute too much simplywould not be allowed to use the road.<p><a name="47r"><a name="48r"></p><p>	The introduction of property rights has proven to be beneficial toconservation in a number of other cases.  For example, there is someworry among environmentalists and others that elephants will becomeextinct if something is not done to prevent their slaughter.  Thesolution was to ban the ivory trade.<a href="#47">[47]</a>  Yet such asolution does not make economic sense. If ivory is banned, it willbecome more rare, making trade in ivory more lucrative.  Prohibitingthe ivory trade will tend to actually increase rather than decreaseincentives.  The fact that such trade is illegal will attractindividuals who have few scruples.  If elephants were privatized, thatis, owned by individuals and private corporations, the danger of theirbecoming extinct would be vastly reduced.  But such a solution is notmere utopian polemics. There is empirical evidence to support it. InKenya and other East and Central African countries, governmentsresorted to a common property management strategy, whereas elephantswere owned by no one. As a result, the elephant population in that partof the world has declined by more than 50% in the last decade.<ahref="#48">[48]</a>  But in Zimbabwe, elephants are privately owned byregional tribal councils, who take an ownership interest.  As a result,the elephant population has increased. Further, Asian elephants, whichhave been domesticated for many years, are not in danger of extinction.<p>	A comparison might also be made between cattle and bison.  Inthe "wild west" period of U.S. history, bison (buffalos) were owned byno one.  They were hunted down and killed indiscriminately.  They werenot protected because they had no owners.  In contrast, cattle wereprivately owned by ranchers. As Americans became more wealthy, theystarted to eat more meat which, coupled with advances in technology andtransportation, greatly increased the demand for beef.  Although therewas poaching of cattle, just as in the case of buffalo, cattle werenever in danger of extinction.  Because cattle were always privatelyowned, their owners took an ownership interest by branding, fencingtheir herds, guarding them and shooting rustlers.  The law was on theirside because it was illegal to steal cattle.  Government protected theproperty rights of the cattle owners who exercised them.  The tragedyof the commons that applied to buffalo (and still exists today for someelephants) was avoided in the case of cattle because they wereprivately owned.  Could it be that there is some relationship betweenprivate property rights and the danger of species extinction?  Why isit that privately owned animals such as chickens, dogs, cats and cattleare not in danger of extinction, but wild animals like whales and baldeagles are?  It is clear that the solution to saving animals fromextinction would be to privatize them.<p><a name="49r"><a name="50r"></p><p>	While such a solution might be relatively easy to implementfor some species, such as bison, the privatization solution might bemore difficult for others like whales, dolphins, tuna and othermigratory sea animals.<a href="#49">[49]</a>  But even privateownership of these species is not impossible.  In the short run,portions of some bodies of water could be privatized so that only theowner would be permitted to harvest water-based animals in a certainwell-defined location.   Selling the continental shelves, rivers andlakes might be feasible in the short-term.  If lakes can be sold toprivate parties, can the Mediterranean Sea be far behind? In thelong-run, as technology improves, it might be possible to fence-offsome larger areas, perhaps by laser or sonar technology, so thatanimals from one sector would not travel onto another.  Once propertyrights are established, the market would tend to find solutions to suchproblems.<a href="#50">[50]</a>  But in the absence of property rights,there is no incentive to even attempt to find solutions because thereis no payoff.</p>	<center><h4>IV.  Additional Comments</h4></center><p><a name="51r"><a name="52r"></p><p>	Why is it that economists who usually favor pure or full freemarkets opt instead for TERs when it comes to pollution?<ahref="#51">[51]</a>  In some cases, it is because they cannotvisualize, or imagine, how a full private property rights free marketregime could actually function.  At least this is an implication thatemerges from reading works that do not even mention such analternative. In others, the market is rejected after what can best bedescribed as a superficial coverage, almost an afterthought.  But thereis at least one case where the market is considered in full detail --and then rejected outright in an intensive and exhaustive analysis. This is true of Dolan,<a href="#52">[52]</a> in a paper which we shallnow scrutinize.<p><a name="53r"><a name="54r"></p><p>	Dolan begins by describing what he takes to be the operationof a private property system in its confrontation with acid rain.  Atrue Coasian, he offers two scenarios, one in which "... it weredetermined that density of the pollution source did not convey theright to send clouds of noxious gases into the neighboring forest"<ahref="#53">[53]</a> and one in which it did.  We need not concernourselves with the second system of law, for despite the Coasiancontention that absent transactions costs and wealth effects eitheralternative will imply the same allocation of resources, this latterscenario would be anathema to a Lockean-oriented private propertyrights system.<a href="#54">[54]</a>  (If the pollution sourcehomesteaded the factory, and the forest owner in similar manner "mixedhis labor" with the forest, the former would never obtain the right tosend airborne pollutants to the latter.)</p><p>	In the words of Dolan,</p><ul>		<p>	<a name="55r">	</p>	<p>	The forester would begin by demanding that emissions cease.  In	response, the polluter might stop the offending activity or install	control equipment that allowed production to continue without further	emissions. Instead, the polluter might offer a payment to the	forester in exchange for allowing continued emissions. If a payment	less than the cost of abatement turned out to exceed the forester's	evaluation of the damage, a deal would be struck along these	lines. As still another alternative, the polluter might offer	to buy the forest outright and decide what to do about future	emissions on the basis of internal benefit-cost	calculations.<a href="#55">[55]</a> 	</p></ul>	<p><a name="56r"></p><p>	But our author rejects this market model (not "market-based model,"as he contends).<a href="#56">[56]</a>  In the terminology we are employing, the demandthat emissions cease is a pure or full free-market solution.  Dolan'sown proposal, TER, in contrast, is characterized as being"market-based," or a "quasi-market" alternative.	<p>	Why does Dolan reject the market? There are four reasons. First, scientific uncertainties.  Says Dolan,</p><ul>		<p>	<li>The causes of Mount Mitchell's dying trees, New York's and Canada's	dead lakes, and Vermont's summer haze are not known with	certainty.	</p>		<p>	<li>Even if air pollution is accepted as the culprit, no one area's	pollution can be traced to a particular source.	</p>		<p>	<li>The property rights of the owners of pollution sources, the owners of	damaged properties, and other parties indirectly affected are matters	of dispute, and:	</p>		<p>	<a name="57r">	</p>	<p>	<li>Even if the first three points were resolved, the transactions costs of	private negotiations between numerous source owners and numerous	owners of damaged property would appear to be	prohibitive.<a href="#57">[57]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="58r"><a name="59r"></p><p>	Let us consider these four objections each in turn.  In thefirst case, the uncertainty is due, our author informs us, to threefactors.  On the one hand, more than one pollutant, in combination, mayhave caused the problem, and assessing the damage caused by each"becomes difficult."<a href="#58">[58]</a>  Yes, difficult, but this is no reason to throwthe baby out with the bath water.  Why should this complication, on itsown, serve as a justification for rejection of a private propertysystem upon which our entire western civilization may be said to bebased? Surely, our jurisprudence is set up to deal with the challengeof combined causes, and does so in a myriad of other contexts. Inautomobile accidents, for example, there is contributory negligence. Toeach person is apportioned a part of the blame, and the penalty isbased on this allocation.<a href="#59">[59]</a><p><a name="60r"></p><p>	On the other hand, there are "non linearities and thresholdeffects."<a href="#60">[60]</a>  It is worth quoting him in full on this:</p><ul>	<p>	<a name="60r"><a name="61r">	</p>	<p>	One such non-linearity concerns the formation of acid rain.  The	rate of formation depends not only on the presence of precursors --	the oxides of nitrogen and sulfur emitted by pollution sources	-- but also on the presence of oxidizing agents, which promote	acid formation, and alkaline substances, which retard acid formation.	 Depending on the presence of oxidizing and alkaline agents, an	increment of pollution might add greatly, slightly, or not at	all to the acidity of precipitation.  Another threshold effect	involves the 'buffering' properties of soils in areas where	acid precipitation falls. Buffering compounds in the soil may	for years prevent acid rain from doing environmental damage.  At some	point, however, cumulative acid deposition exhausts the buffering	capacity and damage rapidly escalates.<a href="#61">[61]</a>	</p></ul><p>	Alkaline substances and buffering compounds need not trouble us. They are an irrelevant complication.  They reduce the effect of thenoxious airborne chemical, so the profit seeker can have no realcomplaint about them. Oxidizing agents, in contrast, are a completelydifferent matter. These exacerbate the harmful effects of the trespass,and in Dolan's view, presumably, it is improper for the court to blamethe polluter since he created only some of the harm, the rest beinglaid at the door of the oxidizing agent.<p><a name="62r"></p><p>	However, there are already legal precedents on the books thatare fully capable of dealing with this objection. In order to see this,let us consider the case of ordinary (human) trespass, not theintrusion of pollutants onto the property of the victim. In the moreusual case, let us say, a second story man breaks into the premises ofthe homeowner. Unbeknownst to the intruder, the victim has a weak heartand is easily frightened (the analog of the oxidizing agent, in thatthis personality characteristic amplifies the harm committed by theperpetuator of the crime.) As a result of the trespass, the homeownerdies. Is the trespasser guilty of manslaughter? Yes, because of thedoctrine of "you take your victim as you find him."<ahref="#62">[62]</a> Similarly, if the mugger commits assault andbattery upon a heart attack proven victim who dies as a result, he isor should be considered guilty of manslaughter no matter how light thebodily contact.<p>	To return to the polluter, he should be forced to "take theatmosphere as he finds it." If oxidizing agents worsen the harm of hisemissions, he should, in like manner, be held responsible for theentire damages, both that part created by his pollution, and that addedto this by the oxidizing agents in the air.		<p>	On the third hand, Dolan points to the fact that	</p><ul>	<p>	<a name="63r">	</p>	<p>	Acid rain does not kill trees directly. The mechanisms involved	may be quite complicated. To give one example, Lee Klinger, working	with the National Center for Atmospheric Research in Boulder,	Colo., sees a link between forest diebacks and certain mosses	that are nearly always present in dying forests. The mosses produce	organic acids that mobilize aluminum naturally present in the	soil, forming compounds toxic to the feeder roots of trees. Although	the mosses are naturally present in most forests, their growth	appears to be greatly promoted by acid	precipitation.<a href="#63">[63]</a>	</p></ul><p>	But we have already answered this objection. Here, the mossesbecome the catalytic agents, increasing the harm.<p>	Next, our author considers the transportation problem, and again isworthy of quotation at length.</p>	<ul>	<p>	Even if the available evidence linking environmental damage to	pollution is accepted, there remains the problem of tracing the	acid rain at a given site to a particular source of pollution.	To date, research on transportation models for pollution has	been able to give only general, probabilistic answers.  In general,	pollution is known to travel from west to east, which is unfortunate	in that the largest concentrations of emission sources are in	the midwestern United States, and the most vulnerable environments	along the eastern seaboard. Some pollution is thought to cross	the U.S. -- Canadian border, often from south to north, but in	some cases of some emitters in Ontario, it travels from north	to south.  Pollution from sources in the east is often blown	out to sea, where the resulting acid precipitation is thought	to be relatively harmless.	</p>		<p>	Incomplete knowledge of pollution transportation pathways is a	significant complication in devising regulatory solutions to the acid	rain problem. It is an even more serious barrier to implementing	market-based pollution control efforts.  Unless it is known where the	pollution from a given source travels, there is no way to know	who is entitled to enjoin whom, who should negotiate with whom,	or who should compensate whom.	</p>		<p>	<a name="64r">	</p>	<p>.	....It has been suggested that major pollution sources could be	required to tag their emissions with distinctive combinations	of isotope markers that could be read at downwind sites subject	to acid precipitation. If technically feasible, that would certainly	clarify some of the transportation issues. However, the problem	would remain that shifting atmospheric currents would mix pollutants	and deposit them in constantly changing and unpredictable patterns,	so that a system of compensation founded on the transportation	pathways of a base period would not necessarily remain valid	for subsequent periods.<a href="#64">[64]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="65r"></p><p>	The first problem here is the short shrift Dolan gives to theisotope solution. One is tempted to reply, "So what" that changing windconditions will deposit pollutants in "constantly changing andunpredictable patterns." Criminals first rob people in neighborhood A,then in B, then in C in "constantly changing and unpredictablepatterns." Does this mean that our society should not pursue criminals,wherever they operate?<a href="#65">[65]</a>  Such would seem to be theimplication of the Dolan analysis. If so, it is problematic.<p>	But there is a second difficulty as well -- the virtually completefailure of the discipline of environmental forensics to emerge.Forensic medicine, in contrast, is a growing and healthy science.  Theforces of law and order are now able to trace perpetrators based on thetiniest bit of their blood, semen, saliva or flesh (as under thefingernails) left on the bodies of their victims. But suppose that wenever had laws against murder. It is unlikely in the extreme that anysuch capabilities would have been developed.<p><a name="66r"></p><p>	Something of this sort seems to have occurred with regard toairborne pollutants. Ever since the 1830s,<a href="#66">[66]</a> it hasnot been illegal to trespass soot particles onto the property of otherpeople for reasons compatible with, although by no means the same asoffered by Dolan.  Is it any wonder that environmental forensics hasnot only atrophied, but died stillborn? Now reverse this situation, atleast in the form of a mental experiment. Suppose, that is, that thejurisprudence in effect until the 1830s (a more or less rigid system ofproperty rights, where polluters were subject to fines, injunctions,and so forth) had instead continued up to the present day.<p>	Is there any doubt that we would have long since been blessedwith a robust and accomplished industry dedicated to environmentalforensics, which would have been fully capable of discharging theobligations Dolan "regrets" we can not now accomplish? In those earliertimes, the chemical and atmospheric difficulties posed by this authorwould have been easier to deal with -- matched by the lesser scientificcapabilities of that epoch. The present challenges look so dauntingbecause we are berift of the some 150 years of R&D that would havetaken place had the law upheld the victims' property rights in thatbygone era.<p><a name="67r"><a name="68r"></p><p>	Dolan's third objection to the free enterprise system is perhapshis weakest. It consists solely of the claim that there are disputes asto the property rights of the polluters. The implication is that untilthese disputes are resolved (perfectly? to the satisfaction of allconcerned parties?) we cannot go ahead and implement the law oftrespass. He admits that the common or natural law view is that peoplehave a right "to exclude pollutants from their air space"<a href="#67">[67]</a> but asserts that "counterclaims can be made thatare difficult to dismiss out of hand."<a href="#68">[68]</a><p>	There are many difficulties with this view. Even if it were true, itby no means follows that the usual structures concerning privateproperty rights could not be implemented with regard to acid rain;there are "disputes" about practically everything -- as anyone canattest who has read a recent issue of any law review. Were we to allowdisputatiousness to cancel law, we would be in a very sorry stateindeed. In any case, it by no means follows that aweakened-by-disputations common law -- even if Dolan could show this --would be inferior to the TER scheme.<p>	Fortunately, we need not press on to a benefit-cost analysis ofthese two alternatives. For it is reasonably easy to "dismiss out ofhand" all of the disputations created, manufactured or discovered byDolan. Let us now consider them.</p><p>First, we are told that:</p><ul>	<p>	<a name="69r">	</p>	<p>	Midwestern utilities are joined by producers of Appalachian high	sulfur coal. The coal interests point out that they have made	long-lived investments and entered into long-term contracts to	supply fuel to utilities. These contracts met all environmental	regulations in force at the time they were entered into. To	change the rules of the game now would impose job and revenue	losses that should not go uncompensated.<a href="#69">[69]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="70r"><a name="71r"></p><p>	But it is easy to dismiss this argument "out of hand" sinceit is identical, in logical form, to the one used by the slave ownersof the Confederacy, after they lost the Civil War.  The plantationowner, too, argued that his initial purchases of slaves, and laterdominion over them "was … in accordance with all federal and state …standards in force at the time (that these events occurred).<ahref="#70">[70]</a>  And Dolan is as correct in his argument as are the"midwestern utilities" in theirs.<a href="#71">[71]</a> Slavery, afterall, was perfectly legal in the United States, up until the time of theemancipation proclamation.  In like manner, if the utilities hold"first in time" rights, then so do the enslavers. If the midwesternpolluters "should be compensated" for the pollution abatement costs,"then this privilege should (have been) extended to" the owners ofblack human beings as well.<p><a name="72r"></p><p>	Put in this way, however, it is easy to see the fallacy ofthe argument. Just as in the case of the slave owners, the utilitieswere given "rights" which clearly did not belong to them as a matter ofnatural law.<a href="#72">[72]</a>  It is gross legal positivism of theworst sort to insist, as does Dolan, that because a legislature saw fitto enact certain rules, that they have any proper force. This sort oflegal positivism can be used to justify not only slavery, but Naziconcentration camps, Soviet gulags, and any and all other atrocitiesthat man has perpetrated on other men under the guise of a spuriouslegality.<p>	As for the second part of this argument, that concerning thecomplaints of the producers of Appalachian high sulfur coal, there werefactors complementary to the slave holding plantation system, too, theowners of which were rendered out-of-pocket upon its demise. Thehandcuff manufacturers, whip makers, runaway slave chasers, and soforth, had also "made long lived investments, and entered intolong-term contracts to supply" factors of production to the slavesystem. When that rascal, Lincoln, freed the slaves, he "change(d) therules of the game ... and impose(d) job and revenue losses that shouldnot go uncompensated."<p>	Bosh and tosh. Rather than being compensated, the slave ownersand their allies in the whip business should have been subjected to theseverest penalties of the law.  This also applies to the case of theNazi concentration camp guards, the oven builders, and the CommunistEast German border guards who quite "legally" shot to death hundreds oftheir countrymen whose only "crime" was to attempt to escape that vastprison. Similarly, for the midwestern utilities and Appalachian coalinterests. Their claims for compensation are an outrage, and should be"dismissed out of hand." The real issue is whether, and to what extent,they should be penalized.<p>	Dolan's fourth and last point concerns transactions costconsiderations. Again, we allow him to speak for himself:</p>	<ul>	<p>	Consider a simple example. Suppose I am looking for a piece of land on	which to build a drag strip. In doing so, I must face the possibility	that although some people would consider a neighbourhood drag	strip an amenity, others are likely to consider it a nuisance.	Fortunately, there are many possible sites for the strip. Some	will be large enough that noise from the strip will not carry	beyond the property line, although, of course, it will be costly to	buy so much acreage. Alternatively, there will be smaller, less	expensive sites where I can first negotiate an option to buy,	and then negotiate with the neighbours regarding compensation for the	noise. Through a process of competitive bargaining in which I	simultaneously negotiate with owners of various drag-strip sites and	with the neighbours of those sites, I finally settle on the	alternative that is least costly to me. Because all externalities	have been internalized through the competitive bargaining process,	that will also be the most efficient solution from the point of	view of the community as a whole.	</p>	<p>	Regrettably, quite aside from the scientific and legal uncertainties,	the drag-strip model is not workable in the case of acid rain.	Two features of the acid rain case enormously raise the transaction	costs of a privately negotiated agreement. One is the fact that	the number of parties involved is far greater -- dozens of electric	utilities, thousands of smaller industrial pollution sources,	and millions of downwind property owners. The other is the fact	that the pollution sources that cause the greatest concern are	already in place, as are their sources of fuel supply, their	customers, and their work forces. Thus, in place of the ex-ante	competitive bargaining of the drag-strip model, the acid rain	issue involves ex-post bargaining among parties who are already	locked into inflexible relationships with one another by virtue	of non-redeployable, site-specific investments. These circumstances	encourage individual parties to play the free-rider if they are	on the paying side or to hold out for a greater share of the	potential gains from any agreement if they are on the receiving	side. If free-riders, holdouts, and the sheer problem of numbers	inflate transaction costs to the point where they exceed the	potential gains from an agreement, nothing will be done.	</p>	<p>	<a name="73r">	</p>	<p>	What is meant by "doing nothing" depends, it should be noted, on how	property rights issues are resolved. If utilities' claims to free use	of the airshed are upheld, then doing nothing means letting pollution	continue unabated, even if the marginal gains from pollution	abatement exceed the marginal costs of abatement. If the claims	of downwind landowners are fully upheld against the polluters,	then "doing nothing" means no pollution. Sources must either	shut down or install equipment that will reduce pollution to an	imperceptible level, even if at that opposite margin, marginal	abatement costs exceed the marginal benefits of abatement. Neither	extreme is optimal, viewed apart from transaction	costs.<a href="#73">[73]</a>	</p></ul><p><a name="74r"></p><p>	This is perhaps the strongest of his four arguments, but it,too, is flawed. First of all, Dolan severely underestimates the abilityof the market to internalize externalities, or, in his own terminology,to convert the acid rain situation into one at least approximating thatof the "drag strip." An alternative way of stating this is that heunduly minimizes the effects of socialistic acts of government in othersectors of the economy in rendering problems in this part moreintractable. A case in point is the large numbers of contractingparties, for example, millions of automobile owners, who pollute theatmosphere. However, if government were to allow private ownership ofstreets, roads and highways,<a href="#74">[74]</a> the numbers would bereduced -- at one fell swoop -- from several million to perhaps severaldozen.<p>	The point is that, under private ownership, no one would suethe individual automobile owner-drivers.  Instead, one would holdresponsible the highway corporation, for running, as it were, a"pollution bawdy house."  One of the reasons the legal scenario isdismissed out of hand is that it is difficult to see how it would bepractical to sue millions of people.  But privatization renders theobjection less telling.<p>	As we have seen, the common law tradition, on the basis of which weare writing, would interpret "doing nothing" not as "letting pollutioncontinue unabated." But it would not require "no pollution," either,the only other option offered by Dolan. More precisely, natural lawwould allow no pollution that violates the property rights of victims,but it would allow any and all emissions that do not amount totrespass.<p>	How could emissions into the air be justified on this basis,given large numbers of transactors (although not as many as per Dolan),hold outs, free riders, and so forth. Our author himself has mentionedor suggested several options:scrubbers, isotope marker emission tags,cleaner burning fuels.<p><a name="75r"></p><p>	In addition, property rights themselves can come to the rescue,paradoxically, from the perspective of the "first in time" concept wehave rejected above. We did so, before, because the "rights" given outby the government to the utility polluters were illegitimate. They wereestablished by arbitrary state edict. There is, however, a legitimatesource of these rights: the Lockean homesteading principle.<ahref="#75">[75]</a><p>	How would this work? Suppose, for example, that a factory hadbeen polluting an area of nine square miles, while claiming ownershipover only a central core of this area of one square mile, while otherpeople had moved into the additional eight square miles after thefactory emissions had begun. Under these circumstances, the firm wouldown the property rights to its one square mile, but the pollutionrights to the other eight square miles. This would not be, as perDolan, due to legislative legerdemain; on the contrary, it would flowfrom the Lockean insight that he who first uses a previously non-ownedresource, by that fact alone arrives at a legitimate ownership rightover it. This, after all, presumably, is how the firm established itstitle over the one central square mile it physically occupies.<p>	Under these conditions, the amount of pollution that wouldensure under a property rights regime would be far greater than thezero level or "no pollution" claimed by Dolan, if "the claims ofdownwind landowners are upheld against the polluters." One might evenclaim, as we do, that the optimal amount of emissions would ensue underthese institutional arrangements.<p>	Another point is that the problem of the "holdout" as is depicted inthe Dolan analysis is unsatisfactory. Indeed, the very terminologyemployed here implies that the holdout doesn't "really" value hishomestead, or peace and quiet, or clean air, at all, let alone at theelevated level he says he does. He is merely "holding out" for greaterfinancial remuneration. But how can this author, or any other outsideobserver, know this? On the contrary, if preferences are subjective, wecannot treat the holdout differently than any other market participantwith a reservation price for his property.<p>	That being said, it must also be mentioned that it is by no means asimpossible to solve the problem of possibly strategic behavior asclaimed by Dolan. In order to see this, we have only to reflect uponthe concept of options. A factory is attempting to locate in a placewhere there will be hundreds, if not thousands, of pollutees. It neednot commit to that one area. Instead, it could purchase options to buysmoke emissions rights, at stipulated prices, at some half dozenplaces. Then, if holdouts are discovered, in two or three of theseareas, they can be played off one another.<p>	But there is a further difficulty with this author's position.In his view, the main barrier to markets is unacceptably largetransactions costs. His solution is not a market in property rights,but instead a "quasi market" scheme of TERs. Transaction costs,however, like all other costs, are amenable to being reduced. But thiscan occur if and only if markets are allowed to function.<p>	Historically, computer costs, television costs, automobilecosts, were all very high, indeed, exceedingly so, when these productswere first introduced. They were priced out of the reach of the middleclass; they were playthings of the rich.  But then, however, thanks tospecialization, division of labor, investment, and so forth, thesecosts were all markedly reduced. If transaction costs are ever tofollow this pattern, a result Dolan must at least implicitly favorsince he mentions it as a prime obstacle to markets, we must allowproperty rights, not ride rough shod over them as in the MPP proposal.<p>	This author's public policy recommendation, then, must be viewed as arecipe for the very market failure it decries. For without upholdingthe claims of downwind landowners as against polluters (who do not ownthe requisite pollution rights) a market in these rights is renderedall the less likely.<p><a name="76r"></p><p>	Dolan<a href="#76">[76]</a> is mired in a static model notonly with regard to transaction costs, but also as far as smokeabatement technology is concerned. Consider the open ended smokestack.Open ended, that is, to the air and thus to the property of otherpeople. Is it so difficult to imagine that if in the 1830s the legalregime of property rights had not been overturned, that we would bylong before now have enjoyed a nonpollution intensive technology wherethere were no open ended smokestacks? Where these pipes would have leadback to chemical cisterns, the latter to capture otherwise errant sootparticles?<p>	Dolan ends his analysis with an obeisance to cost benefit analysis.And yet, as we have seen, this concept is fundamentally.  Utility ofdifferent people is simply incomparable.  How does this author knowthat at the "opposite margin (upholding victim-landowner rights)marginal abatement costs exceed the marginal benefits of abatement." He cannot know, nor can he adduce any evidence for this conclusion.<p>	The beauty of the property rights approach, in contrast, is that itneed not become mired in these subjectivist quicksands. It assignsproperty to its rightful owners, and places the burden of purchase onthose who could alter these allocations.</p>	<center><h4>V.  Conclusion</h4></center><p>	The introduction of marketable trading permits into environmentaleconomics is a major innovation in that permits allow "market" forcesto be unleashed into what would otherwise be a command system. Marketable trading permits result in a much more efficient allocationof resources, which makes it possible to have both less pollution andlower operating costs.  Yet they suffer from a major structuraldeficiency because trading permits are, in effect, a license topollute, a license to violate property rights.  A true market regimerecognizes rather than ignores property rights.  The problem withrecognizing property rights in the area on environmental economics isthat air, water, roads, many forests, and so forth, are publicly owned,which really means owned by no one.  As a first step towardimplementing a true market regime, we must find ways to privatize these"commons" so that market forces will be able to operate to reducepollution and costs.  Much research needs to be done in this area, butnow that the problem has been identified, we at least know in whichdirection research should proceed.</p>	<hr>	<p>	The authors would like to thank Vivian Lugo and John Tortorafor their research assistance.  An earlier version of this PolicyAnalysis was published in Fordham Environmental Law Journal, Vol. 6,No. 1 (Fall, 1994), 51-77.  Nothing written here is to be construed asnecessarily reflecting the views of the Dumont Institute or as anattempt to aid or hinder the passage of any bill before Congress.</p><hr noshade><h4>End Notes:</h4><ol><p><a name="1"><li>	This scheme also goes by the names tradable	emission rights (TERs), tradable pollution rights (TPRs) and tradable	emission permits (TEPs).		<a href="#1r">Return</a><p><a name="2"><li>	J. H. Dales, Pollution, Property & Prices (1968).	 Other treatises on this subject include Buying a Better Environment:	Cost-Effective Regulation 