t of the individual provide for continuous gains in productivityand quality. A system in which production errors can not get into finishedproducts. <BR><BR>Lastly a system that will create a veritable deluge of innovation. Basicinnovation, and process and product innovation. <BR><BR>As must be true with all new knowledge, you will see concepts that havebeen tried in the past and did not work. This was not a fault in the principle,but rather in the implementation. It is the old system -- the system ofcompensation based in Being There -- that can not withstand the scrutinyof logical examination. <BR><BR>The system described is one used in all advanced, volitional societies.The question is not if it will be adopted on this planet, but when. Nothingelse makes sense. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> |</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER><A NAME="BAC"></A>BACKGROUND</CENTER></H3><H4>The book, The Virtual Corporation</H4>The Virtual Corporation by Davidow and Malone1 has begun to tie togethermany of the technological and managerial solutions to today's business problems.Yet there remain basic flaws with the way companies are structured and theway people are compensated, both for production and innovation. The bookdoes not address these basic problems. <BR><BR>Because of these flaws, almost all of the tampering with the current businessstructure and methods is nothing more than Band-Aid therapy. It is liketrying to repair a Rube Goldberg machine for which the drawings have beenlost, and there has been no configuration control. It is possible to tinkerwith it and improve things here and there, but there can be no dramatic,overall improvements on a system that needs replacing rather than repair.<BR><H4>Historical background of business structure</H4>Just as there has been no change in principle in so-called governments sincethe dawn of history, with man continuing to be ruled by a combination offorce and fraud, so there has been no real change in business structures.<BR><BR>The business structure has been based on two concepts: <BR><UL>  <LI>a hierarchy of bosses, whether it is a two-level system or one withtwenty or more levels;   <LI>a system of production compensation based on the concept of what Icall <B>Being There</B>. <p>People are paid based on their presence in theworkplace, almost regardless of the quantity or quality of production.</p></UL><H4>Problems of the old system</H4>Discussing the fact that something is terribly wrong with our economy andthe way business is done, Davidow and Malone say, &quot;The uneasiness comesfrom the intuition that the problem cannot be solved simply by another taxreform or shift in monetary policy. Working harder and longer does not appearto be the solution to individuals either unable to find work or alreadyholding down more than one job.&quot;2 <BR><BR>The old system, <B>&quot;Being There&quot;</B>, creates a number of problems,but they can all be traced back to two basic things: People are not heldaccountable for their errors, and the system does not motivate people. Ifyou were trying to design a system that had a negative effect on motivationyou could not do better than the current business structure. <BR><BR>And if you are thinking of disagreeing with me on the subject of error accountability,let's look at the situation more closely first. I agree that for large errorsa person may be demoted or terminated, but this is not what I am reallytalking about. <BR><BR>The errors I am most concerned about are the ones just above &quot;the noiselevel.&quot; They are recognizable as errors, but they are not terriblybad errors. Just &quot;routine&quot; errors. Yet recognizable as errors,and something that costs the company money or loss of image. Such as anerror that gets to the customer. These errors are much more significantthan the ones that are recorded and for which a person is disciplined. Why?<BR><BR>Because it is recognized as an error even by the person who made the mistake,although he may not admit it to others, and perhaps hardly even to himself.And it is &quot;swept under the carpet.&quot; He does not pay for it, sincethe company absorbs the cost and passes it along to the hapless consumerin the form of a higher price and perhaps even a product with a defect.<BR><BR>This creates two potentially devastating consequences. One is the loss ofself-esteem caused by &quot;getting away with&quot; the error. The otheris loss of opportunity to learn from the error. <BR><BR>Both of these are bit like radiation damage. The effect is cumulative, withthe person passing up countless opportunities to learn and becoming moreand more incompetent as time passes. The damage to the ego and self-esteembrings on an increasing sense of hopelessness. Of having lost control ofone's life and destiny. It is this loss of self-esteem and the feeling ofhaving lost control of one's life that is the root cause of most of theproblems of society today. Whether it comes from the underemployment ofthe Being There system, or actual unemployment. <BR><BR>A favorite buzzword these days is empowerment. Essentially it means to passdecision-making responsibility and authority down to the lowest levels.When this is not done individuals lose interest in their jobs and have noincentive. Not only the incentive to do what is right, but even to the extentof not having any interest when they see things being done wrong or notin the best, most efficient way. The current hierarchial system mitigatesagainst empowerment. <BR><BR>Attempts are made to correct the problem by another hot concept, benchmarking.In principle this is a good idea, yet because of the business organizationthere are serious potential problems. The concept is often used as a toolto monitor people and demand higher performance in a system in which theyare not, and can not be properly compensated for the additional output.The end result is heightened confrontation between labor and management.<BR><BR>As Jude Rich of Sibson & Company says, &quot;The old motivational toolshave lost their magic. The great challenge that lies before us is to restructurehow we do work and reward people.&quot;3 <BR><BR>Another major problem with the current business system is innovation. Whilethe United States has been the world leader in innovation virtually sinceits founding, other countries are catching up as the US flounders. Evenwhile the other countries use the same defective business system as theUS. <BR><BR>And, as Frank R. Lichtenberg has noted, &quot;... analysis indicates thatthe rate of return on such intangible investments [investment in research& development] actually exceeds the return on expenditures for plant andequipment by a factor of as much as 7 to 1. That is, a dollar of privateR&D investment appears to be seven times more potent in facilitating productivitygrowth and higher per capita income than a dollar of conventional capitalinvestment.&quot;4 <BR><BR>And, as Davidow & Malone state, &quot;Inventions and their interactionswill be the engine of the virtual corporation.&quot;5 Innovation is theengine of industry. Without it there are no products and no process to producethem. Yet the way we compensate people for innovation is appalling. Oftenthe compensation is even negative in the sense that the idea is stolen fromthe person and they spend years trying to get proper compensation ratherthan engaging in further innovation. Even in the best of cases the rewardis often minuscule. <BR><BR>All of these create a situation in which there is no real, deep-seated motivationtoward productivity, quality, and innovation. Where cost control and qualityseem like abstract concepts that must be imposed on an organization andits uninterested and unwilling people. Where products are designed by themarketing and engineering departments according to their view of the world,rather than what the consumer might want. <BR><BR>The system creates a &quot;winner-loser&quot; mentality. A circle of confrontationthat can not be truly broken by traditional methods. Management trying tokeep ahead of labor and vice-versa, and internal company organizations againsteach other. Because of emphasis on cost controls, and rigid company structures,promotions and pay increases are in danger of extinction. In a sense businessis becoming almost like the film industry. In the film industry as the storygoes, you can not become a member of Screen Actors Guild until you havebeen in a film. And you can not be in a film unless you are a member ofSAG. It is becoming increasingly more difficult for school-leavers to findjobs because they don't have experience. Yet how are they expected to haveexperience if they have been in school all their life? <BR><BR>All of these problems of the current business and compensation structurebreed frustrations. Employees feel they have lost control of their livesand destiny. Employers feel they have lost control of everything. It iswhen this feeling becomes deeper that people begin to think of escape intoharmful behavior. The feeling of loss of self-control of one's life anddestiny is in fact the root cause of both juvenile and adult delinquency.<BR><BR>In summary, the problems of the current system are: <BR><UL>  <p>  <LI>it pays people almost regardless of the quantity and quality of theirproduction;</p> <p> <LI>people work and produce as a group rather than as individuals. Productionoutside of the norm of the group presents a problem with no real solutionunder the present scheme of compensation;</p>  <p> <LI>being compensated as part of a group, virtually all individual incentiveis lost. Work Teams do not truly solve this problem;</p> <p> <LI>all levels of worker have not only a fairly rigid cap on their income,but also a cap on any so-called &quot;merit&quot; increases;</p> </UL><p>Yet there is a simple, elegant solution to all these problems.</p><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> |</CENTER><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER><A NAME="SOL"></A>THE SOLUTION</CENTER></H3><H4>Concept</H4>My concept of the virtual corporation is different than that of Davidowand Malone. Theirs is &quot;virtual&quot; more by the nature of the productsand the implementation of technology. With respect for their studious collectionof current Band-Aid therapy, their system is still the same old tired, worn-outstructure, even if individuals have been empowered to do more things. <BR><BR>This concept does not consist of companies in the current concept of suchthings. My concept of a virtual corporation is an entrepreneur orchestratingthe activities of a number of independent contractors brought together tocreate a product, whether tangible or intangible. The independent contractorsand the project on which they are working will change from time to time.They may work on more than one project for him or on projects for otherentrepreneurs. Yet this is not the independent contractor or piece-worksystem of old. <BR><BR>The independent contractors may themselves be entrepreneurs, orchestratingtheir own product or service for one or more entrepreneurs. What binds themtogether is the abilities required for a project, integrity, and a cost-effective,quality service. Again this may be a tangible product or an intangible service.Creating a physical part or service, or providing an intellectual product.<BR><BR>While abilities and other things are crucial, it is integrity that is theglue which will hold everything together. As Davidow and Malone say, <BR><BLOCKQUOTE>&quot;The virtual corporation is built upon unprecedented levelsof trust. Between the company and its suppliers and customers. Between managementand labor. Between senior and middle management.&quot;6 </BLOCKQUOTE>The only thing I would disagree with in that statement is the concept ofmanagement and labor, and senior and middle management. Those concepts cannot exist in the true virtual corporation. <BR><BR>My concept of a virtual corporation is: <BR><BLOCKQUOTE>&quot;An organization existing at any one time for the purposeof creating one or more products, whether tangible or intangible. It isorganized by an entrepreneur and consists of Production Associates, eachoperating under contract as individual companies, each responsible for thecompletion of one or more error-free tasks, for which they are compensatedbased on the market value of the task(s). <BR><BR>&quot;For innovation, whether basic, product, or process, royalties arepaid to the individual innovator(s) for the life of the innovation on amutually agreed basis between innovator and user. Such royalties are paidonly by those who use the innovations of others in the creation of a product(tangible or intangible), and not by end-users of a product. <BR><BR>&quot;The relationship between the entrepreneur and each Production Associatebegins, continues, and ends at mutually agreed times and on a mutually agreed,mutually profitable basis. <BR><BR>Production Associates acquire their contracts either directly or throughagencies or clearing houses based on mutually profitable relationships withtheir clients, both the entrepreneurs and the Production Associates.&quot;</BLOCKQUOTE><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H3><CENTER><A NAME="IMP"></A>IMPLEMENTATION</CENTER></H3><H4>General</H4>There is one important, all-encompassing, over-riding concept that mustbe observed if any attempt is to be successful in solving the problems ofproductivity and innovation. This is that the solution must be personallyprofitable to each and every participant. The company, the individual, andthe consumer. <BR><BR>Implementation of my concept of the virtual corporation, in which peopleare compensated solely on the basis of their error-free production, is simplein a manufacturing-type environment. This is because manufacturing costaccounting concepts are well defined and extensively used. The concept isless easy to apply in a &quot;white collar,&quot; &quot;overhead,&quot;or &quot;exempt&quot; environment for the reason that cost accounting andperformance benchmarks are often less well defined. Yet all that is requiredto apply the concept to all areas of production (which includes services)is more thought, imagination, and experience. <BR><BR>For this reason I would say it is even more important to implement the performancestandards of the virtual corporation in this environment. Like all otherproblems in our universe, it only requires more knowledge and we will havethe answers. <BR><BR>The thought of converting to the compensation concepts of the virtual corporationwill produce a certain amount of anxiety in people. Therefore, it is importantto smooth the transition by basing compensation on existing cost accountingstructures. Thus, assuming the person performs as before, they will be makingthe same amount of money. However, this will no longer be guaranteed. Onthe other hand, when a person can produce better and faster, they can earnmore. There is no arbitrary cap on income. <BR><H4>Implementing A Production Compensation System</H4>The basic inputs for the compensation system of the virtual corporationcome from standard cost accounting systems. The system that defines thetasks that go into a product or service and the amount of time requiredto do the tasks for people with certain assumed levels of education, experience,and ability. <BR><BR>To create a proper compensation system for the virtual corporation it isonly necessary to create standard cost accounting figures for the processesof the organization. If it is a new company or a new process within an existingorganization you must then acquire people with the appropriate skills. Thesame as you would do if they were to be compensated on the basis of BeingThere. If you are converting existing workers to virtual corporation conceptsyour hiring work is already done for you. <BR><BR>In both cases it is necessary to explain to workers the advantages, procedures,and obligations of being compensated solely on the basis of error-free taskcompletion. As a refresher these are: <BR><UL>    <p>  <LI>No arbitrary cap on income;  </p>    <p>  <LI>payment is made solely on the basis of error-free task completion;  </p>    <p>  <LI>within the limits of the production scheduling system, individualsmay choose the number of hours they work and when they work;</p> <p>  <LI>in addition to being paid for production, if they create product orprocess innovations a separate compensation will come into effect.</p></UL>One of the first things that will happen is that some people will completetheir tasks ahead of schedule. This means they will earn more per unit oftime than had been planned. This is good for them, but has not helped thecompany to reduce costs. What should be done to correct this? <BR><BR>When the productivity increase reaches a certain level, by prior agreement--andon a mutually profitable basis--the benefits will be shared between thecompany and the individual. The individual will still make more per unitof time, but the company will also pay less per error-free task completion.The major benefit for the both the individual and the company is still tocome, from product or process innovation. <BR><BR>The only guide line to be followed concerning the amount of the productivityincrease that accrues to the entrepreneur or company and to the individualis that it should be that percentage and amount that maximizes the longterm interest and profits of the two parties involved. It should maximizethe individual's motivation while providing an adequate return on investmentand productivity increase for the entrepreneur or company. <BR><H4>Implementation Details</H4>How do we implement a system of paying only for error-free task completion?As indicated above we start with the standard cost accounting system. Fromthis you will have determined the hourly rate for the people doing tasksand the amount of time required for the task. With this you can determinethe task value, which is the basic input for determining individual pay.The following table illustrates the principle: <BR><P><CENTER><TABLE border> <TR> <TH>Task</TH> <TH>Hrly Rate</TH> <TH>Timeto Complete (Mins.)</TH> <TH>Task Value</TH> </TR> <TR> <TD>A</TD> <TD>10.00</TD><TD>20</TD> <TD>3.33</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>B</TD> <TD>12.50</TD> <TD>75</TD><TD>15.63</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>C</TD> <TD>15.00</TD> <TD>3</TD> <TD>0.75</TD></TR> <TR> <TD>D</TD> <TD>10.00</TD> <TD>7</TD> <TD>1.17</TD> </TR> <TR><TD>E</TD> <TD>10.00</TD> <TD>15</TD> <TD>2.59</TD> </TR> </TABLE> </CENTER><P>With this task value, and knowing the actual production of each individualyou can then calculate individual compensation for the period. As an example:<BR><P><CENTER><TABLE border> <TR> <TH>Individual</TH> <TH>Task</TH> <TH>TaskValue</TH> <TH>Task Completed</TH> <TH>Payment</TH> </TR> <TR> <TD>Adams</TD><TD>A</TD> <TD>3.33</TD> <TD>32</TD> <TD>106.56</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>Baker</TD><TD>B</TD> <TD>15.63</TD> <TD>10</TD> <TD>156.30</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>Charles</TD><TD>E</TD> <TD>2.50</TD> <TD>43</TD> <TD>107.50</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>David</TD><TD>C</TD> <TD>0.75</TD> <TD>127</TD> <TD>96.25</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>Evans</TD><TD>C</TD> <TD>0.75</TD> <TD>1.43</TD> <TD>107.25</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>Evans</TD><TD>D</TD> <TD>1.17</TD> <TD>23</TD> <TD>26.91</TD> </TR> </TABLE> </CENTER><P>At the moment I am assuming implementation of the concept in an on-goingorganization, including the fact that people have been trained for theirjobs. In a new, startup operation, it would be necessary to create the costaccounting system as a planning forecast and to conduct training. In thisnecessarily brief article I can not go into all of the details of such anoperation, but anyone who is in business should know what to do. <BR><BR>In the true virtual corporation, training would be the responsibility ofeach individual. A company or entrepreneur could provide part of it forhis associates as an incentive or benefit, but I think it best not to provideall of it on a no-charge basis. People will derive more benefit from trainingwhen they know there is at least some cost to them. <BR><H4>Errors</H4>What about errors? How do we handle them? In the process of learning anddoing things errors are sometimes difficult to prevent or avoid. Individualswill however give more thought to them when there is a monetary cost tothem for making errors. Further, it is immoral for a person to be requiredto pay for the errors of another. This is separate from the fact that itis also irrational in the long term for one person to pay for the errorsof another. It deprives the individual of a very basic means of learningand improving their competence. <BR><BR>First and foremost, in accordance with the principles of the true virtualcorporation, pay is only for error-free task completion. When an error ismade, there is the option of correcting the error through a repair, or re-doingthe task without error. If materials and services have been wasted in theprocess, then the company or entrepreneur must be compensated for them.Including any &quot;overhead&quot; costs for warehousing, issuance, disposal,etc. <BR><BR>I know this will be controversial, but if the error has caused consequentialdamages, these must be for the account of the creator. As indicated above,to not do so is both immoral and irrational. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H3><CENTER><A NAME="PRO"></A>THE PROBLEMS</CENTER></H3><H4>Production Scheduling</H4>Yes, I know there will be production scheduling problems. I also know thatthey, like all other problems, can be solved with greater knowledge. And,since this is the only rational way to compensate people, the problems mustand will be solved. <BR><BR>There are many unanswered questions here, but it is expected that the readerwill think of how they can be solved on a mutually profitable basis. Forexample, what happens when the entrepreneur or the company conceive of aproductivity increase? Perhaps in the form of automation. Whatever the outcome,including eliminating the need for a human operator, a generalized solutionmust be in the production contract. There should be no reason why the companyshould keep or pay a person when they do nothing. Yet an attempt to findsomething for the individual to do can bring long term rewards to both parties.<BR><BR>This is a very brief discussion of production scheduling, but it is a verywell known subject and should present few problems to a professional. Ihave a full discussion of the subject in my book-in-progress. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H3><CENTER><A NAME="DIF"></A>THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN THIS AND PREVIOUS SYSTEMS</CENTER></H3>Hopefully, the differences between this system and previous attempts tosolve the problem of productivity should be obvious: <BR><UL> <p><LI>This system maximizes the income and profits of both	parties--the individual and the company;</p> <p>  <LI>it puts a premium on not making mistakes;  </p>    <p>  <LI>it removes arbitrary caps on individual income;  </p>    <p>  <LI>cost control is definitive and absolute.  </p></UL><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H3><CENTER><A NAME="INN"></A>IMPLEMENTING AN INNOVATION COMPENSATION SYSTEM<A/></CENTER></H3>The innovation compensation system is also easy to implement. In principle,innovation is compensated in the same manner as production, and that isaccording to the market value of the associated innovation. However, ratherthan just paying for more production, you must also pay a royalty basedon the market value of the innovation. This is true whether it is productor process innovation. <BR><BR>Why should a royalty be paid? Several reasons. One is that it is the onlymoral thing to do. The other is that the prospect of a significant paymentis a major motivating factor in innovation, and such payment will provideadditional motivation for future innovation. The company should be happyto make such a payment, because it is in their own best interest. It iswhat will create a stream of innovation, and in the end this is what makescompanies successful. <BR><H4>Handling the case of more than one innovator per innovation</H4>Calculating a royalty for one innovator is a simple matter. There may becases where there is more than one innovator. How do we handle that? <BR><BR>The first thing of course is to identify the people involved and quantifytheir contribution as well as is possible. It is not necessary to spenda great amount of time doing this, or is it necessary to write a book onthe subject. An outline of the contribution of each individual will certainlydo as a starting point. <BR><BR>Then pick the first person on the list and assign an arbitrary value totheir innovation. Say 100. Then go to the next name and assign a value totheir innovation relative to that of the first person. If, for example,it appears the innovation of the second person is worth twice that of thefirst person, assign it a value of 200. If that of the third person is halfthat of the first, assign a value or 50. <BR><BR>When finished, the entrepreneur would review the assessments in his ownmind. And then with all innovators as a group. It is almost certain therewill be some disagreement and discussion. This is a negotiating sessionto arrive at figures that are acceptable to all of the innovators. Lookat your figures -- those of the entrepreneur -- as the starting point. Thenit should really be up to the individual innovators to set mutually agreedrelative values. It is almost certain there is no one with better knowledgeon what was done than the individual innovators. Further, the entrepreneurshould have only one interest at this point. That the finally selected valuesare in fact agreeable to all of the innovators. <BR><BR>When this has been agreed, a table such as the following can be created:<BR><P><CENTER><TABLE border> <TR> <TH>Innovator Name</TH> <TH>Relative InnovationValue</TH> <TH>Percent of Total</TH> </TR> <TR> <TD>Andrews</TD> <TD>100</TD><TD>23.53%</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>Baker</TD> <TD>200</TD> <TD>47.06%</TD> </TR><TR> <TD>Clifford</TD> <TD>50</TD> <TD>11.76%</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD>Danforth</TD><TD>75</TD> <TD>17.65%</TD> </TR> <TR> <TD><HR NOSHADE></TD> <TD><HR NOSHADE></TD><TD><HR NOSHADE></TD> </TR> <TR> <TD><B>TOTAL</B></TD> <TD><B>425</B></TD><TD><B>100.00%</B></TD> </TR> </TABLE> </CENTER><P>Knowing the market value of the innovations as a group for a certainperiod of time, and assuming a royalty percentage, it is now possible tocalculate the individual royalties for that period. <BR><H4>Innovations added to innovations</H4>It is almost certain the market unit that exists now will be improved inthe future. How do we handle that? <BR><BR>When we remember that innovations are compensated based on their marketvalue the answer is simple. We only need to know the market value of theinnovation and go through the above exercise with the individuals involvedin this new innovation. <BR><H4>The Royalty</H4>How much should the royalty be? There is no magic number. It is what willprovide the best return to both the company and the individual. We mightpick a figure of 10% for the sake of discussion. <BR><BR>Suppose a worker makes an innovation that increases company sales by $1million. Then his royalty should be $100,000. I can hear the screams now.&quot;You must be crazy! That is too much money!&quot; If you say that--andyou want to think in terms of short-term economics--I suggest you look atit from the standpoint of the return on your investment. You are investing$100,000 and obtaining a return of $900,000. Not too shabby. Especiallywhen you consider it probably occurred in one year. Further, it is a returnyou would not have had if the innovation had not occurred. And, if sucha payment in principle is not made, you can be sure innovative thinkingwill not occur again for a long time. Or, if it does, the individual willstart their own company to capitalize on it. I personally know of individualswho had ideas, offered it to their company, and the idea was rejected. Theythen quit, started their own company, and were very successful. I have onefriend who eventually sold his company for $241 million. <BR><BR>You might be wondering what the worker will do with the money. Is it reallythat important to anyone but him? There are a few possibilities: <BR><UL>  <p>  <LI>He might just quit and retire with his wife to Montana.  </p>    <p>  <LI>He might quit, leave his wife, and head for the South Seas.  </p>    <p>  <LI>He might like the idea of the &quot;quick hit,&quot; and work on doing	it again.	</p></UL>He might use some of the money to buy computer, workshop, or laboratoryequipment to enhance his innovation abilities. He might also spend someof his time taking specialized training courses that will further enhancehis ability to innovate. <BR><BR>Whatever he does, he has provided the company with an increase in salesand profits that vastly outstrips the associated cost. At the very leastit will serve as an example of what others can do. <BR><BR>One last word on this subject. The royalty should and must be paid for aslong as this innovation is providing value to the company. If you must askwhy, review the previous paragraphs and think. <BR><BR>Further, no innovation may be used without the permission of the innovator.If you don't understand why, remember that an innovation is property isthe property of the person who creates it. In principle it is no differentthan tangible property, such as a painting. If you liked the painting ofan artist, wanted it, but you could not agree on the price, would you justtake it anyway? <BR><BR>If nothing else, look at it from a practical standpoint. People who do notreceive proper payment for innovations have been known to just stop innovating.Or, if they did not stop, they kept their innovations to themselves, preferringthat to receiving less than the value they placed on them. <BR><BR>On the other hand, when a person is properly rewarded for their intellectualoutput it acts as a stimulus. Proper, market-value compensation while createa veritable deluge of innovation. Basic innovation, and product and processinnovation. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H3><CENTER><A NAME="UNI"></A>UNIONS</CENTER></H3>The virtual corporation could spell the end for unions in their presentform, however there is hope for them. They could reconstitute themselvesas an educational organization and a clearing house for contract workers.<BR><BR>As an educational organization they could teach such traditional coursesas English and basic science and mathematics, and then more advanced, specializedcourses to allow individuals to continually increase their educational qualifications.<BR><BR>As a clearing house, they could maintain -- on a contractual basis -- individualnames and associated experience and qualifications. Entrepreneurs and companiescould then consult the clearing house to obtain people with certain specifiedskills. Unlike their current activities, unions would need to do these thingson a mutually profitable, fee-paying basis, such as is currently done withemployment agencies. <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | </CENTER><P><HR NOSHADE><H3><CENTER><A NAME="LEG"></A>LEGAL AND FINANCIAL SITUATION</CENTER></H3>I am not a lawyer and therefore can not give legal advice. For that youmust contact a lawyer. I will only give some thoughts and ideas for youto consider and possibly discuss with an attorney. <BR><BR>The American political r&eacute;gime seems to live in fear of independentworkers and has some very strict guidelines that must be followed to supportthe fact you are not an employee. Once that has been done there are sometax advantages -- and liabilities -- to being independent. It also movesthe burden of some bureaucratic paper work previously done by the employeronto the individual. <BR><BR>Generally you must have a business license if you are independent in thenature of being a &quot;consultant.&quot; This would probably be the closestthing to an individual who works independently and on contract. <BR><BR>As with any business, it is imperative that you keep good records. Thismeans both the legal and &quot;administrative&quot; records, and financialrecords. As an independent businessman and, in effect, an entrepreneur,you will be entitled to certain tax breaks. But, as mentioned above, therewill also be some additional hits by the IRS. Probably the most prominentis that you must pay the other half of what the IRS euphemistically calls&quot;social security&quot; tax. Depending on the type of work you are doingyou may be entitled to a tax break on special clothing and on a home office.But again as stated above, you must make absolutely sure you are followingappropriate IRS guidelines. <BR><BR>While you would not directly receive the medical and pension benefits ofan employee, there is no reason you could not be a member of a group plan.This could be another function of a new type of &quot;union,&quot; whichwould be more like a professional society than a union. As far as pensionsare concerned, with an investment ,of as little as $10 a week starting whena person is twenty-one, they can have more than $500,000 in assets in today'sdollar upon reaching age 65, and draw a pension income of more than $50,000.This would exceed the working income of the average worker, and also illustratesthe fraudulent nature of so-called &quot;social security.&quot; Which inany case is only a money laundering operation, transferring part of theincome from a number of people to one other person while at the same timeextracting a large &quot;handling&quot; fee. How else can you explain thefact there is less money in what is euphemistically called &quot;your account&quot;than what you and the employer &quot;contributed&quot; over the years? <BR><BR><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>| <A HREF="#TOP">Top of Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE></CENTER><H3><CENTER><A NAME="SUM"></A>SUMMARY</CENTER></H3>The environment of a proper virtual corporation creates a new type of companyand a new class of &quot;worker&quot; who is no longer a worker. Each &quot;worker&quot;is now an individual and not a cog in a machine. The individual is now atthe very least a budding entrepreneur who has an ability to earn limitedonly by their experience, education, imagination, and drive. The abilityto continually advance based truly on individual merit, becoming a full-fledgedentrepreneur in their own right. <BR><BR>The prime consideration is innovation and error-free production. It is independentof color, religion, sex, politics or another other arbitrary, non-performance-relatedconsiderations. An intelligent entrepreneur or company director should onlybe interested in the long-term results for his or her organization. <BR><BR><HR><H4>Footnotes</H4><OL>  <LI>William H. Davidow and Michael S. Malone, &quot;The Virtual Corporation&quot;New York: Harper Business Books, 1992)   <LI><I>Ibid</I>, p. 15.   <LI>Nagel & Dove, &quot;21st Century Manufacturing Enterprise Strategy,&quot;vol. 1, p. 10.   <LI>Frank R. Lichtenberg of Columbia University Business School, <I>BusinessWeek</I>, Economic Trends, Gene Koretz, 12/16/92, page 12.   <LI>Davidow & Malone, &quot;The Virtual Corporation&quot; (New York, NY:Harper Business Books, 1992) p. 79   <LI><I>Ibid</I>, p. 183. </OL><HR NOSHADE><CENTER>Copyright &copy; 1993--WWMorgan <HR NOSHADE>| <A HREF="#TOP">Topof Page</A> | <HR NOSHADE>&copy; 1995 - The Universal Salvage Corporation <BR><I>Specialists in Dying Civilizations</I> </CENTER><HR NOSHADE><BR><B>Contact Information:</B><BR>E-Mail: administrator@Freedom-Server.co.uk<BR><BR><HR><BR>The URL of this page is: <BR><P><CENTER>&lt;http://www.freedom-server.co.uk/Virtual-System.html&gt;<HR NOSHADE></CENTER> </BODY></HTML>
