<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE></TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffccff"><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="rule.1.jpeg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="1" WIDTH="432"HEIGHT="9" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><H1><CENTER>PRIDETIME Personalities<BR><IMG SRC="rule.3.jpeg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="1" WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="9"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>The Inside Scoop</CENTER></H1><H1><IMG SRC="pridetime.paul.jpeg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="108"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3">Paul Gagnon</H1>Someone once called me the &quot;best straight gay man in the business&quot;...I'mnot quite sure what that means, but I'll take it as a compliment! Most ofmy training in the communications field has been in radio. I actually startedin the business at a small AM station in Quincy, MA. I began as a receptionist,then a copy writer, and finally on air as an Arts and Entertainment reporterfor the station. <BR>I moved to Florida and landed a morning show at an FM Adult Contemporarystation and held that position for about 4 years. In that time I was fortunateenough to host beauty pageants, conventions and telethons live and on television.I also directed and produced dinner theater productions of shows like &quot;AChorus Line&quot; and &quot;the 1940's Radio Hour&quot; at citrus hill inFlorida. <BR>I decided to move back to Boston (my real home) and am I glad I did! I wasfortunate to meet Mary Kennedy, the Producer of Pridetime. I began by doingsome voice-over work for the show and one or two commentaries. Then thehost at the time moved on and I was asked to step in. I still remember thefirst Gay Pride march I hosted with Georgia Ragsdale. I was a nervous wreck,and remember saying the route of the parade would pass through South Bostoninstead of the South End of Boston. I was quickly corrected, and even afterthat I've been allowed the honor of hosting the last three marches and allof the shows in between.<BR>Pridetime has given me the opportunity to explore my desire to learn andunderstand and by asking questions of community leaders, celebrities andwriters. I try to ask thoughtful questions that most people would like toknow the answers to. I'll ask the tough questions when the situation callsfor it, but I enjoy the positive side: the coming out process, the way eventschange a persons perspective, etc.<BR>Some of my favorite guests have included Judy Tenuta, local film consultantGeorge Monseur, Cambridge City Councilor Katherine Triantifilou, authorLeroy Aarons (Prayers for Bobby) and my personal favorite Harvey Fierstein.<BR>I look forward to my own understanding of our community and serving ourcommunity with uplifting and intelligent talk, as well as challenging andbreaking down stereotypes using televisions power to mix word and images.<BR><BR>I look forward to seeing you next time on Pridetime! <BR><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="rule.3.jpeg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="1" WIDTH="432"HEIGHT="9" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><H1>Mark Adams</H1>It all began at a small 5000-watt radio station in the Merrimack Valley- I'd had a &quot;falling out&quot; with the administration of Boston University'sSchool of Communications when they'd determined I'd be better off anywherebut there. This mid-market station hired me as a news man - after severalweeks, they too determined I'd be better off doing anything but news, sothey gave me a mid-morning call in cooking show, quite appropriate, actually,as I knew not how to fry water! From there, I hit several other mid sizedradio outlets, doing DJ work , talk shows, and reviews of numerous highschool performances of ARSENIC AND OLD LACE. Tiring of the daily grind ofbroadcasting, I took to teaching. Teaching broadcasting, that is, at a now-defunctschlock Career Academy Broadcasting school, where many thousands of dollarswas more than enough for admittance. Out of over 500 students taught I canclaim two success stories, One a morning DJ at a Miami station, the othera news anchor at an ABC affiliate in Fresno, California. Oddly, enough,they are both gay, and they eventually became lovers. After the Academy'snon-voluntary closing, I returned to the radio biz at what was then Boston'sonly country radio station, a low-budget operation that paid in barteredcowboy hats and boots instead of cash. From there it was on to a more successfulcountry radio station on the FM dial, where I became close friends withthe likes of Boxcar Willie. I regained my sanity when a former paramutualsuggested I open a video store - I think there were 3 in New England atthe time. And thus began - THE MOVIE PLACE, which now has the largest selectionof all-male titles and lesbian films. I was then asked to write a videocolumn for IN NEWSWEEKLY, which I still do, and recently met Mary Kennedy,who foolishly thought I could do a good job of reviewing gay themed videosfor her wonderful PRIDETIME show. The rest, as they say, is fictional history.<BR><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="rule.1.jpeg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="1" WIDTH="432"HEIGHT="9" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><H1><IMG SRC="pridetime.mike.jpeg" WIDTH="76" HEIGHT="106" NATURALSIZEFLAG="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM">Mike Ceceri</H1>Some people consider watching television something to do when they are bored.I have always considered it a major part of my life. I have always lovedevery aspect of it, and for as long as I remember I knew I wanted to bea part of it. <BR>I am a true gypsy at heart. Born and raised in Rhode Island, I learned ata young age that life is short so enjoy it. After graduating Coventry HighSchool in 1988, I moved away to study Graphic Design and Musical Theaterat Flagler College in St. Augustine, Florida. I returned in 1991 to RI andlanded several parts in semi-professional theater. I also worked officejobs and did the whole starving actor thing. I then decided to get a jobdoing design work. In May of 1995 I took a job as Production Manager forthe New England Community Guide's Pink Pages. I got involved in Pridetimeduring Pride 95. I started out by filling in for a missing crew member,immediately I was hooked. I enjoy being a part of the talented productionteam, suggesting segments, helping on shoots and my favorite... being oncamera. Interviewing Judy Gold was my favorite project so far. I look forwardto every show because it allows me an opportunity to meet different membersof the community I would not be exposed to otherwise. <BR><P><CENTER><B>Go To<BR><A HREF="pridetime.home.html">Pridetime Home Page</A> | <A HREF="index.html">PinkWeb Home Page<BR></A><A HREF="referral.suggestion.html">Ideas or Comments</A><A HREF="index.html"><BR></A></B><BR><IMG SRC="rule.2.jpeg" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="1" WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="9"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><P>To contact us by E-Mail<BR><A HREF="mailto:comments@pinkweb.com">&copy;1996 kp media group </A><BR></BODY></HTML>
