<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>laser.tattoo.html</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#f5aecc" TEXT="#6e0051"><H1><CENTER><HR>LASER TREATMENT<BR><CITE>Tattoo Removal,<BR>Skin Resurfacing<BR>and Leg Vein Treatment</CITE></CENTER></H1><P><CENTER><CITE>Skin Medicine &amp; <BR>Surgery Centers, Inc.<BR>1-800-535-SKIN(7546) Normate T. Kpea, DO, MPH, MBA - Medical Director ,<BR>Paul Drago, MD, William Sahl, MD, Olga H Harbar, RNP. Specializing in: TattooRemoval &#183; Electrolysis &#183; Diseases &amp; Treatment of Hair, Skinand Nails &#183; Laser, Skin Cancer &#183; MOH's Surgery &#183; Sclerotherapy&#183; Cosmetics<BR></CITE><BR><IMG SRC="Tattoo-before.gif" WIDTH="180" HEIGHT="108" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER><H3><CENTER><I>before................after</I></CENTER></H3><H2><CENTER>1-800-535-SKIN(7546)</CENTER></H2><H4><CENTER><I>Mastercard, Visa, American Express and Discover Accepted<BR>Talk to us at laser@pinkweb.com/</I><A HREF="mailto:comments@pinkweb.com">&copy;1996kp media group</A></CENTER></H4><H2><CENTER>Tattoo Laser Treatment</CENTER></H2><H3>Why is the laser a safe treatment? The Candela laser is safer than traditionalmethods because of its unique ability to selectively treat the tattoo orlesion pigment. Thus, it will eliminate the tattoo or pigment while leavingthe surrounding skin undamaged.<BR><BR>What conditions are treated with the Candela laser system? Pigmented lesionslike nevus of ota and multicolored tattoos (amateur and professional) includingblack, blue, and other colors are treated. The effectiveness of the laseris dependent upon the age, location, depth, and type of tattoo/pigmentedlesion, as well as on the composition of the pigments.</H3><H2><CENTER>Tattoo before treatment</CENTER></H2><H3><BR>Why would someone have a pigmented lesion or tattoo removed? Many peopleare uncomfortable with unsightly pigmented lesions like nevus of ota, orwith tattoos they had applied several years ago. It is estimated that asmany as 50 % of individuals with tattoos regret the permanency of the tattooand wish to have it removed. With the Candela lasers, treatment is now possible.<BR><BR>What does treatment involve? Treatment with the Candela lasers varies frompatient to patient depending on the age, size and type of tattoo, colorof the patient's skin and depth to which the tattoo<BR><BR>The skin's reaction to the laser is tested during the first visit to determinethe most effective treatment. Treatment consists of placing a handpieceagainst the surface of the skin and activating the laser. As many patientsdescribe it, each pulse feels like the snapping of a rubber band againstthe skin. Smaller tattoos/lesions will require fewer pulses, while largerones will require more. All tattoos will require retreatments, necessitatingmultiple patient visits. The Candela system is less painful and requiresless recovery time than some other treatment methods. The degree of discomfortvaries with each person, depending on his/her pain threshold. Most patientsdo not require anesthesia. In some cases, however, depending on the natureand location of the tattoo or lesion, the physician may elect to use someform of anesthesia.<BR><BR>Is it possible to have a tattoo or pigmented lesion treated that was previouslytreated by another modality? Patients with previously treated tattoos maybe candidates for the Candela systems. Tattoos or pigmented lesions thathave not been effectively removed by other treatments may respond well toCandela laser therapy.<BR><HR></H3><H3><CENTER><IMG SRC="Medical-face.gif" WIDTH="192" HEIGHT="158" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></CENTER></H3><H1><CENTER>Skin Resurfacing</CENTER></H1><H3>As time marches on, our facial skin begins to reflect our years. Finelines and wrinkles appear around the eyes; creases deepen in the mouth andforehead areas. Your image is no longer a reflection of how you feel aboutyourself...Youthful, Healthy, Vibrant.<BR><BR>How does the laser work?<BR>Guided by your surgeon, the CO2 laser uses light pulses to accurately andpercisely vaporize damaged tissue layer by layer. The light pulses remainon the skin for very short periods of time. So short, that surrounding tissueis not damaged.<BR><BR>The area to be treated is usually marked preoperatively. The laser low powerbeam is then applied to the skin or wrinkles, in the microscopic first layersof skin are vaporized. The laser beam itself is obsorbed by the water inthe skin's cells causing them to dry. The dead cells are then gently wipedaway from the treated area. <BR><BR>The laser's fine control offers the patient a safer, more predictable procedurewithout bleeding, minimizing the risk of complications. <BR>The procedure usually takes any where from thirty minutes to two hours basedon the areas treated. Depending on the type and depth of the wrinkle orscar, one or more sessions may be scheduled.<BR><BR>Laser Skin Resurfacing may also be performed in conjunction with eyelidsurgery.<BR><HR></H3><H2><CENTER>Laser Treatment of Leg Veins<BR>Question and Answer</CENTER></H2><H2><BR>What conditions are treated with the Candela Sclerolaser?</H2><H3><BR>The Sclerolaser treats telangiectasia or spider veins (less than 1 millimeter)commonly seen on the legs. The precise origin of the disorder is unknownbut reports have shown that pregnancy, hormonal changes, weight gain, leginjury or prolonged standing may influence the occurrence.</H3><H2>Why should I have my leg veins treated?</H2><H3><BR>The majority of patients seeking treatment for removal of leg veins arefor cosmetic reasons. Most are uncomfortable with the appearance of theseveins during the warmer months when shorts/skirts are worn.</H3><H2>How does the Sclerolaser work and why is it a safe treatment?</H2><H3><BR>The Sclerolaser produces an intense but gentle burst of laser light thatpasses harmlessly through the skin and is selectively absorbed by the vessel.The light produced by the laser generates heat within the vessel, destroyingit without causing thermal injury to any of the surrounding tissue.</H3><H2><BR>Are there other methods used to treat leg veins?</H2><H3>The most common therapy used to treat leg veins is sclerotherapy. Sclerotherapyinvolves needle injections of sclerosing agents; such as saline, into thevessels to be removed. </H3><H2><CENTER>1-800-535-SKIN(7546)</CENTER></H2><H4><CENTER><I>Mastercard, Visa, American Express and Discover Accepted<BR>Talk to us at laser@pinkweb.com/</I><A HREF="mailto:comments@pinkweb.com">&copy;1996kp media group<BR><BR></A>Back to <A HREF="Laser.Dermotology.html">Skin/ Laser Home Page<BR></A><BR>Go to<A HREF="../index.html"> </A><A HREF="index.html">Pink Web Home Page</A></CENTER></H4><H3><BR><HR>&copy;1996 Skin Management Systems, Inc.</H3></BODY></HTML>
