<HTML><HEAD>    <TITLE>Commitment Cerimonies Article</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="com.cer.jpeg"><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="rule.2.jpeg" WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" BORDER="1"></CENTER><H1><CENTER>Commitment Ceremonies</CENTER></H1><P><CENTER><B>by Fred Kuhr</B><IMG SRC="rule.1.jpeg" WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" BORDER="1"></CENTER><P><B>Why are so many gay and lesbian couples getting married? Same gendercommitment ceremonies are not legally recognized anywhere in the country.Such ceremonies do not automatically give you spousal health insurance benefitsor inheritance rights or the right to make medical decisions in the eventthat your spouse is incapacitated. Well, as most newly 'committed' lesbiansand gay men will tell you, the joys that come along with affirming and celebratinglove in front of many friends and family are not limited to heterosexuals.Many claim that the ceremony has great emotional, social, and spiritualmeanings.<BR><BR>When it comes to commitment, no one knows more about nesting than lesbians.And this is reflected in the number of calls received by Private Affairs,a gay-owned service that arranges commitment ceremonies. Over 70 percentof inquiries are from lesbian couples.<BR><BR>Regardless of gender, planning your ceremony can be a joyful yet complicatedundertaking. Jewelers, printers, photographers, caterers, clergy and floristsneed to be contacted, catering halls need to be booked, and tuxedos or gownsneed to be purchased. <BR><BR>According to Joe and his 'husband' Patrick, the only real problem is schedulingchurch time since these ceremonies have become so popular. Currently, fifteenclergy and Justices of the Peace are willing to perform commitment ceremoniesin the Boston area. If a couple chooses to have their ceremony performedby clergy, pre-nuptial couples counseling is required. Sessions are usuallylimited to 2 or 3 two-hour meetings prior to the service. On the other hand,a Justice of the Peace usually does not require counseling. Currently, Justicesdo not perform legal ceremonies but tend to have their own special romanticceremonies for same gender couples. These are nondenominational and suitmany non-traditional couples.<BR><BR>The big question is: Will it be legal? Two lesbians, Genora Dancel and NiniaBaehr, are challenging the issue in Hawaii. In 1991, three Hawaiian couples,two lesbian and one gay, sued when the state refused to issue marriage licensesto them. In the spring of 1993, the Hawaii Supreme Court recognized thatthis denial amounted to discrimination on the basis of sex. The court evencompared this &quot;different gender restriction&quot; on marital choiceto old laws prohibiting interracial marriage which were eventually struckdown as being racially discriminatory. Since Hawaii has an equal rightsamendment which makes sex discrimination unconstitutional, the court concludedthat denying same gender couples marriage licenses might be unconstitutional.<BR><BR>The Hawaii Supreme Court sent the case back to trial court with the instructionto review the state's marriage policy under &quot;strict-scrutiny,&quot;meaning that the state must prove that it has a &quot;compelling interest&quot;in maintaining its restriction. Starting from the assumption that equaltreatment, not discrimination, is mandated by the state's constitution,this ruling puts the burden of proof on the state.<BR><BR>In reaction, Hawaii's legislature passed a law in June 1994 affirming itsdiscriminatory intent; the only state interest it named was &quot;propagationof the human race.&quot; Legal experts believe this will not stand as a&quot;compelling reason&quot; and the trial court will rule against thestate. &quot;Hawaii certainly doesn't require heterosexual couples to submitfertility tests or confirm their intentions to have children before issuingthem marriage licenses, and the lesbian baby boom belies the notion thatsame-sex couples don't have kids,&quot; according to Susan Murray and BethRobinson, two Vermont attorneys working with the Boston-based Gay &amp;Lesbian Advocates &amp; Defenders (GLAD) on the same gender marriage issue.<BR><BR>Once the case is thrown back to the Hawaii Supreme Court, the conventionalwisdom is that it will uphold its earlier decision. The freedom for samegender couples to marry, therefore, will become law in Hawaii. The caseis being tried by the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, and a finaldecision is expected by mid-1996 or early 1997.<BR><BR>Until that time, gay and lesbian couples continue to plan for and celebratetheir not yet legally recognized marriages. According to Private Affairs'Pereira, however, three big questions need to be answered before a coupleembarks upon any matrimonial journey - When? Where? and How much? Most samegender couples have a certain date in mind for their wedding. If a coupleis having trouble deciding, Pereira asks if they have a month or time ofyear that is special to them, such as the day the two met. He noted thatwhile most straight weddings occur on Saturdays, most same gender couplesopt for a Friday evening or Sunday afternoon. &quot;Gays and lesbians preferto be a little bit different,&quot; Pereira said.<BR><BR>Most same gender couples prefer to have their ceremonies near where theylive. In Boston, for example, the Arlington Street Church is a favoritebecause of the role it has played in the gay and lesbian community. Severalother chapels, such as King's Chapel, are also happy to accommodate samegender couples. Some couples, however, prefer a more natural setting, andboth Provincetown and Ogunquit, Maine, are popular places for both the ceremonyand the honeymoon. Some P-town guesthouses overlook the bay while othershave lovely gardens and outdoor spaces. Weather permitting, the nationalseashore's dunes make for a magnificent setting for a memorable ceremony.<BR><BR>As far as budgetary concerns, the ceremony's price tag depends upon howmuch the couple is willing and able to spend - and the couple's imagination.One &quot;Victorian wedding&quot; that Pereira handled, including partsof the wedding party arriving in horse drawn carriages, cost $11,000. Themost expensive affair he put together was for 210 people at the CambridgeMarriott costing a whopping $16,000. For his own, Pereira and husband spenta mere $5,000. Unfortunately, the most unique request he has received, fromtwo lesbians who wanted to be married underwater, was called off in theplanning stages and never got a price tag.<BR><BR>For Pereira, getting married is simply &quot;one more step towards a morefulfilling commitment,&quot; regardless of legal recognition. He does predictthough that once same gender marriage becomes legal, &quot;You'll see moreand more gays and lesbians getting married.&quot; For him, this should meana booming business. &quot;I think (same gender marriage) is more acceptednow. It's not a big shock anymore. It does happen. And it is now a partof life.&quot; </B><H2><CENTER>We offer a complete <BR>business service guide to palnning <BR><A HREF="cc.list.index.html">commitment ceremonies</A>!</CENTER></H2><P><CENTER><IMG SRC="rule.1.jpeg" WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN="BOTTOM"NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" BORDER="1"><BR><BR>Go to<BR><A HREF="boston.index.html">Metro Boston Navigational Page</A> | <A HREF="pinkpages.navagational.html">PinkPages Navagational Page</A> | <A HREF="index.html">Pink Web Home Page</A><BR><A HREF="pp.order.html">Order a Pink Pages</A> | <A HREF="referral.suggestion.html">Referrals- Corrections - Suggestions<BR></A><BR><IMG SRC="rule.3.jpeg" WIDTH="432" HEIGHT="9" ALIGN="BOTTOM" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" BORDER="1"><BR></CENTER><P>To contact us by E-Mail<BR><A HREF="mailto:comments@pinkweb.com">&copy;1996 kp media group </A><BR></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
